[White "📌 Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2127765594251748"]

{Hi! Welcome to the Bird Opening! I would like to start by thanking you for choosing me and Simon Williams, the GingerGM, to guide you to opening success! I assumed responsibility for making this course in late January. I had thought making the course would be fun and simple! How naive I was... Bird's opening turned out to be one of the most complex openings I've ever had to analyze in my life. Having spent an enormous amount of time analyzing, checking, and poring through all the material I can confidently say I've given this my very best. It's taken months of sleepless nights and chaotic days, but alas the course is done. The course is structured around the lichess database for players rated between 1200 and 1800 so if you are in this category, the repertoire will synchronize perfectly with the lines your opponents are choosing in your own games. Whenever possible, I have sought out lines to surprise your opponent with and give them the toughest time figuring things out. The structures arising in this repertoire are like no other − they don't resemble anything close to king or queen pawn structures. This is ideal for our repertoire, as frequent practice will amass a wealth of experience and know-how inaccessible to our opponents who rarely encounter such structures. Though the variations are structured in accordance with the database, I have made sure to make this repertoire bulletproof. Even if your opponent preps deeply against you knowing you will play the Bird, you will be fine and can count on at least equality in every single position. I did not want to put my name on something that could not be played at the highest level and toward that end have been playing the Bird exclusively in all my games online and in tournament practice. I've gotten mixed results, but at the same time, I have come to be certain that this is playable at all levels, and all time controls, FOR A WIN. I have played it against several GMs online and have won. I haven't played much classical this year, but I did beat two IMs rated around 2400 with it. If you think you'll like watching me play the Bird opening, feel free to subscribe to my YouTube channel GMRaven. I'd like to specify the way I used arrows in the positions. The green arrows are good ideas for either side that has them. The red arrows mean some idea that can no longer be played. In situations where there exists a red arrow, there is normally a green arrow close by to explain why the idea of the red arrow no longer works. The yellow arrows are slightly different than both of these. When yellow arrows only exist for our side, they denote longer-term ideas to be played only after those more immediate ideas marked by the green arrows have been carried out. There are other situations in which yellow arrows are marked for both sides. These denote ideas that are connected to one another. Examples of this are recaptures or other instances in which we only go for a specific idea if they have gone for something specific of their own. I hope these explanations make sense, I would have used more colors but Chessbase only has 3 available!} 1. Z0 *

