[Black "The Solid Pin: 2...Nf6 3.e3 Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A03"]
[PlyCount "21"]
[GameId "2127765594341861"]

1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Placing the [c6]-steed under an annoying pin.} e6 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7] Now Black's queenside is shattered and any plans to castle queenside need to be abandoned.} 8. d3 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7][%cal Ge3e4,Gb1d2,Gb1c3] White will play [Nd2] or [Nc3], castle, and then play [e3]-[e4].} Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5] This is Black's best bet, to get some play with ...[e6]-[e5].} 9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O e5 11. e4 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7][%cal Gf4f5] Things in the center might fizzle out, but the weak c-pawns will remain, endowing us a slight edge! Black must begin trades in the center immediately. If Black dawdles at all, we will play [f4]-[f5] with a favorable structure.} *

