1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Nc3 $5 ({This move is not seen nearly as often as the more popular} 6. b3 {. Nonetheless, it looks like the best and most fighting option. White keeps the position flexible and maintains options of moving [g3], [d3], or [b3]. Here, Black has six options, but we will primarily focus on the most popular one, ...[Bb4].}) 6... Bb4 {The bishop locks in on the [c3]-knight preparing a potential exchange followed by ...[Ne4].} 7. g4 ({I consider this move to be better than the much more popular} 7. a3 {. We expand on the kingside yet again. This move opens the [g2]-square for the bishop while manifesting the latent threat of [g4]-[g5].}) 7... Bxc3 {This move is what the majority of games have followed with and it also happens to be the most accurate. Obviously, in hindsight, [g4] made more sense than [a3], which would have just burnt a move to incentivize the same exchange.} 8. bxc3 {Here, White has the two bishops and the doubled pawns don't hamper our development or structural health much.} Nbd7 9. d3 $14 {[%csl Gc3,Gd3,Rd7,Ge3,Gf4,Rf6][%cal Gf1g2,Ge1g1] Black's knights lack good outposts and White's structure keeps a lot of flexibility. We will set up our pieces correctly and slowly expand with the aim of opening larger diagonals for the bishops. We could start with [Bg2] and castle kingside.} *

