1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 {We will deal now with Black's choice of avoiding pushing ...c7-c5 early. Please see the chapter regarding 2...c5 3.e3 Nc6 for coverage of positions in which ...[Bf5] is combined with ...[c5] earlier on. As we will see, if our opponents play in this sneaky way, they can actually give us the most problems. Black needs to wait for us to commit our bishop to [e2] before playing ...[c5] since our classic response to ...[c5] is [Bf1]-[b5]. If we carry on with [b3] and [Bb2], then the computer insists we are just slightly worse. And while it is always possible to squeeze water from a stone, I did not want to spend ages to show we could get to boring equal endgames. If you like the queenside fianchetto enough and want to gamble that your opponent won't know to delay ...[c5] until after we've committed our bishop, then feel free to go for it in a similar spirit to the other chapters. The good news is: first off from 2.Nf3 , only 2% of Black players go for this. Here we have a very interesting rarely tried move. The one weak point of the bishop's placement on [f5] is that it gives us a tempo if we can achieve [e3]-[e4]. Can you guess what we should play????} 4. Nc3 $1 {The chances of your opponent having gone for this are very small so I'll keep the variations relatively brief. Suffice it to say that [Nc3] has only been seen in 4200 games at the time of writing. For a position on move 4, that is extremely low! We will try to throw in [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4] quickly. Our knight has cleared the [b1]-square so we only need to play [Bd2] and [Qe2] to castle queenside − this will be a recurring idea as well.} e6 {This move enjoys the most popularity, being played in 59% of games.} 5. d3 {Simple chess. We stunt the [f5]-bishop and prepare ideas of [Qe2] and [e3]-[e4]; [Ne5] and [g4] might also be an idea.} Bb4 {The pin is the most popular, with 32% of games going for it.} 6. a3 {Will the bishop trade or not?} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 {We are fine with the doubled c-pawns. They are not particularly vulnerable and the dark-squared bishop was Black's best asset.} O-O 8. Be2 c5 9. O-O Nc6 10. a4 $13 {[%cal Gc1a3,Yd1e1,Ye1g3,Yg3h4,Gh2h3,Gg2g4] Our bishops looked a bit ugly, but they are getting better by the second! We will move our bishop from [c1] to [a3]. We can then think of improving our position by transferring our queen to the kingside via [e1]-[g3] or [e1]-[h4]. An idea for pawn play could be to advance [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4] to begin harassing the [f5]-bishop. Things are equal, and White has a good share of chances.} *

