1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {Now we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This setup was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 Bd6 {This is played 15% of the time. The bishop fights more directly against White's control over the [e5]-square, but this scheme seems slightly awkward. The black pawn will likely come to [c5] at some point and that formation is traditionally best paired with a bishop on [e7]. By blocking the d-file, it will be hard for Black to push for ...[d5]-[d4], which is a common idea in other lines.} 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Rg1 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] This move is a rarity and the resulting position has only been reached 24 times. It will certainly take your opponent by surprise. Buckle up, it's gonna be a bumpy ride.} Nc6 {It makes sense to bring in pieces to fight for the center in an attempt to fight White's attack with the g-pawn.} 7. g4 {Already Black's back is up against the wall. In real games, Black has yet to find the proper response.} Re8 {Preparing the thematic ...[e6]-[e5] push. If given time to play this move, Black will be in the driver's seat.} 8. g5 {Encroaching on Black's camp. The [f6]-knight is kicked from its nice position.} Ne4 9. d3 Nc5 10. d4 {The natural progression has turned the position into a Stonewall that's very favorable for us.} Ne4 11. Nbd2 $16 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf1d3] White will play [Bd3] and force Black to trade off the one well-placed knight. The impressive pawn phalanx will leave the rest of Black's pieces cramped. We are playing a Stonewall up several tempi; the achievement of [g4]-[g5] gives us great control over [e4], as Black can never play ...[f7]-[f5] on pain of en passant.} *

