1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {Now we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This setup was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Be7 {This seems to be the most testing, even though it has only been chosen in 33% of games.} 6. Bb5+ Nbd7 {Quite a rare continuation, at a frequency of 9%. But any move that avoids the structural weakening after ...[Nc6] [Bxc6]+ must be investigated. Black's move rates surprisingly high, with the computer intuiting that Black has a slight edge after perfect play. Fortunately for us, we are not interested in proving an objective advantage with 30 moves of opening theory. We want to enter a chaotic maze that only we will know the way out of.} (6... Nc6 {is played a third of the time but just transposes to 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Be7 .}) 7. Bd3 $3 {Perhaps this doesn't deserve 2 exclamation marks but what can I say, I love it. It is objectively sound and it has been played in only 5 games out of 2548. This means that it will have the effect of a novelty against the vast majority of your opponents. The move carries a unique beauty. We didn't go to [d3] immediately because the knight could have harassed it via [c6]-[b4]. Here, on the other hand, the knight is farther away. We will scope the kingside with our two bishops on [d3] and [b2]. Because our [d2]-pawn can't move, we will avert away from the classic plan of [d2]-[d3] and [Nb1]-[d2] and instead opt for [Nc3] with more sophisticated knight transfers in mind.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc5c4] With the not so subtle idea of advancing ...[b7]-[b5] and then to gradually evict our fancy bishop with ...[c5]-[c4].} (7... b6 8. O-O O-O {will just transpose to 7...O-O 8.O-O b6 .}) 8. c4 $1 O-O 9. O-O b6 {It's always natural once the knight comes to [d7] to aim for [b7] with the bishop.} 10. Qc2 Bb7 11. Nc3 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb2g7,Yc3e2,Ye2g3] The position is unbelievably tense and is one in which experience will make all the difference. It seems that neither side is eager to trade in the center. We should aim to solve the issue of our [c3]-knight's disharmony with the bishop on [b2] and seek to reroute it over to the kingside via [e2]-[g3]. Depending on what happens, flicking in [f4]-[f5] could unsettle the black [e6]-pawn enough into helping us usurp control over the important [d5]-square.} *

