1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {Now we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This setup was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Be7 {This seems to be the most testing, even though it has only been chosen in 33% of games.} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 ({This is the natural and overwhelming popular continuation being chosen in 57% of games.} 6... Nc6 {is played a third of the time but just transposes to 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Be7 .}) 7. Bxd7+ {This might seem to simplify, but we are left with good pieces and a seriously asymmetrical structure. White should have full chances in the upcoming struggle.} Nbxd7 {This is by far the most popular recapture at a frequency of 80%. Taking with the queen is also reasonable and we'll look at that as well.} 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 $1 {This is only played in 2% of games and yet it leads to the most asymmetrical double-edged situations. It is also objectively fine and Stockfish even considers it slightly better than the super-popular [d3]. The suggested move is the perfect remedy for using against the opponent who is better versed in the main lines.} (9. d3 {is common here, but I don't like allowing our opponent so much space on the queenside. After} b5 {, Black's play is very simple and straightforward. Black will simply march up the queenside with the a-, b-, and c-pawns. The position objectively remains level but Black's game is easier.}) 9... dxc4 $2 {This is the most popular move and it's just a mistake. We will happily take back on [c4], ridding Black permanently of the essential d-pawn.} 10. bxc4 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gd1e2] We will analyze several variations from here but I'd like to mention some things at this point. We have an extra d-pawn and they have an extra b-pawn. This is the biggest imbalance in the position and signifies our biggest claim to an advantage. We can always play [d3] to shore up the last uncovered square in the center, [e4]. The black knight on [d7] is seriously restricted and its best long-term plan is to burn two moves to return to the natural [c6]-square via [b8]. Our queen will likely end up on [e2]. While advancing [e4]-[e5] might look appealing, it will usually do more harm than good by blocking our [b2]-bishop, [f3]-knight, and weakening our [d4]-square.} Nb6 $6 {[%csl Rb6] This is obviously not the right square for the knight, but we must be accurate in how we respond to it.} 11. Qc2 $14 {We should keep an eye out for ...[Na4] and so this is a better square for the queen than [e2]. The knight is not well placed. We want to play [d3] but that will be met by a discomforting ...[Ng4] check the line with 11.d3 so we will play [a4] first to cover the [a4]-square and potentially throw in [a4]-[a5] and then [d2]-[d3].} (11. d3 $2 Ng4 {and our [e3]-pawn is vulnerable. Black is waiting for us to move the queen to protect the pawn with [Qd2] or [Qe2], when Black will be able to bother our bishop with ...[Na4].}) *

