1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {Now we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This setup was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd6e5] A rare continuation that makes some sense. The ...[e6]-[e5] break is always thematic if it's properly supported.} 6. g4 $5 {Going for all the glory. Yet again we see a completely sound [g2]-[g4] that has barely ever been played 47 games. While the position remains dynamically balanced, I consider getting to these positions a psychological victory. This is not the type of game Black was looking to get when they chose this calm setup. 62% of Black players chose either to capture on [g4] or castle here.} O-O {This move has been played in 30% of games but it is already a serious inaccuracy. You can probably guess what we're gonna play...} 7. g5 $1 Ne4 $2 {Believe it or not, this blunder is executed in 76% of games.} 8. d3 {[%csl Re4] The black knight has run short of squares and is in quite the pickle.} Qa5+ 9. c3 $18 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd3e4] Making sure not to allow the [e4]-steed to trade for anything worthwhile. White is just winning due to the piece we are about to collect.} *

