1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {Now we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This setup was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd6e5] A rare continuation that makes some sense. The ...[e6]-[e5] break is always thematic if it's properly supported.} 6. g4 $5 {Going for all the glory. Yet again we see a completely sound [g2]-[g4] that has barely ever been played 47 games. While the position remains dynamically balanced, I consider getting to these positions a psychological victory. This is not the type of game Black was looking to get when they chose this calm setup. 62% of Black players chose either to capture on [g4] or castle here.} Nxg4 {Black willingly steps into the jungle. The journey out will be grueling and treacherous and there will only be room for one of the players to escape. This is a perfect situation for us, as we will likely be exponentially better prepared for the coming chaos.} 7. Rg1 f5 {A natural move to defend the knight and stop the bleeding on the g-file.} (7... Nf6 8. Rxg7 {± and White's bishop dominates the diagonal while White's rook weighs down on the kingside. An important note is that ...[Rg8] will often be met by [Bxf6], attacking the black queen while removing the defender of the [g8]-rook.}) 8. h3 {Booting the knight out. We want to break through on [g7] with the rook, not the bishop.} Nf6 9. Rxg7 Nc6 10. Bb5 Bd7 11. Ng5 $18 {[%csl Gb2,Gb5,Rf6,Gg5,Gg7][%cal Gg5f7,Gb2f6,Gd1h5] Whether or not this position is even tenable, it is obvious Black is under enormous discomfort. We have every reason to be satisfied with the opening. White's pieces dominate and the threat of [Nf7] or [Bxf6] followed by [Qh5] will likely decide shortly.} *

