. It will take a lot of work from Black to kick our knight out of this natural square.} Qc7 {The computer insists the position is only marginally better for White, but I cannot help feeling there is an enormous practical edge. Black's bishop on [c8] is awful and there is no straightforward way to remedy it. The computer recommendation in this position is for Black to sacrifice the pawn with ...[c5]-[c4] almost immediately, with the aim of opening several diagonals.} (8... Qb6 9. c4 {will follow a similar trajectory to 8...Qc7. Black's queen is just comparatively worse placed and will have to waste a move after White's thematic knight transfer from [c3] to [a4].}) 9. c4 {We immediately shut out any opportunities of ...[c5]-[c4]. While it may be slightly less of an advantage than castling, it seems very playable and simple. I'll leave you with a few lines to show how play could develop.} O-O 10. O-O {Black must challenge the [e5]-knight immediately. Other tries don't trouble White in the slightest.} a5 {The idea of this move is to get in ...[a5]-[a4] at some point and undermine our structure, thereby opening the game for the dormant bishops.} 11. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3a4] Fortunately for us, our knight will come to [a4], blocking the a-pawn indefinitely. Black's last move appears to have been just a waste of time.} *

