n exchange immediately or play slower with [O-O]. I investigated both options.} 9. Nxc6 {After serious deliberation I chose to go with this move.} (9. O-O O-O 10. d3 {, I like the idea of keeping the position tense but after a precise move by Black, we will have to rethink things.} Be8 $1 {⩱ , Black will play ...[Nd7], trade our knight off and then play ...[f7]-[f6] to stunt our bishop and ...[b7]-[b5], ...[c5]-[c4], etc., to expand on the queenside. White is still in the fight, but this is a White repertoire after all and this position is undoubtedly better for Black, making it hard to recommend. Fortunately, in contrast to this position, the course recommendation gets good play and reaches a position with good chances.}) 9... bxc6 {We inflicted the doubled pawns on Black, but this is their best version of the situation. The [e7]-bishop already cushions the pressure on [f6], freeing the queen to move without having to worry about responding to [Bxf6] with ...[gxf6]. The computer insists things are dead equal, but I'm confident Black's position is the more difficult of the two to play.} 10. Nc3 {I really like this move because of how unorthodox it is. The classic setup is [d2]-[d3], [Nd2] and [Nf3]. Here, [Nc3] is more unnatural, but it's objectively just as strong as the aforementioned plan. Meanwhile, we are keeping things as chaotic as possible so that our opponent is more likely to slip up. It is only played 4% of the time making it extremely likely that our opponents have never seen it before. The good news is that most Black players immediately start making strategically dubious moves like ...[d5]-[d4]. The following variations depict a foggy forest in which both players wander through − a contest ensues between them as to who can stumble less. Paying careful attention to these lines will serve as the flashlight of knowledge to guide us through the unknown.} O-O 11. O-O d4 {This is far and away the most popular move in this position with 52% of Black players opting for it. We should smile whenever we see it, as it wrecks Black's structure irreparably and gives us an easy edge.} 12. Nb1 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Rc5,Rc6][%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c4,Gc4e5] Our knight will glide to [a3] and then to [c4] where it will blockade the weak black c-pawns and target the tender [e5]-square. Notice that with our bishop on [b2], the transfer to [c4] via [a4]-[b2]-[c4] will take a bit longer and so in this case we choose the path from the knight's original footing, [b1].} *

