diately brings the fight to the implanted knight.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. d3 {While Stockfish is adamant that the situation is level, such positions are like the many others in this course − full of ideas that allow the player with more experience and a better grasp on the position to achieve victory.} O-O 11. O-O {We both decide that it’s time to castle.} Re8 {Here [Nd2] is played in the vast majority of games. We want to beckon our opponent into foggy terrain, and so we should opt for other ideas whenever they're of equivalent strength.} 12. Qf3 {This is played only 4% of the time.} e5 {We will not trade on [e5] here, as our [e3]-pawn would simply end up a target after all the exchanges. Instead, we will play calmly − Black isn't threatening anything yet.} 13. Nd2 {This position has only been reached 16 times. I will cover the 4 most frequent continuations of this limited sample.} e4 {Black can't resist advancing the pawn and digging into our territory. But our bishop which can again scan the full board isn't complaining!} 14. Qg3 d4 {[%cal Gd4e3,Ge4d3] Black threatens a violent resolution on the e- and d-files, but we can simply develop our last piece in anticipation of it.} ({After} 14... exd3 15. cxd3 {↑ , White can think about playing [Rae1] and [e4]-[e5] in the coming moves. White is the one in the driver's seat.}) 15. Rae1 $13 {[%csl Gb2,Rd4,Ge1,Re4,Gf1][%cal Ge3d4,Gd3e4] I have to end the variation at some point. The pawn tension will resolve rather soon, when White's activity makes our position preferable.} *

