1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Whenever we see the knight here we should look to pin immediately.} 4. Bb5 Nf6 $6 {Allowing the doubling of the c-pawns is a no no here.} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. b3 {This will likely transpose to the French chapter unless Black immediately throws the bishop out of the pawn chain.} Bg4 {This is dubious. Black pins the knight on [f3] and prepares to exchange there if harassed by [h3]. The problem is that we already got a similar exchange on [c6] except with the bonus of wrecking Black's pawns.} 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 {Black hasn't gotten any structural concession out of us. We should be comfortably better with simple play. The only choice that remains is whether to put the bishop on [e7] or [g7].} e6 9. Bb2 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 {This might look ugly, but the knight could go to [a4] to target [c5] or support [e3]-[e4].} d4 {This an extremely popular idea by Black players in this position. It doesn't work out for them though, as we will see!} 12. Na4 {Pressing upon the [c5]-weakness. We would like for nothing more than for Black to trade on [e3], when we can recapture with the d-pawn. Any such resolution of the pawn tension will leave Black with a hideous structure on the queenside.} Qd5 {The most common move in this position. Perhaps Black never received the memo. Black's structure is awful so they shouldn't be seeking the endgame.} 13. Rae1 {[%cal Ge3e4] Preparing [e3]-[e4].} Qxf3 14. Rxf3 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gb2d4,Ge3d4] There is enormous pressure on [d4].} Rad8 15. exd4 cxd4 {We fix the black pawns for the moment...} 16. f5 $16 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ge1e7,Gf5e6] Just to break them again!} *

