1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {We will deal now with Black's attempts to go for a combination of a kingside fianchetto with ...[d5] and ...[c5]. While it's very rare at lower levels, this mixing of ...[d7]-[d5] with ...[g6]-[g7] is extremely common among the elite. Every time I play a GM or IM in Titled Tuesday they play it with only rare exceptions.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... g6 {Black abandons all notions of the French setup, placing confidence in the kingside Fianchetto instead.} 5. Bb2 Bg7 {We now face a difficult decision: where to place our bishop?? Its goal was to pin the [c6]-knight from [b5] but Black has correctly delayed the development of the [b8]-knight for as long as possible. We must make do without the pin and instead, settle for another natural square.} 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Nc6 {Black's knight smirks as it enters the ring. Our bishop would look like a fool to burn another move to go to [b5] now.} 8. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] Our knight enters the center.} Qc7 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 (9... bxc6 {wouldn't make any sense − what was the point of ...[Qc7] then?!?!} 10. Be5 {⩲ , we will play [Nc3], and perhaps [Na4] to target [c5] if the moment is right. Our queen will go to [e1] and onward to [g3] or [h4] and our bishop will go to [d3]. We have a nice edge due to the better structure.}) 10. Bf3 {[%cal Gf3c6,Gb2g7] Our bishops are impressive.} Bf5 11. d3 {[%cal Gd1e2,Gb1d2,Ge3e4] Preparing [Qe2], [Nd2] and [e3]-[e4].} Rfd8 12. Qe2 $132 {[%cal Gb1d2,Ge3e4] The game is level with chances for both sides. White has the nicer bishops and simpler game, being able to play for [e4] with [Nb1]-[d2].} *

