1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} (3. e3 {We will now cover the less popular third moves for Black. They tend to be weaker than the top moves} Nf6 {and 3...Bg4 .}) 3... e5 {As wacky as this looks, it is played 9% of the time.} 4. fxe5 Bg4 {The most popular move being essayed 49% of the time. Fortunately for us, we are just better with straightforward moves. As we will see, it is much more difficult than it appears for Black to regain the [e5]-pawn.} ({After} 4... f6 {, now} 5. Bb5 {or 5.exf6 might be slightly objectively stronger, but we can just transpose back to positions we know from 3...f6 & 4...e5 with 5.d4!}) 5. Bb5 $1 {Pinning the knight. Black has two moves to keep White's advantage manageable but in practice, they both receive minimal attention. Instead, Black's most popular tries are all further errors.} a6 {This is most popular in spite of being very dubious. We'll happily chop on [c6].} (5... Bxf3 $2 6. Qxf3 Qd7 7. d4 {and we are a healthy pawn up.}) 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. O-O {[%csl Ge5] Black is nowhere close to encircling the [e5]-pawn − the knight would take 2 moves to get to [g6] and there is no clear way for the [f8]-bishop to target it. Black is also behind in development, making their position close to lost.} Ne7 8. h3 {Calling the bishop's bluff.} Be6 {Now that the challenge to the [f3]-knight has been removed, the stability of our [e5]-pawn is beyond question. We will be able to maintain it easily.} (8... Bxf3 $2 9. Qxf3 {, defending [f7] puts Black in quite the conundrum.}) 9. Nc3 Ng6 10. b3 Be7 11. Bb2 $16 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc3a4,Gb2d4] We will grip onto the weak [c5]-square with [Na4] and [Bd4]. Black is down a pawn with a worse position and worse pieces. We are close to winning.} *

