1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} (3. e3 {We will now cover the less popular third moves for Black. They tend to be weaker than the top moves} Nf6 {and 3...Bg4 .}) 3... Bf5 {The bishop does little here but just the same it is played 14% of the time. It is worse than ...[Bg4] for a few reasons. First, it doesn't inconvenience our [f3]-knight in any way. Second, our knight can go to [d4] in certain instances and attack the bishop perhaps with a double attack against a [c6]-pawn gaining a free tempo. The one small advantage of the bishop's placement on [f5] over [g4] is that White doesn't have a way to immediately harass the bishop with [h2]-[h3].} 4. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Pinning the knight and immediately creating ideas of [Bxc6] to ruin Black's structure. We will look at Black's 6 most popular moves.} e6 5. Bxc6+ {We are happy to take and inflict the classic doubling on Black's structure.} bxc6 6. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] Our bishop will go to [b2] and lay siege to the long diagonal.} Nf6 {The most popular move and the most natural.} 7. Bb2 {Our long-term strategy is to play for one of a few plans. First [Nf3]-[e5] might be an option to attack [c6] and threaten an intrusive [Ne5]-[c6]. From [e5] our knight also supports [g2]-[g4], which might become opportune if Black doesn't take adequate care of the [f5]-bishop. Second and more commonly, we will play for a slow [e3]-[e4] after preparations involving [d2]-[d3], [Nbd2], and [Qe2].} Bd6 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 {Notice we are not committing to the kingside with our king yet. There might very well be a moment when it makes more sense to castle queenside. In the meantime, we will play [Qe2] and either [e3]-[e4] or [Nf3]-[e5] to increase the tension. Black sorely misses the [c6]-knight, as without it, achieving the ...[e6]-[e5] push is nearly impossible.} c5 {It's interesting... This move makes a lot of intuitive sense since it moves a relatively useless [c6]-pawn to [c5] where it fights for the important [d4]-square. Even so, it is a slight mistake according to the computer. I believe it comes down to the fact that it blocks the [d6]-bishop completely along the [a3]-[f8] diagonal. Black's options will henceforth be limited in this capacity. We should take care to keep our knight on [d2]. If it moves, then Black will begin to have opportunities to sacrifice ...[c5]-[c4] to self-destruct our beautiful pawn structure.} (9... Ng4 {is the most popular here, but I can't really understand it.} 10. Qe2 {± , we protect [e3] and are about to castle queenside and play [e3]-[e4] and [h2]-[h3] with many free tempi. The ...[Ng4] intrusion hasn't accomplished anything for Black.}) 10. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5] Now [e3]-[e4] and [e4]-[e5] threaten to win a minor piece.} Bg4 {Sidestepping the [e4] bounty. White should happily take the bishop pair back.} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 {[%cal Ge3e4] We will play [e4] with great tension in the center.} (12. Nxf3 $2 {is not accurate because the knight should have stayed on [d2] to cover ...[c5]-[c4]. For instance, Black can now play} a5 {, threatening ...[a5]-[a4] with some nice tension for Black on the queenside. After} 13. a4 c4 {∞ , White might be winning a pawn, but the structure will undoubtedly take on some weaknesses in the process. Black is doing fine.}) 12... a5 13. e4 $16 {[%csl Yc4,Rd6,Rf6][%cal Ge4e5,Yd5d4,Yd2c4] Black faces an uncomfortable dilemma: [e4]-[e5] looms and so Black will have to move a minor piece back now or trade on [e4] when we will recapture with [dxe4]. After retreating, what can Black hope to play for? Pushing ...[d5]-[d4] gives us a great outpost on [c4] for the [d2]-knight. Trading on [e4] just lets White take back with [dxe4], when the black c-pawns are extremely ugly. It is easy to see the drawbacks to Black's ...[c6]-[c5] advance, as the [d6]-bishop is completely locked in.} *

