diately slip on the [c4]-banana peel and can't make it to move 10 with equality.} (5. c4 {Two moves keep the game level:} a6 {and 5...d4 .}) (5. h3 $6 {might seem like an interesting way to transpose to positions reached in the chapter on 2...Nf6 3.e3 Bg4 . After 5...Bxf3 6.Qxf3 , Black doesn't have to switch back to those positions with ...[Nf6]. Instead, Black can play more forcefully with 6...a6 ( 6...O-O-O!? could also be interesting. ) 7.Bxc6+ Qxc6 , when White has to deal with the threat to [c2]. 8.Nc3 e6 and Black's position carries a latent poison associated with routing the knight to [f5]. 9.O-O Nh6 10.d3 Nf5 ∓ , Black will castle queenside and play ...[h7]-[h5]. The knight stands fantastic on [f5]. If it is harassed by [e3]-[e4], it will glide into [d4], while if it is attacked by [g2]-[g4], it will simply retreat, when White has weakened the kingside too much.}) 5... dxc4 {This is the most popular move played against our central lunge, having been chosen 31% of the time.} 6. Na3 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ga3c4] We plan to recapture with [Na3xc4] with tempo against the queen on [d6]. This has only been played once thus far, yet it poses enormous practical problems for Black. Black only has one precise way to fight for equality and it involves getting the [g8]-knight to [e7] before the bishop on [f8] comes out − not obvious by any means!} (6. Bxc4 $6 {is the most played, but it's just a mistake. It allows Black speedy development and a quick ...[e7]-[e5] as evidenced by the following sample variation.} O-O-O 7. O-O e5 $1 8. fxe5 $2 {This opens the game up even more for Black.} Nxe5 {, White is left with two very ugly hanging pawns on [d2] and [e3]. They are both on open files for the opponent so they will always be targets for the remainder of the game.}) 6... O-O-O 7. Qa4 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5c6,Ga3c4] White will take on [c4] and then split open the queenside pawns with [Bxc6] and a queen trade if Black recaptures with the queen.} Qd5 8. Bxc6 Qxc6 9. Qxc6 bxc6 10. Ne5 $16 {[%csl Rc4,Rc6,Rf7,Rg4] A quadruple fork! We will recollect our pawn investment on [c4] shortly and can pressure [c6] with [Nc4]-[a5] and an eventual [Rc1]. The computer insists White's advantage is not decisive yet, but my intuition tells me otherwise. :} *

