1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} e6 {This is opted for 8% of the time and so is worth looking at as well.} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} ({I prefer this move over the more popular} 5. Bxc6+ {. We are preparing to place our bishop on [b2]. In this position, it makes sense to wait before executing [Bxc6]. At the moment, the knight isn't going anywhere, and if Black plays ...[Bd7] later, then this combination of 4...e6 with a later ...[Bd7] seems like a worse version of 4...Bd7 .}) 5... Bd6 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O a6 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Ne5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ge5c6]} Bxe5 {Played most often, but this is just a strategic blunder. Black will sorely miss the dark-squared protector.} 10. fxe5 {[%csl Rf6] Digging the knight out of [f6].} Nd7 11. Qg4 $36 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gb1d2,Gd2f3,Gf3g5,Gf1f3,Gf3g3,Ga1f1] And we can get goin' on the kingside. We can play [d2]-[d3] and transfer our knight via [b1]-[d2]-[f3]-[g5] where it can combine with [Qh5] for dangerous threats. We can also amp up the pressure with our rooks lifting one from [f1]-[f3]-[g3] and bringing the other one on [a1] over to [f1] to keep control over the f-file. Black's position is awful with no counterplay whatsoever to go for.} *

