1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} Bd7 {The most popular response. The black bishop counters the pin and prepares ...[a6], when Black won't have to suffer any break in the structure.} 5. O-O {The most popular move. There is no reason to execute the exchange on [c6] yet. We will leave our bishop there as long as possible and only after Black invests a tempo to prod it with ...[a7]-[a6], will we consider the trade. Depending on how things shake out, we may even see the bishop simply retreat to [d3] in search of more relevant pressure on the opponent's kingside.} a6 {(This is the most popular move 44% compared to 5...e6 , which is seen 43% though it doesn't make complete sense.) (Black's position isn't good enough to merit spending two tempi ...[Bd7] and ...[a7]-[a6] on the white bishop. Here, the vast majority of players have captured on [c6], which is understandable, but there's actually a much stronger opportunity...)} 6. Be2 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc2c4] This move carries the strong idea of a quick [b2]-[b3], [c2]-[c4], and [Bb2]. If White achieves this setup, we will have a healthy control of the center with [c4] and [f4] working in tandem to control [d5] and [e5]. Black's structure will come under a lot of pressure, as the knight on [c6] blocks the c-pawn and bishop on [d7], but moving it will allow White's [f3]-knight into [e5]. While the computer rates these positions as close to equal, they carry a very spicy practicality to them. From my perspective as a grandmaster, I can honestly say I wouldn't be certain what strategic plan to go for from here as Black. It's that uncertainty that gives me confidence this will work wonders at lower levels.} (6. Bxc6 Bxc6 7. Ne5 {does seem to put White in the driver's seat, as White scores an impressive 59% from this position. But if Black responds accurately with} Bd7 $1 {, things are not so clear. Black aims to play ...[Bf5], ...[e7]-[e6], and ...[Nd7].}) 6... e6 {From the 1500 or so games that reached this position, 55% of Black players essayed this.} 7. b3 Bd6 {This has seen the most popularity with 39% of games following this path.} 8. Bb2 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gb2e5,Gf4e5,Gf3e5] Clamping down on the [e5]-square.} O-O 9. c4 {White is only slightly better objectively, but our position is so much more comfortable. Black's pieces evoke a sense of confusion and ambiguity. The bishop on [d7] is weak and Black has nothing to play for in the center. The [e5]-square is firmly under White's control. 68 games have reached this position and yet not one player has found the most accurate move here. It is important to fix the faulty knight on [c6], which obstructs the bishop and c-pawn.} Re8 {[%cal Ge6e5] With the sensible idea of preparing ...[e6]-[e5]; if Black is able to do this, Black will likely liquidate our strong f-pawn and even have good chances of seizing the initiative. A situation could easily arise in which we're left with hanging pawns on [d2] and [e3].} (9... dxc4 {, we are always happy to see this, as it lets us gain greater control over the center. After} 10. bxc4 {⩲ , we will play [d2]-[d4] shortly with an overwhelming center.}) 10. d4 $1 {[%cal Re6e5,Gd4e5,Gf4e5] Shutting down any hopes of ...[e6]-[e5]. This move notably weakens the [e4]-square so it is worth noting how to deal with the knight hop.} Ne4 11. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2e4] We want to trade and then put our other knight on [d2] or [e5].} f5 (11... f6 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nd2 f5 14. a3 {± is simply the same type of position that we get after 11...f5 , only with Black having wasted another move on ...[f7]-[f6].}) 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Nd2 Bf8 14. a3 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gc4c5,Gd2c4] White can expand on the queenside slowly while Black is left without counterplay. Some ideas are [b3]-[b4] or [c4]-[c5] followed by [Nd2]-[c4]; [d4]-[d5] to open our [b2]-bishop is another idea that might become strong at some point.} *

