1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} Bd7 {The most popular response. The black bishop counters the pin and prepares ...[a6], when Black won't have to suffer any break in the structure.} 5. O-O {The most popular move. There is no reason to execute the exchange on [c6] yet. We will leave our bishop there as long as possible and only after Black invests a tempo to prod it with ...[a7]-[a6], will we consider the trade. Depending on how things shake out, we may even see the bishop simply retreat to [d3] in search of more relevant pressure on the opponent's kingside.} e6 6. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] The bishop will be fianchettoed on [b2] in classic Bird style.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5,Ge7][%cal Gd6e5,Gd8e7] The most popular continuation, with 27% of Black players choosing it. This move makes intuitive sense. It fights for [e5] and keeps the [e7]-square available for the black queen.} (6... a6 {is the second most popular with 23% of games opting for it.} 7. Be2 {transposes to the 5...a6 variation.}) 7. Bb2 {Gripping the long diagonal.} O-O {Here only 2% of the games have found the best move.} 8. Be2 $1 {The bishop retreats and prepares [c2]-[c4] to challenge Black's center.} (8. d3 {is the most popular move here, but it doesn't hold much water. Black can immediately grab the bishop pair with ...[a7]-[a6], when they might already be in the driver's seat. After} a6 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. Ne5 Be8 {⇆ , many players would already prefer Black here. We have a good grip on the dark squares for the moment, but Black will play ...[Nd7] and ...[f7]-[f6] soon enough.}) 8... Re8 {This prepares ...[e6]-[e5] in a less committal way than ...[Qe7]. Here [d4] wouldn't be as strong since it can be met with ...[Nc6]-[e7]-[g6] or ...[Nc6]-[e7]-[f5]. For that reason, we should instead begin with the knight hop.} 9. Ne5 (9. Ne5 {The computer lines are very unnatural, which is a great sign. Even though White is only slightly better, all of the moves recommended by Stockfish are counterintuitive. Options 2-4 are} Ne7 {, 9...a6 , and 9...a5 . The top option is 9...Rf8 , LOL! This is exactly what we want to see, as we are not playing supercomputers, but humans who use logic and will not decide on most of these.}) 9... Bxe5 {At grandmaster level, this type of exchange is considered an amateur mistake, but it may very well be seen at lower levels so let's take a look!} 10. fxe5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Ge5f6]} Ne4 11. d3 {Booting the knight!} Nc5 12. Bh5 $1 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gh5f7] Scoping [f7] and encouraging ...[g7]-[g6], which would weaken the dark squares surrounding the black king.} g6 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7,Rh6]} (12... Rf8 13. Ba3 b6 14. d4 {+- and White will scoop up at least an exchange.}) 13. Qf3 Qe7 (13... gxh5 14. Qxh5 {is also covered, of course. To see how the attack unfolds, check the relevant section.}) 14. Qg3 {[%csl Gf6,Rf7][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f3,Gf1f6] White's attack will play itself. We will transfer the knight via [d2] to [f3] and further to [g5] potentially. We will use the [f6]-square to install the [f1]-rook and will bring the other rook to [f1] to pressure the weak [f7]-pawn more. White is winning.} *

