1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} g6 {This is played 2% of the time as a 2nd move. This frequency is good for us because Stocky gives some of the most unfavorable evaluations you'll see in the entire Bird's opening. I didn't know it even existed but in several Titled Tuesdays, I kept getting hit by it. So here we are grinding our teeth against the silicon beast looking for good playable positions.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Bg7 {Fianchettoing immediately is by far the most popular.} 4. c4 $1 {Flipping the script on Black and surprising their surprise. Only 2697 games have reached this position − keep in mind it's just move 4. We challenge [d5] and immediately begin asking Black some questions. Black needs to follow a precise path to pose any problems − the chances of this happening in a practical game are 0.} c6 {This is chosen in 36% of games.} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. d4 $1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gb1c3,Gf1d3,Ge1g1] What was meant to be the pride of Black's position, the [g7]-bishop is pointed into stone. White has adopted a good Stonewall in which we have easy development. We will play [Nc3], [Bd3], and [O-O]. While our dark-squared bishop is normally a big problem, here we can place it on [d2] where it will be arguably just as relevant as its counterpart on [g7].} Nc6 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O {[%cal Gc1d2,Gf3e5] We can play [Bd2] and [Ne5]. We will focus our attention on the open c-file. White has a small but comfortable edge. The classically weak [e4]-square is under our control.} *

