1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} c6 {This is chosen 3% of the time. Black immediately reinforces the [d5]-pawn in spite of it not yet being challenged by White.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Bg4 {The chances of this transposing into some form of the ...[Bg4] variations analyzed in the main chapters is high. So the coverage of these positions will be limited.} 4. Be2 {Our bishop cushions the pin. We are happy to meet ...[Bxf3] with [Bxf3].} Nf6 (4... e6 5. O-O Nf6 6. b3 Nbd7 7. c4 {will likely transpose to the 4…Nf6 variation.}) ({After} 4... Bxf3 5. Bxf3 {⇆ , we get the bishop pair but the position is still level since Black will play ...[e7]-[e6] erecting a structure perfectly against our light-squared bishop. We will castle kingside and then play for our pick of [c2]-[c4], [d2]-[d4], or [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4].}) 5. O-O Nbd7 (5... Nbd7 {Here} 6. c4 {and 6.b3 are both given as best by Stocky. I'd prefer the queenside fianchetto, as it carries similar ideas to the rest of our repertoire.}) 6. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} e6 7. c4 (7. Bb2 $6 {is slightly inaccurate due to} Bd6 {, when Black has a strong plan of ...[Qe7] and ...[e6]-[e5].}) 7... Bd6 8. Nc3 {With pressure against [d5] so that Black can't just play ...[Qe7] and ...[e5]. The position is level. We can play [Bb2] or [d2]-[d4] and [Bd2]; [Nd4] could make sense to welcome a trade on [e2] and recapture with our queen.} *

