1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {Here White can try} 5. d4 {, 5.d3 , or 5.Bc4 , but I like a more unique move in the vein of the rest of the course.}) 5. Bb5 {What a strange position! After [Bb5] we are playing a Rossolimo Sicilian with [f2]-[f4] thrown in, a Rossolimo Grand Prix if you will! This position has only been reached around 61 thousand times in the database and keep in mind most of those started from Sicilians.} (5. Bb5 {If you get this from the Bird, there is a good chance your opponent will be completely on their own from this position. The most common moves are} e6 {and 5...a6 . We will look at the top 4 moves played in this position.}) 5... a6 {This leads to fine versions of the Rossolimo. As mentioned in other variations, the inclusion of [f2]-[f4] will be to our benefit after the ensuing exchange.} 6. Bxc6 bxc6 7. d3 {Solidifying our pawn and light squares. We need to play carefully with our pawns. It's essential to be able to play [e4]-[e5] to stunt the [g7]-bishop, and [c3]-[c4] to build concrete against the light-squared bishop should it move to [a6] or [e6]. Neither of these pawn pushes is mandatory and should not be rushed recklessly, but we do need to keep them as options as the middlegame twists and turns − they will be essential for handling Black's bishop pair.} d5 {[%csl Rc5] This is most popular, but it seriously jeopardizes the stability of the [c5]-pawn.} 8. Be3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge3c5] Targeting the weakness. Here Black has tried 3 moves, all of which give us a big advantage.} dxe4 {The queen trade just leads to an endgame full of weaknesses for the Black player.} 9. dxe4 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Nf6 11. Nbd2 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Rc5][%cal Gd1c2,Yd2b3,Yb3c5,Gd2c4] The pawn on [c5] is extremely weak and if Black plays ...[Nd7], we can target it further with [Nb3]. Another advantage is that our knights have a great outpost on the [c4]-square. Our king will sit well on [c2]. It is the endgame after all so not being castled is not an issue of safety.} *

