1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {Here White can try} 5. d4 {, 5.d3 , or 5.Bc4 , but I like a more unique move in the vein of the rest of the course.}) 5. Bb5 {What a strange position! After [Bb5] we are playing a Rossolimo Sicilian with [f2]-[f4] thrown in, a Rossolimo Grand Prix if you will! This position has only been reached around 61 thousand times in the database and keep in mind most of those started from Sicilians.} (5. Bb5 {If you get this from the Bird, there is a good chance your opponent will be completely on their own from this position. The most common moves are} e6 {and 5...a6 . We will look at the top 4 moves played in this position.}) 5... e6 $2 {This is just a positional mistake. Just like I mentioned in another variation, Black's 'M' formation on the kingside with pawns on [e6] and [g6] just doesn't cut it. There are weaknesses on the dark squares: [d6] and [e7].} 6. Bxc6 {It's the perfect time to cash in on [c6]. We double the opponent's pawns and Black will be left with one of the worst light-squared bishops imaginable.} bxc6 {Compared to after ...[dxc6], the [c8]-bishop has at least some hope of finding relevance on [a6].} ({After} 6... dxc6 7. d3 {, (we've gotten a Rossolimo Sicilian with the inclusion of [f2]-[f4]. This is a brilliant improvement since [e4]-[e5] is a thematic way to shut their bishop out, and here it will be solidified in concrete. We will aim to keep both bishops shut out. The [c8]-bishop can still dream of a future on [a6] e6 and [c6] are locked in so this is the last option so we will also play [c3]-[c4] sooner or later. The bishops will be dead and we can improve our pieces after castling with [Nc3]-[e4]. Black is close to strategically lost.)}) 7. d3 d5 (7... Nh6 $1 {is the best move objectively, but for someone to find this is unrealistic. It has been played twice in 1725 games to reach this position. The idea is for Black to be able to aim at the [f5]-square and get ready to place a knight there in the event of ...[d7]-[d5] and of White responding with [e4]-[e5]. After} 8. Qe2 O-O 9. O-O {⩲ , White is better. We will aim to keep things as closed as possible for our knights to prosper.}) 8. e5 {[%csl Ge5,Rg7] Cutting the [g7]-bishop's scope in half. We want to keep that dragon in the cage as long as possible.} Nh6 {Aiming at the [f5]-square.} (8... Ne7 {doesn't change anything. After} 9. Be3 {, Black will be facing the same problems as in the main line.}) 9. Be3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge3c5,Gb1d2,Gd2b3,Yd1a4,Ya4a3] Black has the uncomfortable task of defending [c5]; ...[Qb6] places the queen in an uncomfortable pin, but ...[Bg7]-[f8] is also an unpleasant move to have to make. We will castle shortly and if the black knight comes to [f5], we can place our bishop on [f2], dominating the [f5]-knight's advances. If Black plays ...[d5]-[d4] here, we will not budge and instead play [Be3]-[f2]. We would then aim our knights at the weakened [e4] and [c4]-squares. It is essential to keep the diagonals closed! Black has the bishop pair so if we trade too many pawns, things could go wrong. [Qd1]-[a4]-[a3] would be an interesting maneuver to target both pawns.} *

