1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 {This is played 7% of the time, constituting Black's 5th most popular option.} 4. Bb5 {Going for Rossolimo-style pressure against the [c6]-knight. While the game is level here, Black tends to immediately err, with 80% of games seeing erroneous pawn moves in this position that allow us to advantageously chop on [c6].} e6 {This is seen 20% of the time.} 5. Bxc6 $1 {Chopping toward a pseudo-Rossolimo structure. While in the variation where Black had played ...[a7]-[a6], ...[bxc6] made little sense due to that diagonal having been obstructed by the a-pawn, here ...[dxc6] makes no sense as ...[e6] has already blocked the [c8]-bishop's path past [d7].} bxc6 6. b3 {The old reliable. Black can play ...[d5] at any point, when we return to structures analyzed in the French chapter of ...[d5] systems in the 6...[Be7] sideline. Therefore I will limit my coverage here to positions in which Black avoids this push. Of course, ...[d5] is extremely natural here and the sidelines in rejecting such an approach will take on a markedly unusual resemblance.} Be7 7. c4 $1 (7. Bb2 $6 {is surprisingly bad here.} c4 $1 {and Black will get decent compensation since when we take on [c4], they can respond with ...[Rb8], gaining a tempo on our exposed bishop. Another part of this sacrifice is that Black will be able to crunch on [c4] with ...[d5], when pawns will be traded and diagonals will be opened for their bishops.} 8. bxc4 Rb8 9. Bc3 d5 $1 {∞ . The computer insists White has a slight edge, but it looks messy and the advantage is much smaller than the one which follows the recommended 7.c4 .}) 7... d5 {This is not covered in the aforementioned French setup but play closely resembles such lines anyway. I'll leave one sample line.} 8. O-O O-O 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc3a4,Gc1a3,Gd2d3,Ge3e4,Ge4e5] Keeping the position flexible. An idea could be [Nc3]-[a4] and [Bc1]-[a3] to target [c5] or [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4]-[e5].} Bd6 {The bishop might as well fight for the [e5]-square.} 10. Qc2 Ba6 {When the bishop comes to [a6], it's time for the cement!} 11. d3 Nd7 {Black sees the writing on the wall and opens the f-pawn to fight for the contention of the [e4] and [e5]-squares with ...[f7]-[f5] and ...[f7]-[f6] respectively.} 12. e4 f5 {Attempting to get some space with a pawn on their fourth rank. But Black should have known... a pawn on the fifth rank is better than a pawn on the fourth!} 13. e5 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6][%cal Yg2g4] Encroaching further on the cramped black pieces. Both bishops are chronically blocked. We should look for a break that does not allow the roadblocks on [c5] which blocks the dark-squared bishop or [c6] which keeps the long diagonal closed to the light-squared bishop to clear, so we will slowly prepare the [g4]-break.} *

