1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 {This is played 7% of the time, constituting Black's 5th most popular option.} 4. Bb5 {Going for Rossolimo-style pressure against the [c6]-knight. While the game is level here, Black tends to immediately err, with 80% of games seeing erroneous pawn moves in this position that allow us to advantageously chop on [c6].} a6 $2 {This is the most popular move and yet it works out great for us.} 5. Bxc6 {We get the exchange we want with a free tempo since Black's ...[a7]-[a6] was otherwise useless.} bxc6 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Rc8a6] Played twice as often as the other recapture. Now [a6] looks particularly out of place in view of Black's [c8]-bishop being blocked from a natural square on [a6].} 6. O-O {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge3e4,Yb2b3,Yc1b2] It is better to keep flexibility for the moment. We might play for [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4] or [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2].} d6 7. b3 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gc1b2] For maybe the thousandth time, our bishop comes to the awesome [b2]-square.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] Black adopts the fianchetto to eventually contest the long diagonal with their own dark-squared bishop.} 8. Bb2 Bg7 9. d3 O-O 10. Nbd2 $14 {[%cal Gd1e2] We'll play [Qe2] with a healthy structural advantage. When Black moves the knight, we will trade bishops gladly. Black is left with an ugly [c8]-bishop who can only be relevant in trading for [f3]. Our structure is flexible. We could play for [e3]-[e4] and go for breaks of either [d3]-[d4] or [e4]-[e5] depending on circumstances.} *

