1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nf6 ({This position is reached only a third as often as the position after} 3... Nc6 {is. Here we'll go for a less essayed but nonetheless strong option.}) 4. Bb5+ $1 {Our bishop returns once again to [b5]. We are fine with trading the bishops if they block with ...[Bd7]. Meanwhile, if they block with the [b8]-knight on either square, we will have promising opportunities.} Bd7 {This is the most popular response, being chosen 59% of the time.} (4... Nc6 {is chosen 23% of the time. We should be happy to see this since it allows us the classic favorable exchange on [c6].} 5. Bxc6+ {, the return of the chop chop! After} bxc6 {, we see the old reliable weak doubled c-pawns. This transposes right into the lines discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter in the 4...[d6] variations.}) 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 ({The bad news: this is the best move and we only have level chances. The good news: it's only played a quarter of the time and} 5... Nbxd7 {is played far more often.}) 6. c4 $1 {This position has only been reached 6! times giving it the strength of a novelty against your opponents who quite likely have never seen it. We dig into [d5] and prepare the positional complement to [c4], [Nc3]. We will analyze 4 natural moves from this position. I want to be clear: as with other specific parts of this course, the game is even, but if we bring a higher degree of experience, understanding, and Chessable training, we will certainly have the upper hand. These structures are unlike any other and so it is very easy for players of all skill levels to slip up, grandmasters included. :} g6 {Black prepares to move the bishop to [g7].} 7. O-O Bg7 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d3 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5,Ge4,Ge5][%cal Ge3d4,Gd3e4,Gc4d5,Gf4e5] Yet another weird structure. We control the center with four pawns that don't occupy any of it!} d5 {Here we are best advised to accept the endgame with [e3]-[e4]. If we leave the [c4]-[d5] tension even a bit longer, Black will play ...[Rd8] with good x-ray pressure on the weak [d3]-pawn.} (9... O-O 10. e4 {and we've finally arrived at a normal-looking Anti-Sicilian. The game is even and a complicated struggle awaits. We can start with [h2]-[h3] to prevent ...[Ng4] and then play [Be3] and [Qd2].}) 10. e4 $1 d4 {[%csl Gd4] We arrive at a reversed Czech Benoni structure in which Black's [d4]-pawn grants the second player a lot of extra space.} (10... dxc4 11. dxc4 {transposes to 10...dxe4 11.dxe4 .}) 11. Nd5 {The knight never gets to this stronghold in the normal Czech Benoni.} Nxd5 $2 {This allows us to get a pawn to [d5], which will debilitate Black's entire position.} 12. exd5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Rc6e5,Gf3e5] Booting the knight from [c6]. Our knight waits with anticipation for the opportunity to break ground on [e5].} Nb4 13. Ne5 Bxe5 14. fxe5 $18 {[%csl Yd5,Ye5][%cal Yd5c6,Yd5e6,Ye5d6,Ye5f6] With 2 golden pawns on [e5] and [d5], Black's pieces suffocate under the lack of space.} *

