1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nc6 4. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5] I like this move for several reasons. Objectively, it's one of the best moves. According to the database, Black immediately loses their path, and when this happens, we can count on a hefty advantage. Third, even if Black traverses the dangerous forest flawlessly, we reach a weird unorthodox version of a Carlsbad with a pawn on [f4] in which our experience should count for the difference. I expect great things from [d4] and will watch its career with great interest. We aim to play [d4]-[d5] to kick the knight out of [c6] with tempo. Black must stop this in one form or another, or immediately be left in the dust.} (4. Bb5 {would be the most natural move for us, pinning the knight on [c6].} Bd7 {is the most popular move at a frequency of 53%. After this, I was not able to find anything good for White. Black's position is harmonious and any trade on [c6] will allow the [d7]-dragon to breathe fire down the diagonal from [c6].}) ({For this reason, I went with the more obscure and less simple} 4. d4 {. Sure, the positions here are close to equal, but the practical chances here compared to those after [d4] are infinitely bigger.}) 4... cxd4 5. exd4 $1 {Keeping our pawn high up top in the center. Our [c1]-bishop breathes a sigh of relief, as one of the impediments on the [c1]-[h6] diagonal is already out of the way. Here we continue to threaten a favorable [d4]-[d5]. I am confident about our chances given that here the only two moves to keep things level for Black get a combined play frequency of 24%!} Nf6 {The most popular, as it's played 25% of the time.} 6. d5 Nb8 7. c4 g6 8. Nc3 (8. Nc3 {After} Bg7 {, we transpose to 5...g6 positions.}) *

