1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nc6 4. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5] I like this move for several reasons. Objectively, it's one of the best moves. According to the database, Black immediately loses their path, and when this happens, we can count on a hefty advantage. Third, even if Black traverses the dangerous forest flawlessly, we reach a weird unorthodox version of a Carlsbad with a pawn on [f4] in which our experience should count for the difference. I expect great things from [d4] and will watch its career with great interest. We aim to play [d4]-[d5] to kick the knight out of [c6] with tempo. Black must stop this in one form or another, or immediately be left in the dust.} (4. Bb5 {would be the most natural move for us, pinning the knight on [c6].} Bd7 {is the most popular move at a frequency of 53%. After this, I was not able to find anything good for White. Black's position is harmonious and any trade on [c6] will allow the [d7]-dragon to breathe fire down the diagonal from [c6].}) ({For this reason, I went with the more obscure and less simple} 4. d4 {. Sure, the positions here are close to equal, but the practical chances here compared to those after [d4] are infinitely bigger.}) 4... cxd4 5. exd4 $1 {Keeping our pawn high up top in the center. Our [c1]-bishop breathes a sigh of relief, as one of the impediments on the [c1]-[h6] diagonal is already out of the way. Here we continue to threaten a favorable [d4]-[d5]. I am confident about our chances given that here the only two moves to keep things level for Black get a combined play frequency of 24%!} Bg4 {This is played 19% of the time even though it's quite a serious blunder.} 6. d5 {The old reliable flick of the heel.} Nb8 7. h3 {Laying claim to the bishop pair, which would pair well with the space advantage established by our [d5]-pawn.} Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nf6 9. Be3 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] Developing the bishop to the fianchetto is natural here.} (9... e6 $2 {We will meet ...[e6] with a trade, when Black would be left with several weak pawns.} 10. dxe6 fxe6 11. Qxb7 {+- , Black drops a pawn and [e6] looks awfully weak. Black is dead lost.}) 10. Bd4 {[%cal Gd4h8] A nice pin to keep the knight frozen.} Bg7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. O-O-O $18 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh3h4,Gh4h5,Gg4g5] We will throw our pawns forward on the g- and h-files with the goal of unleashing the power of our rooks on the enemy king. Of course, Black wants to get something going on the queenside against our king. But such play is heavily delayed. The pawns are farther back and their pieces aren't even ready to support such advances yet. White is strategically winning.} *

