1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({These systems are not as popular as those with} 2... d6 {, but they still deserve consideration. Keep in mind that in many of these positions, ...[d7]-[d5] is the most popular move, but it will be ignored in this chapter, as those positions revert straight into lines covered in the chapters on the ...[d5] systems.}) 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Nf6 {can also be tried first, but it will likely transpose to 3...Nc6 or if Black plays ...[d5] soon, then back to the ...[d5] systems. In either case, this won't lead to anything not covered elsewhere in the course.}) 4. b3 (4. Bb5 $2 {was what I wanted to work, but Black can ruin all our plans of chopping with} Nge7 $1 {and we'll never rupture any structure! If anything, Black is better, as they will be able to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] fast.}) 4... a6 {This is played 9% of the time.} 5. Bb2 d5 {We have reached a weird version of the French setup in which [Bb5] is not possible on account of ...[a7]-[a6]. Only 4 games! have ever reached this position in the database.} 6. c4 {[%cal Gc4d5] A move 6 novelty! Tension is immediately introduced into the center.} Nf6 7. Ne5 {Entering the party on [e5] uninvited. If Black takes on [e5], we will respond with the classic [fxe5] to gain important central space.} Bd6 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Qf3 {Prophylaxis against the ...[d5]-[d4] advance − having protected the pawn on [f4], this pawn push isn't coming any time soon.} O-O 10. Be2 $13 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd2d3] We will castle and play [d2]-[d3]. The doubled c-pawns are very hard to target and so we aren't better, just equal. We should be hesitant to play [Nc3]-[a4], as the knight on [c3] blocks the [b2]-bishop and might allow Black to achieve the energetic ...[e6]-[e5].} *

