1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3,Gd8h4] Another popular move. It's played 33% of the time so almost at the same frequency as ...[g7]-[g5]. Black threatens to capture on [f3] and follow with a dangerous check on [h4].} 5. e3 {[%cal Gd1f3]} Nc6 6. d4 Qe7 7. c3 O-O-O 8. Bd3 {Black hasn't been able to seriously pressure White's position at all.} Nf6 9. O-O {[%csl Yb1,Yc4][%cal Gd1e2,Gd1c2,Ge3e4,Gb1a3,Ga3c4,Yb1d2,Yd2c4]} Ne4 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Re3e4] Occupying [e4] to prevent [e3]-[e4] from becoming a possibility makes strategic sense, but here it backfires.} 10. Qc2 f5 11. Nbd2 Nxd2 ({After} 11... Rde8 12. Nc4 {, White will initiate play with [b2]-[b4]-[b5]. We will likely trade on [d6] at some point and keep the queenside pawn roll going. While Black has maintained control of the [e4]-square, the knight is frozen in place since behind it lies the [f5]-weakness.}) 12. Bxf5+ {[%cal Gc2f5,Gc1d2] White snatches a pawn before recapturing on [d2].} *

