1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 g5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 34% of relevant games.} 5. g3 g4 (5... h5 {has been tried in five games but after} 6. d4 {, the threat of [Bg5] freezes Black's plan of going ...[g5] and ...[h4].} f6 7. Qd3 {+- and the hunter becomes the hunted. [Qg6] is an uncomfortable threat and Black is still down a pawn.}) 6. Nh4 (6. Nd4 $5 {is also interesting and would make a nice alternative. It doesn't stop ...[h5]-[h4], which makes it a tad riskier. I'll leave it to the student for independent analysis since our analysis of 6.Nh4 will be perfectly sufficient.}) 6... Be7 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Ge7h4] This is played with the idea to push the knight out of [h4] and then throw the h-pawn down with ...[h7]-[h5]-[h4].} 7. Ng2 h5 {What's important to understand about these variations is that while it appears like we're simply responding to our opponent's threats and therein giving them ample time, all these pawn pushes will likely backfire on them later. All these far advanced pawns will be not strong but rather weak and exposed.} 8. Nf4 h4 9. Bg2 {[%cal Gg2h1,Rh4g3,Gh2g3] The rook is protected so ...[hxg3] isn't scary.} hxg3 10. hxg3 Rxh1+ 11. Bxh1 Qd4 $2 {[%cal Gd4g1] Like most other variations, the mate threats are counterproductive to Black's entire operation if we can just react calmly.} (11... Bh4 $4 {is a dubious trick. If White captures, Black will retake with the queen and soon win [h1] and then [d1].} 12. Kf2 $1 {The king is alright! White defends the threat and can begin occupying the center with pawns on [d4] and [e4].}) 12. e3 Qh8 {[%cal Gh8h2] The queen navigates the whole board, looking for a way in.} 13. Bg2 Qh2 14. Kf2 $18 {[%cal Gf2g3,Gd1h1] The queen's voyage ends and White can trade the queens off with [Qh1] whenever we want to enter a winning endgame.} *

