1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 g5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 34% of relevant games.} 5. g3 g4 (5... h5 {has been tried in five games but after} 6. d4 {, the threat of [Bg5] freezes Black's plan of going ...[g5] and ...[h4].} f6 7. Qd3 {+- and the hunter becomes the hunted. [Qg6] is an uncomfortable threat and Black is still down a pawn.}) 6. Nh4 (6. Nd4 $5 {is also interesting and would make a nice alternative. It doesn't stop ...[h5]-[h4], which makes it a tad riskier. I'll leave it to the student for independent analysis since our analysis of 6.Nh4 will be perfectly sufficient.}) 6... Ne7 7. d4 Ng6 {[%cal Gg6h4]} (7... Ng6 {Here both} 8. Nxg6 {and 8.Ng2 are promising. [Ng2] retreats and keeps the h-file closed but does so at the cost of the [f1]-bishop's coordination. In this repertoire, we will only focus on [Nxg6], but feel free to analyze [Ng2] on your own.}) 8. Nxg6 hxg6 {[%csl Rg3,Rh2][%cal Gh8h1,Gd6g3] The whole point of Black's maneuver. The h-file is opened and ...[Bxg3]+ looms over White's kingside.} 9. Qd3 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Gd3g3]} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gd6g3,Yd8d4] The underlying logic of such positions is the following: White is materially and strategically better due to the two extra central pawns. We will have to play precisely to dodge the various tricks that get thrown our way, but if we can manage that, we will be much better. Here ...[Nxd4] followed by ...[Bxg3]+ is threatened so White should cement the [d4]-pawn.} 10. c3 Bf5 11. e4 {[%cal Ge4f5]} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7e1] Pinning the [e4]-pawn to our king.} 12. Bg2 O-O-O 13. Be3 Rxh2 {[%cal Gd6g3]} 14. Rxh2 Bxg3+ 15. Kd1 Bxh2 16. exf5 Re8 17. Bd2 $18 {[%cal Gd1c2,Gb1a3,Ga3c4] White will play [Kc2], and [Na3] and should be able to eventually convert.} *

