1. f4 b6 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {Here Black should really revert back to the standard QID setup with ...[e7]-[e6]. All other options give White the chance for a huge advantage.} g6 {This is chosen 20% of the time. Black opts for a double fianchetto setup. We should be happy to see this move since it allows us to take a full stake in the center.} 4. d4 {Taking the full center!} Bg7 5. Nf3 {[%csl Yd4,Ye4,Yf4] Three fantastic pawns on the fourth rank, what more could we ask for?} e6 {Played 48% of the time.} 6. Bd3 Ne7 {Black is taking care to not push ...[d7]-[d5] for a reason... They want the Hippo setup with ...[d7]-[d6] and ...[Nd7]!} 7. O-O d6 8. f5 {[%cal Gc1g5] Striking before Black is ready. Our bishop can now zoom to [g5] where it will lay siege to the [e7]-knight.} gxf5 9. exf5 exf5 10. Bg5 $18 {[%csl Rd8,Re7,Rf5][%cal Gd1d2,Ga1e1,Gg5d8] Black might be up a pawn temporarily, but the [f5]-apple will drop shortly. We will play [Qd2] and [Rae1] with overwhelming pressure. Black is already lost.} *

