1. f4 e6 2. Nf3 (2. e4 {is too soon. Black will play} d5 {with a good French.} 3. e5 {would turn into an ugly type of setup with [f4] vs. the French Defense. Black would play ...[c5] to pressure [d4] and a knight would glide to [f5]. Perhaps it's close to equal, but Black is already in the driver's seat.}) 2... b6 (2... Nf6 3. e3 b6 {will transpose into positions already discussed in the 1...Nf6 lines.}) 3. e4 {Let's take the center finally!} Bb7 {This is played 92% of the time so it will be the move we focus the most on.} 4. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb4c3,Gb7e4] This is played 48% of the time and is by far the most popular choice. Black threatens to chop on [c3] and scoop up [e4].} 5. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2e4] Our queen reinforces [e4]. This may look like it blocks our [f1]-bishop, but we can always opt for a kingside fianchetto with [g2]-[g3]. This strong move is rarely tried though, and already on move 5, we are at a position that has only been reached roughly 4000 times. We will look at Black's only two commonly chosen moves in this position, each of which has a frequency of 40%.} Bxc3 {Black chops in the hope of getting better control over the central light squares that our knight was defending, even if it costs the bishop pair. Here we have an interesting dilemma, as both captures make sense. It is better to open our bishop with [dxc3], or strengthen our central presence with [bxc3]?} 6. dxc3 {It turns out both captures are equally valid; objectively though they lead to quite different struggles. The move chosen leads to a healthier dynamism and a comfortable advantage derived from speedy development and an open d-file. If it's not your cup of tea, feel free to investigate [bxc3].} Nf6 {Attacking [e4].} 7. e5 {[%csl Rf6]} Nd5 $2 {This is a big mistake that happens to be by far the most popular move, at a frequency of 70%. The knight obstructs the [b7]-dragon and is a sitting duck for the inevitably problematic [c3]-[c4].} 8. Bd2 {[%cal Ge1c1]} O-O $2 {This is natural and also quite common. But just like after 7...Ne4 , Black's last hope had been to castle queenside.} 9. O-O-O Nc6 10. h4 $18 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6] Throwing the pawn forward. There is no answer to this. If Black stops our pawn with the h-pawn, we can simply use their advanced pawn as a hook and advance our g-pawn to crunch on it. We have a winning strategic advantage. We can kick the [d5]-knight with [c3]-[c4] whenever we like but again, there is no rush. Black's position is completely bankrupt of play. Their pieces are weak and nearly every pawn Black pushes will weaken things more for them than it helps. This last fact is largely due to the fact that our pieces scope the board and will keep an eye on any square Black's pawn moves weaken.} *

