1. f4 f5 {The famed copycat opening. Bird's opening is quite unique in that Black can respond in this way with minimal risk. Against 1.e4 , 1.d4 and 1.c4 playing the copycat risks a lot. Here however Black can continue mirroring our moves up until around move 10. For this opening, I went in a relatively different direction from the rest of the repertoire and opted for the fianchetto system with [g2]-[g3]. This is because with the bishops on the long diagonals, there is more dynamism to the position, making it harder for Black to copy us at little cost. This chapter will only deal with moves where Black copies us as long as it's viable. There is a chance they deviate sooner but the vast majority of players who go for 1...f5 just like to sit back, relax, and mimic us until it becomes unfeasible.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 {The one time in the course we go for a kingside fianchetto. The bishop will scope the board via [g2].} g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 {Introducing the potential of [e2]-[e4] in the future.} d6 {[%cal Ge2e4]} 6. Nc3 {Reinforcing [e2]-[e4] even more.} Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] With some interesting pressure in the center.} e5 9. exf5 {Finally, we reach a crossroads in which Black can only keep copying at the extreme detriment of their position.} Bxf5 10. h3 {The bishop on [f5] begins to feel the heat.} exf4 11. Bxf4 h6 {Trying to get back to the copycat strategy doesn't work.} 12. Nh4 Nh5 13. Nxf5 Nxf4 {Black literally doesn't care.} 14. Nxg7 Nxg2 15. Ne6 Ne3 16. Qe2 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gd8e7,Ge2e3]} (16. Qe2 {And finally the copycat ends.} Qe7 {is met with} 17. Qxe3 {, defending our knight.}) 16... Rxf1+ 17. Rxf1 $18 {Black can choose between giving up the queen or the knight.} *

