1. f4 Nc6 {This unusual move is essayed 6% of the time on move 1. We should be humble in how we judge it; after all, we did open the game by moving the f-pawn up two squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 (2... d5 {will transpose back to the several chapters covering 1...d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 . 2...e6 3.e3 will transpose to a terrible version of the French setup in which Black has preemptively removed any chance to achieve ...[c7]-[c5] by blocking the c-pawn with the knight.}) 3. e3 (3. e3 {Likely Black will play} d5 {, transposing back into the Two Knights system of 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 in the ...[d5] system. We will look at the only other viable options for Black here.}) 3... d6 4. d4 {[%cal Gd4d5] We want to advance to [d5].} Bg4 $2 {This is by far the most popular but doesn't deal with White's threat.} (4... e6 {can't be taken seriously. The [e6] and [d6]-pawns control the center from a very timid stance and carry the serious downside of blocking both bishops.} 5. Nc3 {⩲ , we will play [Bd3] and castle. White is better.}) 5. d5 Nb4 6. e4 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb1c3,Gf1b5] Our move laid a cunning trap for Black.} Bxf3 {[%csl Gc2,Gd1][%cal Gd1c2,Rb4c2] Make sure not to take with the queen here, we wouldn't want to allow ...[Nxc2].} (6... Nxe4 7. c3 {, opening the diagonal for the queen,} Na6 8. Qa4+ {+- .}) 7. gxf3 $16 {With [a3] booting the knight from [b4] and [Nc3] to follow, perhaps with [Bb5]+ thrown in; we will eventually castle queenside with a great space advantage.} *

