{Welcome! This chapter will be discussing when to go for certain positional devices and pawn breaks! The Bird is one of the most complex and rich openings I've seen, and as you go through the material, you will understand the significance of this chapter. What lies ahead are some guidelines I’ve come up with, that will hopefully assist you in figuring out when to do what. Enjoy!} 1. Z0 *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Bird Opening"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "🗝 Key Ideas"]
[Black "To chop or not to chop − Part 1"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2n1p3/1Bpp4/5P2/4PN2/PPPP2PP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "2"]
[GameId "2127765595480602"]

{The most important method in the entire course − the karate chop on [c6]. Our bishop points at the knight on [c6], weighing serious pressure on it. We will see the bishop come to [b5] in this manner not only in ...[d5] systems but also in variations against Black's Sicilian setup with 1...c5. Simply put, in almost every situation available, if Black cannot recapture with a piece, we should smash through the queenside to ruin Black's structure. I cannot think of a single time we do not take in these situations. The structure for Black with doubled pawns on [c5] and [c6] unequivocally gives us a healthy game.} 1. Bxc6+ {[%cal Gb5c6]} bxc6 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6,Rc8,Rd5,Rf8][%cal Rf8c5,Rc8b7] Black is given an ugly structure with weak, disharmonious pawns on the c-file. Now [c5] will be a permanent target for our pieces. Additionally, Black's [c6]-pawn is fixed in place, making it relatively impossible for Black to use the light-squared bishop effectively on the long diagonal from [b7]. It should be mentioned that [a6] will likely be no better for the light-squared bishop, as we can always blunt its perspective with [d2]-[d3].} *

