[GameId "2127765595501084"]

{Here we see a more nuanced situation. The bishop on [d7] is ready to recapture on [c6], keeping Black's structure healthy. In such scenarios, we will still prefer chopping to retreating, but here there is more of an argument towards waiting for Black to spend a move nudging us with ...[a7]-[a6]. In this exact position, taken from the French Setup chapter, we immediately traded on [c6], but it would have also been fine to wait with [O-O].} 1. Bxc6 (1. O-O a6 2. Be2 $2 {(Retreating when the pawn is on [c5] would just be bad. Black has healthy control of the center and with the extra space may be able to begin playing for an advantage shortly; ...[a7]-[a6] was a useful move, as it assists Black's expansion on the queenside with ...[b7]-[b5]. So remember, with the pawn on [c5] and the knight on [c6], never retreat! We will observe exceptions to this if the knight has been developed to [d7] where it is always inferior to the [c6]-position. But the [c6]-chop must always be chosen over the retreat when the pawn is on [c5].)}) 1... Bxc6 {In these cases, we have not achieved any structural weakening, so what was the justification for ceding the bishop pair in this fashion? Well, we have great control over the [e5]-square, which our knight can immediately take advantage of.} 2. Ne5 $1 {[%csl Gb2,Rc6,Gd2,Ge3,Gf4][%cal Ge5c6,Gb2e5] Renewing the threat to ruin Black's structure on [c6]. Our position resembles a harmonious reversed Queen's Indian setup in which our pawn phalanx and fianchettoed bishop dominate the dark squares.} *

