[White "🗝 Key Ideas"]
[Black "Post chop structures: c5+c6"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/p3bppp/2p1pn2/2pp4/5P2/1P2PN2/PBPP2PP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "5"]
[GameId "2127765595517471"]

{If I had to pick a structure in this course for you to memorize, it would be this one − the post chop with pawns on [c5] and [c6]. Black's [c5]-pawn is fundamentally weak, it can never be defended by a pawn; it resembles the [c4]-pawn in Nimzo-Indian structures, which is a permanent target for the black pieces. Unlike the Nimzo-Indian, however, our opponent has not gotten an overwhelming center by advancing the king pawn since our [f4]-pawn digs into that square. Black has 3 principled methods of counterplay, all involving their pawns, and we have 3 measures of prevention to preempt each of those three. We start with the biggest: ...[c5]-[c4]. Black wants to throw the c-pawn down to [c4] for several reasons: it would unblock their bishop; it gets Black one step closer to opening the diagonal for a bishop on [b7] with ...[c6]-[c5]; it guarantees some type of trade, which will also benefit the light-squared bishop.} 1. c4 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rc5c4] Nipping ...[c5]-[c4] in the bud. What is Black's next biggest threat in these structures? It's a tie between two pawn breaks on [a4] with ...[a7]-[a5]-[a4] and [e5] after ...[e6]-[e5] has been adequately prepared. In both cases, we will proactively stop such breaks as best we can.} (1. d3 $2 {allows} c4 $1 {Black is often happy to do this even if it means losing a pawn. Here for instance Black has full compensation for the pawn due to the diagonals being opened.} 2. dxc4 Qb6 {, the queen highlights another diagonal that has been opened by the pawn sacrifice.} 3. Re1 Ba6 {∞ Black has full compensation. Compare the quality of their bishops and queen to that of the starting position − they are a world apart.}) 1... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] The pawn is coming to [a4]... What to do?} ({Black can also play for ...e6-e5 with} 1... Bd6 {. Make no mistake, if Black achieves this, they will be very close to equal. Luckily in this position, we can clamp down on this for good with} 2. Ne5 $1 {The pawn is not going anywhere. ( I'll waste some moves with White to show what could happen if Black actually achieves ...e6-e5 in this structure. 2.Kh1? Nd7 3.Kg1? Qc7 4.Nc3 e5! Several pawns are about to get traded and Black's bishops will flourish in the more opened position. The [c8]-bishop in particular can breathe a sigh of relief that it will get out along the diagonal to somewhere useful like [f5] or [g4] eventually. )}) 2. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Gc3a4] Our knight grooves into [a4] where it will pressure the [c5]-weakness and hold back any ...[a4] tricks.} (2. d3 $2 a4 $1 {If Black trades on [b3], then we will have a new weakness there, but [bxa4] would fracture our structure and lead to other weaknesses on the a-file. So Black has equalized because they've achieved this.}) 2... Bd6 3. Na4 $16 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ga4c5,Ga1c1,Gf3e5,Ge5d3] And the pawn on [a5] is frozen in space. You will get this position countless times. You can simply pile up on the [c5]-pawn with moves like [Rc1], [Nf3]-[e5]-[d3], and when the time is right cash in on [c5]. Keep in mind that [cxd5] will open up the venomous [c8]-viper that's been lurking in the dark cellar the whole game, so only exchange on [d5] if you're getting more than enough to compensate for this.} *

