[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/2p2ppp/2p1pn2/p2p4/5Pb1/1P2PN2/PBPP2PP/RN1Q1RK1 w kq - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2127765595529760"]

{In this post-chop structure, Black has just pushed ...[a7]-[a5], attempting to break with ...[a5]-[a4] and get the [a8]-rook more activity. Black is also trying to get rid of what could potentially be a vulnerable isolated pawn later in the endgame. There are always 2 responses to this − we must blockade it with either a pawn or a knight. The [a5]-pawn must be kept still!} 1. a4 $1 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb2c3] Black appears to have just created a new weakness, which will be a target to [Bc3] now and forever after. Additionally, we would relish the [d5]-pawn budging at all, which would give our [b1]-knight great prospects on the [c4]-outpost. White has a healthy static advantage. Note that if our c-pawn had already moved, then this thrust to [a4] would have weakened [b3] a bit, and so would have been inferior to the knight transfer to [a4].} (1. Nc3 $5 {would also be good. The knight will plant itself on [a4] and hold the pawn in place while eyeing the weak [c5]-square.}) *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Bird Opening"]
