[White "🗝 Key Ideas"]
[Black "Post chop structures: c7+c6 − Part 1"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/2p2ppp/p1pbpn2/3p4/5P2/1P2PN2/PBPP2PP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2127765595537953"]

{These structures are a bit different than those with pawns on [c5] and [c6]. First, while [c5] is a weak square, it no longer has a vulnerable pawn placed on it, making Black's pawn structure a bit healthier. Without the pawn on [c5], we no longer have to make preparations against ...[c5]-[c4]. If Black pushes ...[c5], we will always be able to throw [c2]-[c4] right back at them, freezing the pawn on the ugly square and keeping the diagonals relatively closed. In these structures, Black has one central idea − to liberate the position with ...[e5]. This would open the [c8]-bishop to the light and also give the rook on [f8] a real purpose when it reaches [e8]. We will watch out for this thrust, and if Black gets close to playing it, we will clamp down with the classic knight shimmy.} 1. Ne5 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Re6][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3a4] The e-pawn isn't going anywhere. We have a healthy advantage due to our grip on the structure. We should think about aiming our other knight at the [c5]-weakness. This could be done through the classic transfer [Nb1]-[c3]-[a4].} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Bird Opening"]
