[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "🗝 Key Ideas"]
[Black "Post chop structures: c7+c6 − Part 2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/p1p2ppp/2pbpn2/3p4/5P2/2N1PQ2/PPPP2PP/R1B2RK1 w - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "7"]
[GameId "2127765595542050"]

{But what do we do when we can't fully control the [e5]-square with our pieces? Well, we must play for [d3] and [e4]! This will create uncomfortable tension against the black pawns. Our dream would be if Black traded on [e4], thereby rendering the already ugly doubled pawns isolated and exposed. As long as [d5] stays on the board, it is hard for us to get at the [c6]-vulnerability, but once it's removed, the pressure grows naturally.} 1. d3 $1 (1. d4 $2 {clamps down on [e5], but this is not a good Stonewall!} c5 $1 {and Black has very nice tension against our center. Black looks to trade on [d4] and undermine our 2nd [d4]-pawn with ...[c7]-[c5]. We’ll discuss the rules, regarding when to go for a Stonewall, in more detail in the future.}) 1... e5 {Black has achieved the liberating push. Notice that even without the light-squared bishops, this push frees critical space for the [d6]-bishop and the rook which will move from [f8] to [e8].} 2. e4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Re4d5] The tension on [d5] is uncomfortable. If White is given time, we will play [f4]-[f5] with a really nice pawn phalanx pointed to the kingside.} dxe4 ({After} 2... Re8 3. f5 $1 Bc5+ 4. Kh1 {± , [f4]-[f5] has been achieved and this guarantees that the center and e-file will be closed for a while. We can throw our g-pawn forward to [g4] and [g5] and bring the heavy-s over to the kingside for a picturesque denouement. See my game against Leinier Dominguez in the model games chapter for more info on this type of position.}) 3. Nxe4 Nxe4 4. Qxe4 {The pawns are traded and White retains a nagging edge. The c-pawns will never not be a weakness in this type of position. The computer insists things are close to level, but we are not playing against cold-hearted silicon beasts; instead, we are playing humans who hate ugly doubled pawns!} *

