{The last thing to mention is: when it's clear you're playing for [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4], then the knight is well placed on [c3]. Here we see a position from the Solid ...[Bf5] chapter in which our plan is to erect a [d3]/[e4] phalanx against the [f5]-bishop.} 1. Nc3 $1 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gc1d2,Ye3e4] We will play [d2]-[d3] and eventually strive to prepare [e3]-[e4]. Our [c1]-bishop will stay locked beneath the surface for a while and will likely develop to the solid [d2].} *

