[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2127765595599400"]

{The question of whether to go for a Stonewall (with pawns on [d4]-[e3]-[f4]) is quite tricky and depends on the special circumstances of every position. The structure is inherently risky due to its weaknesses on the light squares, in particular [e4], which has been made an outpost for the enemy pieces. Black can play for an advantage against the structure in two ways: either by weighing down on the [e4]-weakness with ...[Bf5] or by initiating favorable tension with ...[c7]-[c5]. It might be confusing as to why we are talking about Black's ideas when this is a White repertoire, but you will begin to get the point as we move forward. If for whatever reason, Black doesn’t have to waste time on either of these ideas, or if one or both of them is indeed possible, then we should NOT opt for the Stonewall. In the next examples, we'll discuss what would make these strong ideas impossible.} 1... c5 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Re3,Rf4][%cal Gb8c6,Gf8g7,Gc8f5] Black is already better and will follow with ...[Nc6], ...[Bg7], and ...[Bf5] with healthy pressure against our center. The game is not over yet, but already our pieces' prospects are significantly inferior to those of the opponent.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Bird Opening"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "🗝 Key Ideas"]
[Black "The Stonewall question − Part 2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b1kbnr/ppp1pppp/2nq4/3p4/5P2/4PN2/PPPP2PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2127765595607593"]

{Here Black has obstructed the [c7]-pawn, making ...[c5] very hard to accomplish. Moreover, Black has rushed the queen out to [d6] and is aiming at an immediate ...[e7]-[e5], which a Stonewall structure would perfectly clamp down upon. Therefore...} 1. d4 $14 {We have a good Stonewall. We will follow with [c2]-[c4] and if possible expand with [c4]-[c5] to gain more space. Black's pieces on [c6] and [d6] are looking very silly now that ...[e7]-[e5] is off the table. ♚ Moral of the story: if our opponent's knight is on [c6], a Stonewall structure already might be justified since ...[c7]-[c5] is impossible to achieve without Black burning a useless move on the [c6]-knight.} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Bird Opening"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "🗝 Key Ideas"]
[Black "The Stonewall question − Part 3"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bqkbnr/ppp1pppp/2np4/8/5P2/5N2/PPPPP1PP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2127765595611690"]

{It is always a matter of identifying the factors favorable to the Stonewall. If you spot one, the Stonewall should be okay. If you spot two, drop what you're doing and start laying the bricks. In this example, the knight on [c6] is again misplaced, and Black has burned a move on ...[d6] − this is important since if Black doesn't advance it to [d5], nothing will be fixing our Stonewall in place and stopping us from advancing [e3]-[e4]. So the knight on [c6] is 1 strike and the pawn being on [d6] means a free tempo which is another strike; it's time to advance!} 1. d4 $14 {A healthy Stonewall. Black is best advised to push ...[d6]-[d5] but of course, they will have wasted a lot of time and this doesn't begin to address the knight on [c6]. I want to emphasize that if your position has 2 of the following criteria, you should probably advance the Stonewall: Black's knight is on [c6] and the pawn is still on [c7]. Black's [c8]-bishop is blocked by an obstruction from reaching [f5]; for instance, if a pawn had been pushed to [e6]. If Black's pawn spent two moves getting to [d5] or is currently on [d6]. If Black has contorted their position with unusual moves like ...[Qd6] or ...[f7]-[f6] to quickly achieve ...[e5] in the opening moves. MEANWHILE, if any of the criteria below exist, do NOT advance the Stonewall: You have pushed [b3]. Regardless of whether you have fianchettoed the bishop already or not, this push tends to not work in conjunction with the Stonewall. This is partly due to it being costly in time and also that the bishop on [b2] pointing into White's [d4]-concrete will affect nothing. Black's pawn is already on [c5]. There are no exceptions to this when Black has pawns on [d5] and [c5]. There is however an exception if they've elected a Sicilian structure with ...[d6] and ...[Nc6]; feel free to check that chapter out for more info.} *

