{Here, it is recommended to play [Rg1], kicking the game into top gear. There's not an exact no-no tied to this, rather this is just a reminder − the more aggressive and reckless a move is, the more you need to practice it lest you have to apply it in a slightly different situation. I relish the reckless wrecking of Black's position but only when the moves are correct. If you apply a reckless move in a slightly incorrect scenario, the results could be dire and you could even lose the game.} 1. Rg1 c5 2. g4 {White's g-pawn will go from 0-100 as it runs down the board. It is also objectively sound, with the computer indicating a balanced game after the best play by both sides.} *

