[White "📌 Introduction to 1...d5 Systems"]
[Black "Introduction to 1...d5 Systems"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "5"]
[GameId "2127765595767344"]

1. f4 d5 ({Welcome to the largest section of the course. The} 1... d5 {systems are most common against the Bird and can occur through a series of transpositions. Black can start with 1...Nf6 , 1...d5 , or even 1...e6 , and in each case be heading for the same type of strategy on the light squares. Black's setups can be divided into two families: those in which the knight is placed in front of the pawn on [c6], and those in which Black delays ...[Nc6] in order to get a reversed Queen's Gambit setup with ...[c7]-[c5]. The first set of plans is characterized by more aggressive, energetic play, while a more positionally sound strategy defines the second. Both require serious care in our study of the plans and ideas.}) 2. Nf3 Nf6 (2... Nf6 {Here we have arguably the most important decision in the entire course.} 3. b3 {, 3.d3 , 3.e3 , and 3.g3 are all popular, but which one should we go for? Generally, [d3] and [g3] are played together, meaning if one is played on move 3 the other is played on move 4. On the other hand, while [e3] is frequently paired with a queenside fianchetto after [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2], this is not always the case. I initially tried to build this course around the [g3]/[d3] setups but it left too bad a taste in my mouth and I ended up canning the system for [e3].}) 3. e3 $1 {Opening up the bishop. Our bishop will probably come to [b5] but might also stay more reservedly on [e2]. We will aim for a queenside fianchetto with good pressure on the central dark squares.} ({➢} 3. d3 $6 {was a move I spent a lot of time on prior to deciding on 3.e3. White prepares to (play [g3], fianchetto the bishop, and play a reversed Leningrad System. Allow me to sum up my reasons for avoiding it. First, there can quickly arise some really uncomfortable positions with Black throwing the b-pawn down the board see the end of this variation. Second, Black has lots of other critical tries all of which require at least as much precision by White as it does by Black. This isn't ideal since we want our opponents to be the ones to have to find strong hidden moves. Third, most Bird players 55%, while the [d3] and [g3] systems only get chosen by 17% of players play [e3] in this position, and I wanted to make a repertoire accessible to that majority. )} e6 4. g3 b5 5. Bg2 Be7 {⩱ . These positions are just uncomfortable for White. The b-pawn can always come to [b4] to kick out a knight that arrives at [c3]. And moving the knight to [d2] is very risky in Leningrad setups since it blocks the bishop's coverage over the weak [e3]-square. White's breaks on [e4] or [c4] won't pack much punch. I really want to stress that I tried very hard to make these lines work, but the positions that arose were all at least slightly preferable for Black, and the ones that were closest to equal were very boring infinitesimally worse endgames. I love the Leningrad Dutch and one of my motivations for this course was being able to apply some of the same ideas to the White side. The likelihood your opponent knows this system might be small, but all the same it is very hard for me to recommend a path that would allow this.}) ({➢} 3. g3 $6 {might be even more hated by the computer than [d3]. It aims for the same systems with a kingside fianchetto and pawns on [d3] and [g3]. Black can adopt several promising strategies, one of them being} e6 4. Bg2 b5 {⩱ . Again, this is not the end of the world, but Black's space is already annoying. This course is supposed to be a lifetime repertoire, and while I could build a repertoire around such positions with tons of tricks and gimmicks, the sustainability of this approach is dubious.}) *

