1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bh5 $2 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gf4f5,Gg2g4] This has been played in nearly 3000 games but it is already losing. We can see the benefits of having our pawn advanced to [f4] − it will be able to advance to [f5] to lock the bishop in due time.} 5. g4 Bg6 6. f5 $18 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gf5g6] The bishop is lost. No comment needed!} *

