1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bf5 {This infrequently played move makes little sense. If the bishop wanted to go to [f5] why didn't it go there instead of [g4] on move 3? Here White can expand in a healthy way.} 5. g4 {[%cal Gg4f5]} Be4 (5... Bg6 6. f5 {+- and the bishop drops on [g6].}) 6. d3 {Batting the bishop back. Retreating to [g6] is no good, as [f4]-[f5] will trap it. Black has to cede the bishop for the [f3]-knight.} Bxf3 {Obviously, this is not optimal for Black, as ...[Bxf3] could have been played on move 4. Instead, Black gave White free tempi in making the useful moves [g4] and [d3].} 7. Qxf3 e6 {While this position looks great, it is important to know how to handle it. Let's observe the following moves to trace some thematic patterns.} 8. Bg2 Nc6 9. O-O g6 {[%cal Re3e4,Gc6d4] White will look to play [e3]-[e4] but aims to do it at the proper time. If White goes for it now, ideas of ...[Nc6]-[d4] could be annoying.} 10. Nc3 Bg7 11. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5,Ge4d5] Twin threats of [e5] and [exd5] loom in the air; [e5] will kick out the [f6]-knight while locking the [g7]-bishop off the board; [exd5] on the other hand, will open things up for play on the [e8]-king and the [d5]-square.} Nd4 $2 {This jump packs no punch here.} 12. Qf2 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf2d4]} (12. Qf2 {The knight is hanging and if Black goes for} c5 {, they unnecessarily burn time, allowing White to open the game with} 13. exd5 {.}) 12... dxe4 13. dxe4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf1d1]} Nc6 14. e5 Nd7 15. Ne4 $18 {[%csl Rc6,Rd7,Ge3,Gg2,Rg7][%cal Gc1e3,Ga1d1] White will play [Be3] and the bishops will scope the board. Meanwhile, the rook will glide from [a1] to [d1] to seize the d-file. White is already strategically winning. Black's minor pieces are all dominated.} *

