1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bf5 {This infrequently played move makes little sense. If the bishop wanted to go to [f5] why didn't it go there instead of [g4] on move 3? Here White can expand in a healthy way.} 5. g4 {[%cal Gg4f5]} Bd7 ({The safest retreat but one that makes Black's strategy even more confusing.} 5... Bg6 6. f5 {+- and the bishop drops on [g6].}) 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. d3 e6 8. O-O $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rd7][%cal Gd1e1,Gd1e2,Ye3e4] Black's [d7]-bishop and [c6]-knight paint a peculiar picture. However, White's setup is quite harmonious. White can play for [Qe1]/[e2] and [e3]-[e4] or can aim to fianchetto the queen's bishop with [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2]. Both ideas look enterprising.} *

