1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Placing the [c6]-steed under an annoying pin.} Qd6 {We have several options to keep a level game. In the making of this course, I sought out the most dynamic of the bunch.} 7. d4 (7. Nc3 e6 8. b3 g6 9. Bb2 a6 10. Bxc6+ Qxc6 11. Ne2 {was one way to play, when the structure remains largely undefined. Depending on the situation, White can play for pushes on [g4], [d3] and [e4], or [c4].}) 7... a6 8. Bd3 Nb4 9. Nc3 Nxd3+ 10. cxd3 e6 11. Bd2 Be7 12. O-O O-O {[%csl Gd3][%cal Rf6e4,Gd3e4,Gd2e1,Ge1h4,Gg2g4,Ga1c1] Some ideas are [Be1]-[h4], [g2]-[g4], or simple play along the c-file starting with [Rac1]. The game is balanced, but we have our chances.} *

