1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Placing the [c6]-steed under an annoying pin.} Qd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] The queen reinforces the knight in a healthy way. The queenside won't be leveled by [Bxc6] for the moment.} 7. d3 {Preparing for development while keeping the [e4]-square under control.} a6 8. Ba4 {Preserving the bishop for the time being.} b5 9. Bb3 Na5 {[%cal Ga5b3] Black will promptly take the bishop on [b3].} 10. Bd2 $5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gd2c3,Gc3a5] A curious move. First, it rushes the [a5]-knight to make a decision. Secondly, it prepares to put the bishop to [c3] where it will exert annoying pressure along the long diagonal.} Nxb3 11. axb3 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Ga1a6] The structure has been changed and White has an inkling of a positional edge. The [a6]-pawn has become an obvious target.} e6 12. Bc3 {[%cal Gc3f6] Scoping the diagonal. What a strange analogy for a fianchetto!} Bd6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 {[%csl Gb2,Gb3,Rf6,Rh7][%cal Rg7f6] Both sides have doubled pawns but White's are more compact; [f6] and [h7] could become vulnerable in the middlegame or endgame.} 14. Nd2 O-O 15. e4 $14 {[%csl Yf5][%cal Ye6e5,Yd2f1,Yf1e3,Ye3f5,Ge1g1] White has the more comfortable position. Notice that while both sides look solid, it is much harder to do things with Black's structure. If it moves at all, it might accrue irreparable damages. For instance, pushing the e-pawn will create a beautiful outpost on [f5] for our knight. We will castle and play the position patiently, being very hesitant with pawn moves, as they are irreversible in nature.} *

