1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Placing the [c6]-steed under an annoying pin.} Qd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] The queen reinforces the knight in a healthy way. The queenside won't be leveled by [Bxc6] for the moment.} 7. d3 {Preparing for development while keeping the [e4]-square under control.} a6 8. Ba4 {Preserving the bishop for the time being.} b5 9. Bb3 Na5 {[%cal Ga5b3] Black will promptly take the bishop on [b3].} 10. Bd2 $5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gd2c3,Gc3a5] A curious move. First, it rushes the [a5]-knight to make a decision. Secondly, it prepares to put the bishop to [c3] where it will exert annoying pressure along the long diagonal.} Nxb3 11. axb3 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Ga1a6] The structure has been changed and White has an inkling of a positional edge. The [a6]-pawn has become an obvious target.} e6 12. Bc3 {[%cal Gc3f6] Scoping the diagonal. What a strange analogy for a fianchetto!} Be7 13. b4 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Gb4][%cal Rb5b4] Preventing any harassment by ...[b5]-[b4] and fixing the [a6]-pawn in place. The game is still equal, but if White is given time to get the knight to [b3], we will have a huge edge. For that reason, Black has to undermine the [b4]-pawn with ...[c5] or ...[a5] immediately. An example of what could happen if Black doesn't achieve this is as follows.} O-O 14. Nd2 c6 $2 (14... c5 $1 {is necessary, to trade off our strong [b4]-pawn, therein ridding Black of the nagging weaknesses on [c5] and [a5]. We are best advised to trade on [c5] and follow with [Nd2]-[b3] with a level position.}) 15. Nb3 $14 {[%csl Ga5,Gc5][%cal Gb3c5,Gb3a5,Ge1g1,Rc6c5,Ra6a5,Gf3g3,Gf4f5] The queenside is fixed and White has an edge. Notice that for Black to ever accomplish ...[c6]-[c5], the bishop will have to be deflected from its critical defense of the [f6]-knight. So pushing ...[c6]-[c5] will engender [Bxf6] and ...[gxf6], when Black's kingside suffers. We will castle and then begin creating threats on the kingside with moves like [Qg3] and [f4]-[f5].} *

