1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Placing the [c6]-steed under an annoying pin.} e6 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7] Now Black's queenside is shattered and any plans to castle queenside need to be abandoned.} 8. d3 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7][%cal Ge3e4,Gb1d2,Gb1c3] White will play [Nd2] or [Nc3], castle, and then play [e3]-[e4].} Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5] This is Black's best bet, to get some play with ...[e6]-[e5].} 9. Nc3 O-O 10. O-O Re8 $2 {This is too slow!} 11. e4 e5 12. f5 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5,Rf6][%cal Gg1h1,Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gg5f6] White has kept the center sealed. We will move the king to [h1] and throw the g-pawn up the board to [g5] to evict the black knight.} *

