1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 c6 {Here most players have elected to fianchetto their queen's bishop with [b2]-[b3], but we have a much more natural move at our disposal.} 6. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5] Gaining space on the kingside and introducing ideas of [g4]-[g5].} Nbd7 7. Nc3 {White wants to play [g5], when the [f6]-knight won't be able to advance to [e4].} e6 8. g5 {[%cal Gg5f6]} Ng8 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gg8e7,Ge7f5] The [f5]-square has been weakened by our g-pawn's advance and that will be the target of the [g8]-knight in the coming moves. As Black completes development, Black will aim to put the knight there with ...[Ng8]-[e7]-[f5].} 9. h4 {Expanding further and opening up [h3] to our bishop.} h5 $1 {[%cal Rh4h5] The best move, holding White's h-pawn advance back.} (9... h6 {instead would allow us slightly favorable complications after} 10. b3 g6 11. Bb2 Bg7 12. h5 {, when we can castle queenside and continue to ask Black a few questions.}) 10. Bh3 {[%cal Re6e5,Gh3c8] A nice square for the bishop. For now, it looks into concrete, but if Black ever hopes to push ...[e6]-[e5], Black will have to contend with the bishop shooting down the light squares. Here, Black must get the bishop to the long diagonal before White's [c1]-bishop gets to [b2] to rake the board.} Qc7 $2 ({This natural move preparing queenside castle is actually a big mistake.} 10... g6 {will transpose after} 11. d3 Ne7 {.}) 11. b3 O-O-O 12. Bb2 Ne7 13. O-O-O Rh7 {[%cal Rb2h8,Gh8h7] Such a move is necessary due to the tricks on the long diagonal.} ({Notice that} 13... Rg8 {would have kept the rook closer to getting into the game along the 8th rank, but it just hangs a pawn:} 14. Qxh5 {+- . White is a clean pawn up and can simply retreat the queen and advance the kingside majority with a straightforward game.}) (13... g6 14. Nb5 $1 {scoops up the exchange.}) 14. e4 g6 ({After} 14... dxe4 15. Nxe4 {, White is much better with good pieces and the bishop pair. If you have any doubt, just glance at the silly [h7]-rook!}) 15. d3 {[%cal Gc1b1,Gh1f1,Yf4f5] White will play [Kb1], maybe [Rhf1], and eventually crash through with [f4]-[f5]!} *

