1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Nc3 $5 ({This move is not seen nearly as often as the more popular} 6. b3 {. Nonetheless, it looks like the best and most fighting option. White keeps the position flexible and maintains options of moving [g3], [d3], or [b3]. Here, Black has six options, but we will primarily focus on the most popular one, ...[Bb4].}) 6... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4] The knight looks a bit strange being placed in front of the c-pawn like this, but in fact, the threat of ...[Nb4] is annoying and we should prevent it.} 7. a3 Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5] Black is about to get ...[e6]-[e5] in with good play − we must prevent this!} 8. d4 $14 {[%csl Ge4,Rc6][%cal Gf1d3,Gc1d2,Gg2g4,Yg4g5] White goes for the rock-solid Stonewall to hamper the [d6]-bishop and [c6]-knight. The normal problem with this structure is the weakness of the [e4]-square, but here the [c3]-knight secures it comfortably a3 stops any ...[Bb4] pin. We will play [Bd3] and [Bd2] followed by kingside expansion with [g2]-[g4] and potentially [g4]-[g5]. White will likely castle queenside, when Black will have to work hard and spend ample time to initiate a pawn storm notice how the knight on [c6] just gets in the way of this.} *

