1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Nc3 $5 ({This move is not seen nearly as often as the more popular} 6. b3 {. Nonetheless, it looks like the best and most fighting option. White keeps the position flexible and maintains options of moving [g3], [d3], or [b3]. Here, Black has six options, but we will primarily focus on the most popular one, ...[Bb4].}) 6... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4] The knight looks a bit strange being placed in front of the c-pawn like this, but in fact, the threat of ...[Nb4] is annoying and we should prevent it.} 7. a3 d4 $5 {An interesting way to create tension. We would never take, as it would give the [c6]-knight a prime spot in the center on [d4]. Instead, we must react calmly.} 8. Ne2 dxe3 9. dxe3 {Calmly preparing for an eventual [e3]-[e4], when our central control will begin to impress.} Be7 $2 {This is a natural mistake.} 10. Nc3 $1 {Reverting back to the old square. The black queen can no longer force a trade from [d5]. Our bishop is also ready to flex on [b5] or [d3] whenever we want.} O-O $2 {A logical move that makes the position even worse.} 11. Bd2 {[%cal Ge1c1] Preparing a healthy castle to the queenside.} Qd7 12. O-O-O {The queen begins to feel uncomfortable. With each move, we appreciate more and more why 9...Qd5 was essential.} Rad8 13. g4 $18 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg4g5,Gh3h4,Gh4h5] White will play [Bd3] which can't be harassed by any ...[Nc6]-[b4] hijinks and throw the pawns forward on the kingside with [g4]-[g5] and [h3]-[h4]-[h5]. White is already objectively winning.} *

