1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Nc3 $5 ({This move is not seen nearly as often as the more popular} 6. b3 {. Nonetheless, it looks like the best and most fighting option. White keeps the position flexible and maintains options of moving [g3], [d3], or [b3]. Here, Black has six options, but we will primarily focus on the most popular one, ...[Bb4].}) 6... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4] The knight looks a bit strange being placed in front of the c-pawn like this, but in fact, the threat of ...[Nb4] is annoying and we should prevent it.} 7. a3 d4 $5 {An interesting way to create tension. We would never take, as it would give the [c6]-knight a prime spot in the center on [d4]. Instead, we must react calmly.} 8. Ne2 Be7 {This allows us to trade favorably on [d4].} 9. exd4 {If Black doesn't take immediately, we will complete the thematic Christmas tree structure with [c2]-[c3].} Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 {The [c6]-knight has been traded off and from its absence, we spot a ripe apple on [b7].} 11. Qxb7 O-O 12. Qf3 $14 {Black is way ahead in development, but we will gradually push them back with [c3] and [d4]. We will eventually castle and be up a healthy pawn.} (12. Qf3 Ne4 {is Black's best bet, when the threat of ...[Bh4]+ warrants us to spend a move on pushing our pawn with} 13. h4 {. Instead, 13.g3?? Nxg3 cleans up on aisle 7! 14.Qxg3 Qe4 + -+ and the death of the mango leaves White's position with a rotten smell.}) *

