1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Nc3 $5 ({This move is not seen nearly as often as the more popular} 6. b3 {. Nonetheless, it looks like the best and most fighting option. White keeps the position flexible and maintains options of moving [g3], [d3], or [b3]. Here, Black has six options, but we will primarily focus on the most popular one, ...[Bb4].}) 6... c5 {This allows White to give a probing check with the bishop.} 7. Bb5+ Nbd7 ({Better than} 7... Nc6 {, as it avoids the structural weakening.}) 8. b3 Bd6 9. g4 a6 10. Bd3 {[%csl Gb2,Gd3][%cal Gc1b2] The bishops will load up on the queenside from [b2] and [d3]. This setup is an important one to remember for us. The [d3]-bishop will scope the light squares and the important [h7]-square while the [b2]-bishop, after [Nc3]-[e2], will stabilize the dark squares. Notice the knight on [d7] is not well placed. It almost always belongs on [c6], where it fights for [d4] and [e5]. So when it is not on this ideal square, we should not consider a trade for it.} O-O 11. Bb2 b5 {Continuing the advance on the queenside. White's [d3]-bishop is about to feel the heat of ...[c5]-[c4].} 12. g5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gg5f6] Booting Black's cavalry.} Ne8 13. h4 (13. Ne2 $2 {commits the cardinal positional sin of blocking both of our [d3]-bishop's diagonals. Indeed, it is simply trapped after} c4 {. Now, the double bishop sacrifice does not work at all here due to the [e8]-knight's defense of [g7].} 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 $1 {and Black survives. After 16...Kxg7 17.Qh6+ Kg8 18.g6 , obviously Black would have massive problems if not for the knight on [e8] protecting [g7]. In this position, both 18...Ndf6 and 18...fxg6 win for Black.}) 13... c4 14. Be2 $132 {[%csl Yc3,Yg4][%cal Gh4h5,Gg5g6,Gh5h6,Gc3d1,Gd1f2,Gf2g4] The bishop had to retreat to save itself. Here, White can continue expansion on the kingside while also entertaining a rerouting of the knight to [g4] via [c3]-[d1]-[f2]-[g4].} *

