1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Nc3 $5 ({This move is not seen nearly as often as the more popular} 6. b3 {. Nonetheless, it looks like the best and most fighting option. White keeps the position flexible and maintains options of moving [g3], [d3], or [b3]. Here, Black has six options, but we will primarily focus on the most popular one, ...[Bb4].}) 6... c5 {This allows White to give a probing check with the bishop.} 7. Bb5+ Nc6 $6 {This is a very logical move, but it allows a permanent weakening of the structure. The damage must be inflicted immediately.} 8. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6] The pawns on [c5] and [c6] constitute a lingering problem for Black's position.} 9. O-O c4 {[%cal Gf8b4] The [c5]-pawn is a target as long as it exists and it also blocked the [f8]-bishop. Meanwhile, if Black advances it to [c4] as in the current position, White can simply crunch on it with [b2]-[b3], when a trade on [b3] will allow [axb3] and the [a1]-rook to target a new weakness on [a7].} 10. b3 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb3c4] Allowing a pawn trade on [c4] would assign Black two hideous doubled c-pawns.} cxb3 11. axb3 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6][%cal Gc1b2,Ga1a4,Gf1a1] The [c5]-weakness might have disappeared, but Black's position remains full of problems; [a7] is weak, [c6] is weak. White will put a bishop on [b2] and potentially double on the a-file with [Ra1]-[a4] and [Rf1]-[a1]. White can also consider [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4] in order to challenge Black's healthy control over the [d5]-square.} *

