1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Nc3 $5 ({This move is not seen nearly as often as the more popular} 6. b3 {. Nonetheless, it looks like the best and most fighting option. White keeps the position flexible and maintains options of moving [g3], [d3], or [b3]. Here, Black has six options, but we will primarily focus on the most popular one, ...[Bb4].}) 6... c6 7. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5] Not hiding our aggressive intentions.} Nbd7 8. g5 {[%cal Gg5f6]} Ng8 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gg8e7,Ge7f5] While these positions are called level by the computer, I feel the White player with experience in how to handle them will have an enormous practical advantage over any unprepared opponent.} 9. h4 {White begins advancing the pawn. Notice that with the position so closed, White does not risk any punishment for investing so early in so many pawn moves.} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5]} 10. b3 Nf5 11. Bb2 {[%cal Gc3d1,Gd1f2,Gf2d3,Gf2g4] The knight will move to [d1] and [f2] and later [g4] or [d3] depending on circumstances. The [b2]-bishop offers White a serious edge. Notice with the white pawn phalanx from [d2]-[e3]-[f4]-[g5], Black has no way to place the bishop on, [f6], [e5], etc, to oppose ours.} Rg8 {[%cal Rb2h8,Gh8g8] Trying to get the rook out of the way to lay ...[g6] and finally get the bishop to [g7].} 12. h5 g6 13. h6 $14 {[%csl Rf8]} ({The bishop should give up on getting to the long diagonal already!} 13. e4 $1 {was objectively better, but who can resist the text move, which completely dominates Black's bishop?!?!?}) *

