1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bg4 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gg4d1,Ge7e6,Gf8e7] This is the most popular move in games played between 1200-1800s online, with 23% of the Black players electing for it. The bishop pins the knight. Black hopes to play ...[e6], ...[Be7], and develop normally with a quiet game. White should take the fight to Black by immediately challenging the pesky bishop.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Nc3 $5 ({This move is not seen nearly as often as the more popular} 6. b3 {. Nonetheless, it looks like the best and most fighting option. White keeps the position flexible and maintains options of moving [g3], [d3], or [b3]. Here, Black has six options, but we will primarily focus on the most popular one, ...[Bb4].}) 6... Be7 7. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5] White gains space and looks to evict the knight with [g4]-[g5].} Nc6 8. g5 Nd7 9. h4 d4 {A natural way for Black to try to resist the tide as they say. Now the game could follow an interesting and unique path.} ({After} 9... h6 10. d4 {, White will put the bishop on [d2] and castle queenside with a comfortable edge due to the space advantage.}) 10. Ne4 {The knight sits comfortably on [e4].} Nb4 {[%cal Rf1d3,Gb4d3] It is important to note here that White does not want to play [Bd3] allowing a trade for the knight on [b4]. Instead, White's move is quite unorthodox.} 11. Kd1 {[%cal Rd5d4,Gf3b7] Despite looking weird our king is safe here. Importantly, the ...[d5]-[d4] push by Black has compromised all the light squares on the long diagonal. This means that if we can eventually wiggle out, we should be better.} dxe3 12. d3 Nb6 13. Bxe3 Qd7 14. Bg2 Rd8 {White is slightly better due to the battering bishops. One line I particularly like is a pawn sacrifice aimed at reaching a pleasant endgame. It goes as follows:} 15. Bd2 Nc6 16. c3 Qxd3 17. Qxd3 Rxd3 18. Kc2 Rd8 19. Raf1 {[%csl Gd2,Gg2][%cal Gh4h5] White's [g2]-bishop continues to press against the board. White can continue advancing on the kingside in efforts to breach new barriers and unlock new pawn weaknesses.} *

