1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 {In this small chapter, we will deal with Black's choice of avoiding pushing ...c7-c5 early. Please see the chapter regarding 2...c5 3.e3 Nc6 for coverage of positions in which ...[Bf5] is combined with ...[c5] earlier on. As we will see, if our opponents play in this sneaky way, they can actually give us the most problems. Black needs to wait for us to commit our bishop to [e2] before playing ...[c5] since our classic response to ...[c5] is [Bf1]-[b5]. If we carry on with [b3] and [Bb2], then the computer insists we are just slightly worse. And while it is always possible to squeeze water from a stone, I did not want to spend ages to show we could get to boring equal endgames. If you like the queenside fianchetto enough and want to gamble that your opponent won't know to delay ...[c5] until after we've committed our bishop, then feel free to go for it in a similar spirit to the other chapters. The good news is: first off from 2.Nf3 , only 2% of Black players go for this. Here we have a very interesting rarely tried move. The one weak point of the bishop's placement on [f5] is that it gives us a tempo if we can achieve [e3]-[e4]. Can you guess what we should play????} 4. Nc3 $1 {The chances of your opponent having gone for this are very small so I'll keep the variations relatively brief. Suffice it to say that [Nc3] has only been seen in 4200 games at the time of writing. For a position on move 4, that is extremely low! We will try to throw in [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4] quickly. Our knight has cleared the [b1]-square so we only need to play [Bd2] and [Qe2] to castle queenside − this will be a recurring idea as well.} Nc6 {This is the 2nd most popular continuation, being chosen by 21% of Black players.} 5. Bb5 {The plan you already know. The knight has committed to [c6] and we can play [Bf1]-[b5] in one effective single move.} a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. d3 e6 8. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd1e2,Ge3e4] With a healthy edge against the doubled pawns. White will castle, play [Qe2] and [e3]-[e4].} *

