his is the best way for Black to deal with the pin.} 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 Bd6 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Ne5 $132 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2d4,Ge2g3] This looks similar to many positions we analyze in the 2...Nf6 3.e3 e6 setup, except with two conflicting differences. First, in White's favor, Black hasn't achieved ...[c7]-[c5] and the bishop on [c6] stands in the way of that natural push. In Black's favor, the white knight is misplaced on [c3]. We should move our knight to [e2] and from there to [d4] or [g3] depending on circumstances. We are not objectively better, but our experience in such structures should give us the upper hand.} *

