...[Nc6] with a classic setup where they have escaped the wrath of our [Bf1]-[b5]. We must not let them achieve this peacefully. If that happens, Black will not just be equal but will have a slight edge!} 6. Ne5 {Attacking [c6] and [g4]; both of these details will come to matter as you will see.} Bd6 {This leads to one of the most endgame variations in the course. Unfortunately, I couldn't avoid it, please forgive me.} 7. e4 dxe4 8. dxe4 Bxe5 (8... Bxe4 $2 {We can punish this natural capture with a few precise moves.} 9. Nb5 $1 Be7 10. Qxd8+ $1 {± , when Black has an uncomfortable choice − to allow a knight to [d6], or to allow one to [f7]!}) 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. fxe5 Nxe4 {We are down a pawn but have the bishop pair, and Black will have to burn a move or two fixing the king on [d8].} 11. g4 {[%cal Gf1g2] Opening the [g2]-square for our bishop with tempo.} Bg6 12. Bg2 Nxc3 13. Bxb7 (13. bxc3 Kc7 {∓ and we are down a pawn; [e5] and [c2] are weak so the bishop pair doesn't bridge the difference.}) 13... Be4 $1 {Attacking the bishop on [b7] and rook on [h1].} 14. Bxa8 Bxa8 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Ga8h1]} 15. Rf1 $13 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gf1f7] Black will save the knight and we will win [f7] with a very active rook on the 7th rank. Black has two minor pieces but they are a ways off from being properly coordinated. The game is completely dynamically balanced.} *

