1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5 {In this small chapter, we will deal with Black's choice of avoiding pushing ...c7-c5 early. Please see the chapter regarding 2...c5 3.e3 Nc6 for coverage of positions in which ...[Bf5] is combined with ...[c5] earlier on. As we will see, if our opponents play in this sneaky way, they can actually give us the most problems. Black needs to wait for us to commit our bishop to [e2] before playing ...[c5] since our classic response to ...[c5] is [Bf1]-[b5]. If we carry on with [b3] and [Bb2], then the computer insists we are just slightly worse. And while it is always possible to squeeze water from a stone, I did not want to spend ages to show we could get to boring equal endgames. If you like the queenside fianchetto enough and want to gamble that your opponent won't know to delay ...[c5] until after we've committed our bishop, then feel free to go for it in a similar spirit to the other chapters. The good news is: first off from 2.Nf3 , only 2% of Black players go for this. Here we have a very interesting rarely tried move. The one weak point of the bishop's placement on [f5] is that it gives us a tempo if we can achieve [e3]-[e4]. Can you guess what we should play????} 4. Nc3 $1 {The chances of your opponent having gone for this are very small so I'll keep the variations relatively brief. Suffice it to say that [Nc3] has only been seen in 4200 games at the time of writing. For a position on move 4, that is extremely low! We will try to throw in [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4] quickly. Our knight has cleared the [b1]-square so we only need to play [Bd2] and [Qe2] to castle queenside − this will be a recurring idea as well.} e6 {This move enjoys the most popularity, being played in 59% of games.} 5. d3 {Simple chess. We stunt the [f5]-bishop and prepare ideas of [Qe2] and [e3]-[e4]; [Ne5] and [g4] might also be an idea.} Bb4 {The pin is the most popular, with 32% of games going for it.} 6. a3 {Will the bishop trade or not?} Ba5 {This is a common mistake in this position. We'll snag the bishop pair yet again.} 7. b4 Bb6 8. Na4 $14 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Ya4b6,Yc7c6,Ya7a6] We don't need to rush to take on [b6]. We'll capture only when the bishop threatens to run away, for instance after ...[c7]-[c6] or ...[a7]-[a6]. We'll play [Be2], castle kingside, and then capture on [b6]. Our bishop on [c1] will fit perfectly on [b2] from where it will survey the board. Notice we do not want to play [Bb2] while the [b6]-bishop is still on the board exerting pressure on [e3].} *

