1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 Be7 ({This is seen slightly less frequently than} 4... c5 {, being played 25% of the time.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Rg1 $1 {[%cal Gg2g5,Gg4g5,Gg2g4] Kicking the game into top gear. White's g-pawn will go from 0-100 as it runs down the board. This has only appeared 47 times in online games so it will likely take your opponent by surprise. It is also objectively sound, with the computer indicating a balanced game after the best play by both sides.} Ne4 {[%cal Rg2g4,Ge7h4] The best move although it has only been played in 9% of the games. Black's bishop and queen battery create the option of ...[Bh4]+ so we can't play [g2]-[g4] just yet.} 7. Nc3 {Trading off the knight on [e4].} (7. d3 $2 {is actually quite a big mistake. After} Nd6 {, Black will play ...[c7]-[c5] and ...[b7]-[b5] when, if White attempts to castle queenside, that will be met with an immediate pawn storm. Moreover, Black will be able to play ...[d5]-[d4] whenever they need to stunt the [b2]-bishop.}) 7... c5 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Ng5 {[%csl Re4] Flicking our knight out and attacking [e4] at the same time.} Bxg5 10. fxg5 Qxg5 11. Qe2 b6 12. g4 Ba6 13. Qg2 Bxf1 14. Rxf1 f5 (14... Qh4+ 15. Rf2 {doesn't inconvenience White at all.}) 15. O-O-O Qxg4 16. Qf2 $13 {[%cal Gf1g1] Black is up two pawns but the king is vulnerable and White's bishop rakes the board. The game is balanced but I'd happily take White if I had to choose.} *

