1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 Be7 ({This is seen slightly less frequently than} 4... c5 {, being played 25% of the time.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Rg1 $1 {[%cal Gg2g5,Gg4g5,Gg2g4] Kicking the game into top gear. White's g-pawn will go from 0-100 as it runs down the board. This has only appeared 47 times in online games so it will likely take your opponent by surprise. It is also objectively sound, with the computer indicating a balanced game after the best play by both sides.} Nc6 {It doesn't seem to make much sense to block the c-pawn like this, but it has been tried enough to merit our attention. The knight on [c6] and bishop on [e7] don't make much sense, as the knight is geared toward the ...[e5] push but the bishop is aimed at the ...[c5] push.} 7. a3 {[%cal Rc6b4,Gf1d3] ...[Nb4] is prevented and White can entertain ideas of [Bd3].} a5 8. Be2 (8. Bd3 {immediately would restrict White's development. After} Ne4 9. Nc3 {, Black has many options to keep the game on equal terms:} Nc5 {, 9...Nxc3 , or 9...f5 .}) 8... Bd6 (8... Ne4 {can now be met with} 9. c4 {followed by [Qc2], [Nc3], etc. Had the bishop been on [d3], ...[Nc5] would have been unpleasant.}) 9. g3 {Strengthening [f4] in anticipation of ...[d5]-[d4].} ({Notice how White doesn't respond with} 9. g4 {, as Black will react with} d4 $1 {, when} 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bxf4 {is very unpleasant for us. Instead, we will go about it more calmly...}) 9... Re8 10. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5e8] The bishop pins the knight and freezes out ...[e5].} Bd7 {Now Black can't play ...[e6]-[e5] due to White always having [Bxc6].} 11. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5]} e5 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. fxe5 {[%cal Ge5d6,Ge5f6] White is already close to winning though Black can muddy the waters with some fireworks in the center.} d4 {[%cal Gc6h1] Unleashing the power of the sun.} 14. g5 $1 ({White must not stumble, as the consequences could be grave.} 14. exf6 $4 dxe3 {, too much tension in the center leaves the white king besieged.}) 14... Rxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. gxf6 Qxf6 {In spite of being up a rook, White's king is exposed, and we must find the next precise move to keep our advantage.} 17. Qh5 $16 {[%cal Rf6h4,Re5h2,Gg1f1,Gc6f3,Ye1d1,Yd1c1] Covering ...[Qh4]+ and ...[Bxh2]. White will likely bring the king to the queenside with [Rf1] to cover against ...[Bf3] via [Ke1]-[d1]-[c1] slowly since the knight can't use [c3] for the time being. We are up a rook, but the position remains murky.} *

