1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 Be7 ({This is seen slightly less frequently than} 4... c5 {, being played 25% of the time.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Rg1 $1 {[%cal Gg2g5,Gg4g5,Gg2g4] Kicking the game into top gear. White's g-pawn will go from 0-100 as it runs down the board. This has only appeared 47 times in online games so it will likely take your opponent by surprise. It is also objectively sound, with the computer indicating a balanced game after the best play by both sides.} c5 7. g4 Nc6 8. g5 Ne4 9. Bd3 {[%cal Gb1c3] White looks to play [Nc3] and trade off Black's steed on [e4].} (9. d3 $2 {It is essential to remember why this natural move doesn't work. After} Nd6 {∓ , Black will soon play ...[Nf5], when our weak pawn on [e3] will suffer a long time.}) 9... f5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf5e4] This solidifies the knight on [e4] but weakens the [e5]-square. With the knight on [e4] so secure, [Nc3] wouldn't pack any punch. And so we deviate to a more positional strategy...} 10. Bb5 $132 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rf7f5,Gb5c6,Rc6e5,Gf3e5,Yd2d3,Yb1d2,Yd2f3] Looking to trade on [c6] and install a knight on [e5]. After achieving [Ne5], White will play [d2]-[d3], [Nbd2], and [Nd2]-[f3]. The game is objectively balanced, but White's play looks easier. It goes without saying that such an unusual position will give the player who has more experience with it, an enormous practical edge.} *

