1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 Be7 ({This is seen slightly less frequently than} 4... c5 {, being played 25% of the time.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Rg1 $1 {[%cal Gg2g5,Gg4g5,Gg2g4] Kicking the game into top gear. White's g-pawn will go from 0-100 as it runs down the board. This has only appeared 47 times in online games so it will likely take your opponent by surprise. It is also objectively sound, with the computer indicating a balanced game after the best play by both sides.} c5 7. g4 d4 {This was recommended by Grandelius in his Grand Toolbox course. We will respond logically and aggressively.} 8. g5 Nd5 {The knight pressures [e3]. Remember in such situations to never budge! We must not move the [e3]-pawn on pain of the rest of our phalanx collapsing. Instead, we must punch from the other side.} 9. Na3 $1 {Our knight comes to [c4], when it will increase our sway over the heavily contended dark squares.} dxe3 {I expect most players to go for this here. After all, it is a free pawn.} (9... Nc6 {can be met with} 10. Nc4 {with a very complex, balanced, and interesting battle to come.}) 10. Nc4 $1 {Entering the arena. Black has a choice of apples to pick.} exd2+ 11. Qxd2 {This leads to a position in which we have enormous compensation. We will castle queenside and throw the kitchen sink at Black on the kingside. A line I very much like is:} Nc6 12. O-O-O b6 {Black simply continues development as if nothing is the matter and is not down a million tempi in this race between the flanks.} 13. f5 $1 {Introducing threats of [f5]-[f6] and [fxe6]! The pawn is untouchable due to the pressure against the lonely pony on [d5].} Bb7 {At this point, Black is just asking for it.} 14. f6 $1 Bd6 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 16. fxg7 {Taking the chocolate syrup.} Rfd8 17. c4 $1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd1d8] Before eating the ice cream! The knight will drop on [d5] and White is winning.} *

