1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 Be7 ({This is seen slightly less frequently than} 4... c5 {, being played 25% of the time.}) 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Rg1 $1 {[%cal Gg2g5,Gg4g5,Gg2g4] Kicking the game into top gear. White's g-pawn will go from 0-100 as it runs down the board. This has only appeared 47 times in online games so it will likely take your opponent by surprise. It is also objectively sound, with the computer indicating a balanced game after the best play by both sides.} c5 7. g4 d4 {This was recommended by Grandelius in his Grand Toolbox course. We will respond logically and aggressively.} 8. g5 Nd5 {The knight pressures [e3]. Remember in such situations to never budge! We must not move the [e3]-pawn on pain of the rest of our phalanx collapsing. Instead, we must punch from the other side.} 9. Na3 $1 {Our knight comes to [c4], when it will increase our sway over the heavily contended dark squares.} dxe3 {I expect most players to go for this here. After all, it is a free pawn.} (9... Nc6 {can be met with} 10. Nc4 {with a very complex, balanced, and interesting battle to come.}) 10. Nc4 $1 {Entering the arena. Black has a choice of apples to pick.} Nxf4 11. dxe3 $1 {Our structure without the f-pawn looks hideous and we're down a pawn, so why not trade queens?!?!?!?!? Well, our pieces will more than make up for it!} Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 {The black knight as we will see begins to have serious problems.} Nd5 (12... Ng6 13. h4 $1 {and we'll bury the knight in the corner with [h4]-[h5]. Following} Nc6 14. h5 Nh8 15. Bd3 {+- , we're down a pawn but just look at Black's kingside!}) 13. e4 Nb4 {[%csl Rc2] Attacking [c2], but we can respond in grand fashion.} 14. Rg2 $1 {Our pieces paint a beautiful portrait. Black's position continues to teeter on the brink. It is very easy for Black to fall apart with a few imprecise moves.} b6 $6 15. Bf6 $1 {[%csl Re7] Attacking the bishop on [e7], which doesn't have much of anywhere to run!} N8c6 $2 (15... N4c6 {would have kept Black's position afloat.}) 16. c3 Na6 17. Nce5 $1 {The initiative never abates.} Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Bxf6 19. gxf6 g6 20. Bb5 $18 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gb5c6] White is still down a pawn but has an ironclad grip on the position. We will install the bishop on [c6] and invade with the rooks down the d-file at the proper moment. Not a single one of Black's pieces has prospects, and the [f6]-pawn is grooved firmly in place, making the position always full of back-rank checkmating threats.} *

