1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 Bd6 {This is played 15% of the time. The bishop fights more directly against White's control over the [e5]-square, but this scheme seems slightly awkward. The black pawn will likely come to [c5] at some point and that formation is traditionally best paired with a bishop on [e7]. By blocking the d-file, it will be hard for Black to push for ...[d5]-[d4], which is a common idea in other lines.} 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Rg1 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] This move is a rarity and the resulting position has only been reached 24 times. It will certainly take your opponent by surprise. Buckle up, it's gonna be a bumpy ride.} c5 {Preparing ...[d5]-[d4] to stunt White's pressure along the long diagonal.} 7. g4 Nc6 8. g5 {The pawn goes a step farther clearing the [f6]-knight and getting a better grasp on the diagonal.} Nh5 {[%cal Gd1h5,Rh2h4,Rh4h5] The knight looks a bit awkward out here on [h5] we might have tricks with the queen's x-ray on [h5] but capitalizing on this isn't so easy. The knight stops our h-pawn's advance and so our response will be very different from what we play against ...[Nd7].} (8... Ne4 $2 {just drops a piece.} 9. d3 Qa5+ 10. c3 {+- and the knight is lost.}) 9. Qe2 g6 {[%cal Gg6h5] Securing the [h5]-knight.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Ge1c1] Preparing castling queenside.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black wants to pawn storm on the queenside with ...[b7]-[b5].} 11. O-O-O b5 12. Bh3 {[%cal Gh3g4]} c4 13. Bg4 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gg4h5] The threat of [Bxh5] looks serious but actually, Black is best advised to accept it.} a5 ({The best move.} 13... Ng7 $2 {This natural move is actually a blunder. After} 14. h4 {→ , White will play [h4]-[h5] and begin an attack with [Qh2] and [Rh1]. We will be first to the punch before Black's queenside play gets going.}) 14. Bxh5 gxh5 $2 (14... a4 $3 {∞ and White is up a piece, but the game is objectively unclear, as Black is about to begin crashing through on the queenside.}) 15. Nh4 {[%cal Ge2h5,Gg5g6] Qxh5 with ideas of [g5]-[g6] should win one way or another.} *

