d Black threatens ...[Qh4]+.} ({The greedy} 9... Bxf4 {will soon bring Black into big trouble since after} 10. g5 Ne8 11. Qh5 {, White will finish development with [Bb2], [Nc3], [O-O-O], and initiate a powerful attack.}) 10. Bb2 {This holds the balance for White.} Qh4+ 11. Ke2 {We must remember to play this very counterintuitive move. No central files are open and for the moment White's king is sufficiently safe. If Black waits, we will simply play [Qe1]-[g3], when our king can hide on [d1] if need be.} (11. Rg3 $4 e5 12. f5 e4 {-+ and White is busted.}) 11... Qxh2+ 12. Rg2 Qh6 13. Nc3 $13 {[%cal Gd1e1,Ge1g3] I'll stop the analysis here. I expect no Black player to ever reach this position without having bought this course. The game is balanced and crazy. We could start by transferring our queen over to [g3] via [e1].} *

