1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 Bd6 {This is played 15% of the time. The bishop fights more directly against White's control over the [e5]-square, but this scheme seems slightly awkward. The black pawn will likely come to [c5] at some point and that formation is traditionally best paired with a bishop on [e7]. By blocking the d-file, it will be hard for Black to push for ...[d5]-[d4], which is a common idea in other lines.} 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Rg1 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] This move is a rarity and the resulting position has only been reached 24 times. It will certainly take your opponent by surprise. Buckle up, it's gonna be a bumpy ride.} Nc6 {It makes sense to bring in pieces to fight for the center in an attempt to fight White's attack with the g-pawn.} 7. g4 {Already Black's back is up against the wall. In real games, Black has yet to find the proper response.} Re8 {Preparing the thematic ...[e6]-[e5] push. If given time to play this move, Black will be in the driver's seat.} 8. g5 {Encroaching on Black's camp. The [f6]-knight is kicked from its nice position.} Nd7 9. d4 {[%csl Rc6,Rd6,Rd7][%cal Gd4c5,Gd4e5] Cramping all of Black's minor pieces. The [d7]-knight, [c6]-knight, and bishop on [d6] all point into White's pawns. That's not even mentioning the dormant [c8]-bishop. White will play [Nc3], [Bd3], and [Qd2] or [Qe2]. Depending on how things shake out, the king might park on [f2] or castle queenside.} Ne7 {The knight transfers to the strong [f5]-square.} 10. Nc3 Nf5 {[%cal Gf5e3]} 11. Qd2 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gd2e3]} c5 {[%cal Gc5d4] Black engages the [d4]-strongpoint and seeks to exchange some pawns easing the cramp. We should ignore the push − after all, our pawn on [e3] keeps everything under control.} 12. O-O-O Qa5 {Here we have a counterintuitive way to secure an advantage.} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nd4 {[%csl Rd5,Rf5][%cal Gd4f5,Gc3d5] Threatening a structure-wrecking [Nxf5] followed by [Nxd5].} Nxd4 15. exd4 Bb4 {Black has some pressure on the [a5]-[e1] diagonal, but look at the rest of their pieces! Black has no other counterplay.} 16. Kb1 Nf8 {[%cal Gc8d7] Space has to be created for ...[Bd7] and ...[Rac8] somehow.} 17. h4 Bd7 18. h5 Rac8 19. Rg3 $16 {[%cal Gg3c3] White will escape the pin next move with [Qd2]-[e3]. Our pawns dominate the board and Black's pieces are stuck. White will slowly prepare a gradual attack on the kingside with a rerouting of the [c3]-knight to somewhere like [g4] or [e5]. When the time is right, [g5]-[g6] or [h5]-[h6] should decide.} (19. Rg3 {A sample line is} Rc7 20. Qe3 {(with the idea [Qe5] followed by [h6])} Rec8 21. Qe5 $1 ({not} 21. Rd3 e5 $1 {, when the complications favor Black}) 21... Bxc3 22. h6 f6 23. gxf6 g6 24. f5 $1 Bxb2 (24... exf5 25. Rxc3 Rxc3 26. Qe7 {is where we see the point of f5.}) 25. fxg6 hxg6 26. h7+ Kxh7 27. f7 {with mate to follow soon. Also after 21...Rxc3 instead, Black's position will remain in the line of fire: 22.Bxc3 Rxc3 23.Rxc3 Bxc3 24.Rd3 , with the same [h6] mating ideas.}) *

