e [d7]-knight, [c6]-knight, and bishop on [d6] all point into White's pawns. That's not even mentioning the dormant [c8]-bishop. White will play [Nc3], [Bd3], and [Qd2] or [Qe2]. Depending on how things shake out, the king might park on [f2] or castle queenside.} Ne7 {The knight transfers to the strong [f5]-square.} 10. Nc3 Nf5 {[%cal Gf5e3]} 11. Qd2 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gd2e3]} c5 {[%cal Gc5d4] Black engages the [d4]-strongpoint and seeks to exchange some pawns easing the cramp. We should ignore the push − after all, our pawn on [e3] keeps everything under control.} 12. O-O-O Qa5 {Here we have a counterintuitive way to secure an advantage.} 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Nd4 {[%csl Rd5,Rf5][%cal Gd4f5,Gc3d5] Threatening a structure-wrecking [Nxf5] followed by [Nxd5].} Nd6 15. Kb1 {[%csl Rd6,Rd7][%cal Rc8d7,Rc5d6] Black's knights offer a strange impression whose strength isn't immediately clear. However, looking at how disharmoniously they block the bishops, it becomes obvious they are not ideally placed.} Bb4 {[%cal Gd6e4] ...[Ne4] is a big threat.} 16. Bd3 {[%cal Rd6e4,Gd3e4] Covering any ...[Ne4] ideas.} Nf8 17. Ndb5 {[%cal Ga2a3] Creating the threat of [a2]-[a3], which makes Black trade on [b5].} Nxb5 18. Bxb5 Bd7 19. Qd4 $16 {[%csl Gb2,Gd4][%cal Gb2g7] Creating strong pressure on the long diagonal.} e5 {It's important to know how to respond to this. If White slips up here, either ...[Bxb5] or ...[Bxc3] will grab a piece.} 20. Qxd5 {[%csl Rc3,Rd7][%cal Gd5d7,Gb4c3,Gb5d7] Our attack on the [d7]-bishop evens the threat to the hanging knight on [c3].} Bxb5 21. Nxb5 $16 {With a safer king and a healthy pawn, we are close to winning.} *

