1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Be7 {This seems to be the most testing, even though it has only been chosen in 33% of games.} 6. Bb5+ Nbd7 {Quite a rare continuation, at a frequency of 9%. But any move that avoids the structural weakening after ...[Nc6] [Bxc6]+ must be investigated. Black's move rates surprisingly high, with the computer intuiting that Black has a slight edge after perfect play. Fortunately for us, we are not interested in proving an objective advantage with 30 moves of opening theory. We want to enter a chaotic maze that only we will know the way out of.} (6... Nc6 {is played a third of the time but just transposes to 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Be7 .}) 7. Bd3 $3 {Perhaps this doesn't deserve 2 exclamation marks but what can I say, I love it. It is objectively sound and it has been played in only 5 games out of 2548. This means that it will have the effect of a novelty against the vast majority of your opponents. The move carries a unique beauty. We didn't go to [d3] immediately because the knight could have harassed it via [c6]-[b4]. Here, on the other hand, the knight is farther away. We will scope the kingside with our two bishops on [d3] and [b2]. Because our [d2]-pawn can't move, we will avert away from the classic plan of [d2]-[d3] and [Nb1]-[d2] and instead opt for [Nc3] with more sophisticated knight transfers in mind.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc5c4] With the not so subtle idea of advancing ...[b7]-[b5] and then to gradually evict our fancy bishop with ...[c5]-[c4].} (7... b6 8. O-O O-O {will just transpose to 7...O-O 8.O-O b6 .}) 8. c4 $1 Nb6 $2 {This was played in the only game to reach this position.} 9. Qc2 $14 {The knight on [b6] and pawn on [a6] offer a weirdly benign impression. Obviously, the knight isn't placed well and will have to burn time rerouting elsewhere in the future. We will castle and play [Nc3] with good play. Notice that, because the black knight is nowhere close to [c6], we had no reason to fear ...[Nc6]-[b4] and so placed our queen on [c2] without a worry.} *

