1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Be7 {This seems to be the most testing, even though it has only been chosen in 33% of games.} 6. Bb5+ Nbd7 {Quite a rare continuation, at a frequency of 9%. But any move that avoids the structural weakening after ...[Nc6] [Bxc6]+ must be investigated. Black's move rates surprisingly high, with the computer intuiting that Black has a slight edge after perfect play. Fortunately for us, we are not interested in proving an objective advantage with 30 moves of opening theory. We want to enter a chaotic maze that only we will know the way out of.} (6... Nc6 {is played a third of the time but just transposes to 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Be7 .}) 7. Bd3 $3 {Perhaps this doesn't deserve 2 exclamation marks but what can I say, I love it. It is objectively sound and it has been played in only 5 games out of 2548. This means that it will have the effect of a novelty against the vast majority of your opponents. The move carries a unique beauty. We didn't go to [d3] immediately because the knight could have harassed it via [c6]-[b4]. Here, on the other hand, the knight is farther away. We will scope the kingside with our two bishops on [d3] and [b2]. Because our [d2]-pawn can't move, we will avert away from the classic plan of [d2]-[d3] and [Nb1]-[d2] and instead opt for [Nc3] with more sophisticated knight transfers in mind.} O-O (7... b6 8. O-O O-O {will just transpose to 7...O-O 8.O-O b6 .}) 8. O-O b6 9. c4 {Fighting for the center and introducing some tension to the position.} Bb7 10. Nc3 Ne4 {Taking here would be positionally unwise. A black pawn on [e4] would dig into our weak [d3]-square. Of course, there also might be the tactical issue of ...[dxe4], hitting our [d3]-bishop and [f3]-knight, but my point is that regardless of this, we do not want our weak [d3]-square exposed. After ...[dxe4], it will be pressing upon [d3] and also have opened up the d-file Black's rooks to pressure down via [d8].} 11. Qc2 Ndf6 12. Ng5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gg5e4] Initiating tension on the black knight. Only one move holds equality for Black, but it is not at all obvious.} Nxg5 $4 {A natural capture...} (12... Nxc3 13. Bxh7+ Kh8 14. Bxc3 {+- and we're just up a kingside pawn, making an attack against the black king a good idea long term.}) 13. fxg5 {Black is just busted now!} Ne4 14. cxd5 $1 {This forces the [c4] and [e6]-pawns out of the way, which will make an enormous difference later in the variation.} exd5 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Qc3 {And the point is revealed. Similar to other variations, Black has to play ...[f6] but without [e6] and [c4] on the board, White will have opportunities on the diagonal.} f6 17. Bc4+ Kh8 18. Rf2 $18 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ga1f1] It's hard to believe, but White is just winning. White will build pressure on the f-file with [Raf1] and this, combined with the weakness of [e4] being stranded away from the rest of the structure, spells Black's defeat.} Bd5 19. Raf1 Bxc4 20. Qxc4 {[%csl Re4] And the [e4]-pawn will drop!} *

