ng the [f3]-knight on the fertile [e5]-soil.}) 15. Ne5 {The knight lands in prime real estate. But where is our play following this?} Kh8 {Sidestepping [Bc4] tricks.} 16. d4 $1 {We are happy to open the d-file. The point is that the [f5]-[e4] pawn phalanx weakens Black's whole position. It blocks the knight on [f6] and bishop on [b7] from doing active things in the center. Meanwhile, [f5] can never move back to [f6], making the black king a permanent target for our latently strong [b2]-bishop. In short, Black has lots of weaknesses due to being overextended and this is best exploited by opening up the c- and d-files.} exd3 17. Bxd3 {[%csl Rf5] The [f5]-pawn must be defended somehow; ...[g7]-[g6] is ill-advised, as Black's kingside dark squares would be way too vulnerable in that case.} Ne4 18. Rad1 Qe8 19. Qe2 {[%cal Gd3b5] White can count on [Bb5], bringing fantastic activity with [Rd7] later on.} a6 {Stopping White's idea, but there was another hidden threat in the position...} 20. Bxe4 Bxe4 21. Nd7 {Oops! White nabs a pawn with the fork. The knight will capture on [b6] before rerouting back to [e5] via [c4]. White is a clean pawn up with great winning chances.} *

