1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Be7 {This seems to be the most testing, even though it has only been chosen in 33% of games.} 6. Bb5+ Nbd7 {Quite a rare continuation, at a frequency of 9%. But any move that avoids the structural weakening after ...[Nc6] [Bxc6]+ must be investigated. Black's move rates surprisingly high, with the computer intuiting that Black has a slight edge after perfect play. Fortunately for us, we are not interested in proving an objective advantage with 30 moves of opening theory. We want to enter a chaotic maze that only we will know the way out of.} (6... Nc6 {is played a third of the time but just transposes to 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Be7 .}) 7. Bd3 $3 {Perhaps this doesn't deserve 2 exclamation marks but what can I say, I love it. It is objectively sound and it has been played in only 5 games out of 2548. This means that it will have the effect of a novelty against the vast majority of your opponents. The move carries a unique beauty. We didn't go to [d3] immediately because the knight could have harassed it via [c6]-[b4]. Here, on the other hand, the knight is farther away. We will scope the kingside with our two bishops on [d3] and [b2]. Because our [d2]-pawn can't move, we will avert away from the classic plan of [d2]-[d3] and [Nb1]-[d2] and instead opt for [Nc3] with more sophisticated knight transfers in mind.} O-O (7... b6 8. O-O O-O {will just transpose to 7...O-O 8.O-O b6 .}) 8. O-O b6 9. c4 {Fighting for the center and introducing some tension to the position.} Bb7 10. Nc3 Ne4 {Taking here would be positionally unwise. A black pawn on [e4] would dig into our weak [d3]-square. Of course, there also might be the tactical issue of ...[dxe4], hitting our [d3]-bishop and [f3]-knight, but my point is that regardless of this, we do not want our weak [d3]-square exposed. After ...[dxe4], it will be pressing upon [d3] and also have opened up the d-file Black's rooks to pressure down via [d8].} 11. Qc2 f5 {Black takes on a Stonewall structure to cement the [e4]-knight further. The drawback is that it weakens the [e5]-square terminally, potentially giving us a good outpost for our knight long term.} 12. Be2 {Many alternatives exist, but I wanted to choose the one with the most flexibility. Our move removes the bishop from [d3] where it was no longer pressuring the [e4]-steed in any capacity. Meanwhile, we can play [d2]-[d3] at the right time to evict the knight. There are many plans for both sides. Given the fact that this position is extremely unlikely to be reached, I will limit myself to a few illustrative variations.} dxc4 {This is always positionally ruinous in the Stonewall structures since it gives us a clean shot of the [e6]-weakness.} 13. Bxc4 Rf6 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. d3 {[%csl Re4,Rf6][%cal Gb2f6] Black will have to trade the bishop for the knight on [f3] to not lose material.} Bxf3 16. Rxf3 (16. Bxf6 $4 Bxf6 $1 {, when our hanging rook gives Black everything they need to hold on.}) 16... Rg6 17. e4 {[%cal Ge4f5,Ga1e1] Black avoided material losses but the pieces are all terrible. Black's rook on [g6] isn't part of an attack so it is just misplaced. White has several ways to continue, the most straightforward being to double rooks on the e-file and open things up with [exf5].} *

