1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Be7 {This seems to be the most testing, even though it has only been chosen in 33% of games.} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 ({This is the natural and overwhelming popular continuation being chosen in 57% of games.} 6... Nc6 {is played a third of the time but just transposes to 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Be7 .}) 7. Bxd7+ {This might seem to simplify, but we are left with good pieces and a seriously asymmetrical structure. White should have full chances in the upcoming struggle.} Qxd7 $1 {This is played 19% of the time. The queen capture is more natural for Black's setup and the knight will heavily benefit from being able to be deployed to [c6] in one move. Indeed, in the lines of ...[Nbxd7], Stockfish frequently indicates Black should burn a tempo to achieve this with ...[Nd7]-[b8]-[c6]. Because of this [c6]-knight, we will not be advancing [c2]-[c4] like in the lines of ...[Nbxd7]. Objectively White has no more than equality in the lines that follow, but that doesn't mean we can't seek double-edged positions that will offer good practical chances.} 8. Qe2 {Ne5 would also be fine, but I don't like how it leads to simple exchanges for Black after the inevitable ...[Nb8]-[c6]. The more pieces that we can keep in the position the better. [Qe2] keeps things more flexible and prepares thematic ideas of [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4]. It is only played 1% of the time, endowing it to have a strong surprise effect on your opponent who's likely to have never seen it before.} Nc6 9. O-O a6 {[%cal Gb7b5]} ({This has been tried a few times. It carries the obvious intention of advancing ...b7-b5.} 9... O-O 10. Ne5 {will just transpose to 8...O-O .}) 10. d3 b5 11. Ne5 (11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Nd4 13. Nxd4 cxd4 {⇆ and our [c2]-pawn will feel quite weak, as Black doubles down the file with heavy pieces; [e4] is also under pressure. White is ahead in development, so things are objectively okay nonetheless.}) 11... Qc7 12. Nd2 O-O 13. c4 {The position is not going to be resolved anytime soon. With [c2]-[c4] we prevent any funny business with ...[c5]-[c4] for Black to open the queenside.} Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Qd7 15. e4 $13 {[%cal Gf1f3,Ga1f1,Ga1e1] Our d-file is a bit vulnerable so it makes sense to cover [d3] with [Rf3]. We can follow up with [Raf1] or [Ra1]-[e1]. On the itinerary are ideas of [f4]-[f5] to open the f-file, or trading on [f6] followed by [e4]-[e5].} *

