ine, but I don't like how it leads to simple exchanges for Black after the inevitable ...[Nb8]-[c6]. The more pieces that we can keep in the position the better. [Qe2] keeps things more flexible and prepares thematic ideas of [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4]. It is only played 1% of the time, endowing it to have a strong surprise effect on your opponent who's likely to have never seen it before.} O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Ne5 {This might seem to simplify, but I really like the statistics here. 50 percent of players have traded on [e5] immediately, setting the tune for a rich strategic battle.} Qc7 {This is the much simpler response, but one that is rarely ventured just the same. Black wants to trade on [e5] and respond to White's [fxe5] with ...[Nf6]-[d7].} 11. d3 d4 {Black immediately tries to shut out our bishop.} 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. e4 {We must react quickly here. If we dawdle around and allow Black to throw the pawns forward on the queenside, we will be worse. Black would love to advance ...[b7]-[b5] and ...[c5]-[c4] to open up the game and create play on the c-file. Our [e3]-[e4] takes away the classic regrouping ...[Nf6]-[d5]. It also releases any pressure on [d4], making our bishop on [b2] to be pointed at concrete − we will have to reroute the bishop to [c1] sooner or later.} b5 {While this is obvious to players at a grandmaster level, I don't think such an advance will be so obvious to your opponents. For one thing, this structure doesn't normally arise from their [e6]-[d5] opening setup and so they will likely not be familiar with the thematic ideas.} 14. a4 {Trying to poke a hole in the [c4]-square.} a6 $1 ({The only move to hold things together.} 14... b4 {is strategically terrible. We get the [c4]-square for our knight on a platter and Black has no way to break through long term. For now, the computer thinks White is only slightly better, but this should grow as it's able to sit here and get to higher depths.}) 15. Nd2 Nd7 16. Nf3 $13 {[%cal Gb2c1,Gc1d2,Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] We will play [Bc1]-[d2] shortly, where our bishop won't be similarly obstructed as it is momentarily on [b2] by the [d4]-concrete. We will look to advance our pawns on the kingside: [g2]-[g4]-[g5] or [h2]-[h4]-[h5] come to mind. Black will look to play ...[c5]-[c4] sooner or later and when that happens, it is critical for us to not panic and simply work to minimize the amount of vulnerable points on the queenside.} *

