1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Be7 {This seems to be the most testing, even though it has only been chosen in 33% of games.} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 ({This is the natural and overwhelming popular continuation being chosen in 57% of games.} 6... Nc6 {is played a third of the time but just transposes to 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Be7 .}) 7. Bxd7+ {This might seem to simplify, but we are left with good pieces and a seriously asymmetrical structure. White should have full chances in the upcoming struggle.} Qxd7 $1 {This is played 19% of the time. The queen capture is more natural for Black's setup and the knight will heavily benefit from being able to be deployed to [c6] in one move. Indeed, in the lines of ...[Nbxd7], Stockfish frequently indicates Black should burn a tempo to achieve this with ...[Nd7]-[b8]-[c6]. Because of this [c6]-knight, we will not be advancing [c2]-[c4] like in the lines of ...[Nbxd7]. Objectively White has no more than equality in the lines that follow, but that doesn't mean we can't seek double-edged positions that will offer good practical chances.} 8. Qe2 {Ne5 would also be fine, but I don't like how it leads to simple exchanges for Black after the inevitable ...[Nb8]-[c6]. The more pieces that we can keep in the position the better. [Qe2] keeps things more flexible and prepares thematic ideas of [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4]. It is only played 1% of the time, endowing it to have a strong surprise effect on your opponent who's likely to have never seen it before.} O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Ne5 {This might seem to simplify, but I really like the statistics here. 50 percent of players have traded on [e5] immediately, setting the tune for a rich strategic battle.} Qc7 {This is the much simpler response, but one that is rarely ventured just the same. Black wants to trade on [e5] and respond to White's [fxe5] with ...[Nf6]-[d7].} 11. d3 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 (12. fxe5 Nd7 {would be no good. Our pawn on [e5] is too weak and we have to push another pawn to a dark square with [d4] to defend it, making our bishop really terrible.} 13. d4 Rac8 {⩱ , with uncomfortable pressure of ...[cxd4] and ...[Qxc2].}) 12... Qc6 13. Nd2 d4 $2 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf6d7] With the idea of ...[Nd7] next, to entrap our cornered bishop.} 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gd2e4] With a huge initiative. We will kick the bishop out with [e4]-[e5] and then follow up with [Ne4] and [Qg4] followed by a rook lift from [f1]-[f3]-[g3].} *

