ine, but I don't like how it leads to simple exchanges for Black after the inevitable ...[Nb8]-[c6]. The more pieces that we can keep in the position the better. [Qe2] keeps things more flexible and prepares thematic ideas of [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4]. It is only played 1% of the time, endowing it to have a strong surprise effect on your opponent who's likely to have never seen it before.} O-O 9. O-O Nc6 10. Ne5 {This might seem to simplify, but I really like the statistics here. 50 percent of players have traded on [e5] immediately, setting the tune for a rich strategic battle.} Qc7 {This is the much simpler response, but one that is rarely ventured just the same. Black wants to trade on [e5] and respond to White's [fxe5] with ...[Nf6]-[d7].} 11. d3 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 (12. fxe5 Nd7 {would be no good. Our pawn on [e5] is too weak and we have to push another pawn to a dark square with [d4] to defend it, making our bishop really terrible.} 13. d4 Rac8 {⩱ , with uncomfortable pressure of ...[cxd4] and ...[Qxc2].}) 12... Qc6 13. Nd2 Nd7 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2,Rc3,Rd2,Ge5] The only move to ever be played in this position. We should avoid the bishop trade. We have after all weakened several dark squares with our pushes of [b2]-[b3] and [d2]-[d3].} 14. Bb2 {It is important to state that even as a GM this position is confusing for me. No pawns have been traded and the front line all over the board has not been established. No black pawns and white pawns touch yet, meaning the structure can freeze in a variety of ways. In general, we want to play around our bishop. So we don't want to push any pawns to dark squares. Instead, we're going to go for pawn play on the light squares with [a2]-[a4] and [e3]-[e4]; [c2]-[c4] might be an option, but it will weaken the [d3]-point so we must be more careful about going for it than going for the other pawn advances.} Bf6 {The most natural move and also the most popular.} 15. Bxf6 {There is nothing else, we have to take.} Nxf6 16. g4 $13 {And the game keeps going. We will advance with [g5] to kick the knight out and then throw the h-pawn forward as well. The idea is to create attacking chances involving opening one of those two files at some point with [g5]-[g6] after having optimally placed rooks and queen behind it. Having advanced so much on the flank, we do not want to open the center. If the center were to open, our king would be extremely weak. For that reason, we will decline all central tension. For instance, ...[d5]-[d4] will be met by [e3]-[e4]. Black will throw the queenside forward and try to create some weaknesses there to target. The game is complex and the 0.00 issued by Stockfish does not tell the whole story.} *

