1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Be7 {This seems to be the most testing, even though it has only been chosen in 33% of games.} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 ({This is the natural and overwhelming popular continuation being chosen in 57% of games.} 6... Nc6 {is played a third of the time but just transposes to 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Be7 .}) 7. Bxd7+ {This might seem to simplify, but we are left with good pieces and a seriously asymmetrical structure. White should have full chances in the upcoming struggle.} Nbxd7 {This is by far the most popular recapture at a frequency of 80%. Taking with the queen is also reasonable and we'll look at that as well.} 8. O-O b5 {This is quite rare, but it is technically an option being played 4% of the time. Through this move order, Black avoids our plans for [c2]-[c4] on move 9.} 9. a4 b4 10. d3 O-O 11. Nbd2 Qc7 {This has only been played once, but it is obviously better than the more popular ...[a7]-[a5].} (11... a5 $6 {For some reason, Black players love playing this here though it doesn't serve any function apart from stopping our a-pawn's advance which wasn't remotely a threat to begin with. It is not even close to the top move of the computer.} 12. Qe2 {and White just won a free tempo from going about our plan to achieve [e3]-[e4].}) 12. Qe2 {[%cal Yd7b6,Yf3e5,Gg2g3,Ge3e4] This is a novelty and at this point, we are out of the path that any online game has ever taken. We want to play [e3]-[e4] and for this reason, should secure our [f4]-pawn which is attacked by the enemy queen with [g2]-[g3]. Then we will continue with [e3]-[e4]. We would love to see Black respond to the e-pawn advance with ...[d5]-[d4], when our knights get the permanent outpost on [c4]. On an aside, if Black tries to force through ...[c5]-[c4] with ...[Nb6], we will happily strengthen our control over that square with [Nf3]-[e5].} *

