1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Be7 {This seems to be the most testing, even though it has only been chosen in 33% of games.} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 ({This is the natural and overwhelming popular continuation being chosen in 57% of games.} 6... Nc6 {is played a third of the time but just transposes to 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Be7 .}) 7. Bxd7+ {This might seem to simplify, but we are left with good pieces and a seriously asymmetrical structure. White should have full chances in the upcoming struggle.} Nbxd7 {This is by far the most popular recapture at a frequency of 80%. Taking with the queen is also reasonable and we'll look at that as well.} 8. O-O Qc7 ({This will likely be followed by Black castling kingside when things will just transpose to} 8... O-O {. The only unique setup to consider here would be if Black chooses the unorthodox queenside castle.}) 9. c4 O-O-O (9... O-O 10. Nc3 {will follow similar play to the lines described after 8...O-O .}) 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5] Immediate ideas of [Nb5] loom.} Kb8 {The c-file was always on the verge of opening with [cxd5] in the air, so the king sidesteps any potential chaos.} 11. Nb5 Qb6 12. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5] Preparing to harass the queen. If we could advance [a4]-[a5]-[a6], Black would have to respond with ...[b7]-[b6] to avoid opening a file, but in the process, this would install our knight permanently on the [b5]-square.} Ne8 13. a5 Qc6 14. a6 b6 15. Qe2 $18 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5,Rg7][%cal Re8d6,Gb2g7] The knight enjoys its outpost and White is just strategically winning. An important point is that Black cannot easily trade off the knight with ...[Nd6] or ...[Nc7], as that would drop the pawn on [g7].} *

