1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Be7 {This seems to be the most testing, even though it has only been chosen in 33% of games.} 6. Bb5+ Bd7 ({This is the natural and overwhelming popular continuation being chosen in 57% of games.} 6... Nc6 {is played a third of the time but just transposes to 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Be7 .}) 7. Bxd7+ {This might seem to simplify, but we are left with good pieces and a seriously asymmetrical structure. White should have full chances in the upcoming struggle.} Nbxd7 {This is by far the most popular recapture at a frequency of 80%. Taking with the queen is also reasonable and we'll look at that as well.} 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 $1 {This is only played in 2% of games and yet it leads to the most asymmetrical double-edged situations. It is also objectively fine and Stockfish even considers it slightly better than the super-popular [d3]. The suggested move is the perfect remedy for using against the opponent who is better versed in the main lines.} (9. d3 {is common here, but I don't like allowing our opponent so much space on the queenside. After} b5 {, Black's play is very simple and straightforward. Black will simply march up the queenside with the a-, b-, and c-pawns. The position objectively remains level but Black's game is easier.}) 9... Rc8 {This is a very unclear situation after all so such mysterious rook moves will be seen often. The rook doesn't do much on [c8], but it does more than before, and there might be a time after White exchanges with [cxd5] that Black plays ...[exd5] and has a pawn majority on the queenside. We should continue playing slowly.} 10. d3 Qc7 11. Nc3 Nb8 {This rerouting from [d7] to [c6] was waiting to be played for a while now. The knight on [d7] blocked the d-file and didn't fight for the center as actively as it would have from [c6].} 12. Ne5 $1 {Hopping into the center, as the [d7]-knight has just hopped away.} Nc6 13. Nb5 $1 {I like this line because it shows the latent tactical resources in this seemingly calm position. The knights hit a variety of squares in Black's camp so already Black is pressed for options.} Qb8 14. Nxc6 Rxc6 15. Qf3 $36 {[%cal Ge3e4] We will play [e3]-[e4] with a healthy initiative in the center. Keep in mind, as with most positions of this ilk; [e3]-[e4] is good but [e4]-[e5] will likely blind our [b2]-dragon's eye. Meanwhile, if Black responds with ...[d5]-[d4] to our [e3]-[e4], we can just reroute our bishop to [c1] and play for [f4]-[f5] and [g2]-[g4]-[g5].} (15. Be5 {could also be worth a try. Most Black players won't like the looks of putting their queen on [a8] even though it's the only move to keep things equal. All other moves just drop the [a7]-pawn.}) *

