s very simple and straightforward. Black will simply march up the queenside with the a-, b-, and c-pawns. The position objectively remains level but Black's game is easier.}) 9... b6 $6 {This pawn push looks dubious, as there is no bishop on [c8] begging for the [b7]-square.} 10. Qe2 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gd2d3,Ge3e4] We will follow with [Nc3], [d2]-[d3], perhaps [e3]-[e4] or [Ne5]. Similar to other positions, we want something double-edged in which our better experience will be the difference. White is marginally better due to the better bishop.} *

