s very simple and straightforward. Black will simply march up the queenside with the a-, b-, and c-pawns. The position objectively remains level but Black's game is easier.}) 9... dxc4 $2 {This is the most popular move and it's just a mistake. We will happily take back on [c4], ridding Black permanently of the essential d-pawn.} 10. bxc4 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gd1e2] We will analyze several variations from here but I'd like to mention some things at this point. We have an extra d-pawn and they have an extra b-pawn. This is the biggest imbalance in the position and signifies our biggest claim to an advantage. We can always play [d3] to shore up the last uncovered square in the center, [e4]. The black knight on [d7] is seriously restricted and its best long-term plan is to burn two moves to return to the natural [c6]-square via [b8]. Our queen will likely end up on [e2]. While advancing [e4]-[e5] might look appealing, it will usually do more harm than good by blocking our [b2]-bishop, [f3]-knight, and weakening our [d4]-square.} Nb6 $6 {[%csl Rb6] This is obviously not the right square for the knight, but we must be accurate in how we respond to it.} 11. Qc2 $14 {We should keep an eye out for ...[Na4] and so this is a better square for the queen than [e2]. The knight is not well placed. We want to play [d3] but that will be met by a discomforting ...[Ng4] check the line with 11.d3 so we will play [a4] first to cover the [a4]-square and potentially throw in [a4]-[a5] and then [d2]-[d3].} (11. d3 $2 Ng4 {and our [e3]-pawn is vulnerable. Black is waiting for us to move the queen to protect the pawn with [Qd2] or [Qe2], when Black will be able to bother our bishop with ...[Na4].}) *

