s very simple and straightforward. Black will simply march up the queenside with the a-, b-, and c-pawns. The position objectively remains level but Black's game is easier.}) 9... dxc4 $2 {This is the most popular move and it's just a mistake. We will happily take back on [c4], ridding Black permanently of the essential d-pawn.} 10. bxc4 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gd1e2] We will analyze several variations from here but I'd like to mention some things at this point. We have an extra d-pawn and they have an extra b-pawn. This is the biggest imbalance in the position and signifies our biggest claim to an advantage. We can always play [d3] to shore up the last uncovered square in the center, [e4]. The black knight on [d7] is seriously restricted and its best long-term plan is to burn two moves to return to the natural [c6]-square via [b8]. Our queen will likely end up on [e2]. While advancing [e4]-[e5] might look appealing, it will usually do more harm than good by blocking our [b2]-bishop, [f3]-knight, and weakening our [d4]-square.} Ne4 11. Qc2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc2e4] Pushing the knight back.} Nd6 {[%csl Rc4,Rf5][%cal Gd6c4,Gd6f5] The knight seems strange here, but it looks at a complex of tender squares, the biggest being [f5]. Our [Nc3] is also hard to achieve due to the pressure on [c4].} 12. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Yd2d3] Taking away ...[b5] ideas and testing the waters of a further a-pawn advance. We might want to go further to [a5] and eventually pressure the black b-pawn; [d2]-[d3] followed by [Nc3] is also on the itinerary. The position is slightly better for White.} (12. e4 $6 {Just as mentioned before, this is ill-advised. [e4]-[e5] will walk into ...[Nf5], when [d4] is a pain in White's side.}) 12... Bf6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. a5 Qc7 15. Nc3 $1 Rad8 (15... Nxc4 $4 16. Nb5 {+- and Black loses the knight.}) 16. Rfb1 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gc3b5,Ya1b1,Yb1b5,Yd6b5] The plan is simple. Black's knight on [d6] defends [b7] well so we will trade it with [Nb5] and follow with [Rxb5] and [Rab1].} *

