 confronted with an uncomfortable decision: retreat the knight to [g7] after ...[g7]-[g6] and allow a quick advance of White's h-pawn to [h5], when White threatens to open the h-file with [hxg6] and attack the black king; or allow [Bxh5] to happen, ruining Black's structure irreparably.} Bb7 $1 {Objectively best but such a hard move to play in a practical game.} 12. Bg4 d4 {[%cal Gd4c3] Attacking our knight rather than bothering defending the wayward [h5]-horse.} 13. Bxh5 ({We must make sure not to lose our step with} 13. Nb1 $4 Nb4 $1 {-+ and the threat of ...[Nxa2] smother-mate cedes Black a winning initiative.}) 13... dxc3 14. dxc3 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gd1d8,Yc3c4,Gb2h8] White is up a pawn and maintains a healthy structure. If we are allowed to play [c3]-[c4] we will reactivate this great bishop as well, getting a decisive advantage. Black must do everything possible to keep the [b2]-bishop entombed.} (14. Bxc3 $2 Nb4 {gives Black great compensation for the pawn. Black's king is surrounded by pawns that haven't moved and is much more secure than ours. Black has a very simple plan of advancing the a-pawn to [a4], when our [b3]-pawn will guarantee that Black can open some files. Notice the fact that our [b3]-pawn has already been advanced from its starting square made it very easy to target by the enemy. This type of 'hook' was what we'd want to play on Black's kingside, but Black hasn't advanced any pawns there. For instance, if Black had played ...[g7]-[g6], then we could use that as a hook to initiate tension with [h2]-[h4]-[h5].}) 14... c4 $1 (14... Qc7 15. c4 {+- with fantastic central pressure on the dark squares.}) 15. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gh5f3] With ideas of [Ne4] and [Bf3].} Qc7 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Rhg1 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gg1g8,Ge4f6] Cooking up some spicy appetizers involving [Nf6]+ and a discovery attack on the [g8]-king.} Kh8 18. Bf3 $16 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White is better but the game remains very complex. This will be the type of position where whichever player has more experience makes it out of the jungle unscathed. A good plan could be to advance the h-pawn to [h5] and then make a decision on whether to open files with [g5]-[g6] or compromise Black's dark squares with [h5]-[h6].} *

