 confronted with an uncomfortable decision: retreat the knight to [g7] after ...[g7]-[g6] and allow a quick advance of White's h-pawn to [h5], when White threatens to open the h-file with [hxg6] and attack the black king; or allow [Bxh5] to happen, ruining Black's structure irreparably.} g6 $2 {This natural move compromises the kingside too much. It was better for Black to just sacrifice the knight.} 12. Bg4 Ng7 {The knight moves out of the attack, but now our h-pawn is free to advance down the board.} 13. h4 b4 14. Na4 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ra6a5,Ra5a4] The knight fits into the [a4]-groove holding back the rest of the black pawns.} Bd7 15. h5 $18 {[%cal Ge2h2,Gh5g6] White's attack plays itself. White will build a battery on the h-file with some queen and rook combinations to deliver a saucy checkmate involving [Qh7] or [Qh8].} *

