 [c3]-[d1]-[f2]-[g4].} e5 {This move is a critical attempt to free Black's position. If we respond incorrectly, we could easily find ourselves in a worse position.} 10. Nxd5 exf4 11. Qe2 {[%cal Ge1c1] The king will evacuate soon enough.} Nde5 {[%cal Gc8g4] Black threatens a dangerous ...[Bg4]. We must sidestep the diagonal.} 12. Qg2 Nxf3+ 13. Qxf3 Bf5 14. O-O-O Re8 {[%cal Gf5e4]} 15. Nc3 {Stopping the threat of ...[Be4].} Qd7 {[%cal Gf5g4] Creating a new threat of ...[Bg4].} 16. Rg1 {Covering [g4].} Ne5 17. Qf2 (17. Qxf4 $4 Nd3+ {∓ nabs the queen.}) 17... fxe3 (17... Ng4 {doesn't save the house from fire. After} 18. Qg2 fxe3 19. Bb5 {, Black is still worse.}) 18. dxe3 {[%csl Rd6,Rd7,Rf5][%cal Gd1d7,Gf1b5,Gc3b5] Despite the fragmented pawn structure, White's pressure along the d-file is already convincing. Some form of [Bb5], [Nb5], or [Rxd6] should endow us a decisive advantage.} *

