as our [b2]-bishop needs to be re-engaged for our kingside attack to work. It will go to [d1]-[f2]-[g4], [e2]-[g3]-[h5], or maybe even just [b5] depending on what happens. It could also end up on [d5] if we manage to deflect the [e6]-pawn in some crafty way.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black's fixing for a queenside pawn storm obviously.} (9... d4 {is well met by} 10. Ne4 {followed by [Nxd6], with a better position for White.}) 10. Qe2 b5 {Here we must face our fears courageously. The queenside is looking more vulnerable with each progressive step by the black pawns.} 11. O-O-O {'The cave you fear to enter holds the treasure you seek' − Joseph Campbell.} c4 12. Kb1 a5 $1 {Black's best chance. Black sacrifices the b-pawn for the fastest play on the queenside.} 13. Nxb5 {Otherwise, ...[a5]-[a4] followed by ...[axb3] and ...[b5]-[b4] would just be too strong.} cxb3 (13... a4 14. bxc4 {± , White snags a pawn for good and will hide the king on [a1]. Black can make a few threats but overall, the king will be very safe here, as there is no concrete way for Black to open the a-file.}) 14. cxb3 (14. axb3 a4 $1 {Black is in the driver's seat here with a multitude of attacking ideas already in the air.}) 14... a4 15. Rc1 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gc1c6] Attacking the [c6]-knight while activating the dormant [d1]-rook.} Bd7 16. Qd1 {[%cal Ya4b3,Yd1b3] White will recapture with the queen on [b3].} axb3 17. Qxb3 $14 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gg5g6,Gb3c3,Gf1d3] Despite appearances, White's king is still safe due to Black's lack of coordination. White will soon begin offensive operations on the kingside with moves like [h5], [g5]-[g6], [Qc3], or [Bd3]. We are slightly better though the situation remains extremely complex.} *

