1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd6e5] A rare continuation that makes some sense. The ...[e6]-[e5] break is always thematic if it's properly supported.} 6. g4 $5 {Going for all the glory. Yet again we see a completely sound [g2]-[g4] that has barely ever been played 47 games. While the position remains dynamically balanced, I consider getting to these positions a psychological victory. This is not the type of game Black was looking to get when they chose this calm setup. 62% of Black players chose either to capture on [g4] or castle here.} O-O {This move has been played in 30% of games but it is already a serious inaccuracy. You can probably guess what we're gonna play...} 7. g5 $1 Ne8 {This is the best move objectively but has never been played − a promising development indeed.} 8. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] The h-pawn would be happy to go to [h5] and maybe even [h6].} Nc6 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3][%cal Rb2g7,Gc3d1,Gd1f2,Gf2g4,Yc3e2,Ye2g3,Yg3h5] Unfortunately, we had to block our bishop in this manner to get on with our development. The knight will not be here long term, as our [b2]-bishop needs to be re-engaged for our kingside attack to work. It will go to [d1]-[f2]-[g4], [e2]-[g3]-[h5], or maybe even just [b5] depending on what happens. It could also end up on [d5] if we manage to deflect the [e6]-pawn in some crafty way.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black's fixing for a queenside pawn storm obviously.} (9... d4 {is well met by} 10. Ne4 {followed by [Nxd6], with a better position for White.}) 10. Qe2 b5 {Here we must face our fears courageously. The queenside is looking more vulnerable with each progressive step by the black pawns.} 11. O-O-O {'The cave you fear to enter holds the treasure you seek' − Joseph Campbell.} c4 12. Kb1 Bd7 {This situation is pure chaos and must be dealt with accordingly.} 13. g6 $3 {This guarantees the opening of files shortly. Either capture of ...[hxg6] or ...[fxg6] will be met with [h4]-[h5], creating more tension.} fxg6 (13... hxg6 14. h5 {+- and White has a winning attack on the h-file.}) 14. h5 h6 15. hxg6 Nf6 16. Ng5 $18 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gg5f7,Yh6g5,Ye2h2,Gf7h6] The knight cannot be taken on account of [Qh2]. White has ideas of [Nf7] and [Nxh6]. Black's king is more exposed than ours, which makes all the difference. Stockfish already considers this as nearly winning, though playing it precisely is another matter.} *

