1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd6e5] A rare continuation that makes some sense. The ...[e6]-[e5] break is always thematic if it's properly supported.} 6. g4 $5 {Going for all the glory. Yet again we see a completely sound [g2]-[g4] that has barely ever been played 47 games. While the position remains dynamically balanced, I consider getting to these positions a psychological victory. This is not the type of game Black was looking to get when they chose this calm setup. 62% of Black players chose either to capture on [g4] or castle here.} d4 {This is objectively best yet it has never been seen in online play. Black immediately blocks the diagonal and frees [d5] for the [f6]-knight to hop to. We do not want to capture anytime soon, as that would represent a huge rupture in our central structure.} 7. Bd3 {[%csl Gb2,Gd3] I like this move a lot. The bishops on [d3] and [b2] will eye Black's kingside perfectly.} O-O (7... Nc6 8. g5 Nd5 9. Qe2 O-O {transposes.}) 8. g5 Nd5 9. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2e3] Keeping the integrity of the central phalanx intact.} Nc6 10. Na3 {The knight will likely go to [c4] but may on occasion opt for [b5] instead. White has created the possibility of castling queenside and can, depending on the path the game follows, choose either side. While the pawns are more advanced on the kingside, the king would still be well-covered thanks to the phalanx.} Ncb4 {[%csl Gd3] Our [d3]-bishop is our best minor piece so we should do our best to avoid trading it.} 11. Be4 f5 {[%csl Re5,Re6][%cal Gf7f5] This forces a trade for our bishop but seriously weakens the [e6]-pawn and [e5]-square.} 12. gxf6 Nxf6 13. Bd3 Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 {The trade has finally happened but thanks to Black's weaknesses on the e-file, we are still doing fine. Our knights have a great outpost on [e5] to look towards.} b6 15. O-O-O Bb7 16. Rhf1 $14 {[%cal Ga3c4,Gf3e5] Black is stuck with the weak [e6]-pawn and is slightly worse. It is a matter of time before the tension on [d4] gets resolved and when it does, our [b2]-dragon will breathe fire down the board. Notice we will likely hold off on taking on [d4] anytime soon since [f4] will just drop in return, making the board more open for the black bishops. We will happily await ...[dxe3], when we can recapture with the pawn, keeping good control over the [f4]-pawn.} *

