1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... Be7 {This is played 28% of the time and is the 2nd most popular move.} 7. Bxc6+ {Of course, we take. The doubled pawns should be inflicted at every available opportunity.} bxc6 8. Ne5 {[%csl Rc6] Immediately latching into the center. It will take a lot of work from Black to kick our knight out of this natural square.} Qc7 {The computer insists the position is only marginally better for White, but I cannot help feeling there is an enormous practical edge. Black's bishop on [c8] is awful and there is no straightforward way to remedy it. The computer recommendation in this position is for Black to sacrifice the pawn with ...[c5]-[c4] almost immediately, with the aim of opening several diagonals.} (8... Qb6 9. c4 {will follow a similar trajectory to 8...Qc7. Black's queen is just comparatively worse placed and will have to waste a move after White's thematic knight transfer from [c3] to [a4].}) 9. c4 {We immediately shut out any opportunities of ...[c5]-[c4]. While it may be slightly less of an advantage than castling, it seems very playable and simple. I'll leave you with a few lines to show how play could develop.} O-O 10. O-O {Black must challenge the [e5]-knight immediately. Other tries don't trouble White in the slightest.} Ne4 11. Qe2 f6 {This was half the reason the knight had left [f6]. Now our knight is kicked. The good news is that this ...[f7]-[f6] push seriously weakened the [e6]-pawn and hasn't achieved much for Black in the sense of fixing the bishops.} 12. Nf3 Bd7 13. d3 Nd6 14. Nc3 {Black's knight on [d6] makes a strange impression and will likely need to be rerouted further to [f7] to achieve some semblance of harmony. At the moment it's pointed into the white concrete on [d3] and [c4] and blocks the diagonals of the queen and [e7]-bishop.} Nf5 15. Na4 {[%cal Ge3e4] Now [e3]-[e4] looms and Black continues to wallow in this ugly position.} *

