into the center. It will take a lot of work from Black to kick our knight out of this natural square.} Qc7 {The computer insists the position is only marginally better for White, but I cannot help feeling there is an enormous practical edge. Black's bishop on [c8] is awful and there is no straightforward way to remedy it. The computer recommendation in this position is for Black to sacrifice the pawn with ...[c5]-[c4] almost immediately, with the aim of opening several diagonals.} (8... Qb6 9. c4 {will follow a similar trajectory to 8...Qc7. Black's queen is just comparatively worse placed and will have to waste a move after White's thematic knight transfer from [c3] to [a4].}) 9. c4 {We immediately shut out any opportunities of ...[c5]-[c4]. While it may be slightly less of an advantage than castling, it seems very playable and simple. I'll leave you with a few lines to show how play could develop.} O-O 10. O-O {Black must challenge the [e5]-knight immediately. Other tries don't trouble White in the slightest.} Nd7 {[%csl Ge5] Challenging our central knight.} 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 {It is counterintuitive, but this is the stronger recapture; a deep point is that Black will have ideas to sacrifice the e-pawn with ...[e6]-[e5] to free the position, and if the queen had stayed on [c7], White would be able to recapture in this case with the bishop on [e5], when Black's queen would be under attack.} 12. Qe2 d4 {[%csl Ga2,Gb3,Gc4,Rc8][%cal Rc8a6] This move blocks our bishop but despite appearances, it carries some hidden disadvantages. Black's strategic problem is the ugly structure, which blocks in the bishops, making the bishop pair benign to the White player. With this advance, Black desists on crunching at the [c4]-phalanx. The [c8]-bishop in other words, can give up on ever looking at an open diagonal from [a6].} ({After} 12... a5 13. Nc3 {, Black will not be able to achieve the objective of loosening our structure with ...[a5]-[a4] and ...[axb3]. Instead, we will plant our knight on [a4] with great pressure on the weak [c5]-pawn.}) 13. d3 a5 {Here our knight can't counter in the standard [Nc3]-[a4] manner due to the pesky [d4]-pawn. Fortunately, we can handle the oncoming a-pawn advance in other ways.} 14. Nd2 a4 15. bxa4 Rxa4 16. e4 {[%cal Gd2f3] We will play [Nf3]. Our bishop on [b2] is exposed and pointed into concrete so we will likely reroute it to [c1] and then [d2], where it is less vulnerable and more active in supporting play on both diagonals.} *

