1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... a6 $2 {Similar to other lines, this is a dubious idea. White is happy to double the pawns especially after Black has burned a move on the useless ...[a7]-[a6].} 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. c4 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Gb2,Rc5,Gd2,Ge3,Re6,Gf3,Gf4,Rf8][%cal Rf8c5,Rc8e6,Rc8a6] White could have also gone for [Ne5], but I feel this move is the simplest way to guarantee an advantage. The [f8]-bishop suffers, as the [c5]-pawn will be stuck in its path forever. Meanwhile, the [c8]-bishop is also locked in by the [e6] and [a6]-boulders. White's position on the other hand is one of perfect harmony. The [f3]-knight and [b2]-bishop work in perfect harmony towards the control of the central dark squares.} Nd7 {[%csl Gd7] The black knight is appropriately placed here. If a white knight ever arrives on [a4] to target [c5] and [b6], the knight on [d7] will cushion these squares perfectly.} 9. Nc3 Be7 10. O-O f6 {The most accurate move according to the computer, though I really can't imagine a human making such a move. The [f6]-concrete freezes out our [b2]-bishop long term so we should instead switch strategies and opt for play on the weakened light squares.} 11. e4 $1 {Black must keep the tension here. Pushing the d-pawn will only make matters worse.} d4 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6,Rd4] This removes all the flexibility of Black's structure and freezes it in place. This structure was described with reverse colors in Winning Chess Middlegames by Ivan Sokolov. As you would expect, it came about in a Nimzo-Indian. The issue for Black is that [c5] can never be defended by rooks due to the [c6]-pawn, which stands in its way. So long-term, White should be able to pile up on it with [Nc3]-[a4], [Ne1]-[d3], and [Bb2]-[a3].} 12. Na4 O-O 13. Ba3 {[%csl Rc5]} e5 14. f5 $1 {Keeping things closed. Black's pieces are in an enormous central cage.} Nb6 {This is Black's best hope.} 15. Nxb6 (15. Nxc5 Bd6 {and White is much better, but Black has some practical compensation associated with the pin. When Black plays ...[Qe7] things will be dicey.}) 15... Qxb6 16. d3 {[%cal Ga3c1,Gc1d2,Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Yf1g1,Yg1g3,Ya1g1] Despite appearances, the difference in the health of the pieces gives White a strategically winning advantage. We will reroute the bishop to [c1] or [d2] and then push the g-pawn up the board, perhaps with the help of some doubled rooks on [g1] and [g3]. With the entire center stuck and blocked, Black will have no serious counterplay against this plan.} *

