3,Gf4,Rf8][%cal Rf8c5,Rc8e6,Rc8a6] White could have also gone for [Ne5], but I feel this move is the simplest way to guarantee an advantage. The [f8]-bishop suffers, as the [c5]-pawn will be stuck in its path forever. Meanwhile, the [c8]-bishop is also locked in by the [e6] and [a6]-boulders. White's position on the other hand is one of perfect harmony. The [f3]-knight and [b2]-bishop work in perfect harmony towards the control of the central dark squares.} Nd7 {[%csl Gd7] The black knight is appropriately placed here. If a white knight ever arrives on [a4] to target [c5] and [b6], the knight on [d7] will cushion these squares perfectly.} 9. Nc3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne5 {Attacking [c6]. As we will see, White is happy to recapture [fxe5] if given the opportunity.} Nxe5 12. fxe5 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Ge5,Re6][%cal Re7d6,Re7f6,Rc8e6] White takes doubled pawns of their own, so why is White better? Well, the pawn on [e5] effectively defangs both enemy bishops. The [e7]-bishop can never use the good squares on [f6] and [d6], and with the [e6]-pawn blocked in for good, the [c8]-bishop will never be able to see to [f5] and beyond.} Rb8 13. Qc2 {[%cal Gc3a4] White will play [Na4], when [cxd5] attacking [c5] will become a serious threat.} a5 14. Na4 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc4d5]} Qc7 {[%cal Gc7c5,Yc4d5,Yc6d5] Here [cxd5] allows ...[c6xd5], when the [Qc7] defends the c-pawn.} 15. Rf4 {[%cal Ga1f1] Black might have dealt with the [cxd5] threat, but there remains a simple plan of attacking the kingside.} *

