these positions after ...[dxc4] [Bxc4] to always be superior for White. I will show some sample lines to explain this advantage, but in summation, we will have good pieces. Black's bishops really suffer in the given structure. The one on [f8] is locked in by the [c5]-pawn and the one on [c8] is locked in by [e6].} a6 9. Nc3 Qc7 {[%cal Rb7b5,Rc8b7] Black's plan is to push ...[b5] and place the bishop on [b7]. This would certainly achieve a level of harmony and so White must react precisely to keep the edge.} 10. Bd3 b5 {This push gains some control, but it also weakens the [c5]-pawn. White should zero in on this new weakness.} 11. Rc1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1c5,Yd3b1] This x-rays [c5] and also prepares for a harmonious regrouping. White can retreat the [d3]-bishop to [b1] where it scopes Black's kingside effectively while remaining hidden and invulnerable to enemy attacks. Previously with the rook on [a1], [Bb1] would have locked the rook in on the corner.} Be7 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Bb1 Bb7 {[%csl Gb1,Gb2][%cal Gb2g7,Gb1h7] White's bishops lurk, they have been silent thus far, but they will reveal themselves to be deadly with the next move.} 14. g4 $3 {[%cal Gg4g5] If the pawn isn't taken, we will advance to [g5], booting the [f6]-knight from its defense of the kingside.} Nxg4 15. Rg1 f5 16. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Gc1c7,Gb2g7,Rf5e4,Rf5g4] Unleashing the [b2]-bishop and [c1]-rook while activating the knight on an impossible square.} ({It's important to avoid the natural} 16. h3 $2 Nf6 $1 {∓ when we lack convincing pressure. Black can defend against (White's threats to [g7] with some combination of ...[Bd6] to open the [Qc7]'s defense, ...[g7]-[g6] or ...[Rf7]. Black has netted the pawn after all and our king has long-term problems in the center both rooks have moved and so castling is off the table.)}) 16... fxe4 17. Rxg4 {[%cal Gg4g7] Black must take precautions against [Rxg7].} Bf6 18. Bxf6 Rxf6 19. Bxe4 $16 {White regains the pawn with a clear advantage. We have good pressure on the c-file and a weak square on [e5] for the knight. Meanwhile, White's structure is relatively sound with the potentially weak [d2]-pawn remaining hidden and well-protected.} *

