1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... Qb6 {The queen moves in to support the [c6]-knight while jointly pressuring the bishop to make a decision.} 7. c4 {Initiating some tension against [d5] while defending the bishop.} dxc4 8. Bxc4 {The computer believes these positions after ...[dxc4] [Bxc4] to always be superior for White. I will show some sample lines to explain this advantage, but in summation, we will have good pieces. Black's bishops really suffer in the given structure. The one on [f8] is locked in by the [c5]-pawn and the one on [c8] is locked in by [e6].} Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 Bd7 11. Qe2 {All of Black's pieces block each other d7 points into [c6], which points into [e7], which points into [f6] and so on, but to fix this Black would have to move the knights, which would allow White some splendid opportunities. While it's not the worst position in the world, I could see an inexperienced player losing control quickly and resigning in a dozen moves.} Na5 12. Bd3 Bc6 13. Ne5 {[%cal Gc6a5] Their knight has moved away from [c6] and so our [f3]-knight can now hop straight into the center on [e5]. I discussed this relationship a lot in Chapter 7 of my Domination course.} Rad8 14. Rad1 $16 {[%cal Ge5c6,Yg2g4,Yg4g5,Yf1f3,Yf3h3] We can think about taking on [c6] and then launching an attack on the kingside with [g2]-[g4]-[g5] or [Rf3]-[h3]. Because we will have taken Black's light-squared bishop, the weaknesses this pawn advance would create along the [a8]-[h1] diagonal would not be relevant.} *

