1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... Qb6 {The queen moves in to support the [c6]-knight while jointly pressuring the bishop to make a decision.} 7. c4 {Initiating some tension against [d5] while defending the bishop.} Be7 8. Ne5 Bd7 9. Nxd7 Nxd7 10. Nc3 a6 11. Bxc6 Qxc6 12. Qf3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Yd5d4,Yf3c6] Pressuring [d5]. If the d-pawn budges, we will happily trade on [c6] to inflict the doubled c-pawns on Black's structure.} Nf6 13. O-O O-O 14. d3 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2g3,Ye3e4,Ye4e5,Gg3h5,Gb2g7] The game is level but double-edged enough to offer chances for both sides. One idea for White is to advance [e3]-[e4], recapture on [e4] with [d3] if necessary, and continue on to [e5]. Another is to reroute the knight to [g3] via [e2] in order to unleash the [b2]-bishop on the kingside and create ideas of [Nh5] or, if the [e6]-pawn has been moved, [Nf5].} *

