1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... Qb6 {The queen moves in to support the [c6]-knight while jointly pressuring the bishop to make a decision.} 7. c4 {Initiating some tension against [d5] while defending the bishop.} a6 8. Ba4 ({Keeping the tension.} 8. Bxc6+ {was also fine, with normal strategy on the dark squares after something like [Nf3]-[e5]. 8.Ba4 keeps the pin strong and gives Black the option to try to snatch a pawn.}) 8... dxc4 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Rb3c4,Rb6b2] White can't recapture obviously due to the hanging bishop on [b2].} (8... Bd7 9. Bxf6 $1 {The black queen has moved from [d8] after all.} gxf6 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Nc3 {⩲ and White has the better structure.}) 9. Ne5 $1 {In for a penny, in for a pound.} cxb3 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Na3 bxa2 12. Nc4 Qa7 {We could snatch the exchange with [Bc6], but it's even stronger to just let the pressure simmer.} 13. O-O Bd7 14. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5] We will play [g5], booting the knight from [f6]. And once that is achieved, the [f8]-bishop will be tied to [g7] for good. Black is currently up 3 pawns but they are all awful. White will regain [a2] with ease and can then think about targeting [c6] with [Qf3] or pressuring the long diagonal with [Qa1]. White's advantage is on the verge of decisive.} Rb8 15. Rxa2 Be7 16. g5 $18 {Now [g7] will drop. The [h8]-rook will have to move and the black king will be left hanging in the central vortex, as the palace gets stormed from all angles. Avoiding this gloomy scenario is possible, but at the cost of an exchange. After ...[Rxb2], Black's life will continue to be miserable.} *

