1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... Bd7 {The most popular move and the best one. The bishop cushions [c6] against our threat to ruin the structure.} 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] Arriving to the party on [e5] finally.} Be7 {This is played 22% of the time. Here we can exchange immediately or play slower with [O-O]. I investigated both options.} 9. Nxc6 {After serious deliberation I chose to go with this move.} (9. O-O O-O 10. d3 {, I like the idea of keeping the position tense but after a precise move by Black, we will have to rethink things.} Be8 $1 {⩱ , Black will play ...[Nd7], trade our knight off and then play ...[f7]-[f6] to stunt our bishop and ...[b7]-[b5], ...[c5]-[c4], etc., to expand on the queenside. White is still in the fight, but this is a White repertoire after all and this position is undoubtedly better for Black, making it hard to recommend. Fortunately, in contrast to this position, the course recommendation gets good play and reaches a position with good chances.}) 9... bxc6 {We inflicted the doubled pawns on Black, but this is their best version of the situation. The [e7]-bishop already cushions the pressure on [f6], freeing the queen to move without having to worry about responding to [Bxf6] with ...[gxf6]. The computer insists things are dead equal, but I'm confident Black's position is the more difficult of the two to play.} 10. Nc3 {I really like this move because of how unorthodox it is. The classic setup is [d2]-[d3], [Nd2] and [Nf3]. Here, [Nc3] is more unnatural, but it's objectively just as strong as the aforementioned plan. Meanwhile, we are keeping things as chaotic as possible so that our opponent is more likely to slip up. It is only played 4% of the time making it extremely likely that our opponents have never seen it before. The good news is that most Black players immediately start making strategically dubious moves like ...[d5]-[d4]. The following variations depict a foggy forest in which both players wander through − a contest ensues between them as to who can stumble less. Paying careful attention to these lines will serve as the flashlight of knowledge to guide us through the unknown.} d4 $6 {This move is unique in that is one of the only ways to make Black's structure uglier.} 11. Na4 Ne4 {This looks dubious but was played in 3 of the 5 games to reach this position. I don't see a concrete threat so I assume this was played with the intention of some sort of ...[Bh4]+ hope chess. Anyway, this isn't even a threat, as we have the rejoinder [g2]-[g3].} 12. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Ge3d4] White will castle queenside with an enormous edge. Black's ...[Nf6]-[e4] has simply left the knight loose and given us a strong idea in [exd4], revealing an attack by the [Qe2] on it.} *

