ime. Here we can exchange immediately or play slower with [O-O]. I investigated both options.} 9. Nxc6 {After serious deliberation I chose to go with this move.} (9. O-O O-O 10. d3 {, I like the idea of keeping the position tense but after a precise move by Black, we will have to rethink things.} Be8 $1 {⩱ , Black will play ...[Nd7], trade our knight off and then play ...[f7]-[f6] to stunt our bishop and ...[b7]-[b5], ...[c5]-[c4], etc., to expand on the queenside. White is still in the fight, but this is a White repertoire after all and this position is undoubtedly better for Black, making it hard to recommend. Fortunately, in contrast to this position, the course recommendation gets good play and reaches a position with good chances.}) 9... bxc6 {We inflicted the doubled pawns on Black, but this is their best version of the situation. The [e7]-bishop already cushions the pressure on [f6], freeing the queen to move without having to worry about responding to [Bxf6] with ...[gxf6]. The computer insists things are dead equal, but I'm confident Black's position is the more difficult of the two to play.} 10. Nc3 {I really like this move because of how unorthodox it is. The classic setup is [d2]-[d3], [Nd2] and [Nf3]. Here, [Nc3] is more unnatural, but it's objectively just as strong as the aforementioned plan. Meanwhile, we are keeping things as chaotic as possible so that our opponent is more likely to slip up. It is only played 4% of the time making it extremely likely that our opponents have never seen it before. The good news is that most Black players immediately start making strategically dubious moves like ...[d5]-[d4]. The following variations depict a foggy forest in which both players wander through − a contest ensues between them as to who can stumble less. Paying careful attention to these lines will serve as the flashlight of knowledge to guide us through the unknown.} d4 $6 {This move is unique in that is one of the only ways to make Black's structure uglier.} 11. Na4 O-O {[%csl Rc5,Rc6] The pawn on [c5] begins to ache. The [c4]-square is another casualty of the reckless ...[d5]-[d4] push and so it is conceivable our knight may arrive there at some point via [b2].} 12. O-O {Here ...[Nd5] is far and away the best move and yet it's only played 4% of the time. Again it's easy to stumble in the dark forest.} Nd5 13. Qf3 $14 {Black's best move is ...[Qa5], which is again not an obvious move by any stretch.} (13. exd4 $6 {The pawn is poisoned.} cxd4 14. Bxd4 Nb6 {, the only way to avoid the mangling exchange on [a4] is to cede the bishop for the knight.} 15. Bxb6 axb6 {, Black gets plenty of compensation and will play ...[b6]-[b5] and ...[Qd4]+.}) (13. e4 $6 {releases the tension on [d4] too soon. After} Nb6 14. Nxb6 axb6 {, Black's pawns begin to take cohesive form and lock our bishop out. We are already at a slight disadvantage.}) 13... Nb4 $6 {This was the move played in the only game to reach this position.} 14. c3 $36 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6][%cal Gb2c3,Ga1c1] It's crunch time! We will happily recapture with [Bxc3]. After that, we can put the rook from [a1]-[c1] to put the squeeze on the [c5]-pawn.} *

