 with ...[e6]-[e5].} 12. Qf3 {Black has several interesting ideas here. Similar to other positions, Black can go for ...[c5]-[c4]. Keep in mind that all the positions are relatively level, but whoever has more experience will have a strong upper hand in the ensuing battle. The forest remains dark, and those who have traversed it prior will be able to scale the obstacles and dodge the pitfalls with ease.} Nd7 {[%cal Gf6d7,Yd7b6,Yc3a4] The knight makes room for a bishop to come to [f6] and also creates potential for ...[Nd7]-[b6] to challenge our knight on [a4] should it arrive there.} 13. e4 {Striking in the center. Neither side wants to release the tension in the center. Black's ...[dxe4] would ruin Black's structure by leaving the pawns on the c-file isolated. White's [exd5] meanwhile would fix the black pawns and give Black a great stake in the center.} Bf6 ({After} 13... c4 14. Ne2 {, the knight will continue along to [g3], when White will light up the kingside with a spoonful of [Qg4] and a dash of [Nh5]. Instead, 14.bxc4?? Qb6! drops the bishop.}) 14. e5 Be7 15. d3 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2g3] White will continue with ideas of [Ne2]-[g3] and [Rae1]. If possible, we would love to achieve [f4]-[f5] to open up the kingside more for an effective attack.} *

