f, but it is still essayed 14% of the time. It is likely the bishop will get harassed by one thematic move or another, be it [c2]-[c4], [a2]-[a4], or [Nc3].} 9. d3 Be7 10. a4 $1 {Pushing the bishop to make a decision. Would it prefer being traded or being dislocated on [a6]?} Bd7 {While things are relatively balanced, this strikes me as a huge psychological win. Black gives up on even pretending to hold on to the bishops.} (10... Bc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. O-O {, with the boilerplate advantage from the ugly doubled c-pawns.}) 11. O-O O-O 12. Nd2 {This position is reminiscent of one we look at after 8...Qc7 9.O-O Be7 in which Black preserves the light-squared bishop in a similar fashion. This is a worse version, as Black has burned a few moves on the bishop and so White is playing the same position up a few tempi and with the useful [a2]-[a4] included, hindering Black's queenside expansion with ...[b5].} *

