1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... Bd7 {The most popular move and the best one. The bishop cushions [c6] against our threat to ruin the structure.} 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] Arriving to the party on [e5] finally.} Bb5 {This move seems a little off, but it is still essayed 14% of the time. It is likely the bishop will get harassed by one thematic move or another, be it [c2]-[c4], [a2]-[a4], or [Nc3].} 9. d3 Be7 10. a4 $1 {Pushing the bishop to make a decision. Would it prefer being traded or being dislocated on [a6]?} Ba6 (10... Bc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. O-O {, with the boilerplate advantage from the ugly doubled c-pawns.}) 11. O-O O-O 12. Nd2 {The knight continues on its journey to [f3], or if Black is so generous as to push ...[d5]-[d4], [c4] or [e4].} Nd7 (12... d4 13. Ndc4 {⩲ , getting our knights in a groove! We control the center and can slowly try to undermine the [d4]-pawn. We don't want to trade it yet, as it would allow Black to play ...[c5xd4], opening the bishop on [e7] to new opportunities.}) 13. Qg4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g7] New position, same old structural ideas.} Nxe5 14. Bxe5 {Despite appearances of simplicity, Black has an uncomfortable choice on their hands.} g6 $2 ({Now we get quick play on the dark squares on the kingside. In case of} 14... f6 $6 15. Qxe6+ {⩲ , we snatch a pawn with check.}) 15. Nf3 Qd7 16. Bb2 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7,Rh6][%cal Gf3e5,Yf1f3,Yf3h3] Here [Ne5] followed by [Rf3] is an unpleasant threat. White can also think about advancing [h2]-[h4]-[h5]. Black's kingside is already full of holes so if any further break in the structure is achieved, it could very well be fatal.} *

