f, but it is still essayed 14% of the time. It is likely the bishop will get harassed by one thematic move or another, be it [c2]-[c4], [a2]-[a4], or [Nc3].} 9. d3 Nd7 {If we exchange on [d7], Black will have achieved everything they wanted − Black will have kept the bishop pair while having traded our great piece on [e5].} 10. a4 $1 {Not so fast! Black is forced into an uncomfortable situation. Should Black retreat the bishop to [a6] where it might be sidelined indefinitely, or should they accept the trade?} Ba6 {[%csl Ra6] The best, but the bishop will be dislocated from the action for a while as a result.} 11. O-O Nxe5 12. fxe5 $1 {Digging into the [f6]-square and opening the f-file for our rook.} Be7 13. Qg4 $1 {We have an [e5]-pawn which guarantees us extra space on the kingside their [f7]-[e6]-[d5] pawns serve as a mountain separating their pieces from bothering us. It makes sense to begin an attack, therefore.} O-O 14. Rf3 {Increasing the potential of White's attack. We might play [Rg3], [Rh3], or simply double on the f-file after [Ra1]-[f1]. It is critical that Black immediately open things with ...[c5]-[c4]. This will open the center, giving Black more access to the kingside zone they desperately need to get into.} c4 $1 15. bxc4 dxc4 16. d4 $40 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3,Ge5][%cal Gb1c3,Gf3g3,Ga1f1] Keeping the center as closed and solid as possible. White's attack will continue with ideas such as [Nc3]-[e4], [Rf1], and [Rg3].} *

