f, but it is still essayed 14% of the time. It is likely the bishop will get harassed by one thematic move or another, be it [c2]-[c4], [a2]-[a4], or [Nc3].} 9. d3 Bd6 {Here we could continue with castling and standard ideas of play on the kingside. But there's another much stronger move out there that immediately poses some questions to Black.} 10. c4 $1 {Asking the bishop a very serious question. Will it retreat to [d7] or [c6], allowing a potentially favorable trade for White, or will it go to [a6] from where it might never be rerouted to more normally accessible positions? This move is objectively strong and practically speaking even more poisonous. It is quite rare, only being tried in 5% of games from this position. Most Black players immediately erred by capturing on [c4] and only 17% were able to find the right move to fight for equality. It might be confusing why we would play [c4] here as opposed to [a4] after 9…Be7. It makes more sense here as the bishop on [d6] keeps the d-file more closed, making the weakening of our [d3]-pawn less of an issue than it was before.} dxc4 $2 {This is the mistake that 63% of players opt for here.} 11. dxc4 Ba6 (11... Bc6 $2 12. Nxc6 bxc6 {is just a much worse version of the immediate ...[Bb5]-[c6] since without the d-pawns, Black's c-pawns are much more vulnerable and much less dynamic.}) 12. Qf3 {The trading of the d-pawns has obviously been to the detriment of Black's position! The bishop on [a6] will be severely misplaced as White prepares to lay siege to the d-file.} O-O 13. Nc3 Qe7 14. O-O-O $1 {Our king is completely safe over here. No files are easy to open and the [a6]-bishop, in addition to being completely irrelevant, obstructs the thematic pawn storm of ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5].} Rad8 15. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gc3e4] White wants to play [g5] and [Ne4] with a huge initiative.} Bxe5 16. fxe5 Nd7 17. Ne4 $16 {[%cal Ge4d6,Ge4f6] Ne4-[d6] is always uncomfortable, but we also might have tricks involving [Nf6]+ followed by [exf6] and an attack on the dark squares around the black king.} *

