1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... Bd7 {The most popular move and the best one. The bishop cushions [c6] against our threat to ruin the structure.} 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] Arriving to the party on [e5] finally.} Bb5 {This move seems a little off, but it is still essayed 14% of the time. It is likely the bishop will get harassed by one thematic move or another, be it [c2]-[c4], [a2]-[a4], or [Nc3].} 9. d3 Bd6 {Here we could continue with castling and standard ideas of play on the kingside. But there's another much stronger move out there that immediately poses some questions to Black.} 10. c4 $1 {Asking the bishop a very serious question. Will it retreat to [d7] or [c6], allowing a potentially favorable trade for White, or will it go to [a6] from where it might never be rerouted to more normally accessible positions? This move is objectively strong and practically speaking even more poisonous. It is quite rare, only being tried in 5% of games from this position. Most Black players immediately erred by capturing on [c4] and only 17% were able to find the right move to fight for equality. It might be confusing why we would play [c4] here as opposed to [a4] after 9…Be7. It makes more sense here as the bishop on [d6] keeps the d-file more closed, making the weakening of our [d3]-pawn less of an issue than it was before.} Ba6 $1 11. O-O O-O 12. Nd2 {It is unclear whether the knight will stay on [d2] to keep supporting the [c4] and [e4]-squares, or whether it will continue on to [f3]. In either case, it is more harmoniously placed here than it would be on [c3] where it would block the [b2]-bishop. We will look at the five most popular options in this position, all being played with frequencies between 10 and 20%.} b5 13. Nc6 {It appears we have the same exact trick as after 12...b6 . For a deeper explanation of things, check out that variation. I will limit myself to one line here.} Qc7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qg4+ Kh8 16. Qh4 $1 {[%csl Rf6] Threatening a dangerous check on [f6] followed by a venomous rook lift.} Rg8 17. Qxf6+ Rg7 {This is where the line diverges slightly from that after 12...b6. There is pressure on [c4] here giving Black options of making more relative chaos after White's [Ne5]. We will deviate from the immediate knight hop and instead seek a stable structure.} 18. cxd5 exd5 19. e4 $1 {With the point that we will get a piece back after the knight drops.} Qxc6 20. e5 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf6c6] The pin nets us the bishop. Black will likely restore material equality by getting the pawn back, but the ensuing imbalance of knight vs. bishop will favor us. The opponent's bishop is quite bad and the kingside is also fractured.} *

