1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... Bd7 {The most popular move and the best one. The bishop cushions [c6] against our threat to ruin the structure.} 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] Arriving to the party on [e5] finally.} Bb5 {This move seems a little off, but it is still essayed 14% of the time. It is likely the bishop will get harassed by one thematic move or another, be it [c2]-[c4], [a2]-[a4], or [Nc3].} 9. d3 Bd6 {Here we could continue with castling and standard ideas of play on the kingside. But there's another much stronger move out there that immediately poses some questions to Black.} 10. c4 $1 {Asking the bishop a very serious question. Will it retreat to [d7] or [c6], allowing a potentially favorable trade for White, or will it go to [a6] from where it might never be rerouted to more normally accessible positions? This move is objectively strong and practically speaking even more poisonous. It is quite rare, only being tried in 5% of games from this position. Most Black players immediately erred by capturing on [c4] and only 17% were able to find the right move to fight for equality. It might be confusing why we would play [c4] here as opposed to [a4] after 9…Be7. It makes more sense here as the bishop on [d6] keeps the d-file more closed, making the weakening of our [d3]-pawn less of an issue than it was before.} Ba6 $1 11. O-O O-O 12. Nd2 {It is unclear whether the knight will stay on [d2] to keep supporting the [c4] and [e4]-squares, or whether it will continue on to [f3]. In either case, it is more harmoniously placed here than it would be on [c3] where it would block the [b2]-bishop. We will look at the five most popular options in this position, all being played with frequencies between 10 and 20%.} Nd7 {The best of the bunch. Black immediately challenges the [e5]-knight and will resolve the placing of the [a6]-bishop down the road.} 13. Nxd7 {This capture is executed for concrete reasons. White will pressure [g7] quickly to get some concessions out of Black.} Qxd7 14. Qg4 $1 f5 {This is the move we wanted to elicit. Our bishop on [b2] will scan the diagonal forever as ...[f7]-[f6] can never build concrete against it anymore.} 15. Qg3 $36 {[%cal Gb2g7,Gd2f3,Gf3e5,Yh2h4,Yh4h5,Yh5h6] Our bishop scans the board and we will aim for [Nf3]-[e5]. A strong idea would be to throw up the h-pawn as far as it can go. Sooner or later, Black will have to move one pawn or another to deal with it and when that happens, Black will have created new weak squares on the kingside for us to probe.} *

