ositional threat of [Nxc6] to double the pawns.} 9. O-O Be7 10. d3 O-O {Here, if White wants a solid type of equality, White could trade on [c6]. Of course, you purchased one of GingerGM's courses, which are renowned for their spice so such bland options won't quench your distinguished palate. We will keep more tension in the position even though it carries a little strategic risk.} 11. Nd2 {This is risky because if Black insists, Black can keep the bishop pair with ...[Be8]. Such a move would not give them an advantage or anything, but it would make the position heavily double-edged with chances for both sides.} Rad8 12. Rf3 $1 {The rook plans to swing to [h3] for more tricks and traps.} (12. Ndf3 $2 Be8 {and our activity won't signify much after Black plays ...[Nd7] and ...[f7]-[f6] to stunt our [e5]-knight and [b2]-bishop.} 13. Qe2 b5 14. Rae1 Nd7 {⩱ .}) 12... d4 ({Opening the bishop and attacking the rook.} 12... Be8 13. Rh3 d4 {would transpose.}) 13. Rh3 $1 (13. e4 $6 {Blocking the bishop doesn't turn out well for White since we did not resolve the concrete on [d4] and after} Be8 {, we are worse. Black will play ...[Nd7] shortly and the [e8]-bishop will find greener pastures after ...[f7]-[f6].}) 13... h6 {This cushions the h-file from our rook's pressure so we will readjust to the new target on [g7].} 14. Rg3 $13 {the game remains extremely complicated. Remember, if Black can play ...[Be8] to preserve the bishop, we do not want to play [e3]-[e4]. We might play [Nxc6] and follow ...[Qxc6] with [e3]-[e4], when we can reroute the bishop from [b2]-[c1]-[d2] after [Nd2]-[f3]. Another idea is [c2]-[c4] immediately since after ...[dxc3] [Bxc3], our weakness on [d3] is well cushioned by the [e5]-knight and our bishop would finally look down the diagonal with confidence.} *

