1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... Bd7 {The most popular move and the best one. The bishop cushions [c6] against our threat to ruin the structure.} 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] Arriving to the party on [e5] finally.} Qc7 {Black defends against the positional threat of [Nxc6] to double the pawns.} 9. O-O Be7 10. d3 O-O {Here, if White wants a solid type of equality, White could trade on [c6]. Of course, you purchased one of GingerGM's courses, which are renowned for their spice so such bland options won't quench your distinguished palate. We will keep more tension in the position even though it carries a little strategic risk.} 11. Nd2 {This is risky because if Black insists, Black can keep the bishop pair with ...[Be8]. Such a move would not give them an advantage or anything, but it would make the position heavily double-edged with chances for both sides.} b5 12. Rf3 {[%cal Gf3g3] The rook prepares to move to [h3] or [g3]. Black tends to respond in 4 different ways here.} c4 13. Rg3 {[%cal Ge5g4,Yd2f3,Yf3d4] The game remains tense. We might consider [Ng4] or [Ndf3]-[d4] as ways to increase the pressure. While Black does have the bishop pair, we have great control over the central dark squares, keeping the game double-edged and balanced.} *

