ime. Black immediately brings the fight to the implanted knight.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. d3 {While Stockfish is adamant that the situation is level, such positions are like the many others in this course − full of ideas that allow the player with more experience and a better grasp on the position to achieve victory.} d4 {[%csl Gc4,Rc5,Rc6][%cal Rd5d4] As mentioned in other variations, this is a big positional sin when combined with a set of doubled c-pawns on [c6] and [c5]. It weakens the [c4] and [e4]-squares, and while it does shut the [b2]-bishop out for now, [d4] is under tension and this factor could quickly disappear.} 11. g3 {Reinforcing [f4], which will likely be undermined as [e3] falls.} dxe3 12. Na3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Ga3c4] The knight aims for [c4]. White will duly recollect the pawn with [Qe2] and [Qxe3] or [Nc4xe3]. White has a solid edge due to the ugly black c-pawns.} Nd5 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gd5f4] With serious threats of ...[Nxf4] and ...[Qh4]+ with a mating attack on our king.} 13. Qe2 O-O 14. Nc4 $14 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gc4e3,Ra7a5,Ya2a4] The [e3]-pawn isn't even going anywhere so we don't need to rush to take it. We will castle and eventually capture it at our leisure. Black's structure is really ugly and if they play ...[a7]-[a5] with the idea of trading off the isolated a-pawn with ...[a5]-[a4] and ...[a4xb3], we will respond with [a2]-[a4], freezing the pawn on [a5].} *

