1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 {In this chapter, we'll go over this French setup in which Black voluntarily locks in the [c8]-bishop. For positions in which Black adopts the [e6]-[d5] structure with the bishop already out, check the Delayed French Setup chapter. While this may seem silly, these positions are considered one of the best ways to respond to the Bird, since without their bishop out on [g4] or [f5] we can't gain time harassing it. This chapter was probably the hardest for me in the entire course. It took several sleepless nights to work out all the details, but I feel confident in the approach I found. Several of the positions in this line are 0s according to the computer but heavily double-edged, making for a strong fight with great chances for both players.} 4. b3 c5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 28% of games.} 5. Bb2 Nc6 {By far the most popular continuation, being favored in 46% of games. This position has been reached through various transpositions and is the most common setup against our repertoire. It can also be reached via 2...c5 , 3.e3 Nc6 , (when after we play [b3] ...[Nf6] and ...[e6] or ...[e6] and ...[Nf6] are Black's most popular options by far.)} 6. Bb5 {The most natural move and the most popular. The bishop pins the knight, freezing it out of the fight for [e5]. By placing the bishop in such a way, we are effectively committing to the trade on [c6] if harassed by ...[a7]-[a6].} (6. Rg1 $2 {Applying this aggressive idea in this position is a bit too unorthodox to rationalize. Black hasn't committed the king to the kingside yet and furthermore, Black can jam up any attempted pressure along the long diagonal with ...[d5]-[d4].}) 6... Bd7 {The most popular move and the best one. The bishop cushions [c6] against our threat to ruin the structure.} 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] Arriving to the party on [e5] finally.} Bd6 {This is played 33% of the time. Black immediately brings the fight to the implanted knight.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. d3 {While Stockfish is adamant that the situation is level, such positions are like the many others in this course − full of ideas that allow the player with more experience and a better grasp on the position to achieve victory.} O-O 11. O-O {We both decide that it’s time to castle.} Re8 {Here [Nd2] is played in the vast majority of games. We want to beckon our opponent into foggy terrain, and so we should opt for other ideas whenever they're of equivalent strength.} 12. Qf3 {This is played only 4% of the time.} e5 {We will not trade on [e5] here, as our [e3]-pawn would simply end up a target after all the exchanges. Instead, we will play calmly − Black isn't threatening anything yet.} 13. Nd2 {This position has only been reached 16 times. I will cover the 4 most frequent continuations of this limited sample.} exf4 14. exf4 Qe7 15. g3 {This just transposes to 13...Qe7 .} *

