1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Whenever we see the knight here we should look to pin immediately.} 4. Bb5 Qb6 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rb6b5,Rb6c6] Attacking the bishop and defending against the chop. But [d5] is weakened in the process...} 5. c4 $1 {Crunching in the center and securing our bishop for the moment.} Nf6 {Stressing the [d5]-defenses.} 6. Nc3 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5]} dxc4 {Nf6 Ne5 would transpose to 5...Nf6 6.Nc3 dxc4 7.Ne5 .} 7. Ne5 {There is no need to collect on [c4] though that would also be fine as well. We threaten to wreck the structure first with [Nxc6] and only then recapture on [c4]. The knight also attacks [f7], which may also become relevant in some lines.} Be6 {We have several ways to get an advantage here Qf3 or [Qa4] for instance, but I will recommend the crazy computer line, which aims for full mobility.} 8. b3 $1 cxb3 9. axb3 {[%csl Ga1] The rook is open and White has a fiery initiative; [Qf3] and [O-O] are obviously in White's intentions, but another, even stronger threat, exists as well.} g6 $2 (9... a6 {would have been better, when White keeps great pressure with} 10. Bb2 {↑ . Qf3 and [O-O] will come shortly.}) 10. Ra6 $18 {[%cal Rb7a6,Gb5c6] That's the game!} *

