1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Whenever we see the knight here we should look to pin immediately.} 4. Bb5 Qb6 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rb6b5,Rb6c6] Attacking the bishop and defending against the chop. But [d5] is weakened in the process...} 5. c4 $1 {Crunching in the center and securing our bishop for the moment.} e6 6. Nc3 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Pressuring the pawn further. Black has several options here, none of which gets equality.} Nge7 {[%cal Ge7c6] This looks thematically principled since the knight appears to be able to recapture on [c6], but actually, if we were to chop there, Black would have to take with the queen since [d5] is under too much pressure after ...[Ne7xc6].} 7. Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c6] Weighing down on [c6].} a6 8. Ba4 {Keeping the pressure in place. The positional threat is [Nxc6], when Black will either have to take with the b-pawn, conceding a ruinous structure, or take with the knight, forfeiting the [d5]-pawn.} (8. Bxc6+ {doesn't work so well here, as we're too far extended to safely snatch the [d5]-pawn.} Nxc6 $1 {(8...bxc6?? leads Black to a terrible structure. 9.b3 ± and (White has a near-winning advantage already. The knight will glide to [a4] and White will finish development with [Bb2]/[a3] and [O-O]. The [c5]-pawn will soon drop White might have to play the cool [Ne5]-[d3] to overwhelm Black's defenses there.)) After} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nxd5 Qd8 {, White is up a pawn but dearly misses the light-squared bishop whose absence leaves several (light squares particularly [d3] weak. Black has fine compensation.)}) 8... Qd8 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd8d5] Returning to defend [d5] in time.} 9. b3 $1 {Preparing to play [Bb2] shortly. Notice that with the pawn on [c4], our bishop doesn't need to fear being trapped by any ...[b7]-[b5] advance from Black.} (9. f5 $5 {is a slightly less good alternative that looks cool and chaotic. If it appeals to you more feel free to analyze it at home.}) (9. Nxc6 $2 {, the chop here is surprisingly inaccurate.} Nxc6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 {⩲ , though this looks like a classic post chop bind with our pawns on [f4] and [c4], the fact that we lack the [f3]-knight means Black can play for a very quick ...[e6]-[e5], keeping White's edge to a minimum.}) 9... Bd7 {The only way to try to make sense of Black's setup. Black has to try to force the exchange of the [c6]-knight to make way for ...[Ne7]-[c6] followed by ...[Bf8]-[e7] or ...[Bf8]-[d6].} 10. O-O Nxe5 11. fxe5 {We needn't fear the doubled e-pawns. Our rook has gained immediate pressure on the f-file.} Nc6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black is so close to finishing development... and just needs 2 tempi to secure ...[Be7] and ...[O-O].} 12. Qh5 $1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gh5f7] Too slow! [Qxf7] mate is immediately threatened.} g6 13. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3f7] Continuing the barbaric chess; [Qxf7]# is once again threatened.} Qe7 14. cxd5 {[%cal Gd5d6] White is breaking through the center and [d5]-[d6] threatens to boot the queen out.} Nxe5 15. Bxd7+ Kd8 $1 {The best move, but Black is of course losing if it's come to this.} ({After} 15... Qxd7 16. Qf6 {, the rook or knight will immediately fall.}) (15... Kxd7 {is also bad, unsurprisingly.} 16. Qf4 {and White remains a pawn up with the black king in the center − certainly nothing to complain about.}) (15... Nxd7 16. d6 {+- is a nice deflection to distract the black queen from [f7]. White has a winning attack.}) 16. Qf4 Nxd7 17. Qxf7 $18 {White nets a pawn with superior activity and can look forward to a technically winning endgame.} *

