1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Whenever we see the knight here we should look to pin immediately.} 4. Bb5 Qb6 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rb6b5,Rb6c6] Attacking the bishop and defending against the chop. But [d5] is weakened in the process...} 5. c4 $1 {Crunching in the center and securing our bishop for the moment.} e6 6. Nc3 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Pressuring the pawn further. Black has several options here, none of which gets equality.} d4 {Pushing our knight around, but no matter, we have a wonderful square to venture towards in the center.} 7. Ne4 {The knight sits well here. It targets [d6] and [c5] and deters Black from bringing the knight forward to the natural square on [f6].} Nf6 ({In case of} 7... Bd7 8. exd4 cxd4 9. d3 {⩲ , White has a nice structure. We will castle and get our queenside majority going with [a2]-[a3] and [b2]-[b4].}) 8. Nxf6+ {Wrecking Black's kingside.} gxf6 9. exd4 (9. e4 $5 {could also be interesting, but the engine is adamant that exchanging}) 9... cxd4 {[%cal Gd4d3] Black threatens to throw the pawn to [d3], disrupting our coordination, which forces our next move.} 10. d3 Bd7 {This entire structure both White's and Black's is unique and so I'd assume the majority of Black players here to immediately start fumbling.} 11. O-O Rg8 12. a3 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc1d2] We will continue with normal queenside play of [b2]-[b4] and then look to improve our position with moves like [Bd2]. An interesting idea the computer likes is trading on [c6] followed by [b4]-[b5] and [Bd2]-[b4]. White has a solid advantage and is certainly the one in the driver's seat.} *

