1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nc6 {Whenever we see the knight here we should look to pin immediately.} 4. Bb5 Qb6 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rb6b5,Rb6c6] Attacking the bishop and defending against the chop. But [d5] is weakened in the process...} 5. c4 $1 {Crunching in the center and securing our bishop for the moment.} e6 6. Nc3 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Pressuring the pawn further. Black has several options here, none of which gets equality.} d4 {Pushing our knight around, but no matter, we have a wonderful square to venture towards in the center.} 7. Ne4 {The knight sits well here. It targets [d6] and [c5] and deters Black from bringing the knight forward to the natural square on [f6].} Be7 {[%cal Gg8f6] Preparing to play ...[Nf6], when the bishop can recapture there, but it seems a bit slow.} ({In case of} 7... Bd7 8. exd4 cxd4 9. d3 {⩲ , White has a nice structure. We will castle and get our queenside majority going with [a2]-[a3] and [b2]-[b4].}) 8. b4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c5,Ge3d4] Undermining Black's structure from all angles. White immediately threatens to trade on [c5], when [d4] will be hanging.} cxb4 9. Bb2 {[%csl Rd4,Rg7][%cal Gb2d4] White threatens [Bxd4] with a strong initiative.} Nf6 (9... dxe3 $4 10. Bxg7 {and the mango on [h8] will fall.}) 10. Bxd4 Qc7 11. Nxf6+ {Forcing a weakening of Black's kingside.} gxf6 (11... Bxf6 12. Bxf6 gxf6 {and Black's structure has been compromised all the same.}) 12. O-O $16 {White is just better with a nicer structure and more active pieces.} *

