1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to set up the French structure with ...[e6] with the [c8]-bishop already placed outside on [g4] or [f5]. This tends to be a bit too idealistic for Black and they often get into trouble with the quintessential broken queenside.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... Bg4 5. Bb2 e6 6. h3 {Snagging the bishop pair as usual.} Bh5 {Black attempts to keep the pressure.} 7. Bb5+ {Before we know whether or not to push [g2]-[g4] we want to see how Black will block the check.} Nfd7 {Rarely tried, but it is actually Black's best option. Here [g2]-[g4] isn't yet worth the squeeze. We must be patient.} 8. O-O f6 {Opening the diagonal for the [h5]-bishop to retreat to [f7] if need be. This weakens [e6] though so we should aim to strike with [c4].} 9. Be2 $1 {[%cal Gc2c4] We don't want to lock our bishop on [b5] in with [c2]-[c4].} Nc6 10. c4 Bf7 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nc3 Be7 13. Rc1 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rd5,Rd7][%cal Rd8d5] White has a slight advantage. The pawn on [c5] might become weak and [d5] is also vulnerable since the [d7]-knight can't easily return to [f6] due to obvious reasons. We should plan flexibly but some ideas that could be interesting are [Nc3]-[a4] or [Be2]-[d3]-[b1] to form an eventual battery with [Qc2].} *

