1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to set up the French structure with ...[e6] with the [c8]-bishop already placed outside on [g4] or [f5]. This tends to be a bit too idealistic for Black and they often get into trouble with the quintessential broken queenside.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... Bg4 5. Bb2 e6 6. h3 {Snagging the bishop pair as usual.} Bh5 {Black attempts to keep the pressure.} 7. Bb5+ {Before we know whether or not to push [g2]-[g4] we want to see how Black will block the check.} Nc6 8. g4 Bg6 9. Ne5 {[%cal Ge5c6,Ge5g6] With nice joint pressure on [c6] and [g6].} Nd7 {[%cal Gd8h4] Gambitting the pawn in an attempt to sneak the queen into [h4].} 10. Nxc6 {We accept the gambit.} Qh4+ 11. Ke2 a6 (11... bxc6 12. Bxc6 Rc8 13. Bb5 {± and we're a healthy pawn up. We can meet Black's ...[Qg3] with [Qg1]; ...[Bg6]-[e4] can be met with [Qe1] to attack the black queen on [h4]. We will gradually untangle with a nice middlegame to look toward.}) 12. Ba4 b5 {It seems that Black has achieved their aim of muddying the water. Some silicon moves can bring us an edge though. :} 13. d3 bxa4 14. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2f3] Our knight comes to [f3] and it turns out we have a healthy structure. If the queen comes to [g3], we can respond with [Qg1]. Meanwhile, we look forward to responding to ...[axb3] with [axb3], when we'll have great pressure on [a6].} *

