1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to set up the French structure with ...[e6] with the [c8]-bishop already placed outside on [g4] or [f5]. This tends to be a bit too idealistic for Black and they often get into trouble with the quintessential broken queenside.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... Bg4 5. Bb2 e6 6. h3 {Snagging the bishop pair as usual.} Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Nc6 8. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gb2h8] Going for gold on the g-file. This is not the first nor the last time we have combined a queenside fianchetto with kingside expansion. Black is already in a dilemma since moving the bishop will leave the g-pawn hanging on [g7] after the [f6]-knight gets kicked.} a6 {Stopping any [Bb5] ideas.} 9. Nc3 {This looks ugly here, as it blocks the bishop, but it will probably be rerouted via [e2] to [g3].} d4 10. Ne2 Nd5 11. Bg2 $14 {We have great pressure from our bishops. We can castle to either side depending on how things develop. Sooner or later, the [d4]-pawn will sway and our [b2]-bishop will exert pressure on the second long diagonal.} *

