1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to set up the French structure with ...[e6] with the [c8]-bishop already placed outside on [g4] or [f5]. This tends to be a bit too idealistic for Black and they often get into trouble with the quintessential broken queenside.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... Bf5 5. Bb2 e6 6. Bb5+ Nbd7 7. O-O Bd6 8. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5] Chasing the pesky bishop.} Be4 9. d3 Bg6 10. Bxd7+ {Black is in a pickle. Taking with the queen loosens [f6], but taking with the knight loosens [g7].} Nxd7 11. g3 {Protecting the knight on [h4]; [g7] is now under threat.} Nf6 {Chopping on [g6] is okay here, but we should be more aggressive.} 12. f5 $1 exf5 13. Nxf5 {Now Black has to trade the light-squared bishop anyway, under much better circumstances for White.} Bxf5 14. Rxf5 {[%cal Gb2f6] The [f6]-knight is under a lot of pressure. It is clear the bishop on [d6] should have been developed to [e7].} Be7 15. Qf3 O-O 16. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Yd5d4,Yc3e4,Gf5d5,Gf3d5,Gc3d5] Here [d5] is under a lot of pressure and moving it will cede even more light squares. We can meet ...[d5]-[d4] with a trade on [d4] and [Nc3]-[e4] or [Nc3]-[d5].} *

