1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to set up the French structure with ...[e6] with the [c8]-bishop already placed outside on [g4] or [f5]. This tends to be a bit too idealistic for Black and they often get into trouble with the quintessential broken queenside.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... Bf5 5. Bb2 e6 6. Bb5+ Nbd7 7. O-O Bd6 8. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5] Chasing the pesky bishop.} Be4 9. d3 Bg6 10. Bxd7+ {Black is in a pickle. Taking with the queen loosens [f6], but taking with the knight loosens [g7].} Qxd7 {Taking on [f6] here wouldn't rupture the structure enough to be worth the [b2]-dragon.} 11. Qf3 Bh5 12. Qg3 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gg3g7,Gb2h8] The pressure is getting uncomfortable.} Be7 {[%cal Rg3g7,Rh8g8]} (12... Be7 {Now} 13. Qxg7 {can be met by} Rg8 {.}) 13. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gh4f3,Gf3e5] We'll play for [Nhf3] and [Ne5] with a nice initiative. White is definitely in the driver's seat. Black has the bishop pair momentarily, but the light-squared bishop is so cramped it will probably trade itself on [f3] when the knight lands there.} *

