1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to set up the French structure with ...[e6] with the [c8]-bishop already placed outside on [g4] or [f5]. This tends to be a bit too idealistic for Black and they often get into trouble with the quintessential broken queenside.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... Bf5 5. Bb2 e6 6. Bb5+ Nbd7 7. O-O Bd6 8. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5] Chasing the pesky bishop.} Be4 9. d3 Bg6 10. Bxd7+ {Black is in a pickle. Taking with the queen loosens [f6], but taking with the knight loosens [g7].} Qxd7 {Taking on [f6] here wouldn't rupture the structure enough to be worth the [b2]-dragon.} 11. Qf3 O-O 12. Nd2 Bh5 13. Qg3 {[%cal Gb2f6] Now [Bxf6] is a big threat.} Be7 14. e4 $36 {With an initiative. First, we can bring the rook from [a1]-[e1]. Then we'll follow with [e4]-[e5], [f4]-[f5] or [Ndf3]-[e5]. It's important to note what happens if Black crunches on [e4].} dxe4 $2 15. Nxe4 Bg6 ({Shielding the g7-pawn.} 15... Nxe4 $4 {is not recommended.} 16. Qxg7# {is checkmate.}) 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. f5 $1 {Black must accept the tripled pawns with ...[exf5] to save the bishop. White has a healthier structure, to say the least!} exf5 19. Nxf5 $16 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gf1f2,Ga1f1] Black's [f6]-pawn will be weak. We should look to double rooks on the f-file and remove the knight from [f5] to collect the apple sooner or later.} *

