1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to set up the French structure with ...[e6] with the [c8]-bishop already placed outside on [g4] or [f5]. This tends to be a bit too idealistic for Black and they often get into trouble with the quintessential broken queenside.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... Bf5 5. Bb2 e6 6. Bb5+ Nbd7 7. O-O a6 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. d3 {Notice we don't want to give our second bishop just to double their pawns on [f6].} Bg6 (9... Be7 {transposes to 7...Be7 8.Bxd7 Qxd7 with an extra tempo due to Black having thrown in the useless ...[a7]-[a6].}) 10. Ne5 Qc7 11. Nd2 {Keeping flexibility. We haven't decided yet whether to move knight or queen to [f3].} Bd6 12. Qe1 O-O 13. Ndf3 $13 {[%cal Ge1h4] We will play [Qe1]-[h4] and then prepare [e3]-[e4] with moves like [Rae1] and perhaps a chop on the [g6]-dragon. The position is objectively level, but we have the more fun position, obviously.} *

