1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to set up the French structure with ...[e6] with the [c8]-bishop already placed outside on [g4] or [f5]. This tends to be a bit too idealistic for Black and they often get into trouble with the quintessential broken queenside.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... Bf5 5. Bb2 e6 6. Bb5+ Nfd7 {This is fine though it is rarely chosen, being essayed at a frequency of 1%.} 7. O-O a6 {Here we could trade on [d7], but I prefer to keep the bishop on.} 8. Be2 Nc6 9. d3 $13 {[%csl Rf5,Rg7][%cal Gb2g7,Gb1d2,Ge3e4,Yd1e1,Yf3h4] The pressure on [g7] is uncomfortable and keeps Black from developing normally. White has a very slight edge, though it is very close to equal. We should play against the [f5]-bishop, either with [Qe1] and [Nh4] or with [Nbd2] and [e3]-[e4].} *

