1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to set up the French structure with ...[e6] with the [c8]-bishop already placed outside on [g4] or [f5]. This tends to be a bit too idealistic for Black and they often get into trouble with the quintessential broken queenside.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... Bf5 5. Bb2 e6 6. Bb5+ Nc6 $2 {Those of you who have already studied the other chapters will recognize why this move should be dubious. Yet that doesn't change the fact it is chosen by Black 70% of the time. Instead, moving either of the knights to [d7] would have been the correct way to handle things. We could chop on c6 here, which would likely transpose to the variation analyzed in this chapter after 3...Nc6 and 6...Bf5 , but it makes more sense to add a bit of pressure first.} 7. Ne5 {[%cal Gg2g4]} Qb6 {This is tried on occasion.} (7... Rc8 {will likely transpose to the variation of 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Rc8 7.O-O e6 8.Ne5 . We should just chop with a timely [Bxc6] and then follow with [d2]-[d3] and a controlled [g2]-[g4].}) 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. g4 Bg6 10. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} (10. d3 $2 {wouldn't work here since the [b6]-queen x-rays our [e3]-pawn.} c4 {⩱ , George is getting upset!}) 10... Be4 11. Rg1 {We forego castling kingside. The bishop has some questions to answer now, as [d2]-[d3] and [h4]-[h5] threaten to trap it.} h5 {Here again, [d2]-[d3] runs into [c5]-[c4].} 12. Nc3 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc3e4] Attacking the bishop on [e4] in a different way.} hxg4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Qxg4 $16 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gg1g2,Yd2d3,Ge1c1,Re4f2] We will cover the ...[Nf2] fork with [Rg2] and then castle queenside and push the knight off [e4] with [d2]-[d3]. Black has enormous practical problems such as finding a secure place for the king or figuring out a way to push our knight out of the dominating [e5]-square. While our structure might look worse, the [g7]-pawn is effectively weaker than our [h4]-pawn.} *

