1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to set up the French structure with ...[e6] with the [c8]-bishop already placed outside on [g4] or [f5]. This tends to be a bit too idealistic for Black and they often get into trouble with the quintessential broken queenside.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... Bf5 5. Bb2 e6 6. Bb5+ Nc6 $2 {Those of you who have already studied the other chapters will recognize why this move should be dubious. Yet that doesn't change the fact it is chosen by Black 70% of the time. Instead, moving either of the knights to [d7] would have been the correct way to handle things. We could chop on c6 here, which would likely transpose to the variation analyzed in this chapter after 3...Nc6 and 6...Bf5 , but it makes more sense to add a bit of pressure first.} 7. Ne5 {[%cal Gg2g4]} Qc7 {The top move by far, but it digs Black into an even deeper pit. The queen is not well placed here for a few reasons. It doesn't defend the [f6]-knight making [Bxf6] ideas more destructive to Black's structure. It also sits on a square where it may be a target of [Bb2]-[e5]. And lastly, it does nothing to prevent the doubling of c-pawns if White takes on [c6].} (7... Rc8 {will likely transpose to the variation of 5...Nc6 6.Bb5 Rc8 7.O-O e6 8.Ne5 . We should just chop with a timely [Bxc6] and then follow with [d2]-[d3] and a controlled [g2]-[g4].}) 8. d3 a6 9. Bxc6+ {We are happy to chop.} bxc6 10. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gg2g4] We will play [Qf3], [g2]-[g4]. We could castle either way. We have a great version of things. A simple strategy is to just try to trap the light-squared bishop with kingside expansion like [h2]-[h4]-[h5].} *

