1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 c5 3. e3 Nf6 {This chapter will deal with Black's attempts to go for a combination of a kingside fianchetto with ...[d5] and ...[c5]. While it's very rare at lower levels, this mixing of ...[d7]-[d5] with ...[g6]-[g7] is extremely common among the elite. Every time I play a GM or IM in Titled Tuesday they play it with only rare exceptions.} 4. b3 (4. b3 {If Black plays} e6 {, this will just transpose to the French Setup chapter.}) 4... g6 {Black abandons all notions of the French setup, placing confidence in the kingside Fianchetto instead.} 5. Bb2 Bg7 {We now face a difficult decision: where to place our bishop?? Its goal was to pin the [c6]-knight from [b5] but Black has correctly delayed the development of the [b8]-knight for as long as possible. We must make do without the pin and instead, settle for another natural square.} 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Nc6 {Black's knight smirks as it enters the ring. Our bishop would look like a fool to burn another move to go to [b5] now.} 8. Ne5 {[%csl Ge5] Our knight enters the center.} Qc7 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 (9... bxc6 {wouldn't make any sense − what was the point of ...[Qc7] then?!?!} 10. Be5 {⩲ , we will play [Nc3], and perhaps [Na4] to target [c5] if the moment is right. Our queen will go to [e1] and onward to [g3] or [h4] and our bishop will go to [d3]. We have a nice edge due to the better structure.}) 10. Bf3 {[%cal Gf3c6,Gb2g7] Our bishops are impressive.} b6 {Black prepares to bring their own light-squared bishop to the long diagonal.} 11. a4 {Gaining some space on the queenside. Now, if Black ever chooses to expand there, in the long term it will be more difficult.} Bb7 12. Qe1 $13 {[%cal Ge1h4,Yc5c4,Yb3b4] Our queen will transfer to [h4]. The game is slow and complicated. Neither side really wants to move any pawns, as it would do more harm than good to their structure. We will meet ...[c5]-[c4] with [b3]-[b4], keeping files closed on the queenside. The position is extremely hard to play, which is perfect for us since we will probably have more experience than our opponents, giving us significantly better chances.} *

