1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} (3. e3 {This chapter will cover the less popular third moves for Black. They tend to be weaker than the top moves} Nf6 {and 3...Bg4 .}) 3... f6 {[%cal Ge7e5] A seemingly strange move that does make some sense. ...[Nc6] is fighting for ...[e5] after all, and this move ties into that same idea.} 4. d4 {[%cal Gd4e5,Gf4e5] Shutting down Black's idea.} e5 {This is played 30% and is the most logical of Black's options. Their entire setup had been geared to ...[e5] so even if it doesn't get complete equality, it would be too costly to avert course now.} 5. fxe5 fxe5 (5... Bg4 {could possibly be played first but after} 6. Bb5 {, Black is best advised to trade on [e5], transposing to positions after 5...fxe5 .}) 6. dxe5 {We are happy to hold on to the extra pawn. Despite the ugly nature of our doubled e-pawns, it will be hard for Black to target [e5]. The [f8]-bishop can't attack it easily and if Black opts for ...[Qe7], the [d5]-pawn will become extremely vulnerable. As ugly as our [e5]-pawn is, it keeps the knight out of [f6], and for this we should be quite grateful.} Bg4 {This move enjoys extreme popularity with 60% of Black players opting for it. The situation is very close to level, but we can still put some real pressure on our opponents with some precise moves.} (6... Nxe5 $4 {is played 8% of the time.} 7. Nxe5 Qh4+ 8. g3 Qe4 {, perhaps Black thought this trick worked... but it doesn't:} 9. Nf3 {+- .}) 7. Bb5 {As mentioned before, the health of the [e5]-pawn is critical to evaluating the outcome of the opening. If it drops, Black should be fine while if we can maintain it, its control over the [d6] and [f6]-squares will be a source of permanent discomfort to Black's pieces.} a6 8. Bxc6+ {[%csl Ge5] We are ecstatic to make this trade here. It gives Black the classic doubled c-pawns but much more importantly, it relieves Black of any legitimate hope of scooping up [e5]. Simply we will have too much time to safeguard it before Black attacks it.} bxc6 9. O-O Nh6 10. Qd4 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Ge5][%cal Gb1c3,Yd4f4,Yc6c5,Ge3e4] Our queen sits comfortably here and will readjust to [f4] if it's attacked by ...[c6]-[c5]. Black is nowhere close to rounding up the [e5]-pawn. We want to play [Nc3] and then promptly throw in [e3]-[e4], clearing the lane for our bishop and also clearing the e-file such that we can support the [e5]-pawn.} *

