1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} (3. e3 {This chapter will cover the less popular third moves for Black. They tend to be weaker than the top moves} Nf6 {and 3...Bg4 .}) 3... f6 {[%cal Ge7e5] A seemingly strange move that does make some sense. ...[Nc6] is fighting for ...[e5] after all, and this move ties into that same idea.} 4. d4 {[%cal Gd4e5,Gf4e5] Shutting down Black's idea.} Bg4 {This is by far the most popular try at a frequency of 36%.} 5. c4 {Pressing upon the lack of Black control over the central light squares.} dxc4 6. d5 $1 {Pushing the knight back and digging into the weak [e6]-square. Black's position should be beyond strategic repair at this point. No one has responded this way in a real game sadly, so the first student to play this can say they played a novelty.} Bxf3 7. gxf3 {This capture keeps our queen on [d1] so the knight can't escape to [b4] due to [Qa4]+.} Nb8 8. Bxc4 $18 {Black's position is a disaster. The [e7]-pawn won't move forever due to the [d5]-boulder, but how then will the [f8]-bishop or [g8]-knight be properly developed? White is already winning, though of course, you will still need to make good moves to net the full point.} *

