1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} (3. e3 {This chapter will cover the less popular third moves for Black. They tend to be weaker than the top moves} Nf6 {and 3...Bg4 .}) 3... Bf5 {The bishop does little here but just the same it is played 14% of the time. It is worse than ...[Bg4] for a few reasons. First, it doesn't inconvenience our [f3]-knight in any way. Second, our knight can go to [d4] in certain instances and attack the bishop perhaps with a double attack against a [c6]-pawn gaining a free tempo. The one small advantage of the bishop's placement on [f5] over [g4] is that White doesn't have a way to immediately harass the bishop with [h2]-[h3].} 4. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Pinning the knight and immediately creating ideas of [Bxc6] to ruin Black's structure. We will look at Black's 6 most popular moves.} a6 {This is played 25% of the time and yet, like every other situation in which we threaten to double the black c-pawns, it is just bad. We were going to take on [c6] anyway...} 5. Bxc6+ {Chop chop!} bxc6 {Black has achieved the classic bad structure while having burned a tempo on the completely useless ...[a6] move.} 6. b3 $14 {[%cal Gc1b2] Going for the classic [Bb2]. Black has nothing to do but revert to more classic setups involving ...[e6] and ...[Be7]. Black is just a tempo down over those variations with ...[a6], placing them one move back. Simply play this position with the ideas from the 4....e6 variations in mind and know that due to the extra tempo, we have a better version of every position.} *

