-[e4] or [Nf3]-[e5].} Ng4 $2 {This is a classic idea, synthesizing the discovery themes along the long diagonal and weakness of the [e3]-pawn.} 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 ({After} 10... Nxe3 11. Qe2 Nxf1 12. Bxf8 {+- , the [f8]-bishop will be captured by Black and the [f1]-knight by White and White will be a clean piece up.}) 11. Qd2 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Ge3][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3a4,Yd2c3,Gd2e3,Rg4e3] We have no reason to complain. Our [b2]-bishop was great but Black's was also valuable. Black has set up so many pawns on light squares just look at that kingside fianchetto! and the dark squares are consequentially weak. We should lay siege to the weak [c5]-square via [Nc3]-[a4] and potentially [Qc3] once [e3] is defended. We are close to strategically winning due to these various positional advantages.} *

