1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} (3. e3 {This chapter will cover the less popular third moves for Black. They tend to be weaker than the top moves} Nf6 {and 3...Bg4 .}) 3... Bf5 {The bishop does little here but just the same it is played 14% of the time. It is worse than ...[Bg4] for a few reasons. First, it doesn't inconvenience our [f3]-knight in any way. Second, our knight can go to [d4] in certain instances and attack the bishop perhaps with a double attack against a [c6]-pawn gaining a free tempo. The one small advantage of the bishop's placement on [f5] over [g4] is that White doesn't have a way to immediately harass the bishop with [h2]-[h3].} 4. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Pinning the knight and immediately creating ideas of [Bxc6] to ruin Black's structure. We will look at Black's 6 most popular moves.} Qd6 {Defending against the threat of structural ruin by [Bxc6]. However, the disadvantage with this is that the queen is vulnerable to [Ba3] ideas...} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1a3]} a6 6. Ba3 Qf6 {Here, our rook on [a1] and bishop on [b5] hang. We have to trade on [c6] for tactical survival.} 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 (7... Qxc6 {Now players usually go for} 8. Nd4 {with a knight fork, but it doesn't achieve much after} Qg6 {. Instead, we'll develop toward the center.}) (7... bxc6 8. Nc3 {± and we get everything we ever wanted from the Bird. Black's pawns are ruined, and Black can't play ...[e7]-[e6] on pain of our [Ba3xf8], and the queen stands in the way of ...[Nf6] − enjoy!}) 8. Nc3 f6 $1 {Apparently, this keeps things close to equal. I find it hard to believe any human player would happily continue to delay their already delayed development in this manner.} 9. Nd4 Qd7 10. Nxf5 Qxf5 11. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Yf5c2,Yc3d6,Ge1c1] Black cannot capture on [c2] on pain of [Nxd5] with the annoying threat of [Rc1]. Both sides will castle queenside, when White has a slight edge. The structure is outwardly unusual, but White has a slight lead in development allowing us to look forward to the middlegame with confidence.} *

