1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} (3. e3 {This chapter will cover the less popular third moves for Black. They tend to be weaker than the top moves} Nf6 {and 3...Bg4 .}) 3... Bf5 {The bishop does little here but just the same it is played 14% of the time. It is worse than ...[Bg4] for a few reasons. First, it doesn't inconvenience our [f3]-knight in any way. Second, our knight can go to [d4] in certain instances and attack the bishop perhaps with a double attack against a [c6]-pawn gaining a free tempo. The one small advantage of the bishop's placement on [f5] over [g4] is that White doesn't have a way to immediately harass the bishop with [h2]-[h3].} 4. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Pinning the knight and immediately creating ideas of [Bxc6] to ruin Black's structure. We will look at Black's 6 most popular moves.} Bd7 {While objectively this move makes a lot of sense, as a whole something has gone wrong when 2 consecutive moves have to be made by the same bishop along the same diagonal. Why didn't Black just put the bishop here, to begin with?} 5. O-O Nf6 6. b3 e6 7. Bb2 $14 {[%cal Gb5c6,Yf3e5,Yd2d3,Yb1d2,Yd2f3] This is analogous to positions in the 1...d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 e6 lines, when Black arrives at the same situation except with the pawn on [c5] rather than [c7]. This difference marks a dramatic improvement for us, as we can just go along with the normal plan: [Bxc6], [Nf3]-[e5], [d2]-[d3], and [Nd2]-[f3]. We have a comfortable edge.} *

