[e3]-[e4] after preparations involving [d2]-[d3], [Nbd2], and [Qe2].} Bc5 {The bishop looks a bit weird here, but it carries the prophylactic aim of limiting our plan to play [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4].} 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 (9. Ne5 $6 {would be natural to target [c6], but Black can throw our structure into a state of flux with} d4 $1 {One point is that the knight fork on [c6] burns White, not Black.} 10. Nxc6 $2 dxe3 11. Nxd8 $2 e2+ {, Black wins White's queen right back and when the dust settles, Black will be able to scoop up an extra piece on [d8].} 12. d4 exd1=Q 13. Rxd1 Raxd8 {-+ and we can't equalize material with [dxc5] due to the pin on the d-file.}) 9... Bxc2 $4 {As the rest of the line shows, this is a fatal blunder.} 10. Rc1 $1 {[%csl Rc2,Rc5]} Bxb1 11. Rxc5 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7][%cal Gc5c7] Taking the good bishop and opening the rook's view on the apples on the c-file.} Bg6 12. Rac1 $18 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7][%cal Gc5c7] Black might think they've escaped from the pressure scot-free. But the [c2]-pawn was a booby trap keeping the Black c-pawns hidden. Now that it's been taken, White can take on [c6] and look to take on [c7] maybe with [Be5], or [Bc3]-[a5] with the rooks dominating the half-open c-file. If our [c2]-pawn was still on the board, none of this would be possible.} *

