1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} (3. e3 {This chapter will cover the less popular third moves for Black. They tend to be weaker than the top moves} Nf6 {and 3...Bg4 .}) 3... Bf5 {The bishop does little here but just the same it is played 14% of the time. It is worse than ...[Bg4] for a few reasons. First, it doesn't inconvenience our [f3]-knight in any way. Second, our knight can go to [d4] in certain instances and attack the bishop perhaps with a double attack against a [c6]-pawn gaining a free tempo. The one small advantage of the bishop's placement on [f5] over [g4] is that White doesn't have a way to immediately harass the bishop with [h2]-[h3].} 4. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Pinning the knight and immediately creating ideas of [Bxc6] to ruin Black's structure. We will look at Black's 6 most popular moves.} e6 5. Bxc6+ {We are happy to take and inflict the classic doubling on Black's structure.} bxc6 6. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] Our bishop will go to [b2] and lay siege to the long diagonal.} Nf6 {The most popular move and the most natural.} 7. Bb2 {Our long-term strategy is to play for one of a few plans. First [Nf3]-[e5] might be an option to attack [c6] and threaten an intrusive [Ne5]-[c6]. From [e5] our knight also supports [g2]-[g4], which might become opportune if Black doesn't take adequate care of the [f5]-bishop. Second and more commonly, we will play for a slow [e3]-[e4] after preparations involving [d2]-[d3], [Nbd2], and [Qe2].} Bd6 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 {Notice we are not committing to the kingside with our king yet. There might very well be a moment when it makes more sense to castle queenside. In the meantime, we will play [Qe2] and either [e3]-[e4] or [Nf3]-[e5] to increase the tension. Black sorely misses the [c6]-knight, as without it, achieving the ...[e6]-[e5] push is nearly impossible.} Re8 {This has been tried a bit but doesn't pack much punch. ...[e6]-[e5] is still off the table, as there is no knight on [c6] and we cover [e5] with the [f4]-pawn, [f3]-knight, and [b2]-bishop. Moreover, we will just intrude with the knight immediately.} (9... Ng4 {is the most popular here, but I can't really understand it.} 10. Qe2 {± , we protect [e3] and are about to castle queenside and play [e3]-[e4] and [h2]-[h3] with many free tempi. The ...[Ng4] intrusion hasn't accomplished anything for Black.}) 10. Ne5 {[%csl Rc6] Hitting [c6].} c5 11. Qf3 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4] White will play [g2]-[g4], [h2]-[h4]-[h5] and likely round up the [g6]-bishop. Even if the bishop survives, we can use the free tempi from these pawn advances in conjunction with castling queenside and an attack on Black's kingside involving a pawn storm.} Bxe5 12. fxe5 {This is usually the best way to recapture, digging into [f6] and removing the knight from that square for good.} Nd7 13. h4 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh4h5] Now [g4] and [h5] threaten to trap the [f5]-bishop.} h6 14. O-O-O {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh4h5,Gg4g5] With kings on opposite sides of the board, who can attack the opponent's king first will decide the victory. We will open lines with some combination of [g2]-[g4] and [g4]-[g5] or [h4]-[h5] and due to how far ahead our pawns are compared to Black's on the queenside, we will win the race in exposing the enemy king.} *

