[e3]-[e4] after preparations involving [d2]-[d3], [Nbd2], and [Qe2].} Bd6 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 {Notice we are not committing to the kingside with our king yet. There might very well be a moment when it makes more sense to castle queenside. In the meantime, we will play [Qe2] and either [e3]-[e4] or [Nf3]-[e5] to increase the tension. Black sorely misses the [c6]-knight, as without it, achieving the ...[e6]-[e5] push is nearly impossible.} c5 {It's interesting... This move makes a lot of intuitive sense since it moves a relatively useless [c6]-pawn to [c5] where it fights for the important [d4]-square. Even so, it is a slight mistake according to the computer. I believe it comes down to the fact that it blocks the [d6]-bishop completely along the [a3]-[f8] diagonal. Black's options will henceforth be limited in this capacity. We should take care to keep our knight on [d2]. If it moves, then Black will begin to have opportunities to sacrifice ...[c5]-[c4] to self-destruct our beautiful pawn structure.} (9... Ng4 {is the most popular here, but I can't really understand it.} 10. Qe2 {± , we protect [e3] and are about to castle queenside and play [e3]-[e4] and [h2]-[h3] with many free tempi. The ...[Ng4] intrusion hasn't accomplished anything for Black.}) 10. Qe2 {[%cal Ge3e4,Ge4e5] Now [e3]-[e4] and [e4]-[e5] threaten to win a minor piece.} Bg4 {Sidestepping the [e4] bounty. White should happily take the bishop pair back.} 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 {[%cal Ge3e4] We will play [e4] with great tension in the center.} (12. Nxf3 $2 {is not accurate because the knight should have stayed on [d2] to cover ...[c5]-[c4]. For instance, Black can now play} a5 {, threatening ...[a5]-[a4] with some nice tension for Black on the queenside. After} 13. a4 c4 {∞ , White might be winning a pawn, but the structure will undoubtedly take on some weaknesses in the process. Black is doing fine.}) 12... a5 13. e4 $16 {[%csl Yc4,Rd6,Rf6][%cal Ge4e5,Yd5d4,Yd2c4] Black faces an uncomfortable dilemma: [e4]-[e5] looms and so Black will have to move a minor piece back now or trade on [e4] when we will recapture with [dxe4]. After retreating, what can Black hope to play for? Pushing ...[d5]-[d4] gives us a great outpost on [c4] for the [d2]-knight. Trading on [e4] just lets White take back with [dxe4], when the black c-pawns are extremely ugly. It is easy to see the drawbacks to Black's ...[c6]-[c5] advance, as the [d6]-bishop is completely locked in.} *

