database and the idea makes sense. Black is trying to do the best they can to shore up the control of the center in spite of lacking the [c6]-knight.} 11. h3 {Chasing the bishop back.} Bh5 ({After} 11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 {, we want to keep our eyes out for ...[c5]-[c4], sabotaging our structure and so, if the bishop takes on [f3], we will take with our queen such that our knight on [d2] keeps an eye out for that square.}) 12. g4 Bg6 13. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gf3h4,Rc5c4,Gd2c4] Notice our [d2]-knight does not want to move any time soon as it's stopping Black's ...[c5]-[c4] break when we'd have to take twice with pawns, ruining our nice structure. White has many ideas, [Nf3]-[e5] being the most natural. A nice plan pointed out by Stockfish is to reroute the [f3]-knight to [g2] via [e1] and then follow it with [e3]-[e4] and either [e4]-[e5] or [f4]-[f5].} *

