1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... a6 {This is the most common reaction, but it is just awful. White will get similar positions to those involving [Bxc6] except with Black having wasted a full tempo on the useless ...[a7]-[a6]. The fact that 25% of Black players immediately bite the bullet with this rash pawn move makes me very optimistic about the results we will reap from [Bb5].} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gd2d3,Yb1d2,Yh2h3] We will continue with the classic [Bb2] and follow thematic play against Black's structure such as by [d2]-[d3], [Nbd2], [h2]-[h3], and eventually [Nf3]-[e5].} Nf6 7. Bb2 e6 8. O-O Be7 9. d3 {Freeing the [d2]-square for the [b1]-knight.} O-O 10. Nbd2 Nd7 $1 {This is best, when Black immediately begins anticipating the eventual [Nf3]-[e5], which will come about one way or another. It also prepares ideas of ...[Bf6] to trade off the [b2]-dragon.} 11. e4 $1 Bf6 {This is always meant to be met by the central thrust.} (11... dxe4 12. dxe4 {, the trade of the [d5]-pawn leaves Black's c-pawns alone and vulnerable. White will play [Qe1] next to clear the way for [Rd1], and then follow with ideas of [Nc4] and [Ne5] or [Qe1]-[c3] or [Qe1]-[g3]. Notice that the queen was placed on [e1] to have better access to these diagonals directed at the [g3] and [e3]-squares.}) 12. e5 $1 Be7 13. Qe1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh2h3,Gg2g4] White would love to harass the bishop back to [g6] with [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4]. We could then follow with [Qe1]-[g3] and eventually play for expansion with [f4]-[f5].} (13. Qe1 {Our position is very comfortable, for example,} c5 14. h3 Bh5 (14... Bxf3 15. Nxf3 {⩲ , Black ceded the bishop pair and our [d2]-knight has simply replaced our [f3]-knight on its good square so we cant complain.}) 15. g4 Bg6 16. Qg3 {⩲ , White will happily continue with [Rae1], waiting for the perfect moment for [f4]-[f5].}) *

