1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... a6 {This is the most common reaction, but it is just awful. White will get similar positions to those involving [Bxc6] except with Black having wasted a full tempo on the useless ...[a7]-[a6]. The fact that 25% of Black players immediately bite the bullet with this rash pawn move makes me very optimistic about the results we will reap from [Bb5].} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gd2d3,Yb1d2,Yh2h3] We will continue with the classic [Bb2] and follow thematic play against Black's structure such as by [d2]-[d3], [Nbd2], [h2]-[h3], and eventually [Nf3]-[e5].} Nf6 7. Bb2 e6 8. O-O Be7 9. d3 {Freeing the [d2]-square for the [b1]-knight.} O-O 10. Nbd2 c5 11. Qe1 {Sidestepping the pin. [Nf3]-[e5] will come shortly and the [g4]-bishop will find itself bouncing around the kingside like a billiard ball.} Bxf3 12. Rxf3 $1 {Capturing with the knight to go to [e5] would have been good, but this is simply much better. We may move the rook over to [g3] or [h3] but this isn't the entire picture. The main point is that we want to prevent any hope for Black of achieving the sabotaging ...[c5]-[c4]. As long as our knight stays on [d2], this ...[c4] advance is impossible.} c6 13. e4 {[%cal Ge1e2,Ya1f1,Ra6a5,Ga2a4] We want to play [Qe2], [Raf1] or [Rae1], and then [e4]-[e5]. White's position is much better. Because we've guarded against ...[c5]-[c4], Black is at a loss for active ideas. If Black plays ...[a6]-[a5], we will respond with [a2]-[a4], freezing the a-pawns and preventing any ...[a5]-[a4xb3] ideas.} *

