1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... e6 {The second most common move, being played 20% of the time. We should take the opportunity to chop on [c6] while it still doubles the pawns. Giving Black more time to play ...[Qd7] or ...[Nge7] is not to be advised.} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. b3 {Going for the classic queenside fianchetto.} Bd6 7. Bb2 Nf6 8. d3 {[%cal Gb1d2] Preparing [Nbd2]. As with many other variations, we'd prefer to avoid castling kingside too soon since in some variations we can throw our kingside pawns forward and castle queenside.} O-O 9. Nbd2 Qe7 ({This is just a slightly weaker version of} 9... Re8 {. (With the queen supporting ...[e6]-[e5], it does not tactically work yet since ...[Qxe5] won't be a good idea. Therefore, we can continue with a less confrontational plan than versus ...[Re8].)}) 10. O-O Nd7 11. Qe1 $1 {[%cal Ge1g3,Yf3e5] I must admit a special fondness for this queen sortie, as it reminds me of one of my favorite openings the Leningrad Dutch ...[Qd8]-[e8] for Black. The queen sidesteps the annoying pin creating the option of [Nf3]-[e5] and prepares to deploy to the kingside on [g3] or [h4].} e5 $6 {This is by far the most common try, but it runs into a prepared idea of White's.} 12. Qg3 {[%csl Re5,Rg4][%cal Gg3e5,Gg3g4] Hitting [e5] and [g4]. Black has to cash out and chop on [f3].} Bxf3 13. Nxf3 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gb2g7,Gg3g7] There is annoying pressure on the [e5]-pawn − any movement of it will be met by [Qxg7] mate!} Rae8 {Here the computer recommends going to the 2-rook endgame with massive trades on [e5], claiming it to be better for White. I prefer a more tense and practically dangerous move, however.} 14. e4 $14 {Stockfish insists White is only very slightly better but gosh, how uncomfortable this looks! White has nice pressure on the long diagonal and can play for several ideas such as [Rae1] and [exd5], or [Nh4]-[f5].} (14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Bxe5 Qxe5 17. Qxe5 Rxe5 18. Rae1 {⩲ and apparently, White is significantly better in this endgame. White will play [Rf1]-[f4]-[a4] to target the [a7]-pawn. Meanwhile, our own weakness on [e3] can be easily consolidated with [Kg1]-[f2]-[e2]-[d2]. While it does seem to give some chances, I know how players hate the idea of grinding out a rook endgame when they could be basking in Bird mayhem and for that reason, I recommended 14.e4 instead.}) *

