Black can just keep threatening the trade if [Bc3], Black can play ...[Bb4], for instance.} 11. Qc1 Bxb2 12. Qxb2 $14 {[%csl Gc6,Rd4,Gd5,Re5,Ge6][%cal Yg4f3] Black might have traded off a good piece, but that doesn't change the fact that in setting up the pawns on light squares, the dark-squared bishop was vital to fighting for the central dark squares.} Nd7 $6 13. Qc3 {If Black doesn't immediately trade the light-squared bishop on [f3], White will play [Ne5], when the bishop will be jammed in on the kingside by [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4].} c5 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. fxe5 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gg2g4] In due time, [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4] will push the bishop to the irrelevant [g6]-square where it will only look at the [d3]-concrete. White has many fresh ideas, one of which is to simply install the queen on [a5] where it will eye weak pawns on [c5], [c7], and [a7].} *

