t castled kingside giving us more freedom to immediately throw the h-pawn forward to round up the bishop. The [c6]-pawn is also hanging, making Black have too many issues to solve in too short a period.} Nd7 {[%cal Gd8h4] Introducing ideas of ...[Qh4]+ and ...[f7]-[f6].} 13. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] The h-pawn barrels down the board all the same.} f6 {We can't trap the bishop, but we can ruin Black's structure at least.} 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. h5 $18 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Gh5g6,Yg6g5,Yf4g5,Yb2g7,Gf3h3,Gd1f3,Rd6g3] We will move our queen to [e2] or [f3], castle queenside, and deliver a fierce mate. Black has no way to avoid massive openings on the kingside. Black will either allow [hxg6] or push ...[g6]-[g5], when we can move our queen to [f3] to cover against ...[Bd6]-[g3] tricks and then trade on [g5] and maybe even push [h5]-[h6] to dislodge the [g7]-pawn.} *

