1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... e6 {The second most common move, being played 20% of the time. We should take the opportunity to chop on [c6] while it still doubles the pawns. Giving Black more time to play ...[Qd7] or ...[Nge7] is not to be advised.} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. b3 {Going for the classic queenside fianchetto.} Bc5 {The bishop looks strange here. First, it stands in the way of the two c-pawns, making Black's structure even less flexible. And second, it points at solid concrete on [e3]. Regardless, the setup with a bishop on [c5] is opted for more than 10% of games and should be addressed.} 7. Bb2 f6 {[%csl Re6] This weakens [e6] so we should first try to nab the light-squared bishop to make the pawn even more vulnerable.} 8. h3 Bh5 (8... Bf5 9. g4 Bg6 {transposes, as 9...Be4 10.Nc3 is no improvement when Black has to worry about [Nxe4] as well.}) 9. g4 {We have not castled kingside yet so this expansion works perfectly. Our king can go to the queenside, when a kingside pawn storm will be poised to overrun Black's camp.} Bg6 10. Nc3 Ne7 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gg8e7] A natural consequence of the pawn being placed on [f6] is that the knight has to settle for this second-best square.} 11. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh3h4,Gh4h5] White will castle queenside and throw the h-pawn up the board. White's position plays itself to quote a famous Chessable author and young grandmaster.} (11. Qe2 Bxc2 $2 {fails to either} 12. d4 {or 12.d3 .}) *

