on. Black had been hoping to trade the bishops and actively place the knight on [f6], but now they must readjust and settle for the mediocre [e7]-square.} Ne7 9. O-O O-O 10. h3 Bh5 11. g4 {Nudging the bishop back as expected.} Bg6 12. d4 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5,Re7,Rf6,Yg6][%cal Gf3e5,Gc3a4,Ga4c5] The bishop on [g6] is decent, but that's where the positives of Black's position end. The bishop on [f6] points into concrete and the knight on [e7] is kept out of the nice [f5]-square; [g4]-[g5] is an immediate threat. Meanwhile, our knights can look to plant themselves on the weak squares on [e5] or [c5].} Nc8 {[%cal Gc8d6,Gd6e4] The knight embarks on a slow journey to [e4] via [d6].} 13. Ne5 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ge5c6] Attacking [c6] and encouraging Black to go trade on [e5]. We want to get this trade immediately to stop ...[Nd6]-[e4].} Bxe5 14. dxe5 {[%csl Yc5,Rd6][%cal Ge5d6,Yb2a3,Ya3c5,Yc3e2,Ye2g3,Yf4f5] No more ...[Nd6]-[e4]! We have several nice ideas such as [Bb2]-[a3] to slice through the weak dark squares and potentially post the bishop on the [c5]-outpost or [Nc3]-[e2]-[g3] to play for aggressive kingside operations with [f4]-[f5].} *

