on. Black had been hoping to trade the bishops and actively place the knight on [f6], but now they must readjust and settle for the mediocre [e7]-square.} Ne7 9. O-O O-O 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {We see a common-looking position following the trade on [f3] with the unique nuance of a bishop being on [f6] and a knight on [e7]. Black's c-pawns suffer due to a lack of flexibility and potential vulnerability.} Nf5 12. Na4 {Simple and strong. Our [b2]-bishop wasn't impressing anyone anyway.} Bxb2 13. Nxb2 $14 {[%cal Gb2a4] We will play [Na4] to target the [c5]-square and then will continue with [d2]-[d3] to control the [e4]-square. Long term, we can think about playing [e3]-[e4] to evict the [f5]-knight.} *

