1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... e6 {The second most common move, being played 20% of the time. We should take the opportunity to chop on [c6] while it still doubles the pawns. Giving Black more time to play ...[Qd7] or ...[Nge7] is not to be advised.} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. b3 {Going for the classic queenside fianchetto.} Be7 {This setup with the bishop on [e7] and the knight on [f6] is the most popular, being opted for 30+% of the time.} 7. Bb2 Nf6 (7... Bh4+ {is just an inoffensive check. After} 8. g3 Bf6 9. Nc3 a5 10. a4 {, we can harass the bishop with [h3] and enjoy the better position.}) 8. O-O O-O 9. d3 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gb1d2] Preparing [Nbd2].} Bc5 {If the bishop wanted to come to [c5], why did it stop on [e7]?} 10. Qe1 {[%cal Gf3e5] Defending the pawn and dodging the pin along the [d1]-[h5] diagonal. The imminent [Nf3]-[e5] marks the beginning of problems for the black bishop.} Bxf3 11. Rxf3 Qe7 12. Rg3 $14 {[%cal Gg3g7,Gb2g7] We have pleasant pressure on the kingside. We will look to transfer our knight one of three routes: via [c3] to [a4], via [c3] and [e2] to [d4], or most probably, via [d2] and [f3] to [e5]. If Black harasses our rook with ...[Nh5], we can retort with [Rg5]. Black's position is less comfortable and their play is much less obvious. Black still has ugly c-pawns by the way, which, depending on how the game continues, may become relevant.} *

