1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... e6 {The second most common move, being played 20% of the time. We should take the opportunity to chop on [c6] while it still doubles the pawns. Giving Black more time to play ...[Qd7] or ...[Nge7] is not to be advised.} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. b3 {Going for the classic queenside fianchetto.} Be7 {This setup with the bishop on [e7] and the knight on [f6] is the most popular, being opted for 30+% of the time.} 7. Bb2 Nf6 (7... Bh4+ {is just an inoffensive check. After} 8. g3 Bf6 9. Nc3 a5 10. a4 {, we can harass the bishop with [h3] and enjoy the better position.}) 8. O-O O-O 9. d3 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gb1d2] Preparing [Nbd2].} c5 {This pawn move is irreversible and the pawn can never be moved back to [c6]. Despite the slight change in the position, it has serious consequences for the future of the game. Black blocks the bishop, making it worse but at the same time introduces the potential for a challenge to White's healthy structure with ...[c5]-[c4]. It is due to this structural idea that we will look to recapture on [f3] with the queen rather than the knight (if we have placed it on [d2]) so that our knight can keep guard over the [c4]-square via [d2].} 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nd7 12. e4 $1 c6 13. Nd2 $16 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Ge4e5,Ga1e1,Yd5d4,Yd2c4] We have healthy pressure on Black's center. If Black's d-pawn budges, the [d2]-knight will swarm the [c4]-square. Meanwhile, we can improve with [Rae1] and consider ideas such as [e4]-[e5] to lock out Black's minor pieces. We might consider [c2]-[c4] to crunch even further on the center, but this would take away the potential for our knight to install itself on that square going forward so we should be hesitant to commit to it. White has a much more fun position and also an objectively much better one.} *

