1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... f6 {This move is only played 1% of the time, but it is an interesting idea meant to take the sting out of any [Nf3]-[e5] jumps. Unfortunately, it has 2 significant defects: it weakens [e6] and impedes the [g8]-knight from its best square of [f6].} 5. c4 $1 {[%csl Yb5,Yc6,Re6][%cal Gb5c4,Gc4e6,Rg8f6,Rf6d5,Yd1a4] A perfect move! Both the weakness of [e6] when a bishop recaptures on [c4] and the fact that a knight can't come to [f6] to defend [d5] make this move significantly stronger. As with [c4] in other positions, the potential of a queenside battery with [Qa4] to pressure the [c6]-knight begins to take form.} e5 {For some reason, this is played a lot. It seems unrealistic to think Black can continue playing with such an aggressive hand in the center in spite of not being better developed.} 6. fxe5 dxc4 7. h3 $1 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Qd7 {We do not want to take on [f6] here, as it would speed up Black's development.} 9. O-O {We have the bishop pair and can cash it out on [c6] to ruin Black's structure whenever we want.} O-O-O 10. b3 {We are happy to recapture [axb3] and open our rook on the black king's castle.} cxb3 11. axb3 $36 {[%cal Ga1a7,Gb5d7] Big threats!} *

