ccordingly.} 6. O-O Qd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] The only way to objectively make sense of the position. Black wants to castle queenside.} 7. cxd5 exd5 ({After} 7... Qxd5 8. Nc3 $1 {±, we will play [d2]-[d4] with a beautiful center.}) 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 O-O-O 10. a3 $132 {[%cal Gb1c3] The computer calls this better for White but obviously, it doesn't conform to a type of position we would define with a slight advantage. Both kings have castled on opposite sides but they are relatively safe. Therefore, the middlegame should be defined by both trying to balance ideas of a pawn storm against the enemy king with their own development. For White, this means throwing the b-pawn forward and rerouting the knight either via [c3]-[a4]-[c5] or [c3]-[e2]-[d4] to put pressure on Black's position.} *

