1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... f6 {This move is only played 1% of the time, but it is an interesting idea meant to take the sting out of any [Nf3]-[e5] jumps. Unfortunately, it has 2 significant defects: it weakens [e6] and impedes the [g8]-knight from its best square of [f6].} 5. c4 $1 {[%csl Yb5,Yc6,Re6][%cal Gb5c4,Gc4e6,Rg8f6,Rf6d5,Yd1a4] A perfect move! Both the weakness of [e6] when a bishop recaptures on [c4] and the fact that a knight can't come to [f6] to defend [d5] make this move significantly stronger. As with [c4] in other positions, the potential of a queenside battery with [Qa4] to pressure the [c6]-knight begins to take form.} a6 6. Bxc6+ {We destroy the queenside structure as planned.} bxc6 {Here Black has the usual ugly structure reminiscent of so many variations in this chapter, except this time paired with a really awkward pawn on [f6], which jointly weakens the [e6]-square and the development of the [g8]-knight.} 7. h3 {Asking the bishop the existential question − to take or not to take?} Bxf3 8. Qxf3 e6 9. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Crunching on [d5]. We will slowly move to play [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4], when the [d5]-pawn will feel the burn.} Nh6 10. O-O {It's better to do this before [d2]-[d3] so as to not give Black the option to pin us on [b4].} Be7 11. d3 O-O 12. e4 {[%cal Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5,Gf3d5] Now [d5] threatens to be taken, as 4 white pieces and pawns have piled up on it.} dxe4 13. dxe4 e5 14. f5 $14 {Digging in. White has a great advantage in space thanks to the [f5]-pawn. While White can't target the doubled c-pawns, White has a simple plan of using the open d-file to launch an invasion with the rooks. [c5] is a weak square that could be used as an outpost for the knight or bishop if we can usurp control of it away from the [e7]-bishop.} *

