{⇆ . Compared to other endgames analyzed in the 4...Qd6 variations, this is obviously an improvement for Black with the rook well developed on [b8].}) 5... O-O-O $6 {This is never good here. The problem is that the pin from the [b5]-bishop is very annoying, but if Black tries to resolve it with ...[a7]-[a6], they dig themselves into an even bigger hole, as White can play [b2]-[b4]-[b5] to tear open the black king's castle.} 6. O-O e6 7. Nbd2 $1 {Keeping the option of [c2]-[c4] open and also making [Nxf3] a possible response to the black bishop trading on [f3].} Nf6 8. h3 Bh5 $2 9. g4 {[%cal Gf3e5] And the knight goes to [e5] all the same.} Bg6 10. Ne5 Qd6 {White has a nice idea to get a winning advantage here.} 11. Bxc6 $1 {Wrecking the structure.} bxc6 12. Qe2 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Ge2a6] The queen eyes the weak [a6]-square.} Kb7 13. e4 $3 {[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3b3] A beautiful move suggested by the heartless silicon beast. The 3rd rank is cleared for [Rf3]-[b3] to decide.} Nxe4 14. Rf3 Nxd2 15. Bxd2 $18 {[%cal Gf3b3,Gb3a3,Ge2a6] White's threats of [Rb3]/[a3] and [Qa6] are decisive.} *

