{⇆ . Compared to other endgames analyzed in the 4...Qd6 variations, this is obviously an improvement for Black with the rook well developed on [b8].}) 5... a6 {This is by far the most popular at a frequency of 47%. Black itches to resolve the pin immediately; the queen would love to recapture on [c6].} 6. Be2 $1 {Retreating in grand style. Our bishop cushions the pressure against the [f3]-knight and in buffering the pin against our queen, introduces the idea of [Ne5].} Nf6 7. O-O Bxf3 8. Bxf3 {We could have also taken with the rook. But the bishop capture looks so much more natural.} e6 9. Bd2 {It is best to prepare [c2]-[c4] with this.} (9. c4 $6 {let's the dog off the leash. 9…} dxc4 10. Qc2 b5 {, Black will fight tooth and nail to hold on to the pawn.} 11. b3 Rd8 {with a sneaky trick in mind.} 12. bxc4 Nxd4 $1 {We should collect the knight and hope for some compensation for the exchange we are about to lose on [a1].} 13. exd4 Qxd4+ 14. Kh1 Qxa1 {and now one point of our move 9.Bd2 to prepare [c4] is revealed. With the bishop on [d2] here, we would have [Bc3] trapping the queen.}) 9... Be7 10. c4 dxc4 11. Qc2 b5 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5,Gc4] Black attempts to build a beautiful pawn phalanx from [a6]-[c4]. We must chip away at it immediately.} 12. b3 $14 {[%cal Gb3c4] Next, [bxc4] will be played with an advantage to White.} cxb3 $4 {It's important to know how to respond to this.} 13. Qxc6 $18 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Gb3b2,Gc6a8] We pick up the piece. Black has no time for ...[b3]-[b2], as the rook on [a8] is hanging.} *

