1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... Qd7 $1 {As mentioned before, this is Black's best move though it is only played a meager 9% of the time.} 5. d4 $1 {This is one of the several equal options for White. As usual, I've chosen this based on its practical poison. Black is immediately thrown into a structure reminiscent of a reversed Dutch in which White has played 2.Nc3 and 3.Bg5. Black has several ways to hold the balance but most players as evidenced by the database immediately lose their way.} (5. c4 $6 {Compared to the ...[Qd6] line, ...[Qd7] protects the knight on [c6] without impeding the [f8]-bishop. For this reason, [c4] is less good than before since Black can play ...[e6], when Black has much more natural development.} e6 6. O-O a6 {and White will have to exchange on [c6] under unfavorable circumstances.} 7. Qa4 Bxf3 8. Rxf3 Rb8 {, sidestepping the pin on [a6]. White must cash out:} 9. Bxc6 Qxc6 10. Qxc6+ bxc6 {⇆ . Compared to other endgames analyzed in the 4...Qd6 variations, this is obviously an improvement for Black with the rook well developed on [b8].}) 5... a6 {This is by far the most popular at a frequency of 47%. Black itches to resolve the pin immediately; the queen would love to recapture on [c6].} 6. Be2 $1 {Retreating in grand style. Our bishop cushions the pressure against the [f3]-knight and in buffering the pin against our queen, introduces the idea of [Ne5].} Nf6 7. O-O e6 8. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2f3] Reinforcing the knight on [f3] once more. We didn't want to place the knight on [c3] because it would obstruct the thematic break [c2]-[c4].} Bd6 $2 {This looks healthy, but the placement of the bishop here makes it very hard for Black to contest a knight on [e5]...} 9. Ne5 $1 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Bxe5 $2 {This is strategically self-destructive. Black will really miss the dark-squared bishop and after we recapture on [e5], the knight on [f6] will also be evicted.} (10... Nxe5 11. fxe5 {+- and Black says goodbye to one of the minor pieces.}) 11. fxe5 {[%csl Rf6]} Ng8 12. Qh5 $18 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Yg7g6,Yh5h4,Re8c8] Black is completely stuck. Castling queenside surrenders the [f7]-pawn, while ...[g7]-[g6] surrenders all the dark squares. White is strategically winning.} *

