{⇆ . Compared to other endgames analyzed in the 4...Qd6 variations, this is obviously an improvement for Black with the rook well developed on [b8].}) 5... a6 {This is by far the most popular at a frequency of 47%. Black itches to resolve the pin immediately; the queen would love to recapture on [c6].} 6. Be2 $1 {Retreating in grand style. Our bishop cushions the pressure against the [f3]-knight and in buffering the pin against our queen, introduces the idea of [Ne5].} Nf6 7. O-O e6 8. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2f3] Reinforcing the knight on [f3] once more. We didn't want to place the knight on [c3] because it would obstruct the thematic break [c2]-[c4].} Be7 9. Ne5 $1 {Into the center we go!} Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Nxe5 $2 {We should always be happy to see this, as it means we can move our pawn from [f4] to [e5].} (10... Qc8 {is the best move, but I find it hard to believe most players would be mature enough to play such a backward-looking move when they could just snatch on [e5].} 11. b3 {⩲ , when we will follow with [Bb2] and [c2]-[c4] with a healthy position. White is slightly better and can look for an opportune [c4xd5] or [e3]-[e4] depending on how things transpire.}) 11. fxe5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gf1f7] This unleashes our rook on [f1] and boots the black knight from [f6].} Ng8 (11... Ne4 $2 {just fails tactically.} 12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qg4 {± is a fork to remember. We scoop up a free pawn.}) 12. Qg4 {[%csl Rg7]} g6 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7,Rh6] Black defends the threat but in the process makes the dark squares weaker.} 13. e4 {[%cal Gf1f7,Re8c8] Another point of why [f4xe5] was so favorable was that now our bishop can be useful if we simply move our e-pawn. Black is in quite the pickle here. The f-file is open so castling queenside would run into a painful [Rxf7]. But what else is there to do?} dxe4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd7d4] Here we have to defend [d4] while recapturing.} 14. Qxe4 Nh6 15. Nb3 {[%csl Gd4,Rh6][%cal Gb3d4,Gb3c5,Rc7c5,Gc1h6] The knight sits comfortably here from where it secures [d4] and prevents ...[c7]-[c5] breaks.} Nf5 16. g4 {Glancing over the many knight moves for Black in the notation, we read a tragedy of a steed just trying to find a purpose.} Ng7 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh7h5,Rh5g4,Gg7f5] The knight winds up fianchettoed and completely stifled by the [g4]-pawn. There seems to still be some hope though, if only Black could play ...[h7]-[h5] and then trade on [g4], the knight could find meaning on [f5] again.} 17. Bh6 $18 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf1f4,Ga1f1,Ge4f3] The ...[h7]-[h5] move is prevented and once more the knight's dreams are dashed. Black is lost of course, as there are too many positional issues. White should double and possibly triple on the f-file, when the [f7]-weakness should break.} *

