1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... Qd6 {This natural queen defense of the knight is played 15% of the time. Here, every move under the sun seems to have been played with castling being White's preferred option.} (4... Qd6 {The computer insists that} 5. d4 {is best and gives a slight advantage at around 0.11. I found another move that, while objectively level, leads to chaotic situations, which will leave Black hard-pressed to find the best moves.}) 5. c4 $5 {This has only been played 89 times in the 14000 games, giving it a frequency of 0.6%. The center is immediately brought into tension and a lane has opened for our queen to glide to the brilliant [a4]-square. What I like most about this move is that it immediately throws a curveball at the Black team − they have a choice between several weird structures all of which they've quite likely never studied. The good news is that most players immediately slip on the [c4]-banana peel and can't make it to move 10 with equality.} (5. c4 {Two moves keep the game level:} a6 {and 5...d4 .}) (5. h3 $6 {might seem like an interesting way to transpose to positions reached in the chapter on 2...Nf6 3.e3 Bg4 . After 5...Bxf3 6.Qxf3 , Black doesn't have to switch back to those positions with ...[Nf6]. Instead, Black can play more forcefully with 6...a6 ( 6...O-O-O!? could also be interesting. ) 7.Bxc6+ Qxc6 , when White has to deal with the threat to [c2]. 8.Nc3 e6 and Black's position carries a latent poison associated with routing the knight to [f5]. 9.O-O Nh6 10.d3 Nf5 ∓ , Black will castle queenside and play ...[h7]-[h5]. The knight stands fantastic on [f5]. If it is harassed by [e3]-[e4], it will glide into [d4], while if it is attacked by [g2]-[g4], it will simply retreat, when White has weakened the kingside too much.}) 5... a6 $1 {To Black's credit, this accurate response is the second most popular move, being tried 26% of the time.} 6. Qa4 {[%cal Gf3e5,Ra6b5,Ga4a8] The pin on the [f3]-knight is immediately sidestepped and the queen and bishop build a fearsome battery against [c6]; [Nf3]-[e5] looms. Of course, the [b5]-bishop cannot be taken on pain of the [a8]-rook hanging.} dxc4 7. Ne5 {Hitting the [g4]-bishop and [c6]-knight in one lance.} Bd7 (7... Nf6 $2 {looks natural but doesn't prevent the devastation to Black's queenside.} 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. O-O {± and White will even the material soon enough with [Nxc4]. Black's structure is dreadful with the two c-pawns serving as prime targets for an eventual [Ra1]-[c1].}) 8. Nc3 $1 {Steady hands − Black is again in a bit of a pickle.} Nxe5 9. fxe5 Qe6 {Black has apparently dodged the danger and eyes the [e5]-pawn like a vulture waiting for its next meal.} (9... Bxb5 10. Nxb5 Qc6 11. Nxc7+ $1 {We'll trade queens before scooping up the mango on [a8]. That's the game.}) 10. Bxc4 $1 {[%csl Ra4,Re6][%cal Gc4e6,Gd7a4] Queen for queen!} Bxa4 11. Bxe6 Bc6 $1 (11... fxe6 $4 12. Nxa4 {+- is strategically winning for White. Black's minor pieces will never see the light of day, as White will play [d4], erecting a wonderful buffer for them to ever activate. The bishop won't find relevance against the concrete on [e5] and if Black tries to activate the knight via [h6] to [f5], we can simply stabilize a kingside pawn tree with [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4] to suffocate this.}) 12. Bd5 Bxd5 13. Nxd5 O-O-O 14. Nf4 e6 15. Ke2 $14 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gd2d4,Gh1f1] We will build a beautiful center with [d2]-[d4] and can play for pressure on the weak [f7]-pawn − it is on an open file after all!} *

