banana peel and can't make it to move 10 with equality.} (5. c4 {Two moves keep the game level:} a6 {and 5...d4 .}) (5. h3 $6 {might seem like an interesting way to transpose to positions reached in the chapter on 2...Nf6 3.e3 Bg4 . After 5...Bxf3 6.Qxf3 , Black doesn't have to switch back to those positions with ...[Nf6]. Instead, Black can play more forcefully with 6...a6 ( 6...O-O-O!? could also be interesting. ) 7.Bxc6+ Qxc6 , when White has to deal with the threat to [c2]. 8.Nc3 e6 and Black's position carries a latent poison associated with routing the knight to [f5]. 9.O-O Nh6 10.d3 Nf5 ∓ , Black will castle queenside and play ...[h7]-[h5]. The knight stands fantastic on [f5]. If it is harassed by [e3]-[e4], it will glide into [d4], while if it is attacked by [g2]-[g4], it will simply retreat, when White has weakened the kingside too much.}) 5... a6 $1 {To Black's credit, this accurate response is the second most popular move, being tried 26% of the time.} 6. Qa4 {[%cal Gf3e5,Ra6b5,Ga4a8] The pin on the [f3]-knight is immediately sidestepped and the queen and bishop build a fearsome battery against [c6]; [Nf3]-[e5] looms. Of course, the [b5]-bishop cannot be taken on pain of the [a8]-rook hanging.} Bxf3 7. gxf3 d4 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Rc1c6] Not an obvious move by any stretch, but it makes enormous sense. Our pressure on [c6] is nearing a breaking point. If Black allows [c4] to be traded for [d5], the doubled pawns on the c-file will represent an extremely vulnerable constellation.} 8. Bxc6+ Qxc6 9. Qxc6+ bxc6 10. b3 c5 11. Na3 O-O-O 12. Nc2 dxe3 $2 {This is a serious strategic mistake by allowing the [d4]-square to be cleared.} 13. dxe3 $14 {[%cal Ge1e2,Gc1b2] White will play [Ke2] and [Bb2], fighting for the d-file with [Ra1]-[d1]. The center could prove mobile with [e3]-[e4] at some point. Black's c-pawns are hidden for now, but they are isolated and therefore always potentially vulnerable.} *

