1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... Qd6 {This natural queen defense of the knight is played 15% of the time. Here, every move under the sun seems to have been played with castling being White's preferred option.} (4... Qd6 {The computer insists that} 5. d4 {is best and gives a slight advantage at around 0.11. I found another move that, while objectively level, leads to chaotic situations, which will leave Black hard-pressed to find the best moves.}) 5. c4 $5 {This has only been played 89 times in the 14000 games, giving it a frequency of 0.6%. The center is immediately brought into tension and a lane has opened for our queen to glide to the brilliant [a4]-square. What I like most about this move is that it immediately throws a curveball at the Black team − they have a choice between several weird structures all of which they've quite likely never studied. The good news is that most players immediately slip on the [c4]-banana peel and can't make it to move 10 with equality.} (5. c4 {Two moves keep the game level:} a6 {and 5...d4 .}) (5. h3 $6 {might seem like an interesting way to transpose to positions reached in the chapter on 2...Nf6 3.e3 Bg4 . After 5...Bxf3 6.Qxf3 , Black doesn't have to switch back to those positions with ...[Nf6]. Instead, Black can play more forcefully with 6...a6 ( 6...O-O-O!? could also be interesting. ) 7.Bxc6+ Qxc6 , when White has to deal with the threat to [c2]. 8.Nc3 e6 and Black's position carries a latent poison associated with routing the knight to [f5]. 9.O-O Nh6 10.d3 Nf5 ∓ , Black will castle queenside and play ...[h7]-[h5]. The knight stands fantastic on [f5]. If it is harassed by [e3]-[e4], it will glide into [d4], while if it is attacked by [g2]-[g4], it will simply retreat, when White has weakened the kingside too much.}) 5... e6 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rf8c5] Black passively defends [d5]. Notice that while this move normally is associated with the development of the king's bishop, here the black queen on [d6] works against such an activation. We should seize the moment to take the rest of the center.} 6. d4 {[%cal Gc4c5] White threatens [c4]-[c5], when our phalanx will achieve suffocating proportions. While our advantage is small against best play, I could see this position going off the rails for Black in only a few moves.} Be7 7. c5 $1 {More space, please!} Qd7 8. O-O a6 (8... Nf6 9. Nbd2 $1 {⩲ , we wanted to play [Qa4], but it makes sense to first reinforce the [f3]-knight in this manner. Now we can play [Qa4] since if Black trades on [f3] to avoid [Nf3]-[e5], we will simply recapture with the twin on [d2].}) 9. Ba4 Nf6 10. Qb3 $16 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb3b7,Gf3e5] With an enormous pair of threats in [Qxb7] and [Nf3]-[e5]. Somehow Black is not already losing − we'll leave them to figure out how!} *

