1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nc6 {With this move, Black forgoes playing ...[c7]-[c5] in the short term for speedy development. Ideally, Black would like to use the knight to assist in a quick ...[e7]-[e5] push. While ...[Nf6] setups combined with ...[c5] are more common overall, ...[Nc6] is the most popular second move according to the database, with 27% of Black players opting for it right here from the get-go.} 3. e3 {As usual, we continue with the classic king-pawn push. Our bishop will likely come to [b5] to place the enemy knight under an uncomfortable pin.} Bg4 ({The most popular move.} 3... Nf6 4. Bb5 {just transposes to the chapter covering 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 .}) 4. Bb5 ({This move is less employed than} 4. Be2 {, but I consider it to carry a lot more practical poison. (We immediately threaten [Bxc6] with an ugly structure. The great news is that among the most popular moves, the top 5 don't promise Black full equality. We will look at those 5 as well as the 6th ...[Qd7], Black's best chance and 7th.)}) 4... Qd6 {This natural queen defense of the knight is played 15% of the time. Here, every move under the sun seems to have been played with castling being White's preferred option.} (4... Qd6 {The computer insists that} 5. d4 {is best and gives a slight advantage at around 0.11. I found another move that, while objectively level, leads to chaotic situations, which will leave Black hard-pressed to find the best moves.}) 5. c4 $5 {This has only been played 89 times in the 14000 games, giving it a frequency of 0.6%. The center is immediately brought into tension and a lane has opened for our queen to glide to the brilliant [a4]-square. What I like most about this move is that it immediately throws a curveball at the Black team − they have a choice between several weird structures all of which they've quite likely never studied. The good news is that most players immediately slip on the [c4]-banana peel and can't make it to move 10 with equality.} (5. c4 {Two moves keep the game level:} a6 {and 5...d4 .}) (5. h3 $6 {might seem like an interesting way to transpose to positions reached in the chapter on 2...Nf6 3.e3 Bg4 . After 5...Bxf3 6.Qxf3 , Black doesn't have to switch back to those positions with ...[Nf6]. Instead, Black can play more forcefully with 6...a6 ( 6...O-O-O!? could also be interesting. ) 7.Bxc6+ Qxc6 , when White has to deal with the threat to [c2]. 8.Nc3 e6 and Black's position carries a latent poison associated with routing the knight to [f5]. 9.O-O Nh6 10.d3 Nf5 ∓ , Black will castle queenside and play ...[h7]-[h5]. The knight stands fantastic on [f5]. If it is harassed by [e3]-[e4], it will glide into [d4], while if it is attacked by [g2]-[g4], it will simply retreat, when White has weakened the kingside too much.}) 5... dxc4 {This is the most popular move played against our central lunge, having been chosen 31% of the time.} 6. Na3 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ga3c4] We plan to recapture with [Na3xc4] with tempo against the queen on [d6]. This has only been played once thus far, yet it poses enormous practical problems for Black. Black only has one precise way to fight for equality and it involves getting the [g8]-knight to [e7] before the bishop on [f8] comes out − not obvious by any means!} (6. Bxc4 $6 {is the most played, but it's just a mistake. It allows Black speedy development and a quick ...[e7]-[e5] as evidenced by the following sample variation.} O-O-O 7. O-O e5 $1 8. fxe5 $2 {This opens the game up even more for Black.} Nxe5 {, White is left with two very ugly hanging pawns on [d2] and [e3]. They are both on open files for the opponent so they will always be targets for the remainder of the game.}) 6... O-O-O 7. Qa4 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5c6,Ga3c4] White will take on [c4] and then split open the queenside pawns with [Bxc6] and a queen trade if Black recaptures with the queen.} Qd5 8. Bxc6 Qxc6 9. Qxc6 bxc6 10. Ne5 $16 {[%csl Rc4,Rc6,Rf7,Rg4] A quadruple fork! We will recollect our pawn investment on [c4] shortly and can pressure [c6] with [Nc4]-[a5] and an eventual [Rc1]. The computer insists White's advantage is not decisive yet, but my intuition tells me otherwise. :} *

