1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} a6 {Despite this move making little intuitive sense, it remains the third most popular option, with 11% of Black players opting for it in the relevant database.} 5. Bxc6+ {This was always the plan.} bxc6 6. b3 $1 {[%cal Gc1b2,Yb2a3,Yg7g6] Castling kingside is more popular than this, but I believe it's optimal to first open options for our bishop. Of course, we are preparing an effective fianchetto of the queen's bishop on [b2]. The bishop may also come out to [a3] if Black delays moving the [e6]-pawn.} Bf5 (6... e6 {leads to positions discussed after 4...e6 and 7...a6 .}) 7. Ba3 {[%cal Ye7e6,Ya3f8] This move looks a bit peculiar but has a strong prophylactic undertone. If Black ever plays ...[e6], we will happily trade on [f8], removing Black's right to castle.} e6 8. Bxf8 {We capture as planned.} Rxf8 (8... Kxf8 {doesn't change anything. We can finish our development with} 9. d3 {followed by [Nbd2], [O-O], etc. Black will need a lot of time to castle by hand and is just much worse.}) 9. d3 Qd6 10. O-O {[%cal Gd1e2,Gb1d2,Ge3e4] White will play for [Qd1]-[e2], [Nb1]-[d2] and [e3]-[e4]. Frankly, I am surprised White isn't already winning here, but the computer insists that with precise play, it is still salvageable for Black.} *

