1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} a6 {Despite this move making little intuitive sense, it remains the third most popular option, with 11% of Black players opting for it in the relevant database.} 5. Bxc6+ {This was always the plan.} bxc6 6. b3 $1 {[%cal Gc1b2,Yb2a3,Yg7g6] Castling kingside is more popular than this, but I believe it's optimal to first open options for our bishop. Of course, we are preparing an effective fianchetto of the queen's bishop on [b2]. The bishop may also come out to [a3] if Black delays moving the [e6]-pawn.} Bf5 (6... e6 {leads to positions discussed after 4...e6 and 7...a6 .}) 7. Ba3 {[%cal Ye7e6,Ya3f8] This move looks a bit peculiar but has a strong prophylactic undertone. If Black ever plays ...[e6], we will happily trade on [f8], removing Black's right to castle.} g6 {Black opts to fianchetto the bishop on [g7], but now White has other options.} 8. Ne5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gg2g4] The pawn on [c6] will likely drop soon and beyond that, [g2]-[g4] also looms.} Bg7 {Here we should not take the pawn just yet. It is not going anywhere.} 9. Nc3 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4][%cal Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Gc3e2,Ge2d4] With ideas of [Nc3]-[a4]-[c5] and [Nc3]-[e2]-[d4].} (9. Nxc6 $2 Qd7 10. Ne5 (10. Nxe7 $4 {This extends our position past the point of return.} Bg4 {, dodging [Nxf5] with a nudge to our queen.} 11. Qc1 c5 $1 {and our knight finds itself in a bit of a pickle.} 12. Bxc5 Ne4 {-+ , we have several unhappy pieces and one of them is about to drop.}) 10... Qe6 {∞ and Black will play ...[Ng4] with chaotic pressure on [e5]. The situation is unclear.}) 9... Qc8 (9... O-O 10. Nxc6 {is decisive this time. White will take on [e7] with check and then ruin Black's structure with [Nxf5].}) 10. Nxc6 $16 {[%cal Gf5g4] Black will get a bit of practical compensation after ...[Bg4], which pushes our queen to an awkward position on [c1] or [b1]. But all the same, we will have a big advantage.} *

