1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} a6 {Despite this move making little intuitive sense, it remains the third most popular option, with 11% of Black players opting for it in the relevant database.} 5. Bxc6+ {This was always the plan.} bxc6 6. b3 $1 {[%cal Gc1b2,Yb2a3,Yg7g6] Castling kingside is more popular than this, but I believe it's optimal to first open options for our bishop. Of course, we are preparing an effective fianchetto of the queen's bishop on [b2]. The bishop may also come out to [a3] if Black delays moving the [e6]-pawn.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3]} ({The bishop pins our knight on f3.} 6... e6 {leads to positions discussed after 4...e6 and 7...a6 .}) 7. O-O g5 $1 {[%csl Rg5,Gf4][%cal Gf4g5,Rg5f4] This is Black's best chance to equalize in this position, but just come on! What human player would play like this???? In my database of 5000 games, it has never been tried even once. Black seeks to challenge White's central phalanx and open the g-file, all in one go, while also planning to meet [fxg5] with ...[Ne4], when the position has devolved into chaos! White can still count on an advantage with precise moves, however.} 8. h3 $1 ({Objectively best, but the alternative of} 8. Ba3 {would also be a fine try. After} gxf4 9. exf4 Bg7 10. Qe1 {, the [e7]-pawn starts to bear a heavy burden.} Bxf3 11. Rxf3 Ne4 12. c3 {, White will play [d3] to kick the knight out and then occupy the nice outpost on [c5] with the bishop. While the position remains very close to equal, Black has a much harder practical task ahead.}) 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Rg8 10. fxg5 Rxg5 11. Ba3 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3a4,Ga4c5] The threat of [Nc3]-[a4]-[c5] is a simple and effective plan.} *

