1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} a6 {Despite this move making little intuitive sense, it remains the third most popular option, with 11% of Black players opting for it in the relevant database.} 5. Bxc6+ {This was always the plan.} bxc6 6. b3 $1 {[%cal Gc1b2,Yb2a3,Yg7g6] Castling kingside is more popular than this, but I believe it's optimal to first open options for our bishop. Of course, we are preparing an effective fianchetto of the queen's bishop on [b2]. The bishop may also come out to [a3] if Black delays moving the [e6]-pawn.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3]} ({The bishop pins our knight on f3.} 6... e6 {leads to positions discussed after 4...e6 and 7...a6 .}) 7. O-O e6 8. Bb2 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7] Now is a good time to discuss the structure a bit. Black has a weaker structure due to the doubled pawns but has the bishop pair in return. The latter is of course not relevant, as we can trade off Black's [g4]-bishop with [h2]-[h3] whenever we want. There are a few methods available to us for playing on Black's weaknesses. Notice the c-file is not open our pawn on [c2] clogs it so we cannot simply double rooks on the c-file and begin pressuring [c6] that way. Instead, we must be a bit more creative. First, we could consider preparing [c2]-[c4] to open the file, but the drawback to this is that it really weakens our [d3]-square. Moreover, if we play [c2]-[c4] and [cxd5], Black will be able to recapture with the c-pawn, thereby ameliorating some of their weaknesses. One effective method could be to play on the weakened [c5]-square. To do this we would start by moving the knight from [b1]-[c3]-[a4] and then the bishop to [d4]. Another possible way is to slowly prepare the [e3]-[e4] break with moves like [Qd1]-[e2], [d2]-[d3], and [Nb1]-[d2]. Achieving [e4] would be uncomfortable for Black for a few reasons. First, Black can't trade on [e4] without making the c-pawns isolated, thereby making them more vulnerable than prior to this. Second, the threat of [e4]-[e5] would always loom over their head.} Bd6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd6e5] The bishop is just not well placed here. White will play [d2]-[d3], transfer the queen to [g3] via [e1], and eventually play for [e3]-[e4] or [Nf3]-[e5]. When the pawn reaches [e4], Black, with the bishop on [d6], will face a problematic situation confronting the [e4]-[e5] push. [Nf3]-[e5] is also a serious threat, as Black will have no way to challenge White's dominance on the long diagonal after it.} 9. d3 O-O 10. Nbd2 Qe7 11. Qe1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge1g3,Rg4d1,Gf3e5]} Rfe8 12. Ne5 $1 Bxe5 13. fxe5 Nd7 14. Rf4 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Ge1f2,Ga1f1] White will bring the heavy pieces over with moves like [Qf2] and [Rf1] and then begin harassing the black bishop. Black will have to create space for the bishop with moves like ...[h7]-[h6] or ...[h7]-[h5].} Bf5 15. Qf2 Rab8 16. g4 Bg6 17. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Threatening [h4]-[h5]; Black has to do something.} h6 18. h5 Bh7 19. Rf1 {[%csl Rf7]} Rf8 20. Nf3 $18 {[%cal Gf2g3,Gg4g5] White will play [Qg3] and [g5] with a decisive attack.} *

