c4] and [cxd5], Black will be able to recapture with the c-pawn, thereby ameliorating some of their weaknesses. One effective method could be to play on the weakened [c5]-square. To do this we would start by moving the knight from [b1]-[c3]-[a4] and then the bishop to [d4]. Another possible way is to slowly prepare the [e3]-[e4] break with moves like [Qd1]-[e2], [d2]-[d3], and [Nb1]-[d2]. Achieving [e4] would be uncomfortable for Black for a few reasons. First, Black can't trade on [e4] without making the c-pawns isolated, thereby making them more vulnerable than prior to this. Second, the threat of [e4]-[e5] would always loom over their head.} Bd6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd6e5] The bishop is just not well placed here. White will play [d2]-[d3], transfer the queen to [g3] via [e1], and eventually play for [e3]-[e4] or [Nf3]-[e5]. When the pawn reaches [e4], Black, with the bishop on [d6], will face a problematic situation confronting the [e4]-[e5] push. [Nf3]-[e5] is also a serious threat, as Black will have no way to challenge White's dominance on the long diagonal after it.} 9. d3 O-O 10. Nbd2 Qe7 11. Qe1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge1g3,Rg4d1,Gf3e5]} Bxf3 {This is the best move in such situations. If Black didn't execute this immediately, White's knight would glide to [e5] and the bishop would become a permanent target. Notice that while having the bishop outside the pawn chain makes it more active, the pawn on [e6] keeps the bishop from ever escaping the dragon's den.} 12. Nxf3 c5 13. Qg3 {[%cal Gg3g7,Gb2g7] Amping up the pressure. Black needs to tread extremely carefully. One careless move by the knight or queen could spell immediate destruction for the Black player.} Rfe8 14. Ne5 $18 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge3e4,Gf4e5,Ga1e1,Yf1f3,Yf3h3,Yg2g4,Yf3g3] Believe it or not, White is already close to winning here. Black's position is without counterplay and they will have to watch as White slowly builds up with a variety of ideas. White can play [Rae1] and [e3]-[e4], or [Qh3] and [Rf1]-[f3]-[g3] or [g2]-[g4]. White should be careful about when to push [f4]-[f5], as this will undermine the grasp on the [e5]-square and allow Black to trade on [f5], unlocking the e-file for the queen and [e8]-rook to power down. An important note is we will almost always meet Black exchanging with ...[Bxe5] with [fxe5], booting out the [f6]-knight and revealing an open f-file for our rooks to drill down.} (14. Ne5 {A sample line is} Kh8 15. Rae1 h6 16. Rf3 Nh7 ({Such moves look terrible, but there is really nothing else for Black to do.} 16... c4 17. bxc4 {just drops a pawn for no compensation.}) 17. Nc6 Qf8 {, the only square to defend against both threats.} 18. Qh4 f6 19. e4 $1 {An instructive transformation.} dxe4 20. Rxe4 {+- , Black has survived the attack but has only managed to reach a positional disaster! [e6] is weak, the c-pawns will always be isolated and vulnerable, and Black's pieces are all bad.}) *

