1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} a6 {Despite this move making little intuitive sense, it remains the third most popular option, with 11% of Black players opting for it in the relevant database.} 5. Bxc6+ {This was always the plan.} bxc6 6. b3 $1 {[%cal Gc1b2,Yb2a3,Yg7g6] Castling kingside is more popular than this, but I believe it's optimal to first open options for our bishop. Of course, we are preparing an effective fianchetto of the queen's bishop on [b2]. The bishop may also come out to [a3] if Black delays moving the [e6]-pawn.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3]} ({The bishop pins our knight on f3.} 6... e6 {leads to positions discussed after 4...e6 and 7...a6 .}) 7. O-O e6 8. Bb2 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7] Now is a good time to discuss the structure a bit. Black has a weaker structure due to the doubled pawns but has the bishop pair in return. The latter is of course not relevant, as we can trade off Black's [g4]-bishop with [h2]-[h3] whenever we want. There are a few methods available to us for playing on Black's weaknesses. Notice the c-file is not open our pawn on [c2] clogs it so we cannot simply double rooks on the c-file and begin pressuring [c6] that way. Instead, we must be a bit more creative. First, we could consider preparing [c2]-[c4] to open the file, but the drawback to this is that it really weakens our [d3]-square. Moreover, if we play [c2]-[c4] and [cxd5], Black will be able to recapture with the c-pawn, thereby ameliorating some of their weaknesses. One effective method could be to play on the weakened [c5]-square. To do this we would start by moving the knight from [b1]-[c3]-[a4] and then the bishop to [d4]. Another possible way is to slowly prepare the [e3]-[e4] break with moves like [Qd1]-[e2], [d2]-[d3], and [Nb1]-[d2]. Achieving [e4] would be uncomfortable for Black for a few reasons. First, Black can't trade on [e4] without making the c-pawns isolated, thereby making them more vulnerable than prior to this. Second, the threat of [e4]-[e5] would always loom over their head.} Bc5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gc5e3,Rd2d3] Anticipating ideas of [d2]-[d3], when the [e3]-pawn will be tender.} 9. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1g3,Gg3h4,Gf3e5] This is a classic move in the Bird's opening and one that is worth getting accustomed to. The queen is often better here than on [e2] for a few reasons. It can transfer effortlessly to the kingside via the open diagonal [e1]-[h4]. It also evades the pin on the [f3]-knight, introducing the strong threat of [Nf3]-[e5] with a swift initiative to boot. It's no surprise that Black has to take on [f3] here to avoid being close to lost.} O-O 10. Ne5 {[%csl Rc6,Rg4][%cal Ge5g4,Ge5c6]} Bh5 11. d3 {There was no need to take on [c6].} Qe8 12. Qg3 Bg6 13. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gd2f3,Gf3d4,Gf3g5,Gf3h4] White is much better. We can play [Rae1] and then transfer the [d2]-knight to [d4], [h4] or [g5] via [f3].} *

