1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} e6 {This is opted for 8% of the time and so is worth looking at as well.} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} ({I prefer this move over the more popular} 5. Bxc6+ {. We are preparing to place our bishop on [b2]. In this position, it makes sense to wait before executing [Bxc6]. At the moment, the knight isn't going anywhere, and if Black plays ...[Bd7] later, then this combination of 4...e6 with a later ...[Bd7] seems like a worse version of 4...Bd7 .}) 5... Bd6 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O a6 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Ne5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ge5c6]} c5 {Thus far Black has made logical natural moves, but now we have an opportunity to beckon them into the jungle. The position is about to get wild, buckle up!} 10. Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd8,Rf6][%cal Gb2f6] Kicking the queen away from its defense of the knight.} Qe8 11. Bxf6 Qxc6 $4 {Black is already dead lost!} 12. Qh5 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh5g5] Threatening [Qg5] and after ...[g7]-[g6], [Qh6].} Re8 13. Rf3 {[%cal Gf3g3]} Kf8 14. Be5 {At least Black isn't getting mated here, but that's where the good news ends. Black's kingside remains under siege and something will drop shortly.} Kg8 {This back and forth might look silly, but Black is eyeing to trade on [e5], when White's [fxe5] will reveal the [f3]-rook on it.} 15. Rh3 h6 16. Bxg7 $18 {[%cal Gh5h6] And down falls the London Bridge.} *

