1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} e6 {This is opted for 8% of the time and so is worth looking at as well.} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} ({I prefer this move over the more popular} 5. Bxc6+ {. We are preparing to place our bishop on [b2]. In this position, it makes sense to wait before executing [Bxc6]. At the moment, the knight isn't going anywhere, and if Black plays ...[Bd7] later, then this combination of 4...e6 with a later ...[Bd7] seems like a worse version of 4...Bd7 .}) 5... Bd6 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O a6 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Ne5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ge5c6]} c5 {Thus far Black has made logical natural moves, but now we have an opportunity to beckon them into the jungle. The position is about to get wild, buckle up!} 10. Nc6 $1 {[%csl Rd8,Rf6][%cal Gb2f6] Kicking the queen away from its defense of the knight.} Qe8 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Qh5 Kh8 ({The path is indeed narrow!} 12... Qxc6 13. Rf3 {would transpose to 11...Qxc6 .}) 13. Qh4 {[%cal Gh4f6]} Rg8 (13... Qxc6 14. Qxf6+ Kg8 15. Rf3 Re8 {, clearing [f8] for one last ditch escape.} 16. Qh6 {+- , taking no prisoners.}) 14. Qxf6+ Rg7 15. Rf3 (15. Ne5 $2 {is a mistake. Black can force us into an uncomfortable situation after} Be7 16. Qh6 f6 17. Nf3 e5 {and the bishops, the big pawn center, and the pressure down the g-file start to look really good.}) 15... Kg8 ({After} 15... Qxc6 $4 16. Rg3 Bf8 {, it does look like Black is holding on, but the weakness of the 8th rank does tell!} 17. Rxg7 Bxg7 18. Qd8+ {, OOPS! 18…} Bf8 19. Qxf8# {.}) 16. Ne5 {Now compared to [Ne5] on move 15, Black doesn't have such strong immediate counterplay associated with pushing our queen around.} Be7 17. Qh6 f6 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf6e5]} 18. Nd3 Rg6 19. Rg3 $16 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gg3g8] The rooks will trade off and Black hasn't achieved much activity for the pawn.} *

