1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} e6 {This is opted for 8% of the time and so is worth looking at as well.} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} ({I prefer this move over the more popular} 5. Bxc6+ {. We are preparing to place our bishop on [b2]. In this position, it makes sense to wait before executing [Bxc6]. At the moment, the knight isn't going anywhere, and if Black plays ...[Bd7] later, then this combination of 4...e6 with a later ...[Bd7] seems like a worse version of 4...Bd7 .}) 5... Bd6 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O Ne7 {[%cal Rb5c6] The knight retreats to avoid the crafty [Bxc6]. Alas, the knight can no longer easily venture to [b4], which is why our bishop will likely come to [d3] over the next dozen moves. This is Black's best way to handle this position, but it's rarely ventured, at only a 7% frequency, so you needn't fret much about it.} 8. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1g3,Gg3h4] The queen prepares to glide to [h4] or [g3]. The bishop will rebound to [d3] soon enough and Black's king will begin to feel the heat. Notice we don't want to chop on [f6] anytime soon. Our dark-squared bishop is worth more than slightly breaking their structure.} Ng6 9. Bd3 c5 10. c4 {We see this idea again and again. With the bishop on [d3], this advance is thematic. This advance would not be good with our bishop on [b5], as it could be easily harassed with ...[a7]-[a6] etc. We look to trade on [d5] and/or [f6] at the optimal time.} b6 {Preparing to fianchetto the bishop on [b7]. Black prepares to achieve a healthy scheme of development.} 11. Bxf6 {Exchanging Black's defender of [e4] and [d5].} ({We could continue with simple development like} 11. Nc3 {here, but I really like the wacky exchange on [f6].}) 11... Qxf6 12. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5,Re4][%cal Gc3d5,Gc3e4] Pressuring the weakened central squares.} Bb7 (12... dxc4 {would allow us to gain a grip on the position with} 13. Be4 Rb8 14. bxc4 {, when we have good control of the center and the light squares. While Black technically has the bishop pair, the best option for their bishop will always be coming to [b7], trading for ours on [e4]. Neither side can really advance far in the center without creating weaknesses. We can consider a serious expansion with our g- and h-pawns to get things going on the kingside.}) 13. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gf3g5,Gg2g4] With ideas of [h4]-[h5], poking at the [g6]-knight. We can consider [Nf3]-[g5] or [g2]-[g4] in the future. The game is balanced, but White has more fun in this position.} *

