1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} e6 {This is opted for 8% of the time and so is worth looking at as well.} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} ({I prefer this move over the more popular} 5. Bxc6+ {. We are preparing to place our bishop on [b2]. In this position, it makes sense to wait before executing [Bxc6]. At the moment, the knight isn't going anywhere, and if Black plays ...[Bd7] later, then this combination of 4...e6 with a later ...[Bd7] seems like a worse version of 4...Bd7 .}) 5... Bd6 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O Ne7 {[%cal Rb5c6] The knight retreats to avoid the crafty [Bxc6]. Alas, the knight can no longer easily venture to [b4], which is why our bishop will likely come to [d3] over the next dozen moves. This is Black's best way to handle this position, but it's rarely ventured, at only a 7% frequency, so you needn't fret much about it.} 8. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1g3,Gg3h4] The queen prepares to glide to [h4] or [g3]. The bishop will rebound to [d3] soon enough and Black's king will begin to feel the heat. Notice we don't want to chop on [f6] anytime soon. Our dark-squared bishop is worth more than slightly breaking their structure.} Ng6 9. Bd3 Bd7 10. c4 {Introducing some tension against Black's center. One idea is to take on [f6] and immediately follow with [Nc3]. Another is to take on [d5]. A third is to play [Nc3], [Rd1], and [Bb1] with the idea of maybe opting for [d2]-[d4] later.} Qe7 (10... dxc4 11. bxc4 {⩲ and White has good central control.}) 11. Bxf6 (11. Bxg6 {leads to different, more static positions that might be to your taste. The position is level with our control of the [e5]-square counterbalancing the enemy's bishop pair.}) 11... Qxf6 12. Nc3 c6 13. h4 $13 {[%cal Gh4h5,Ge1g3,Gf3g5] White can consider [h4]-[h5], [Qg3], [Ng5]. Our position looks much more comfortable.} *

