1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} e6 {This is opted for 8% of the time and so is worth looking at as well.} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} ({I prefer this move over the more popular} 5. Bxc6+ {. We are preparing to place our bishop on [b2]. In this position, it makes sense to wait before executing [Bxc6]. At the moment, the knight isn't going anywhere, and if Black plays ...[Bd7] later, then this combination of 4...e6 with a later ...[Bd7] seems like a worse version of 4...Bd7 .}) 5... Bd6 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O Ne7 {[%cal Rb5c6] The knight retreats to avoid the crafty [Bxc6]. Alas, the knight can no longer easily venture to [b4], which is why our bishop will likely come to [d3] over the next dozen moves. This is Black's best way to handle this position, but it's rarely ventured, at only a 7% frequency, so you needn't fret much about it.} 8. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1g3,Gg3h4] The queen prepares to glide to [h4] or [g3]. The bishop will rebound to [d3] soon enough and Black's king will begin to feel the heat. Notice we don't want to chop on [f6] anytime soon. Our dark-squared bishop is worth more than slightly breaking their structure.} c5 9. Bd3 {Bouncing back to the kingside.} Bd7 {Preparing an advance with ...[b7]-[b5] and ...[c5]-[c4].} (9... Ng6 10. c4 {would transpose to 8...Ng6 9.Bd3 c5 10.c4 .}) 10. c4 $1 Ne4 {Black occupies the center and attempts to muffle the [d3]-bishop's scope on the kingside.} (10... Ng6 {again transposes to a variation after 8...Ng6 .}) 11. Nc3 {Challenging the enemy steed immediately!} f5 $1 {Reinforcing the knight. This weakens the [e5]-square terminally, however, and so with a bit of spice, we can continue to set problems to Black.} (11... Bc6 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5 $1 {and White will scoop up a pawn since if Black defends [e4] with ...[f7]-[f5], then [e6] will hang.}) 12. Be2 $1 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Qc7 14. d4 {Quite unbelievably White is close to winning here. The structure is nearly symmetrical so understanding this difference isn't easy. I believe it boils down to the disparity in quality between the knights. Ours is poised to hop into [e5] immediately while theirs is very far 4 moves of ...[Kh8], ...[Ng8]-[f6]-[e4] from our [e4]-square. Moreover, White's queen's bishop is active on the long diagonal and our queen can glide to the kingside via [g3] or [h4]. These 3 differences embody why White's advantage is serious. Feel free to look at the following variations in more detail for these ideas illustrated.} cxd4 15. Bxd4 Nc6 16. Bb2 {The black knight has gotten to a more active position but unfortunately, Black can't place the bishop on [c6] any longer and so it simply changed from having an awful knight on [e7] to having an awful bishop on [d7].} Qb6 17. Qc3 {Big threats!} Rf7 18. Rfd1 {Black has always shown to have a few pieces placed incorrectly. Here, it is the bishops and weak d-pawn who continue to yield problems.} Bb4 19. Qc1 {Making sure to keep an eye on the [e3]-pawn.} Bc5 20. Bd4 $18 {White will trade bishops advantageously. Notice that while our bishop on [b2] was definitely good, trading these off leads to a simpler advantage where Black has an awful bishop on [d7], a weak [e6]-pawn, and a weak [e5]-square.} *

