 the [d3]-bishop's scope on the kingside.} (10... Ng6 {again transposes to a variation after 8...Ng6 .}) 11. Nc3 {Challenging the enemy steed immediately!} f5 $1 {Reinforcing the knight. This weakens the [e5]-square terminally, however, and so with a bit of spice, we can continue to set problems to Black.} (11... Bc6 12. Bxe4 dxe4 13. Ng5 $1 {and White will scoop up a pawn since if Black defends [e4] with ...[f7]-[f5], then [e6] will hang.}) 12. Be2 $1 Nf6 $1 {It is best to avoid the trade. The computer insists White is slightly better here, but the variations it recommends are not obvious at all.} 13. Rc1 {I don't believe we should go any further looking into these variations, as the likelihood of reaching this position is extremely low. Some ideas for White are [Ne5] followed by [Bf3] to add some pressure to the [d5] point. Another idea is to try to grab the important [d6]-bishop which is the only healthy and good defender of the weak [e5]-outpost with [Nc3]-[b5]. One of the reasons White is more comfortable here is that we have the [e5]-square while Black doesn't have as solid a grip on the [e4]-square due to us being able to play [d2]-[d3]. If Black takes on [c4], taking with the pawn or bishop both look good. The pawn increases our central control while taking with the bishop would increase our pressure on Black's weak [e6]-pawn.} *

