1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} e6 {This is opted for 8% of the time and so is worth looking at as well.} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2]} ({I prefer this move over the more popular} 5. Bxc6+ {. We are preparing to place our bishop on [b2]. In this position, it makes sense to wait before executing [Bxc6]. At the moment, the knight isn't going anywhere, and if Black plays ...[Bd7] later, then this combination of 4...e6 with a later ...[Bd7] seems like a worse version of 4...Bd7 .}) 5... Bd6 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O Bd7 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Rc2c4] Here there is an idea of playing [c2]-[c4], and then follow it with a potential [d2]-[d3], [Nbd2], and [Nf3]-[e5]. The problem with implementing this plan immediately is that it would lock our [b5]-bishop out of the rest of the board and inevitably force us to trade on [c6] when it gets harassed. We only want to take on [c6] if it means they have to take with b-pawn and ruin their structure. That's why we want to first preserve our bishop by retreating it before going for the strategic plan.} 8. Be2 $1 {Retreat!} Ne7 $1 {This is a very hard move to make for an inexperienced player. Most players have been conditioned to believe all doubled f-pawns are awful and so I'd bet most players will avoid this move. Trading on [f6] is okay, but our bishop will be missed. For that reason, it is better to continue more calmly.} 9. c4 {Initiating tension against the center.} c5 (9... Ng6 {is the computer's top move, but again I find it hard to believe anyone at the club level would play this way. Now [d2]-[d3] would be improper in view of ...[Ng4], zeroing in on the [e3] weak-point.} 10. Bd3 {, a change of pace. White will now instead go for [Qc2] and [Nc3] with a really interesting pressure against Black's kingside. Notice the bishop on [d3] was not well placed there with a black knight on [c6], as it would have to watch out for harassment from ...[Nc6]-[b4]. Here, on the other hand, it is invulnerable.}) 10. cxd5 Nexd5 11. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4] The knight is en route to the healthy [c4]-spot.} Qe7 12. Nc4 {Threatening [Nxd6].} Bc7 13. Nce5 {Continuing to harass the enemy bishops! White would love to scoop one up to claim the bishop pair.} Be8 {A very ugly move to make, but it has some sense behind it. Black hopes to activate the bishop along the [e8]-[h5] diagonal.} 14. Rc1 $14 {Black's plan will take time though, and any push of the f-pawn has the drawback of weakening [e6].} *

