c4 {Initiating tension against the center.} c5 (9... Ng6 {is the computer's top move, but again I find it hard to believe anyone at the club level would play this way. Now [d2]-[d3] would be improper in view of ...[Ng4], zeroing in on the [e3] weak-point.} 10. Bd3 {, a change of pace. White will now instead go for [Qc2] and [Nc3] with a really interesting pressure against Black's kingside. Notice the bishop on [d3] was not well placed there with a black knight on [c6], as it would have to watch out for harassment from ...[Nc6]-[b4]. Here, on the other hand, it is invulnerable.}) 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Bxf6 {With the e-pawn having been diverted, the exchange on [f6] is now worth its salt!} gxf6 12. Nc3 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7][%cal Ge2d3,Gc3e2,Ge2g3,Yg3f5,Yg3h5] Black's structure is hideous but even so, White only has a small advantage due to the potential of Black's bishop pair. A straightforward plan is [Bd3] followed by [Nc3]-[e2]-[g3] to press upon the weak squares on [f5] and [h5].} *

