1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} Bg4 {Black's light-squared bishop responds with a pin of its own! It is a bit dubious, however, as such a pin means Black will most likely trade on [f3]. This represents a problem for Black, as White will be able to do the same on [c6] but with the added bonus of inflicting a weakening on Black's structure.} 5. Bxc6+ $1 {The majority chose to castle over this move, but who could resist immediately inflicting this weakening on the opponent?} bxc6 {Black's structure has been weakened. While they do not yet constitute a decisive disadvantage, the c-pawns will always be a nuisance to Black's army. They are vulnerable, especially the one on [c6] to knight hops to [d4] or [e5]. White may entertain ideas of opening up the c-file to target these with moves like [c2]-[c4].} 6. h3 Bc8 $6 {Definitely a strange move, but you never know what to expect with the Bird!} 7. O-O e6 8. b3 $14 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gf3e5,Gd2d3,Gb1d2,Gd2f3] This is just a much-improved version of other lines. Black has burned two moves on the useless ...[Bc8]-[g4]-[c8] while White has spent a move on the not-so-useful [h2]-[h3]. White will continue with [Bb2], [Nf3]-[e5], [d2]-[d3], and [Nb1]-[d2]-[f3] with a comfortable edge.} *

