1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} Bg4 {Black's light-squared bishop responds with a pin of its own! It is a bit dubious, however, as such a pin means Black will most likely trade on [f3]. This represents a problem for Black, as White will be able to do the same on [c6] but with the added bonus of inflicting a weakening on Black's structure.} 5. Bxc6+ $1 {The majority chose to castle over this move, but who could resist immediately inflicting this weakening on the opponent?} bxc6 {Black's structure has been weakened. While they do not yet constitute a decisive disadvantage, the c-pawns will always be a nuisance to Black's army. They are vulnerable, especially the one on [c6] to knight hops to [d4] or [e5]. White may entertain ideas of opening up the c-file to target these with moves like [c2]-[c4].} 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e6 8. O-O Bd6 9. Nc3 {Notice that with our queen on [f3], playing [d3] and [Nd2]-[f3] will require burning a move to get our queen out of the way. So instead we're putting the knight on this slightly awkward-looking square with an eye to quick central activity.} O-O 10. d3 $1 {[%cal Ge3e4] White will play [e3]-[e4] and have a much more comfortable position. If Black trades on [e4], we will recapture with the pawn or knight, when Black's c-pawns begin to look weaker.} c5 {[%csl Rc5,Rd6][%cal Rd6c5] This just makes Black's [d6]-bishop worse.} 11. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] The threat of [e4]-[e5] is a serious one.} Be7 12. Kh1 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] There were some ideas of ...[c5]-[c4] and ...[Bc5]+, which are now put to rest. We will continue with [b3] and [Bb2]. The fianchetto will work well here. If Black blocks us with ...[d5]-[d4], our knight gains a fantastic outpost on [c4] and our bishop can simply reroute to [c1].} *

