rly to other variations, the simplifications favor White who looks to have more access to the weak c-pawns.} dxe4 14. Nxe4 Qd4+ 15. Qf2 {From here we can enter several nice endgames. Click through the rest of the moves if you want a deeper coverage, but in terms of memorization, knowing this far is enough.} (15. Kh1 Nd5 {is unclear, when Black has threats of ...[Ne3] and ...[Qxb2].}) 15... Qxf2+ (15... Qxb2 16. Nxf6+ Qxf6 17. Qxf6 gxf6 18. Rxf6 {is a winning rook endgame. Despite the equal material, Black's pawns are all weak. Black will inevitably lose [c6] and then have to suffer with everything else. Meanwhile, White's pawns are relatively healthy, and developing pressure against them will be for naught if White is able to play correctly.}) 16. Kxf2 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Rc6,Rc7][%cal Ge4c5] Getting ready for the endgame!} Nxe4+ {Black has to do this to hope for anything. Without this capture, White's structure will remain pristine and White can sit a knight on the nice [c5]-outpost without issue.} 17. dxe4 Rfe8 18. Ke3 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7,Re4][%cal Gf1f5,Gf5c5,Gc5a5,Ga1d1,Gd1d7] White has a slight weakness on [e4] but with the king helping out, it is for the moment comfortably protected. White will play [Rf5] in an attempt to swing over to [c5] and lay siege to the [c6] and [c7]-pawns. Meanwhile, we will bring the other rook to [d1] where it can cover the [e4]-pawn via [Rd4] or begin targeting the enemy's 7th rank with [Rd7].} *

