1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} Bd7 {The most popular response. The black bishop counters the pin and prepares ...[a6], when Black won't have to suffer any break in the structure.} 5. O-O {The most popular move. There is no reason to execute the exchange on [c6] yet. We will leave our bishop there as long as possible and only after Black invests a tempo to prod it with ...[a7]-[a6], will we consider the trade. Depending on how things shake out, we may even see the bishop simply retreat to [d3] in search of more relevant pressure on the opponent's kingside.} e5 {This has been tried 4% of the time. If it worked, it would be genius, but it doesn't.} 6. Bxc6 {The idea goes SPLAT!} Bxc6 7. fxe5 {[%cal Ge5f6] Digging the knight out of its great square again.} Nd7 8. d4 {[%csl Rc6,Rd7,Rf8][%cal Gc2c4,Gb1c3,Gd4d5] All of Black's minor pieces have depressing prospects. Let me know in the comments which you think is the worst. We can handle the position in several ways. My favorite is a steamroll involving [c2]-[c4] followed by [Nc3] with the hopes of pushing through [d4]-[d5].} *

