te could go for this standard approach but with the bishop on [d6], Black is better positioned to take on the weaknesses on the c-file.} Bxc6 9. Ne5 O-O 10. Nxc6 bxc6 {and unlike analogous positions, Black is poised to immediately break with ...[Qe7] and ...[e6]-[e5]. This means the classic approach of [d3] and [Nd2]-[f3] is too slow.} 11. d3 Qe7 12. Nd2 e5 {⇆ . The position is getting messy and while White still has a good share of the chances, the [e3]-square is weak and the knight fails to impress.}) 8... Qe7 {[%cal Ge6e5] At this point it is clear that Black is itching to push ...[e6]-[e5]. They also might castle queenside, when our entire offensive will have been misoriented to the kingside. It is the perfect moment to switch gears and change the game into a positional struggle...} (8... O-O {will simply transpose to the positions after 7...O-O 8.Be2 with us up a tempo due to Black here having spent the tempo on the useless ...[a7]-[a6].}) 9. d4 $1 {[%csl Rc6,Ge5][%cal Re6e5,Gc2c4,Gc4c5,Rc7c5,Gf3e5] Of the 198 games to reach this position only 11 5% saw this move. It creates a Stonewall structure between [f4]-[e3]-[d4]. The Stonewall has a bad reputation due to the weakness it comes with on the [e4]-square. This is not present here, as Black's bishop is locked on the wrong side of the pawn chain. If the [d7]-bishop were to magically appear on [f5], then we might perhaps be worse. Another improvement over normal Stonewalls is that there is no tension from our opponent's c-pawn against our [d4]. Because of this, we can potentially consider pawn advances with [c2]-[c4]-[c5]. When we plant a knight on [e5], this will be supremely annoying, as Black's dark-squared bishop would never want to trade for a knight but on the other hand, if Black trades the [c6]-knight on [e5], we can take back with the pawn, kicking the same nice bishop out of [d6] permanently.} O-O-O {The majority of games 7 have seen this move but believe it or not, Black is already lost!} ({After} 9... O-O $2 10. c4 $1 {± , [c4]-[c5] is already a huge threat and Black has to play something really ugly like ...[Qe8] or ...[Qd8] to parry it.}) 10. c4 $1 {[%cal Gc4c5] Now [c5] looms to trap the bishop and even if the bishop gets out alive, White will have gained valuable time to push the pawns along on the queenside and make progress towards Black's king.} Qe8 11. c5 Be7 12. Nc3 $18 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gd1b3] White has a very simple plan and can just push the pawns along. In most of the lines, the computer recommends [b4] immediately, without any preparation. If Black takes, this will run into issues soon enough with the [b7]-pawn after [Qb3] and [Rb1].} *

