1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 Nc6 {This is the second most popular move between the ratings of 1200 and 2000. With it, Black forgoes pushing the c-pawn for the purpose of fast development. If Black is allowed to push ...[e7]-[e5] then this development plan will make a lot of sense. We must act quickly to pin this rambunctious steed.} 4. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] The bishop threatens a capture on [c6], which, if it occurs, will define the future struggle. Black's response will determine whether or not White will be able to trade the bishop pair for the long-term weakening of the pawn chain.} Bd7 {The most popular response. The black bishop counters the pin and prepares ...[a6], when Black won't have to suffer any break in the structure.} 5. O-O {The most popular move. There is no reason to execute the exchange on [c6] yet. We will leave our bishop there as long as possible and only after Black invests a tempo to prod it with ...[a7]-[a6], will we consider the trade. Depending on how things shake out, we may even see the bishop simply retreat to [d3] in search of more relevant pressure on the opponent's kingside.} e6 6. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] The bishop will be fianchettoed on [b2] in classic Bird style.} Bd6 {[%csl Ge5,Ge7][%cal Gd6e5,Gd8e7] The most popular continuation, with 27% of Black players choosing it. This move makes intuitive sense. It fights for [e5] and keeps the [e7]-square available for the black queen.} (6... a6 {is the second most popular with 23% of games opting for it.} 7. Be2 {transposes to the 5...a6 variation.}) 7. Bb2 {Gripping the long diagonal.} Qe7 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ge8c8] This has been tried in 18% of games and prepares a potential queenside castle and/or ...[e6]-[e5]. Importantly, if Black isn't able to achieve ...[e6]-[e5], the [c6]-knight, [d6]-bishop, and [e7]-queen, will all be stuck in a jam. So how can we end their hopes of achieving that?!?!} 8. d4 $1 {[%cal Re6e5,Gd4e5,Gf4e5] Of the 1698 games to have reached this position, only 52 times 3% has the White player found this great move! To say that this hasn't yet reached the mainstream would be an understatement. We have seen this idea of opting for a Stonewall in other positions where Black is about to achieve ...[e6]-[e5] and this one is no different. Black's [c6]-knight and [d7]-bishop are both badly misplaced compared to where they should be. The [d7]-bishop should be on [f5] or [g6], enflaming the weak [e4]-square, and while the [c6]-knight is in itself okay, it stands in the way of the important ...[c7]-[c5] launch, and for that reason, it must spend valuable time fixing this discoordination.} *

