1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {On a side note, if you know someone is playing the Sielecki repertoire, you might be best advised to start with a slightly different move order.} (2. e3 $5 {Sielecki does not cover this and given that his recommendation is} Bg4 {and} 3. Z0 Nd7 {against this setup, Black students of his repertoire will immediately be forced to think on their feet from here.}) ({Generally, I cannot see any difference between} 2. e3 {and 2.Nf3 in how it affects our repertoire. We will continue with 3.Nf3 next. Good luck to Black figuring out how to recreate the position with ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] as we cover in the main line.}) 2... Bg4 {This chapter primarily deals with the ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] setup recommended in the Chessable favorite, Keep It Simple For Black by IM Christof Sielecki.} 3. Ne5 {This looks like a more energetic alternative, but it is ultimately a riskier way to play. Our knight can be traded off quickly with ...[Nd7] by Black and we might pay a big price for the fact that the [h4]-square is undefended now.} Bf5 (3... h5 $5 4. c4 {, aggressively fighting for the center.} d4 5. Qb3 $5 {This is just a wild position. Apparently best for Black is} Bc8 {here, with dynamic equality. Feel free to analyze on your own!}) 4. Nc3 {A gamble that I would consider using in a blitz game. We are taunting Black into pushing ...[d4] to try and evict our knight.} d4 (4... e6 $1 {⩱ , if Black doesn't push ...[d4] and responds solidly such as this, well... then we're just worse. I told you it was a gamble, and you just lost your chips!}) 5. e4 $1 {White is better all of a sudden! Our pawns join each other on [e4] and [f4], exercising a strong influence over the center; meanwhile, the [f1]-bishop will glide out.} dxc3 (5... Bd7 $1 {is the best way to manage the situation.} 6. Bc4 {, threatening mate!} e6 7. Ne2 {⩲ and White has the better game. White will continue with [d3], [O-O], and gradually start to get play going on the kingside.}) 6. exf5 $18 {[%cal Gf1c4,Gd1f3] Black will really miss the light-squared bishop while White's will dominate the board. Simple threatening moves like [Bc4], and [Qf3] should bring White an overwhelming initiative.} *

