1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {On a side note, if you know someone is playing the Sielecki repertoire, you might be best advised to start with a slightly different move order.} (2. e3 $5 {Sielecki does not cover this and given that his recommendation is} Bg4 {and} 3. Z0 Nd7 {against this setup, Black students of his repertoire will immediately be forced to think on their feet from here.}) ({Generally, I cannot see any difference between} 2. e3 {and 2.Nf3 in how it affects our repertoire. We will continue with 3.Nf3 next. Good luck to Black figuring out how to recreate the position with ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] as we cover in the main line.}) 2... Bg4 {This chapter primarily deals with the ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] setup recommended in the Chessable favorite, Keep It Simple For Black by IM Christof Sielecki.} 3. e3 {(here or the Aggressive Pin if Black plays) (Before publishing the course, I had looked at this position and assumed it would invariably transpose to other positions already analyzed in the course, such as those from the Solid Pin if Black plays 3...Nf6 3...Nc6 ) . Only after publishing did it come to my attention that there is in fact another try for Black, which is exclusive to this earlier development of the bishop to [g4].} Nd7 4. h3 (4. Be2 {would also be a fine way to play. We will castle and play for straightforward pressure involving [b3] and [c4]. Feel free to analyze this on your own if it is more to your liking.}) 4... Bxf3 (4... Bh5 {just drops the bishop:} 5. g4 Bg6 6. f5 {.}) 5. Qxf3 e5 {Black really wants to achieve their favorite thematic push, but this drops a pawn.} 6. Qxd5 $1 Qh4+ {Despite appearances, this check is not scary.} 7. Kd1 O-O-O 8. fxe5 {White is up two pawns and has an enormous advantage, but we still have to tread a bit carefully.} f6 {Black is hoping we exchange on [f6], when Black can mobilize their dormant knight.} 9. Qc4 {[%cal Gc4h4] Threatening to trade queens. Even if Black regains a pawn, any endgame in which Black is down a pawn against an opponent's bishop pair is near hopeless.} Qh5+ 10. Be2 Qxe5 11. Bf3 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gd2d3,Gc1d2] We will slowly develop with [Nc3], [d3] and [Bd2]. White is a solid pawn up and has a healthy pawn structure. Once we figure out a better spot for the king, and we are able to mobilize our rooks, we might want to begin pushing in the center where White has two extra pawns compared to Black.} *

