1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {On a side note, if you know someone is playing the Sielecki repertoire, you might be best advised to start with a slightly different move order.} (2. e3 $5 {Sielecki does not cover this and given that his recommendation is} Bg4 {and} 3. Z0 Nd7 {against this setup, Black students of his repertoire will immediately be forced to think on their feet from here.}) ({Generally, I cannot see any difference between} 2. e3 {and 2.Nf3 in how it affects our repertoire. We will continue with 3.Nf3 next. Good luck to Black figuring out how to recreate the position with ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] as we cover in the main line.}) 2... Bg4 {This chapter primarily deals with the ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] setup recommended in the Chessable favorite, Keep It Simple For Black by IM Christof Sielecki.} 3. e3 {(here or the Aggressive Pin if Black plays) (Before publishing the course, I had looked at this position and assumed it would invariably transpose to other positions already analyzed in the course, such as those from the Solid Pin if Black plays 3...Nf6 3...Nc6 ) . Only after publishing did it come to my attention that there is in fact another try for Black, which is exclusive to this earlier development of the bishop to [g4].} Nd7 4. h3 (4. Be2 {would also be a fine way to play. We will castle and play for straightforward pressure involving [b3] and [c4]. Feel free to analyze this on your own if it is more to your liking.}) 4... Bxf3 (4... Bh5 {just drops the bishop:} 5. g4 Bg6 6. f5 {.}) 5. Qxf3 Ngf6 6. g4 $1 e5 {Attempting to take the full center and make real use of the [d7]-knight, but it is simply too late for such action in the center.} (6... c6 {transposes to a variation we analyze deeply here.}) 7. g5 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gf3d5,Gg5f6] The knight is hit and Black begins facing problems of how to keep [d5] on the board.} e4 $2 {Weirdly enough, this is a mistake even though it saves the [d5]-pawn.} 8. Qg2 Ng8 9. b3 {[%csl Gd2,Ge3,Gf4,Gg5][%cal Gc1b2] It begins to be clear why ...[e4] was a mistake. Our [d2]-[e3]-[f4]-[g5] phalanx establishes full control on the long diagonal and will pair perfectly with a bishop on [b2].} Ne7 {Gliding to the open square on [f5].} 10. Bb2 Nf5 11. h4 {[%cal Gg2f2,Gf1h3] Black's knight might look nice on [f5] but after [Qf2] and [Bh3], it will begin feeling the heat. The enemy knights have no decent squares. We will get our bishop to [h3], play [Nc3], and probably castle queenside. When we are ready and fully mobilized, we can open the game with [d2]-[d3].} *

