Black threatens an annoying check on [h4].} (9... c6 10. a4 $1 {⩲ , gaining more space and preparing to install the bishop on [a3]. Furthermore, now we can think of playing [Rb1], when Black will not be able to build cement with ...[b7]-[b5].}) 10. O-O {Sidestepping the dangerous check.} Nb6 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb6c4] Covering our [c3]-[c4] ideas to undermine the [d5]-pawn's defense of the [e4]-knight.} 11. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5] Trying to push back the knight with [a4]-[a5].} a5 12. d3 {A classic idea. We sacrifice [c3] to uncoordinate the black knights.} Nxc3 13. Bd2 Ncxa4 14. e4 {Opening up the board with the black knights stuck on the Pacific rim.} O-O 15. f5 $13 {[%csl Ra4,Rb6][%cal Ge4e5,Gf5f6,Gg4g5] We have ideas of attacking on the kingside with [e4]-[e5], [f5]-[f6], or even [g4]-[g5]. Black's knights are useless against this. Black is up two pawns and the computer insists it's 0's and just dead equal. It's a wild position that either side could win. If the center opens up enough, our 2 bishops will dominate the opponent's 2 knights.} *

