1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {On a side note, if you know someone is playing the Sielecki repertoire, you might be best advised to start with a slightly different move order.} (2. e3 $5 {Sielecki does not cover this and given that his recommendation is} Bg4 {and} 3. Z0 Nd7 {against this setup, Black students of his repertoire will immediately be forced to think on their feet from here.}) ({Generally, I cannot see any difference between} 2. e3 {and 2.Nf3 in how it affects our repertoire. We will continue with 3.Nf3 next. Good luck to Black figuring out how to recreate the position with ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] as we cover in the main line.}) 2... Bg4 {This chapter primarily deals with the ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] setup recommended in the Chessable favorite, Keep It Simple For Black by IM Christof Sielecki.} 3. e3 {(here or the Aggressive Pin if Black plays) (Before publishing the course, I had looked at this position and assumed it would invariably transpose to other positions already analyzed in the course, such as those from the Solid Pin if Black plays 3...Nf6 3...Nc6 ) . Only after publishing did it come to my attention that there is in fact another try for Black, which is exclusive to this earlier development of the bishop to [g4].} Nd7 4. h3 (4. Be2 {would also be a fine way to play. We will castle and play for straightforward pressure involving [b3] and [c4]. Feel free to analyze this on your own if it is more to your liking.}) 4... Bxf3 (4... Bh5 {just drops the bishop:} 5. g4 Bg6 6. f5 {.}) 5. Qxf3 c6 {This is recommended by Sielecki.} 6. c4 ({Sielecki does not cover this in his course, instead opting to only look at} 6. d4 {. We immediately pressure [d5] and allow Black to take the game in several directions.}) 6... Ngf6 {(The computer thinks this is slightly inaccurate in that it blocks Black from going for a Stonewall with ...f7-f5 which remains an option after 6...e6 ) .} 7. Nc3 (7. d4 {∞ leads to more orthodox positions but might be objectively better. Feel free to opt for such positions if they are more to your liking. White will continue with [Bd3], [Bd2], and [Nc3]. The game is balanced with White's weak [e4]-square compensated for by the bishop pair.}) 7... e6 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3] The bishop seems strange here, as it can be pushed around by a black knight hopping to [c5].} Bd6 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 $13 {[%cal Gc1b2] White prepares [Bb2]. The pawn structure is relatively inflexible. We want to be very careful with pawn pushes since Black's knights are dynamic and ready to target any newly formed weak points we create. In fact, once I figure out a way to redeploy the knight from [c3] to somewhere that doesn't block the [b2]-bishop's visage, I would likely only consider an eventual pawn push on the g-file with [g2]-[g4]-[g5]. The game is strategically balanced with chances for both sides.} *

