∞ leads to more orthodox positions but might be objectively better. Feel free to opt for such positions if they are more to your liking. White will continue with [Bd3], [Bd2], and [Nc3]. The game is balanced with White's weak [e4]-square compensated for by the bishop pair.}) 7... e6 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3] The bishop seems strange here, as it can be pushed around by a black knight hopping to [c5].} Nc5 9. Be2 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb2b4,Gd2d4] Why didn't we simply play [Be2] to begin with? Why did we want to elicit ...[Nc5]? Well, simply put, the knight is likely worse placed on [c5] than it was on [d7]. It blocks the [f8]-bishop's natural path and might be vulnerable to ideas like [d2]-[d4] or [b2]-[b4], gaining a tempo against it.} Be7 {Solid development.} 10. O-O O-O {Here we can opt for a fine Stonewall.} 11. d4 $1 Nce4 12. Bd3 $132 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd3e4] White has good control over the [e4]-square, making this a decent Stonewall. Black is still equal but will have to force concessions in the center immediately with the break ...[c6]-[c5]. Conversely, if we are allowed to encroach with [c4]-[c5] in a sustainable manner meaning we can support it with [b2]-[b4] and [a2]-[a3] without issue, then we will have a nice space advantage.} *

