∞ leads to more orthodox positions but might be objectively better. Feel free to opt for such positions if they are more to your liking. White will continue with [Bd3], [Bd2], and [Nc3]. The game is balanced with White's weak [e4]-square compensated for by the bishop pair.}) 7... e6 8. Bd3 {[%csl Yd3] The bishop seems strange here, as it can be pushed around by a black knight hopping to [c5].} Nc5 9. Be2 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb2b4,Gd2d4] Why didn't we simply play [Be2] to begin with? Why did we want to elicit ...[Nc5]? Well, simply put, the knight is likely worse placed on [c5] than it was on [d7]. It blocks the [f8]-bishop's natural path and might be vulnerable to ideas like [d2]-[d4] or [b2]-[b4], gaining a tempo against it.} Bd6 {Blacks develop normally in complement to the classic structural motif of achieving ...[e6]-[e5].} 10. O-O O-O (10... e5 $4 {cannot work yet as long as the knight remains on [c5]:} 11. fxe5 Bxe5 12. d4 {+- .}) 11. Rb1 $13 {[%cal Gb2b4] White prepares a potential [b2]-[b4], gaining space on the queenside. Our bishops are still very locked in and for that reason, the game is balanced, but we should look for every opportunity to open diagonals for them. However, we do NOT want to trade on [d5] so soon, as Black would recapture with the [e6]-pawn and would have a nice open e-file for the rook after ...[Rf8]-[e8].} *

