. Qxb7 {is also possible, but it gives Black a lot of activity and we are really lagging in development at this point.}) 9... Bd6 10. fxe5 {We will have new opportunities to develop quickly after either piece recaptures.} Nxe5 (10... Bxe5 11. d4 {with tempo! After} Bc7 12. Nc3 {+- , we are up a pawn with the bishop pair. We will play [Bd3] and castle kingside with a winning advantage.}) 11. Bb5+ {A nice tempo to clear the 1st rank on our kingside.} Nfd7 12. Qd5 $1 {[%csl Rd6] Pressuring the bishop.} Qh4+ {This might look scary, but everything is under control.} 13. Kd1 {It turns out that Black's pieces are in more trouble than White's.} Qe7 (13... Be7 $2 {drops a knight:} 14. Qxe5 {+- , and 13...Bc7 drops a pawn with tempo: 14.Qxb7 +- . White is up two pawns and the king is safe enough for the time being. We should continue with solid, slow, and steady development and let the win come to us once we've achieved full mobilization.}) 14. d4 {Pushing Black's knight back.} Nc6 15. Nc3 $18 {[%cal Gc1d2,Gh1f1,Ga1c1] We will gradually play [Bd2], [Rf1] and [Rc1] with a stable advantage. We should be careful about snatching another pawn by trading on [c6], as that might open too many files for the enemy's pieces. If our king is to sit securely on [d1], it probably requires we hold onto our light-squared bishop to protect several important light squares around the king.} *

