1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {On a side note, if you know someone is playing the Sielecki repertoire, you might be best advised to start with a slightly different move order.} (2. e3 $5 {Sielecki does not cover this and given that his recommendation is} Bg4 {and} 3. Z0 Nd7 {against this setup, Black students of his repertoire will immediately be forced to think on their feet from here.}) ({Generally, I cannot see any difference between} 2. e3 {and 2.Nf3 in how it affects our repertoire. We will continue with 3.Nf3 next. Good luck to Black figuring out how to recreate the position with ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] as we cover in the main line.}) 2... Bg4 {This chapter primarily deals with the ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] setup recommended in the Chessable favorite, Keep It Simple For Black by IM Christof Sielecki.} 3. e3 {(here or the Aggressive Pin if Black plays) (Before publishing the course, I had looked at this position and assumed it would invariably transpose to other positions already analyzed in the course, such as those from the Solid Pin if Black plays 3...Nf6 3...Nc6 ) . Only after publishing did it come to my attention that there is in fact another try for Black, which is exclusive to this earlier development of the bishop to [g4].} Nd7 4. h3 (4. Be2 {would also be a fine way to play. We will castle and play for straightforward pressure involving [b3] and [c4]. Feel free to analyze this on your own if it is more to your liking.}) 4... Bxf3 (4... Bh5 {just drops the bishop:} 5. g4 Bg6 6. f5 {.}) 5. Qxf3 c6 {This is recommended by Sielecki.} 6. c4 ({Sielecki does not cover this in his course, instead opting to only look at} 6. d4 {. We immediately pressure [d5] and allow Black to take the game in several directions.}) 6... dxc4 {Black wants to punch through with ...[e5] without having to worry about a hanging [d5]-pawn.} 7. Bxc4 e5 (7... Ngf6 $2 {seriously misses the mark, as White can build a great center with} 8. d4 {± . White will castle, play [Nc3], [Rd1], and as soon as possible launch the center further with [e3]-[e4].}) 8. O-O Ngf6 9. g4 $5 {[%cal Gg4g5]} ({Playing for an aggressive g4-g5.} 9. Nc3 {is a more calm alternative for those who don't like the chaos that ensues after 9.g4 .}) 9... Bd6 10. g5 {This pawn push asks Black some serious questions. Black must cede the pawn like this.} Nd5 ({After} 10... Ng8 $4 11. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 12. fxe5+ {+- , White will at least regain the sacrificed piece on [d6] with a winning attack.}) 11. Bxd5 cxd5 12. Qxd5 {White is up a pawn, but the queenside is underdeveloped and White has committed all the pawns to the same color as the remaining bishop − a serious issue! Black can get some compensation with precise play.} Nb6 $1 {Forcing our queen to make a decision. We can take on [b7] at many points here and in the future, but playing in such a recklessly greedy way is very risky. I recommend being happy with the extra pawn and quickly attending to our lagging development.} 13. Qb5+ Nd7 (13... Qd7 {allows us to liquidate to a great endgame:} 14. Qxd7+ Nxd7 15. fxe5 Nxe5 16. d4 {. We are a healthy pawn up and will develop with straightforward moves like [Nc3].}) 14. d4 exd4 15. exd4 O-O 16. Nc3 {We have caught up in development, but our structure is still loose and full of weaknesses, compensating Black for the pawn minus. White has a very slight advantage objectively. Be prepared for mayhem in the Birdhouse!} *

