1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {On a side note, if you know someone is playing the Sielecki repertoire, you might be best advised to start with a slightly different move order.} (2. e3 $5 {Sielecki does not cover this and given that his recommendation is} Bg4 {and} 3. Z0 Nd7 {against this setup, Black students of his repertoire will immediately be forced to think on their feet from here.}) ({Generally, I cannot see any difference between} 2. e3 {and 2.Nf3 in how it affects our repertoire. We will continue with 3.Nf3 next. Good luck to Black figuring out how to recreate the position with ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] as we cover in the main line.}) 2... Bg4 {This chapter primarily deals with the ...[Bg4] and ...[Nd7] setup recommended in the Chessable favorite, Keep It Simple For Black by IM Christof Sielecki.} 3. e3 {(here or the Aggressive Pin if Black plays) (Before publishing the course, I had looked at this position and assumed it would invariably transpose to other positions already analyzed in the course, such as those from the Solid Pin if Black plays 3...Nf6 3...Nc6 ) . Only after publishing did it come to my attention that there is in fact another try for Black, which is exclusive to this earlier development of the bishop to [g4].} Nd7 4. h3 (4. Be2 {would also be a fine way to play. We will castle and play for straightforward pressure involving [b3] and [c4]. Feel free to analyze this on your own if it is more to your liking.}) 4... Bxf3 (4... Bh5 {just drops the bishop:} 5. g4 Bg6 6. f5 {.}) 5. Qxf3 c6 {This is recommended by Sielecki.} 6. c4 ({Sielecki does not cover this in his course, instead opting to only look at} 6. d4 {. We immediately pressure [d5] and allow Black to take the game in several directions.}) 6... e6 $5 {[%cal Gf7f5] Keeping options of [f5] available.} 7. Be2 Ngf6 8. O-O e5 {Black pushes for a resolution in the center and hopes that we trade on [e5], giving the [d7]-knight a red carpet entrance into the center.} 9. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5] Pushing for [g4]-[g5] to kick the knight out and undermine Black's stability in the center.} exf4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7e5]} ({Clearing the e5-square for the d7-knight.} 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 {transposes back to a position we already reached after 6...dxc4 .}) 10. g5 {[%csl Rf6] Pushing the other knight out.} Ne4 {[%cal Ge4g5]} (10... Ne4 {Now} 11. Qxf4 {can be met with} Nxg5 {, holding onto [f7]. So instead, we must take with the pawn.}) 11. exf4 {We equalize the material and arrive at an extremely weird situation. We're ahead in development and have a potent bishop pair but have a weak structure. I will give two sample lines.} Be7 12. cxd5 {Loosening Black's structure a bit and opening one more diagonal for our bishop a4-[e8] in this instance.} cxd5 13. d3 Nd6 14. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc3d5] Threatening to take on [d5] and establish our knight on [d5] all in one go.} (14. Qxd5 $6 {⩲ is okay, but our d-pawn will be isolated and relatively harmless. 14.Nc3 is therefore stronger.}) 14... d4 15. Nd5 $14 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ga1e1] The structure looks strange with weaknesses for both sides our kingside is over extended but so is Black's d-pawn. We will play [Bd2] and [Rae1], when our bishop pair gives us an edge.} (15. Ne4 {⩲ is also good, with a slight advantage to White due to the bishop pair.}) *

