t a red carpet entrance into the center.} 9. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4g5] Pushing for [g4]-[g5] to kick the knight out and undermine Black's stability in the center.} exf4 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7e5]} ({Clearing the e5-square for the d7-knight.} 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 {transposes back to a position we already reached after 6...dxc4 .}) 10. g5 {[%csl Rf6] Pushing the other knight out.} Ne4 {[%cal Ge4g5]} (10... Ne4 {Now} 11. Qxf4 {can be met with} Nxg5 {, holding onto [f7]. So instead, we must take with the pawn.}) 11. exf4 {We equalize the material and arrive at an extremely weird situation. We're ahead in development and have a potent bishop pair but have a weak structure. I will give two sample lines.} Bc5+ $1 {Black mobilizes the remaining pieces fast.} 12. Kh2 Qc7 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gc7h2,Ge4g5] Creating a pin on the [f4]-pawn and introducing ...[Nxg5] ideas.} 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Qg2 $1 {[%cal Gd2d3] We see this move in other variations as well. The queen reinforces [g5] against the threat of ...[Nxg5] and opens the bishop's lane. White is ready to kick the black knight out of the center with [d2]-[d3].} O-O 15. d3 Nd6 16. Bg4 $14 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gd6f5,Gc1d2,Gb1c3] Stopping the knight from sitting on [f5] comfortably. White will play [Bd2] and [Nc3] shortly with a slight advantage.} ({It's important not to be greedy with} 16. Qxd5 Rfe8 17. Bg4 Rad8 {, when Black's position is a portrait of energetic industry while ours depicts a situation wrought with sloth. With ...[Nb6] on the horizon, every piece will be shining with activity. Black has enormous compensation and I'm honestly surprised White is only slightly worse objectively here.}) *

