lly likes it. Sielecki recommends this same setup albeit in a slightly different position in which we have played [d4].} 8. g4 $5 {[%csl Rc6,Rd5,Re6,Rf5][%cal Gg4f5,Gc4d5] White attacks Black's Stonewall from all angles. I want to emphasize yet again how markedly strange these structures are. I'm a GM and have never studied anything close to this. Glancing at this position I wouldn't know what to make of it, and it's only with the help of the silicon engine that I can affirm this is a balanced and equal position. I could see players immediately losing their way in the face of this strange situation.} (8. d4 $5 {could also be played and is a fine alternative, but the position begins to resemble one analyzed in Keep It Simple, which we are trying to avoid.}) 8... fxg4 $2 {This is a strategic blunder.} 9. hxg4 {White's space is stupendous. If the black knight comes to [f6], we can boot it with [g4]-[g5] since, now that the [f5]-pawn is gone, Black can no longer sit the knight on [e4].} h5 10. g5 {[%csl Gg5,Rg8][%cal Gg5f6,Gg5h6] Digging the knight on [g8] into a rut.} g6 11. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3,Gf4,Gg5] White's pawns inch closer to the endzone.} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5] Aiming for the last good square for the black knights, the [f5]-square.} 12. Bd2 Nf5 13. cxd5 $1 (13. c5 $2 {wouldn't work due to} b6 {⇆ and White is not able to hold onto the space on the queenside; [b2]-[b4] would simply be met with ...[a7]-[a5].}) 13... cxd5 14. Bd3 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gd3f5] White threatens [Bxf5] since either pawn recapture will drop [d5] or [h5]. Black has serious questions to answer.} Nb6 {Defending [d5]. If we are not winning a pawn, trading the light-squared bishop would be a terrible deal − it is perfectly harmonized with our pawn phalanx along the dark squares.} 15. Ba5 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3,Gf4,Gg5][%cal Ga5d8,Gb1c3,Ge1f2] An annoying pin. We will play [Nc3] and [Kf2] with an enormous advantage due to our space and bishop pair. Part of [Ba5]'s strength is that it guarantees Black's bishop won't get access to [b4] when we develop [Nc3] as opposed to when it stood on [d2].} *

