lly likes it. Sielecki recommends this same setup albeit in a slightly different position in which we have played [d4].} 8. g4 $5 {[%csl Rc6,Rd5,Re6,Rf5][%cal Gg4f5,Gc4d5] White attacks Black's Stonewall from all angles. I want to emphasize yet again how markedly strange these structures are. I'm a GM and have never studied anything close to this. Glancing at this position I wouldn't know what to make of it, and it's only with the help of the silicon engine that I can affirm this is a balanced and equal position. I could see players immediately losing their way in the face of this strange situation.} (8. d4 $5 {could also be played and is a fine alternative, but the position begins to resemble one analyzed in Keep It Simple, which we are trying to avoid.}) 8... dxc4 {[%csl Re6] Normally this capture should be positionally losing for the side with the Stonewall since it gives our bishop direct access to the [e6]-weakness.} 9. Bxc4 {[%cal Gc4e6]} Qh4+ {Trading the queens will ease the pressure. This also clears the 8th rank in case Black wants to castle queenside.} 10. Qf2 Qxf2+ 11. Kxf2 {White has some pressure on [e6], but Black can attempt to liquidate things.} e5 {Here we have only one move to ensure a solid positional edge... take your time − you won't find it!} 12. d4 $3 {The point is quite deep. We are too behind in development to think about winning a pawn. But if we catch up in development, the diagonals are open enough to ensure the side with the bishops a better game.} (12. gxf5 {is another good try, but Black can liquidate things with} exf4 13. exf4 {(13.d4! and we return to positions similar to those after 12.d4. )} Ne7 {threatens to collect the pawn immediately. Following} 14. Be6 Nc5 {, our structure is strewn about the board. This combined with a lack of development does not bode well for us, in spite of our pawn plus and bishop pair.} 15. d4 Nxe6 16. fxe6 Nf5 17. Rd1 Rd8 {⩱ and we are dropping a pawn while retaining the weakness on [e6].}) 12... exf4 13. exf4 Bd6 14. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gc1d2,Ga1e1] We are slightly better. If Black continues to leave the [f5]-pawn unattended, we may take it and hold onto it with [Be6]. We can think about finishing development with [Bd2] and [Rae1].} *

