lly likes it. Sielecki recommends this same setup albeit in a slightly different position in which we have played [d4].} 8. g4 $5 {[%csl Rc6,Rd5,Re6,Rf5][%cal Gg4f5,Gc4d5] White attacks Black's Stonewall from all angles. I want to emphasize yet again how markedly strange these structures are. I'm a GM and have never studied anything close to this. Glancing at this position I wouldn't know what to make of it, and it's only with the help of the silicon engine that I can affirm this is a balanced and equal position. I could see players immediately losing their way in the face of this strange situation.} (8. d4 $5 {could also be played and is a fine alternative, but the position begins to resemble one analyzed in Keep It Simple, which we are trying to avoid.}) 8... Qh4+ {Black can try to trade the queens.} 9. Qf2 Qxf2+ 10. Kxf2 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gd2d3,Gc1d2,Gb2b3,Gc1b2] The good news is that even after the queen trade, the game is perplexing and confusing. Both sides have their chances here, but it's certainly easier to play White. While the computer says this is only 0.2, the position is very hard to handle for Black while for us it's quite easy. We should just slowly develop with [Nc3], [d3], and [Bd2] or [b3] and [Bb2]. We should wait for the right time to trade pawns and open the board for our bishops.} *

