1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} g6 {This is played 2% of the time as a 2nd move. This frequency is good for us because Stocky gives some of the most unfavorable evaluations you'll see in the entire Bird's opening. I didn't know it even existed but in several Titled Tuesdays, I kept getting hit by it. So here we are grinding our teeth against the silicon beast looking for good playable positions.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Bg7 {Fianchettoing immediately is by far the most popular.} 4. c4 $1 {Flipping the script on Black and surprising their surprise. Only 2697 games have reached this position − keep in mind it's just move 4. We challenge [d5] and immediately begin asking Black some questions. Black needs to follow a precise path to pose any problems − the chances of this happening in a practical game are 0.} Nf6 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3,Rg7][%cal Rg7d4] Blunting the [g7]-dragon.} O-O 7. e4 (7. Nc3 $2 c5 {↑ and our center is under too much pressure. This looks like a Grünfeld in which we've wasted quite an important move on [f2]-[f4].}) 7... Nb6 8. Be2 {Black is best advised to immediately challenge our center.} c5 9. d5 {We should do our best to keep things closed.} f5 10. e5 $1 Nxd5 11. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Black is up a pawn, but the [g7]-bishop is entombed for the long haul. We will play [h4]-[h5] and attack Black along the weakened [a2]-[g8] diagonal with [Nc3], [Bc4], and [Qb3]. We have great compensation.} *

