1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} g6 {This is played 2% of the time as a 2nd move. This frequency is good for us because Stocky gives some of the most unfavorable evaluations you'll see in the entire Bird's opening. I didn't know it even existed but in several Titled Tuesdays, I kept getting hit by it. So here we are grinding our teeth against the silicon beast looking for good playable positions.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Bg7 {Fianchettoing immediately is by far the most popular.} 4. c4 $1 {Flipping the script on Black and surprising their surprise. Only 2697 games have reached this position − keep in mind it's just move 4. We challenge [d5] and immediately begin asking Black some questions. Black needs to follow a precise path to pose any problems − the chances of this happening in a practical game are 0.} dxc4 5. Bxc4 Nf6 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Ye3e4] We might go for [e3]-[e4] or [d2]-[d4] depending on what Black opts for.} c5 8. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] Now [e4]-[e5] is beginning to cloud the sky.} Nc6 9. d3 $13 {[%cal Ge4e5] We will play [e4]-[e5] and develop with [Qe2] and [Be3]. The position is complicated. Our pieces are better, but [d3] is a slight weakness.} *

