1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} g6 {This is played 2% of the time as a 2nd move. This frequency is good for us because Stocky gives some of the most unfavorable evaluations you'll see in the entire Bird's opening. I didn't know it even existed but in several Titled Tuesdays, I kept getting hit by it. So here we are grinding our teeth against the silicon beast looking for good playable positions.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Bg7 {Fianchettoing immediately is by far the most popular.} 4. c4 $1 {Flipping the script on Black and surprising their surprise. Only 2697 games have reached this position − keep in mind it's just move 4. We challenge [d5] and immediately begin asking Black some questions. Black needs to follow a precise path to pose any problems − the chances of this happening in a practical game are 0.} e6 $1 {Complicated stuff! Black's best chance at pressuring our position is keeping the diagonal open by developing the knight to [e7]. This is extremely hard to find. In my online practice, the only player to end up playing this against me was Hikaru Nakamura. I lost but had a draw in the ending.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 {This is what FM Christoph Kuberczyk recommends against the Bird in his Chessable course, The Hybrid Grünfeld-Slav.} 6. b4 $1 {Welcome to the jungle of unexplored chess! This has only been seen in 4 games online and 2 games over the board. The move is an interesting preparatory move. Now we can aim for [d4] with less risk of the Stonewall being harassed by the pesky ...[c5] push. Another idea is the more classic [Bb2], making for an extended fianchetto the pawn being on [b4] rather than [b3].} ({Here Kuberczyk only looks at} 6. d4 {, which as we know from our knowledge of the Key Ideas chapter is not a good version of a Stonewall since Black can respond with an energetic} c5 $1 {⩱ in one punch. White may be able to scrounge equality after some precise moves, but that doesn't mean our opening was a success.}) 6... dxc4 7. Bxc4 {Our bishop comes to [c4] immediately without wasting a tempo, which is a definite positive.} O-O (7... c5 $2 {doesn't work at all anymore.} 8. bxc5 {, the ...[c5] push was meant to distract the white d-pawn from the center, not bring the b-pawn further into the middle!}) 8. O-O Nd5 {[%cal Gg7a1,Rd5c3,Rd5b4] Threatening our knight and the [b4]-pawn.} 9. Bb2 {Saccing the pawn momentarily with a brilliant idea in mind.} Nxb4 (9... Nxc3 10. Bxc3 Bxc3 11. dxc3 {⩲ and White is a bit better due to the healthy bishop mixed with the pawns' control on the dark squares.}) 10. Qb1 $3 {[%cal Gc3e4,Gb1b2] I love this move. The queen x-rays the knight and defends the bishop. The plan is to play [Ne4], trade Black's bishop, and lay siege to the weakened dark squares around the black king. White has fantastic compensation and the computer even believes White is slightly better. I'll leave two sample lines.} Nd5 $1 {The knight retreats right back along the path it took to [b4]. The plan is to reinforce ...[f6] in time.} 11. Ne4 {[%cal Gb2g7] White aims to trade bishops and play [Qb2]+.} Nf6 {A strong idea. White will have to trade the strong [e4]-knight if we want to uncover the diagonal.} 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 {Here we could trade on [f6], when our control of the dark squares and Black's poor development offer decent compensation. But the silicon beast is resolute that there is a better option...} 13. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gh5g6,Yg1f2,Yf1h1] With the idea to play [h4]-[h5] and trade on [g6], weakening the black king. Often after the trade of h-pawns, we will play [Kf2] and [Rh1] with the goal of building serious pressure along the h-file. The game is objectively level with White's compensation perfectly balancing the scale − but who wouldn't choose White here!??!?!?!} *

