1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} g6 {This is played 2% of the time as a 2nd move. This frequency is good for us because Stocky gives some of the most unfavorable evaluations you'll see in the entire Bird's opening. I didn't know it even existed but in several Titled Tuesdays, I kept getting hit by it. So here we are grinding our teeth against the silicon beast looking for good playable positions.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Bg7 {Fianchettoing immediately is by far the most popular.} 4. c4 $1 {Flipping the script on Black and surprising their surprise. Only 2697 games have reached this position − keep in mind it's just move 4. We challenge [d5] and immediately begin asking Black some questions. Black needs to follow a precise path to pose any problems − the chances of this happening in a practical game are 0.} d4 {Black's central aggression sets fire on board. There is no going back for either side now, as the game twists and turns down thematically uncharted paths. This is one of Black's best tries and we must respond accurately to hold the balance.} 5. Nxd4 $1 {The only move to keep to the narrow path. Black must chop to ruin our structure, as we threaten to retreat with [Nf3] and play [d2]-[d4] with an enormous center.} (5. exd4 $2 Nh6 $1 {Black won't rush to regain the pawn, electing to slowly reroute the knight to the healthy [f5]-square and recapture the [d4]-bystander at their leisure.} 6. d5 {is a way that we can try to hold onto the pawn, but Black gets a wonderful initiative with the pawn sacrifice} e6 7. dxe6 Bxe6 {. Black is already close to winning. We've pushed too many pawns, weakened too many squares, and developed too few pieces.} 8. d4 Qe7 {, ruh roh! ...[Be6xc4] looms, but how is White expected to deal with this?} 9. Qe2 {tries to stave off the damage, giving back the [c4]-pawn in the hope that the queens can come off the board.} Nc6 $1 {, the start of a beautiful initiative.} 10. d5 Qb4+ $1 11. Qd2 O-O-O $3 {-+ . Even though we forked the minor pieces with [d4]-[d5] a few moves ago, we are left hanging in the air. Black is winning, as their pieces will get stronger and stronger with each passing move. Black will play ...[Rhe8] and ...[Nf5] and crash through one way or another.} 12. Qxb4 {doesn't work since Black can recapture with} Nxb4 {and immediately threaten a dangerous fork on [c2].}) 5... Bxd4 6. exd4 Qxd4 7. Nc3 {[%csl Rd3,Rd4,Rg7] What's going on exactly? Well, on the one hand, Black has given us the prized pearl that was the [g7]-bishop. But on the other hand, we have weaknesses all over our center. We should rush to control the [d4]-square and eventually correct our structure by getting our pawn to [d4]. If we can't achieve this, Black might get a permanent edge by placing a knight there on an outpost.} Qxf4 {The [f4]-pawn drops...} 8. d4 {[%csl Gc1] And our [c1]-bishop breathes a huge sigh of relief − the [f4]-pawn was a Snorlax on its path, while now it can scope the whole diagonal. We also get the center and can continue pushing the queen around the board. Black's position is quite dangerous already.} Qd6 9. Be2 {Simple development is enough to continue building the pressure − [Bd3] would have hung the [d4]-pawn.} Nf6 10. Bh6 $18 {[%csl Re8] Black's king is stuck in the middle of the board. We will castle, mobilize our rooks on the e- and f-files, and break through the trenches. An important tactical idea to keep in mind is that of [Nb5] and [Bf4], which threatens a potentially decisive [Nxc7]+.} *

