7 {, ruh roh! ...[Be6xc4] looms, but how is White expected to deal with this?} 9. Qe2 {tries to stave off the damage, giving back the [c4]-pawn in the hope that the queens can come off the board.} Nc6 $1 {, the start of a beautiful initiative.} 10. d5 Qb4+ $1 11. Qd2 O-O-O $3 {-+ . Even though we forked the minor pieces with [d4]-[d5] a few moves ago, we are left hanging in the air. Black is winning, as their pieces will get stronger and stronger with each passing move. Black will play ...[Rhe8] and ...[Nf5] and crash through one way or another.} 12. Qxb4 {doesn't work since Black can recapture with} Nxb4 {and immediately threaten a dangerous fork on [c2].}) 5... Bxd4 6. exd4 Qxd4 7. Nc3 {[%csl Rd3,Rd4,Rg7] What's going on exactly? Well, on the one hand, Black has given us the prized pearl that was the [g7]-bishop. But on the other hand, we have weaknesses all over our center. We should rush to control the [d4]-square and eventually correct our structure by getting our pawn to [d4]. If we can't achieve this, Black might get a permanent edge by placing a knight there on an outpost.} Nf6 $1 {Black must continue development!} 8. d3 O-O $6 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gc1e3] We'll have to boot the queen out with [Be3] if we want to eventually correct things with [d3]-[d4].} Nc6 10. Be3 Qd6 11. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4,Rf6g4] Stopping any ...[Bg4] or ...[Ng4] disturbances. We plan to fight for [d4] with [Qe2]-[f2], so ...[Ng4] would be particularly troubling.} Rd8 12. O-O-O {[%cal Gd3d4] Now [d3]-[d4] would bring White a huge advantage, as it shores up the weakness and opens up the [f1]-bishop. Black's next move is strategically forced.} Nd4 13. Qf2 c5 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc5d4] Black has gained control of [d4] and so it seems the danger has been averted...} 14. g4 $16 {[%csl Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gf1g2,Gh1e1] Or has it!?!?!?!? Our bishop will dominate from [g2] and we will follow with [Rhe1] with huge pressure on Black's position. From [e1], the rook will cause serious discomfort for Black's [e7]-pawn. We can also consider taking on [d4] and playing [Nb5] at any moment, or booting the [f6]-knight with [g4]-[g5] and following it with [Nc3]-[e4]. Notice that once our e-pawn leaves the board, the best way to make sense of our structure is to play [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4], shoring up the previously weakened squares.} *

