1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} Nh6 {(to transpose in over-the-board blitz games. Black treats our position like White does in the Dutch which resembles a reversed Bird and follows the classic plan of installing the knight in front of our f-pawn. Fortunately, we are a tempo up on those positions.)} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. d3 c5 4. e4 dxe4 (4... Bg4 5. h3 $1 {Bishop pair, please!} Bxf3 6. Qxf3 {⩲ and with a healthy bishop pair and a terrible knight on [h6], Black will suffer due to their opening experiment.}) 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 {Despite the queens coming off, Black still has some problems to solve, the biggest one standing on the [h6]-square! Our [e4]-pawn is much better than their [c5]-pawn − it fights for the center without standing in the way of our king's bishop.} Nc6 7. h3 $14 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gb1c3,Gc1e3,Gb2b3,Gd1c1,Gc1b2] Locking the knight out. We will follow with [Be3], [Nc3], [Kc1], and eventually [b3] and [Kb2]. We have time to go for this plan since Black will have to burn a lot of time fixing the [h6]-knight. We have a healthy center and a nice space advantage.} *

