1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} Nh6 {(to transpose in over-the-board blitz games. Black treats our position like White does in the Dutch which resembles a reversed Bird and follows the classic plan of installing the knight in front of our f-pawn. Fortunately, we are a tempo up on those positions.)} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. d3 Bg4 {The most common way to handle the position.} 4. e4 {We remain unwavering in our belief − all that matters is the twin pair of [f4] and [e4].} dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 $14 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gc1e3,Gd1c2] The position is slightly better for White. We will make a cubby for our king on [c2] with [c2]-[c3]. With the king there, it will stand out of the way of the rooks. We can continue with [Be3] and [Nbd2] and then perhaps some expansion with [b4] or [a4] on the queenside eventually. The position might look like a draw, but I'd like to assure you it's not! The Swedish GM Ulf Andersson regularly played such positions for wins in the 80s against other strong GMs − check his games out for some great lessons on fighting chess in these endgame-style positions.} *

