1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} Nh6 {(to transpose in over-the-board blitz games. Black treats our position like White does in the Dutch which resembles a reversed Bird and follows the classic plan of installing the knight in front of our f-pawn. Fortunately, we are a tempo up on those positions.)} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. d3 g6 {Black prepares a kingside fianchetto to complement the knight on [f5]. Here 3 moves keep equality; one looks hideous and will certainly get a rise out of your unsuspecting opponent.} 4. Qd2 $3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Rd8d2,Gc1d2] The point is quite simple: when we play [e2]-[e4] we want to be able to meet the queen trade with a recapture by our bishop rather than our king if the queen is on [d1], when we would lose castling rights. No one has played this seemingly ridiculous move understandably, and here on move 4 we stand on the frontier. The position is level, but I believe White should have good chances. Our opponent will try to punish us for this, but when that happens in level positions, the punisher tends to get burned!} d4 {A logical idea to prevent our [e2]-[e4].} 5. e4 {We're throwing the pawn forward anyway!} dxe3 6. Qc3 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gc3h8] Poking the rook around. Black can bid goodbye to any expectations of castling normally.} Rg8 7. Bxe3 Nf5 8. Bf2 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Rf5d4,Rf5e3] The bishop sits well on [f2], covering any of the knight's attempts to intrude. Black has chances of equality here but only by walking a tightrope of only moves.} Nc6 (8... Bg7 9. d4 Nc6 {transposes to 8...Nc6 9.d4 Bg7 .}) 9. d4 Bg7 10. Na3 {We will castle queenside with very good space.} Be6 (10... Ncxd4 $4 {walks into trouble.} 11. O-O-O {and Black will probably lose the knight on [d4].}) 11. O-O-O {[%cal Gf1c4,Gc4b5,Yh1e1] White is in complete control. Next, we want to develop the [f1]-bishop to [c4] or [b5] and bring the king's rook to [e1].} *

