pin but doesn't contest the center.} 10. Nbd2 {, we will castle queenside and then play [Ne4] or [Nc4] with an iron grip.}) 10. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Pinning the knight and undermining the defense of the [b4]-square. Now [Bxc6] is also a legitimate threat.} exd4 (10... e4 {simply drops two pawns.} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qxc6+ Bd7 13. Qxe4+ {+- and White has a winning material advantage.}) 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qxc6+ Bd7 13. Qe4+ {A nice check. The queen will sit well on [e4].} Be7 (13... Qe7 14. Ne5 {⩲ and our queen attacks the rook. We will castle shortly and aim to mobilize the white pieces with [Nd2], [Rfe1], and [Rad1].}) 14. Bxd4 {Why do we take with the bishop rather than the knight? Well, when Black's [f5]-knight gets traded, we want to be covering [f5] with our knight so as to avoid any ...[Bf5] ideas by Black.} Nxd4 15. Nxd4 $16 {[%cal Gd4f5,Rd7f5,Gb1c3,Ge1c1] Black doesn't have ...[Bf5]. We will play [Nc3] and castle queenside with a big advantage. Black has the bishop pair but likely won't be able to utilize it well given the fact that the king is stuck in the center.} *

