pin but doesn't contest the center.} 10. Nbd2 {, we will castle queenside and then play [Ne4] or [Nc4] with an iron grip.}) 10. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Pinning the knight and undermining the defense of the [b4]-square. Now [Bxc6] is also a legitimate threat.} exf4 ({This misses the mark, while} 10... e4 {simply drops two pawns.} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Qxc6+ Bd7 13. Qxe4+ {+- and White has a winning material advantage.}) 11. Bxc6+ {Regaining our lost pawn.} bxc6 12. Qxc6+ Bd7 13. Qe4+ $1 {A very nice check.} Qe7 14. Ne5 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Ge4a8] Black's rook is hanging and the queenside must be compromised with another pawn move if Black wants to maintain castling rights.} c6 15. O-O O-O-O (15... f6 16. Nxd7 $1 {Our queen is protected by a neat fork.} Qxe4 17. Nxf6+ {+- and White will net the full point.}) 16. Nc3 $18 {The knight defends the queen, bypassing any pin issues with ...[f7]-[f6]. Black's king's shelter is insecure and the [f4]-pawn is also loose. If Black tries to hold onto the pawn with something like ...[g6]-[g5], we should look for a way to break through quickly and energetically on the queenside.} *

