1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} Nh6 {(to transpose in over-the-board blitz games. Black treats our position like White does in the Dutch which resembles a reversed Bird and follows the classic plan of installing the knight in front of our f-pawn. Fortunately, we are a tempo up on those positions.)} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. d3 g6 {Black prepares a kingside fianchetto to complement the knight on [f5]. Here 3 moves keep equality; one looks hideous and will certainly get a rise out of your unsuspecting opponent.} 4. Qd2 $3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Rd8d2,Gc1d2] The point is quite simple: when we play [e2]-[e4] we want to be able to meet the queen trade with a recapture by our bishop rather than our king if the queen is on [d1], when we would lose castling rights. No one has played this seemingly ridiculous move understandably, and here on move 4 we stand on the frontier. The position is level, but I believe White should have good chances. Our opponent will try to punish us for this, but when that happens in level positions, the punisher tends to get burned!} Bg7 5. e4 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Ge4f5] Pushing forward! The knight on [h6] already begins to feel some heat.} O-O 6. h3 {[%csl Rh6] This locks the knight away on [h6].} Nc6 7. g4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4,Gg4,Gh3][%cal Ye7e5,Yf4f5] Seizing an enormous swath of kingside territory. The central point is that if Black tries to open the center with ...[e7]-[e5], we can force through [f4]-[f5], sealing the center shut with the [h6]-knight entombed.} dxe4 8. dxe4 Qxd2+ {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gg7b2,Rc1d2] Remember to not recapture on [d2] with the bishop here!} 9. Nbxd2 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gg4g5] Now [g5] threatens to immediately trap the [h6]-pony.} f6 {[%cal Gh6f7] Clearing the [f7]-square for the wayward steed.} 10. Nb1 {The knight is best placed on [c3] and so must return to home base momentarily.} Bd7 (10... Nb4 {, the threat to [c2] looks serious.} 11. Rh2 {± dodges the danger. White will continue with [Nc3], [Be3], and [O-O-O] with great control over the position.}) 11. Nc3 {Simple development.} e5 12. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Ge5f4,Gd2f4] The tension is not scary for us. We would be happy to recapture on [f4] with the bishop and begin targeting the weakness on [c7].} *

