1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} Nh6 {(to transpose in over-the-board blitz games. Black treats our position like White does in the Dutch which resembles a reversed Bird and follows the classic plan of installing the knight in front of our f-pawn. Fortunately, we are a tempo up on those positions.)} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. d3 g6 {Black prepares a kingside fianchetto to complement the knight on [f5]. Here 3 moves keep equality; one looks hideous and will certainly get a rise out of your unsuspecting opponent.} 4. Qd2 $3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Rd8d2,Gc1d2] The point is quite simple: when we play [e2]-[e4] we want to be able to meet the queen trade with a recapture by our bishop rather than our king if the queen is on [d1], when we would lose castling rights. No one has played this seemingly ridiculous move understandably, and here on move 4 we stand on the frontier. The position is level, but I believe White should have good chances. Our opponent will try to punish us for this, but when that happens in level positions, the punisher tends to get burned!} Bg7 5. e4 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Ge4f5] Pushing forward! The knight on [h6] already begins to feel some heat.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gg7d4] Gripping in on the [d4]-square.} 6. h3 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Ge4f5,Gh3g4] Locking the [h6]-knight out.} O-O 7. Nc3 {Calling Black's bluff − do we want to go the endgame, or what?!?!?!?!} d4 ({After} 7... dxe4 8. dxe4 Qxd2+ 9. Bxd2 {± , White will castle queenside and establish positional dominance with [g2]-[g4]. The position already verges on winning. The [h6]-knight is simply too bad, and simple threats on the queenside like [Nd5] or [Nb5] could become lethal at any moment.}) 8. Ne2 {[%cal Gc2c3] We have to separate plans here. To go for [g4], [Ng3], and [Qg2] with a strangely advantageous King's Indian structure, or [c2]-[c3] to get the knight immediately back into prime real estate on [c3].} f6 {Clearing the [f7]-square for the wayward [h6]-knight.} 9. g4 Nf7 {[%cal Gg7h6] Here we must be careful to choose the right path forward. Black now has the option of ...[Bh6].} 10. c3 $1 (10. Ng3 $6 {would be ill-timed.} Bh6 {, preparing ...[e7]-[e5]. Following} 11. Qg2 a5 {, Black has good control of the dark squares and can aim for ...[e5] in the future, when White will likely have to trade dark-squared bishops, leading to an inferior version of a King's Indian in which our dark squares, in particular [f4] and [e3], would be weak. While the computer insists it's close to equal, to my eyes Black has a distinct practical edge.}) 10... dxc3 11. Nxc3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gd3d4] We have ideas of [d4], making connect 4 on the 4th rank.} Qd6 12. d4 {This position looks great, but Black has a precise sequence of computer moves to hold the balance.} e5 13. d5 {The classic response.} Ne7 14. fxe5 Nxe5 ({In case of} 14... fxe5 15. Bc4 {(, White has a classic advantage due to the extra space and the fact that a black knight not a black queen belongs) on [d6].}) 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Qf4 $16 {[%csl Rc7,Re7,Gd5,Ge4] Trading queens on [e5] and playing [Be3] with a great endgame. The [c7]-pawn is a latent weakness in Black's position given its placement on White's open file. Meanwhile, the [e7]-knight is also a sight for sore eyes, being dominated by the [e4]/[d5]-pawn tree completely.} *

