1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} Nh6 {(to transpose in over-the-board blitz games. Black treats our position like White does in the Dutch which resembles a reversed Bird and follows the classic plan of installing the knight in front of our f-pawn. Fortunately, we are a tempo up on those positions.)} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. d3 g6 {Black prepares a kingside fianchetto to complement the knight on [f5]. Here 3 moves keep equality; one looks hideous and will certainly get a rise out of your unsuspecting opponent.} 4. Qd2 $3 {[%cal Ge2e4,Rd8d2,Gc1d2] The point is quite simple: when we play [e2]-[e4] we want to be able to meet the queen trade with a recapture by our bishop rather than our king if the queen is on [d1], when we would lose castling rights. No one has played this seemingly ridiculous move understandably, and here on move 4 we stand on the frontier. The position is level, but I believe White should have good chances. Our opponent will try to punish us for this, but when that happens in level positions, the punisher tends to get burned!} Bg7 5. e4 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Ge4f5] Pushing forward! The knight on [h6] already begins to feel some heat.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gg7d4] Gripping in on the [d4]-square.} 6. h3 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Ge4f5,Gh3g4] Locking the [h6]-knight out.} O-O 7. Nc3 {Calling Black's bluff − do we want to go the endgame, or what?!?!?!?!} d4 ({After} 7... dxe4 8. dxe4 Qxd2+ 9. Bxd2 {± , White will castle queenside and establish positional dominance with [g2]-[g4]. The position already verges on winning. The [h6]-knight is simply too bad, and simple threats on the queenside like [Nd5] or [Nb5] could become lethal at any moment.}) 8. Ne2 {[%cal Gc2c3] We have to separate plans here. To go for [g4], [Ng3], and [Qg2] with a strangely advantageous King's Indian structure, or [c2]-[c3] to get the knight immediately back into prime real estate on [c3].} f6 {Clearing the [f7]-square for the wayward [h6]-knight.} 9. g4 Nf7 {[%cal Gg7h6] Here we must be careful to choose the right path forward. Black now has the option of ...[Bh6].} 10. c3 $1 (10. Ng3 $6 {would be ill-timed.} Bh6 {, preparing ...[e7]-[e5]. Following} 11. Qg2 a5 {, Black has good control of the dark squares and can aim for ...[e5] in the future, when White will likely have to trade dark-squared bishops, leading to an inferior version of a King's Indian in which our dark squares, in particular [f4] and [e3], would be weak. While the computer insists it's close to equal, to my eyes Black has a distinct practical edge.}) 10... dxc3 11. Nxc3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gd3d4] We have ideas of [d4], making connect 4 on the 4th rank.} Qd6 12. d4 {This position looks great, but Black has a precise sequence of computer moves to hold the balance.} e5 13. d5 {The classic response.} Nd4 $1 {Sacrificing a pawn to open things up.} 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Qxd4 f5 {Unleashing the [g7]-dragon.} 16. e5 Nxe5 $1 {Again the only move to keep the pot cooking.} (16... Re8 17. Kd1 {± and Black better sacrifice on [e5] immediately to stay in the game. If Black allows the pawns to remain on [e5] and [d5], White will stabilize development with [Be3], [Bd3], and [Kc2], with a winning advantage − [d5] and [e5] simply grant us too much SPACE!}) 17. fxe5 Bxe5 18. Qc4 $13 {White is up a piece, but the king will likely run around the board. Both sides must play precisely − the computer gives White 0.05 according to best play, but this could slip immediately to winning since if White can ever coordinate successfully, the extra piece will mean the difference. The odds of anyone reaching this position are 1 in a billion. I don't expect us to see this position on the board in my lifetime.} *

