3] We have to separate plans here. To go for [g4], [Ng3], and [Qg2] with a strangely advantageous King's Indian structure, or [c2]-[c3] to get the knight immediately back into prime real estate on [c3].} f6 {Clearing the [f7]-square for the wayward [h6]-knight.} 9. g4 Nf7 {[%cal Gg7h6] Here we must be careful to choose the right path forward. Black now has the option of ...[Bh6].} 10. c3 $1 (10. Ng3 $6 {would be ill-timed.} Bh6 {, preparing ...[e7]-[e5]. Following} 11. Qg2 a5 {, Black has good control of the dark squares and can aim for ...[e5] in the future, when White will likely have to trade dark-squared bishops, leading to an inferior version of a King's Indian in which our dark squares, in particular [f4] and [e3], would be weak. While the computer insists it's close to equal, to my eyes Black has a distinct practical edge.}) 10... dxc3 11. Nxc3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4,Gg4][%cal Gd3d4] We have ideas of [d4], making connect 4 on the 4th rank.} Bd7 12. Qf2 (12. d4 {wouldn't be great now due to} e5 13. d5 Nd4 $1 {, launching into the center for maximum activity. (13...Ne7!?= , since Black's [f7]-knight has the [d6]-square available, these structures with the [d4]-[d5] advance are also fine for Black. Unlike the positions with the queen on [d6], the knight can immediately aim for this maneuver. )} 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Qxd4 f5 {, opening up the board.} 16. e5 Nxe5 17. fxe5 Bxe5 {∞ and the bishop on [e5] cannot be recaptured on account of Black's ...[Rf8]-[e8] pin. The position is balanced. White has an extra piece but a very weak king, making for much momentous mayhem.}) 12... e5 13. f5 $16 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ge1c1,Yd3d4] White will catch up in development with [Be3], [O-O-O] and eventually break open the position with [d3]-[d4]. White's impressive phalanx secures us more space and restricts the [d7]-bishop well.} *

