1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} c6 {This is chosen 3% of the time. Black immediately reinforces the [d5]-pawn in spite of it not yet being challenged by White.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Nf6 (3... Nf6 4. Be2 {looks normal, but then Black could play} Bf5 $1 {and sidestep our annoying plan of [d2]-[d3] and [Qe2], which is how we meet 3...Bf5 . This is covered in the course The Chebanenko Slav by Alex Colovic.}) 4. c4 ({This leads to really unique positions. If they are not to your taste, feel free to play more standard things like} 4. Be2 {or 4.d3 .}) 4... Bg4 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Nc3 {[%cal Gd1b3] Choo choo, all aboard the [Qb3] train! [b7] is weak and a perfect vulnerability in Black's structure.} e6 7. Qb3 Qc7 8. Ne5 $5 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Ge5g4,Ge5c6,Yf1b5] The position is crazy. Our development is really stalled − just look at our [c1]-bishop and picture how long it will take to escape. We will throw the bishop to [b5] next, when Black will have some questions to answer. The position is level and whoever knows it better will enjoy a huge practical advantage. I think the chances of reaching this position are essentially 0 so I will end the variation here. Good luck!} *

