1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} c6 {This is chosen 3% of the time. Black immediately reinforces the [d5]-pawn in spite of it not yet being challenged by White.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Nf6 (3... Nf6 4. Be2 {looks normal, but then Black could play} Bf5 $1 {and sidestep our annoying plan of [d2]-[d3] and [Qe2], which is how we meet 3...Bf5 . This is covered in the course The Chebanenko Slav by Alex Colovic.}) 4. c4 ({This leads to really unique positions. If they are not to your taste, feel free to play more standard things like} 4. Be2 {or 4.d3 .}) 4... e6 {Black adopts the classic Triangle System against our [c4]/[f4] Bird hybrid. It is only move 4 and yet only 1290 games have ever reached this position. For reference, the database has 19 million games.} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] The bishop will go to [b2].} Be7 6. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2h8]} O-O 7. Be2 {This position is objectively equal, but that tends to mean extremely double-edged when the structure is this unorthodox. The game is equal if Black continues with ...[b6], ...[a6], or ...[c5]. The most common move, however, is the natural development of the [b8]-knight.} Nbd7 8. O-O b6 9. g4 $1 {We'd love to play [g4]-[g5] to kick the knight out of [f6] and claim a good amount of space.} Nxg4 $6 {This just makes White's advantage bigger.} 10. Nd4 {[%csl Rc6,Rg4]} Nh6 11. Nxc6 Qe8 12. Nxe7+ {Snagging the great dark-squared bishop.} Qxe7 13. Ba3 {[%cal Ga3f8]} Nc5 14. d4 Qf6 {[%cal Gf6a1] Protecting the knight through the pin against the [d4]-pawn and [a1]-rook.} 15. Nd2 Nf5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gf5e3]} 16. Rf3 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Rf8] The dust has cleared and Black's threats have fizzled out. Black will now have to move the [c5]-knight finally and cede the exchange.} *

