1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} c6 {This is chosen 3% of the time. Black immediately reinforces the [d5]-pawn in spite of it not yet being challenged by White.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Nf6 (3... Nf6 4. Be2 {looks normal, but then Black could play} Bf5 $1 {and sidestep our annoying plan of [d2]-[d3] and [Qe2], which is how we meet 3...Bf5 . This is covered in the course The Chebanenko Slav by Alex Colovic.}) 4. c4 ({This leads to really unique positions. If they are not to your taste, feel free to play more standard things like} 4. Be2 {or 4.d3 .}) 4... Bf5 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb3b7]} Qc7 7. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5] Attacking [d5].} e6 8. Nd4 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gd4f5] Nxf5 would mark a wonderful deal, getting the two bishops and destroying their structure.} Bg6 9. f5 $1 {Adding a drop of chaos to the position.} exf5 ({After} 9... Bxf5 10. Nxf5 exf5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 {∞ , the game is similarly chaotic. We are first to the punch with [Bb5], but Black's structure is much better. We have the bishop pair, but [d2] and [e3] could become huge weaknesses − the game is dynamically equal.}) 10. Nxd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 $13 {[%cal Gf1b5,Ge1g1] The computer insists this is equal, but I think nearly everyone would rather be the person about to throw the bishop to [b5].} *

