1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} c6 {This is chosen 3% of the time. Black immediately reinforces the [d5]-pawn in spite of it not yet being challenged by White.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Bf5 {This is chosen 20% of the time. It just seems to be a worse version of 2...Nf6 3.e3 Bf5 . We will adopt a similar plan to the one employed there, with the focus revolving around the achievement of the [e3]-[e4] push.} 4. d3 e6 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {will simply transpose, as Black will just continue here with} e6 {.}) 5. Nc3 {[%cal Ge3e4]} Nf6 6. h3 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4] Creating ideas of [g2]-[g4] to harass the bishop.} Bb4 7. a3 $1 {We should happily accept the trade with open arms. The dark-squared bishop is the prime rib of Black's position. Black's pawn chain wouldn't make sense if they were gonna trade it for our knight.} Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 h6 9. g4 Bh7 10. Bg2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Ga3a4,Gc1a3] We will castle, and activate the [c1]-sleeper via [a3]-[a4] and [Ba3].} *

