1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} c6 {This is chosen 3% of the time. Black immediately reinforces the [d5]-pawn in spite of it not yet being challenged by White.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Bf5 {This is chosen 20% of the time. It just seems to be a worse version of 2...Nf6 3.e3 Bf5 . We will adopt a similar plan to the one employed there, with the focus revolving around the achievement of the [e3]-[e4] push.} 4. d3 e6 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {will simply transpose, as Black will just continue here with} e6 {.}) 5. Nc3 {[%cal Ge3e4]} Nf6 6. h3 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4] Creating ideas of [g2]-[g4] to harass the bishop.} Bb4 7. a3 $1 {We should happily accept the trade with open arms. The dark-squared bishop is the prime rib of Black's position. Black's pawn chain wouldn't make sense if they were gonna trade it for our knight.} Ba5 8. g4 {Closing in on the [f5]-bishop.} Bg6 9. Bg2 O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 {Continuing normal development and contesting our simple idea of [Nf3]-[e5].} 11. Qe2 $14 {The position remains complex but regardless, Stockfish asserts White has a serious edge. We want to slowly close the walls in on the [g6]-bishop. Ideally, we'd play [e3]-[e4] and [f4]-[f5]. Our structure is healthy and if Black contorts their way out of this immediate entrapment, we can still count on a healthy space advantage.} *

