1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} c6 {This is chosen 3% of the time. Black immediately reinforces the [d5]-pawn in spite of it not yet being challenged by White.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Bf5 {This is chosen 20% of the time. It just seems to be a worse version of 2...Nf6 3.e3 Bf5 . We will adopt a similar plan to the one employed there, with the focus revolving around the achievement of the [e3]-[e4] push.} 4. d3 e6 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 {will simply transpose, as Black will just continue here with} e6 {.}) 5. Nc3 {[%cal Ge3e4]} Nf6 6. h3 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4] Creating ideas of [g2]-[g4] to harass the bishop.} Bd6 $6 {This turns out to just be badly placed. Because the [b8]-knight will eventually head to [d7], we will have tricks associated with our queen's x-ray of the bishop.} 7. g4 Bg6 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Kh1 {[%cal Rb6g1] Avoiding any checks on the diagonal. This will be relevant in some of the variations to come.} h6 {This move has to be played sooner or later, as [e3]-[e4] and [f4]-[f5] were going to be played.} 11. e4 $1 dxe4 12. dxe4 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd1d6] Knock, knock! The [d6]-bishop is hanging.} Bc7 13. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gf3e1,Ge1d3,Ge4e5,Yf4f5] We don't want to play [f4]-[f5] too soon, as the [c7]-bishop would look straight into our king's castle. A nice improving plan is [Nf3]-[e1]-[d3]. In this fashion, our knight unlocks the [g2]-bishop and [f1]-rook, which it had obstructed on [f3]; [f4]-[f5] will be nice to lock the [g6]-bishop out, but [e4]-[e5] might be even better to stunt the [d7]-knight and [c7]-bishop.} *

