1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} c6 {This is chosen 3% of the time. Black immediately reinforces the [d5]-pawn in spite of it not yet being challenged by White.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 Bg4 {The chances of this transposing into some form of the ...[Bg4] variations analyzed in the main chapters is high. So the coverage of these positions will be limited.} 4. Be2 {Our bishop cushions the pin. We are happy to meet ...[Bxf3] with [Bxf3].} Nd7 {This sneaky knight move is the most aggressive of Black's options despite appearances. Black wants to save a move by playing ...[e5] without wasting any time on ...[e6].} (4... e6 5. O-O Nf6 6. b3 Nbd7 7. c4 {will likely transpose to the 4…Nf6 variation.}) ({After} 4... Bxf3 5. Bxf3 {⇆ , we get the bishop pair but the position is still level since Black will play ...[e7]-[e6] erecting a structure perfectly against our light-squared bishop. We will castle kingside and then play for our pick of [c2]-[c4], [d2]-[d4], or [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4].}) 5. O-O Bxf3 6. Bxf3 e5 {Here we can play either [d3] or [d4] to maintain even chances in a complicated structure. Taking on [e5] is also fine.} 7. d4 $5 {[%cal Ge3d4,Ge3f4,Re5d4,Re5f4] My personal favorite. Now ...[exf4] will be met by [exf4] and ...[exd4] by [exd4].} e4 8. Be2 $13 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc2c4,Gb1c3,Gd1b3] Black has more space, but we have the bishop pair. The structure is that of a reversed French Defense in which Black has played ...[f7]-[f5]. We should play [c2]-[c4], [Nc3], and [Qb3] with interesting pressure against [d5].} *

