1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} g6 {This is played 2% of the time as a 2nd move. This frequency is good for us because Stocky gives some of the most unfavorable evaluations you'll see in the entire Bird's opening. I didn't know it even existed but in several Titled Tuesdays, I kept getting hit by it. So here we are grinding our teeth against the silicon beast looking for good playable positions.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 c5 {This is only played 2% of the time, but it remains one of the best chances for Black to enter a good structure with ...[d5]. Notice that achieving a queenside fianchetto with [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2] will be difficult here, as Black will meet [b3] with ...[Bg7] immediately, poking at the [a1]-mango. This setup with [c5], [d5] and [g6] is what Svidler recommends in his Grünfeld − Part 2 repertoire against the Bird.} 4. Bb5+ {Svidler does not consider this natural check. We pose Black the same old question − of the 3 options, how should the check be blocked?} Nd7 {This is played only 8% of the time.} 5. c4 $5 {This has only been played in 7 games so far. We only venture for this pawn break when the position particularly suits it. Our weakened [d3]-square is not that visible, as Black is blocking the queen and the queen's knight is far from the [b4]-square.} e6 (5... Ngf6 6. Nc3 {∞ and the game is about to get going! If Black advances with ...[d4] now, we will snatch the pawn. Otherwise, we will start central play with [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4].}) 6. Nc3 Ngf6 7. d3 {[%cal Ge3e4] Preparing [e4].} Bg7 8. e4 $13 {[%cal Yd5d4,Yc3e2,Ge4e5,Ge1g1] We have achieved a solid center and will aim to kick the knight with [e4]-[e5] soon enough. If Black boots our knight with ...[d5]-[d4], we will rebound to [e2] and eventually attempt to reroute it via [g3] to [e4] after [e4]-[e5]. I can't honestly say I've seen such a structure before, and experience will be the most important factor for such an unorthodox one. I definitely prefer White, though our edge is only faint objectively.} *

