1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} g6 {This is played 2% of the time as a 2nd move. This frequency is good for us because Stocky gives some of the most unfavorable evaluations you'll see in the entire Bird's opening. I didn't know it even existed but in several Titled Tuesdays, I kept getting hit by it. So here we are grinding our teeth against the silicon beast looking for good playable positions.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 c5 {This is only played 2% of the time, but it remains one of the best chances for Black to enter a good structure with ...[d5]. Notice that achieving a queenside fianchetto with [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2] will be difficult here, as Black will meet [b3] with ...[Bg7] immediately, poking at the [a1]-mango. This setup with [c5], [d5] and [g6] is what Svidler recommends in his Grünfeld − Part 2 repertoire against the Bird.} 4. Bb5+ {Svidler does not consider this natural check. We pose Black the same old question − of the 3 options, how should the check be blocked?} Nc6 {This can be met with the trade on [c6], of course, but Stockfish points out an interesting opportunity in bringing our queen's knight out.} 5. Nc3 $5 Nf6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. Na4 {Our knight immediately glides into the great [a4]-square. We pressure [c5] and pose Black a serious question: if the pawn stays on [c5], how will the [f8]-bishop be able to free itself to go to [g7]?} Nd7 (7... e6 8. b3 Nd7 {, stabilizing the pawn, but at what cost?} 9. Bb2 {, laying waste to the open diagonal.} f6 10. c4 {⩲ , fixing the weakness in place. We will continue with the classic positional grind similar to other discussed positions.}) 8. b3 Bg7 9. Bb2 {[%csl Rc5] And we trade the bishops while keeping the positional crunch on [c5].} Bxb2 10. Nxb2 O-O 11. O-O e6 $2 {This would be natural, but it wouldn't be recommended.} 12. c4 $16 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb2a4,Ga1c1] Fixing the [c5]-pawn in mid air. Our knight will return to [a4] and the rook will glide to [c1]. Black's position is already on the verge of collapse.} *

