1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} g6 {This is played 2% of the time as a 2nd move. This frequency is good for us because Stocky gives some of the most unfavorable evaluations you'll see in the entire Bird's opening. I didn't know it even existed but in several Titled Tuesdays, I kept getting hit by it. So here we are grinding our teeth against the silicon beast looking for good playable positions.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 c5 {This is only played 2% of the time, but it remains one of the best chances for Black to enter a good structure with ...[d5]. Notice that achieving a queenside fianchetto with [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2] will be difficult here, as Black will meet [b3] with ...[Bg7] immediately, poking at the [a1]-mango. This setup with [c5], [d5] and [g6] is what Svidler recommends in his Grünfeld − Part 2 repertoire against the Bird.} 4. Bb5+ {Svidler does not consider this natural check. We pose Black the same old question − of the 3 options, how should the check be blocked?} Nc6 {This can be met with the trade on [c6], of course, but Stockfish points out an interesting opportunity in bringing our queen's knight out.} 5. Nc3 $5 Bg7 $1 ({The only move to keep things balanced.} 5... Bd7 $2 {drops an egg!} 6. Nxd5 $1 {and White is a healthy pawn to the good.}) 6. O-O Nf6 7. d3 $5 {[%cal Ge3e4] Flipping the script and attempting to make sense of the knight on [c3] by introducing the idea of [e3]-[e4].} (7. Bxc6+ $6 {is no longer venomous, as [Na4] wouldn't come with any sting.} bxc6 8. Na4 Nd7 {and compared to the other line with 5...Nf6 , we are not in time to play [Bb2] here.}) 7... O-O 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. e4 $13 {[%cal Gd1e1,Ge1h4,Ge4e5] We have the better structure, but Black does have the potentially powerful bishop pair. We have ideas of [Qe1]-[h4] or [e4]-[e5]. The game is even, but complex.} *

