1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} g6 {This is played 2% of the time as a 2nd move. This frequency is good for us because Stocky gives some of the most unfavorable evaluations you'll see in the entire Bird's opening. I didn't know it even existed but in several Titled Tuesdays, I kept getting hit by it. So here we are grinding our teeth against the silicon beast looking for good playable positions.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 c5 {This is only played 2% of the time, but it remains one of the best chances for Black to enter a good structure with ...[d5]. Notice that achieving a queenside fianchetto with [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2] will be difficult here, as Black will meet [b3] with ...[Bg7] immediately, poking at the [a1]-mango. This setup with [c5], [d5] and [g6] is what Svidler recommends in his Grünfeld − Part 2 repertoire against the Bird.} 4. Bb5+ {Svidler does not consider this natural check. We pose Black the same old question − of the 3 options, how should the check be blocked?} Nc6 {This can be met with the trade on [c6], of course, but Stockfish points out an interesting opportunity in bringing our queen's knight out.} 5. Nc3 $5 Bg7 $1 ({The only move to keep things balanced.} 5... Bd7 $2 {drops an egg!} 6. Nxd5 $1 {and White is a healthy pawn to the good.}) 6. O-O Nf6 7. d3 $5 {[%cal Ge3e4] Flipping the script and attempting to make sense of the knight on [c3] by introducing the idea of [e3]-[e4].} (7. Bxc6+ $6 {is no longer venomous, as [Na4] wouldn't come with any sting.} bxc6 8. Na4 Nd7 {and compared to the other line with 5...Nf6 , we are not in time to play [Bb2] here.}) 7... Bd7 8. e4 $1 {Initiating the tension.} d4 (8... dxe4 9. dxe4 {and the threat of [e4]-[e5] already causes Black big problems.}) 9. Ne2 {The position begins to resemble a King's Indian in which we've been gifted several free tempi − this is the natural consequence of playing such a baller opening as the Bird!} a6 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. Ng3 {The knight might look strange here, but it will likely reroute to [e4] after [e4]-[e5].} (11. h3 $5 {is a more thematic way to play the position and also should bring chances of a White advantage. Feel free to study this option more deeply if you resonate more with this.}) 11... O-O 12. Qe2 e6 13. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gg3e4,Ya1e1] We continue to wait for the perfect moment to play [e4]-[e5]. Keep in mind that we've intentionally waited as we've made two useful moves with the queen and the bishop. As soon as we play [e5], the black knight will be able to come to [d5] and their plans will likely become much more clear, so in the meantime, we continue to build up. We can play [e5] next or continue stirring the pot with [Rae1].} *

