1. f4 d5 {Black counters with the d-pawn, gaining good control over the central light squares.} 2. Nf3 {Here we will look at rare 2nd moves.} g6 {This is played 2% of the time as a 2nd move. This frequency is good for us because Stocky gives some of the most unfavorable evaluations you'll see in the entire Bird's opening. I didn't know it even existed but in several Titled Tuesdays, I kept getting hit by it. So here we are grinding our teeth against the silicon beast looking for good playable positions.} (2... Bg4 3. e3 {will transpose to other chapters that cover ...[Bg4] in the ...[d5] systems.}) (2... Bf5 3. e3 {will transpose to other ...[d5] systems in which ...[Bf5] is essayed later on. This is covered in other chapters.}) 3. e3 c5 {This is only played 2% of the time, but it remains one of the best chances for Black to enter a good structure with ...[d5]. Notice that achieving a queenside fianchetto with [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2] will be difficult here, as Black will meet [b3] with ...[Bg7] immediately, poking at the [a1]-mango. This setup with [c5], [d5] and [g6] is what Svidler recommends in his Grünfeld − Part 2 repertoire against the Bird.} 4. Bb5+ {Svidler does not consider this natural check. We pose Black the same old question − of the 3 options, how should the check be blocked?} Bd7 {By far the most popular response, being chosen in over 60% of encounters.} 5. Bxd7+ {This is such an unlikely position to occur, so I will only cover this move. Check the alternatives if you want to keep extra Tabasco on the table.} (5. Qe2 $5 {looks like a reversed Bogo-Indian where we've gotten the free [f4] move in. This free tempo is not simple to evaluate though, as the [f4]-pawn is as bad in this position as it is good. For instance, after the eventual thematic [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4], our [c1]-bishop will then just be blocked by [f4].}) (5. a4 $5 {also keeps a bit of tension in the position. White hopes to recapture on [b5] with [a4], when the pawn will wedge out the [b8]-knight from [c6] − classic domination! Though, I should mention that Stockfish is convinced that Black has a faint edge after} Bg7 {⩱ .}) 5... Qxd7 $1 {The better of the two recaptures. The black knight will now be able to come to the better [c6]-square. Similar to the lines in the French where we played [Bb5]+ and [Bxd7], we are just equal after the queen recapture. Equal doesn't mean boring though, and we can most certainly bring our opponents into a complicated mess.} 6. Ne5 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Ge5d7,Yd7d6,Yd7e6,Yd7c7,Yd7c8] Hopping in with a tempo. This move is likely what Black players are afraid of when they choose to opt for 5...Nxd7 . The queen can retreat to any of the yellow options to keep the game balanced. We will analyze the two most popular continuations: ...[Qc7] and ...[Qe6].} Qe6 {This is played 17% of the time and holds the esteemed honor of being the second most popular move in this position. The placement of the queen might seem bizarre, but it is actually quite harmonious. It won't be in the way of any pieces and the [f8]-bishop will go to [g7], making the pawn on [e7] perfectly fine by remaining where it is. Here we have the choice between 2 spicy options.} 7. Qe2 $5 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2b5] Introducing the idea of a scary check on [b5]. In the one game that reached this position, Black played the correct ...[a6] to avoid this. You may not like the positions that arise if Black plays perfectly and if that's the case, feel free to check out the alternative.} (7. c4 $5 {prepares [Qa4]+ and a trade on [d7], so it will likely transpose to the variations after 6...Qc7. For instance} dxc4 8. Qa4+ Nd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 11. Na3 {and we've transposed back to the 6...Qc7 variation.}) 7... Nc6 8. Qb5 {[%csl Rb7,Rc5][%cal Gb5c5,Gb5b7]} ({Attacking 2 vulnerable pawns. Remember, trading with} 8. Nxc6 $2 {just leads to a simply worse position after} Qxc6 {. We have talked about this elsewhere and here once again it is the same old song. White has no logical plan of development for the bishop, as [b2]–b3 is met by ...[Bg7]. Also, we've traded off our good pieces, making this a simply bad classical Dutch.}) 8... Rc8 {We should snatch the pawn here, but precise play will be required to keep the game steady.} (8... Nf6 9. Qxb7 {transposes to the 7...Nf6 move order.}) (8... Rb8 9. Qxc5 {± and White nets a pawn. Without this pawn, we will be able to easily assert control of the dark squares, particularly the critical [d4]-square. Black no longer has the classic crunch of ...[d5]-[d4].}) 9. Qxb7 Bg7 10. Nxc6 Rxc6 11. Qxa7 f5 $1 {Compared to similar variations after ...[Nf6], this one is more complex and less clear. Black gets a lot of space in the center and we can give up on ever hoping for [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4].} (11... Nf6 {transposes to the 7...Nf6 variation.}) 12. Qa4 Nf6 13. O-O O-O 14. c3 $13 {[%cal Ga4c2,Gd2d3,Gd3d4] We are up 2 pawns, but Mr. Stockfish only gives us 0.14. Black has enormous compensation obviously. We need to slowly and carefully untangle the queenside with moves like [Qc2] and [d2]-[d3] or [d2]-[d4].} *

