-knight from [c6] − classic domination! Though, I should mention that Stockfish is convinced that Black has a faint edge after} Bg7 {⩱ .}) 5... Qxd7 $1 {The better of the two recaptures. The black knight will now be able to come to the better [c6]-square. Similar to the lines in the French where we played [Bb5]+ and [Bxd7], we are just equal after the queen recapture. Equal doesn't mean boring though, and we can most certainly bring our opponents into a complicated mess.} 6. Ne5 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Ge5d7,Yd7d6,Yd7e6,Yd7c7,Yd7c8] Hopping in with a tempo. This move is likely what Black players are afraid of when they choose to opt for 5...Nxd7 . The queen can retreat to any of the yellow options to keep the game balanced. We will analyze the two most popular continuations: ...[Qc7] and ...[Qe6].} Qe6 {This is played 17% of the time and holds the esteemed honor of being the second most popular move in this position. The placement of the queen might seem bizarre, but it is actually quite harmonious. It won't be in the way of any pieces and the [f8]-bishop will go to [g7], making the pawn on [e7] perfectly fine by remaining where it is. Here we have the choice between 2 spicy options.} 7. Qe2 $5 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2b5] Introducing the idea of a scary check on [b5]. In the one game that reached this position, Black played the correct ...[a6] to avoid this. You may not like the positions that arise if Black plays perfectly and if that's the case, feel free to check out the alternative.} (7. c4 $5 {prepares [Qa4]+ and a trade on [d7], so it will likely transpose to the variations after 6...Qc7. For instance} dxc4 8. Qa4+ Nd7 9. Nxd7 Qxd7 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 11. Na3 {and we've transposed back to the 6...Qc7 variation.}) 7... a6 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] The best move by far. Black prevents [Qb5]+ and prepares to play ...[Nc6] to exchange our [e5]-knight as planned.} 8. d3 {[%cal Ge3e4] Slowly but surely preparing to build the monolith with [e3]-[e4].} Nc6 {Here we have to make the saddest chop of the course. We won't be ruining their structure in the slightest, unfortunately.} 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 10. e4 Nf6 11. Nd2 (11. e5 $6 {The boot is a bit inaccurate here. After} Nh5 12. O-O Ng7 $1 {∞ , Black will continue with ...[e6], ...[Be7], ...[h7]-[h5] and ...[Nf5]. Black has great control over the light squares and our pawn play has come to a standstill. While the position is still playable, it definitely looks more fun and straightforward for Black.}) 11... Bg7 12. e5 $1 {Compare this to the note after 11.e5 . Here Black will not be able to get the setup with ...[Be7] and ...[Ng7] easily, so White has chances of an edge.} Nh5 13. O-O {[%cal Rh5f4,Gf1f4,Gg2g4] Defending the threat to [f4] while developing, what more could we ask for??? Now [g2]-[g4] is already a serious threat to trap the knight.} f5 {On the one hand, we can no longer play [g2]-[g4]...} 14. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Ge5,Rg7,Rh5][%cal Gc1e3,Ya2a3,Yb2b4] But on the other hand, our pawn on [e5] will stand tall for the rest of the game. Black can never undermine it with ...[d7]-[d6] or ...[f7]-[f6] and so their minor pieces will suffer greatly. We should attempt to create some weaknesses on the queenside with moves like [Be3], [a2]-[a3], and [b2]-[b4]. Black will struggle to get their minor pieces to be relevant in that sector and so any structural opening over there should benefit us.} *

