rse. We won't be ruining their structure in the slightest, unfortunately.} 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 10. e4 Nf6 11. Nd2 (11. e5 $6 {The boot is a bit inaccurate here. After} Nh5 12. O-O Ng7 $1 {∞ , Black will continue with ...[e6], ...[Be7], ...[h7]-[h5] and ...[Nf5]. Black has great control over the light squares and our pawn play has come to a standstill. While the position is still playable, it definitely looks more fun and straightforward for Black.}) 11... Bg7 12. e5 $1 {Compare this to the note after 11.e5 . Here Black will not be able to get the setup with ...[Be7] and ...[Ng7] easily, so White has chances of an edge.} Nd7 13. O-O O-O (13... f6 $1 {was required to maintain the balance.} 14. Nf3 fxe5 15. fxe5 O-O 16. c3 {, if we had time for [d3]-[d4], we would be better, as Black would have another subpar French Defense. Here, however, Black can throw a banana peel on the race track with} d4 $1 {∞ and the game is simply spicy! Both sides have weaknesses. We should aim to finish development quickly with something like [Bd2] or [Bg5] and [Rae1]. The game is balanced and complicated − good luck, or as the French say, bonne chance!}) 14. c3 $14 {[%cal Gd3d4,Gd2f3] We will play [Nd2]-[f3] and [d3]-[d4] with a healthy space advantage. Black will have a bad version of the French Defense, as the bishop should be placed on [e7] with the e-pawn on [e6]. It's also advantageous that our pawn is already on [f4], as we will be able to generate play on the kingside with [g2]-[g4] and [f4]-[f5] a lot quicker than usual.} *

