o follow a precise path to secure the edge.} 10. Nxc6 Rxc6 11. Qxa7 {NSS: Never stop snacking.} Bg7 $1 {We are up two pawns, but our queen is misplaced and Black could easily play ...[O-O], ...[d5]-[d4], and ...[Nd5], when our position would come under tremendous pressure. However, we have a clever queen sortie to avert this.} 12. Qb8+ Rc8 13. Qb5+ $1 {Continuing to disturb the opponent's coordination. The knight wants to come to [d5] or [e4], but here it is best to misplace it to [d7].} Nd7 (13... Rc6 $6 {The rook is not well placed here. It ties the queen down to its defense, thereby incapacitating her majesty from more active opportunities.} 14. O-O O-O 15. a4 {⩲ and we can begin lifting the a-pawn up the board. We will bring our knight to [c3] and if it's harassed by ...[d5]-[d4], we will keep calm and not fragment the structure but instead reroute it to [g3] via [e2], where it can support [e3]-[e4] or [f4]-[f5].}) 14. O-O O-O 15. Qe2 c4 $1 {Black has a nice bind on our queenside. We should be very careful as to how to eventually open the game. If we do it too haphazardly, Black's active pieces will flood the new weaknesses and quickly restore material equality.} 16. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gd2d4] I have to end the line somewhere. Black has great compensation but even so, it is not commensurate to having 2 pawns, so we are a bit better. The position is genuinely exquisite. White will need to untangle one way or another. Based on the lines the computer is giving here, some legitimate ideas are [f4]-[f5] and after ...[gxf5], [Qe2]-[h5xf5] to recapture the pawn. Another idea is [d2]-[d4] to gradually get the bishop out to [d2]. Obviously, this grand position requires both sides to gain a lot more experience before they can play it with even a modicum of accuracy − good luck!} *

