-knight from [c6] − classic domination! Though, I should mention that Stockfish is convinced that Black has a faint edge after} Bg7 {⩱ .}) 5... Qxd7 $1 {The better of the two recaptures. The black knight will now be able to come to the better [c6]-square. Similar to the lines in the French where we played [Bb5]+ and [Bxd7], we are just equal after the queen recapture. Equal doesn't mean boring though, and we can most certainly bring our opponents into a complicated mess.} 6. Ne5 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Ge5d7,Yd7d6,Yd7e6,Yd7c7,Yd7c8] Hopping in with a tempo. This move is likely what Black players are afraid of when they choose to opt for 5...Nxd7 . The queen can retreat to any of the yellow options to keep the game balanced. We will analyze the two most popular continuations: ...[Qc7] and ...[Qe6].} Qc7 {Black's favorite continuation, being chosen in 41% of games to reach here.} 7. c4 $1 {[%cal Gd1a4] Opening the lane for our queen to come to [a4] while initiating pressure again. This has only been seen in one game thus far. There is a wide variety of interesting positions that can be reached from here.} (7. O-O $6 {would be inaccurate, as Black could simply trade off our strong knight with} Nc6 $1 8. Nxc6 Qxc6 {⩱ . We have a classical Dutch structure with our good bishop traded off and with no hope of bringing the other to [b2] on account of Black's ...[Bf8]-[g7]. White is a bit worse.}) 7... d4 {Turning the position into a reversed Benoni.} 8. Qa4+ Nc6 9. d3 {[%cal Ge3e4] We will play [e3]-[e4] next.} Nf6 10. e4 Bg7 (10... Bh6 $1 {is a quirky move that maintains equality. I suspect the idea is to favorably trade the bishops with ...[e7]-[e5] once White's knight on [e5] has moved or been traded.}) 11. O-O O-O $6 {All these moves seem natural, but they hand White a clear edge.} 12. Nxc6 Qxc6 13. Qxc6 bxc6 14. e5 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Rf6][%cal Ge5f6,Gb1d2,Gd2e4] The defense of the [c5]-pawn will be Black's unenviable responsibility for the rest of the game.} *

