-knight from [c6] − classic domination! Though, I should mention that Stockfish is convinced that Black has a faint edge after} Bg7 {⩱ .}) 5... Nxd7 $6 {The weaker of Black's options... but the most popular at a frequency of 70%. As it has been mentioned elsewhere, the black knight should go to [c6] in almost every single position in this course. With the knight on [d7], we have no need to worry about the [d4]-square or any potential ...[d5]-[d4] by Black to break up our structure.} 6. O-O Bg7 7. d3 {[%cal Ge3e4] Preparing [e3]-[e4].} e6 $1 {Only 20% of people find this accurate move.} 8. e4 (8. c4 $5 {∞ is also interesting, with another wacky extremely unorthodox pawn structure.}) 8... Ne7 {Black's knights remind me of Bruce Lee jogging in place, waiting for his opponents to make an incorrect lunge. The central tension is paramount here. Here, [e4]-[e5] is ill advised, as the [e7]-knight will simply swing into the [f5]-square perhaps after a preparatory ...[h7]-[h5]. Black can't really do much with his pawns either... Moving the d-pawn at all will always cede our [b1]-knight the [c4]-square. Importantly, if Black ever plays ...[f7]-[f5], we will happily respond with [e4]-[e5], when Black can neither use the [f5]-square for their knight nor break on our [e5]-nexus with the thematic ...[f7]-[f6].} 9. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga4b5] Controlling the [b5]-square − now if Black's d-pawn ever moves, [c4] will become an effective outpost for our [b1]-knight via [a3] or [d2].} O-O 10. Nc3 {Here, Black must continue to play calmly to keep the tension simmering on. Any anxious move in the center will be swiftly punished.} f5 $2 (10... Nb8 $1 {∞ , the knight slowly reroutes to the correct [c6]-square where it will pressure [d4]. 10...a6!? ∞ , fighting for the control of [b5] is another sound idea.}) (10... d4 $6 {pops the tension in the center like a balloon. Black has no way to challenge our central light squares after this.} 11. Nb5 {, our knight will revolve to the healthy [c4]-square and we will look to crunch on the [g7]-bishop with [e4]-[e5] at the right moment. We don't want to advance it recklessly, as Black's knight will get the [d5] and [f5]-squares.}) 11. e5 {[%csl Rd7,Ge5,Gf4,Rg7] The [d7]-knight and [g7]-bishop are placed in the rubbish bin. We can play for an initiative on the queenside, as Black's pieces are not well placed to meet such an offensive operation and the [d4]-square is potentially vulnerable.} Re8 {Clearing the way for the bishop to reroute to [f8].} 12. Ne2 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge2d4,Gf3d4]} Bf8 13. c3 Nc6 14. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gh2h3,Gg2g4] Black has set up a reasonable defense, but we still have some healthy pressure. We can play for an eventual [b2]-[b4] to dominate the [d4]-square or launch an assault on the kingside with [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4] to gain space.} *

