[Black "Introduction to 1...c5 Systems"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "5"]
[GameId "2127765603701878"]

1. f4 c5 {Black pushes the c-pawn 2 squares. Perhaps Black wasn't really looking and thought that we had pushed our e-pawn 2 squares, to which they were responding with a Sicilian Defense. This ...[c5] move is very tricky and mischievous. White's made it clear we want a chaotic game with this Bird bedlam, but Black is still hoping to return to theory if White plays [e4]. ...[c5] is only played 10% of the time, which is why the bulk of this course is geared toward dealing with Black's exponentially more popular ...[d5] systems. I want to state the arising positions are just as tough for us as those against the ...[d5] systems. While we will get decent positions, it will be critical for us to rigorously study the theory so that we will know the resulting positions better than our opponent.} 2. Nf3 {Though we can choose between many different setups, we will aim to follow this with [e2]-[e3] whenever possible. This is for a few reasons: It is objectively one of the best ways to handle such positions. It is easy to remember since it is the same setup we employ against ...[d5]. This will make any ...[d5] push by Black immediately transpose back into our Bird vs. ...[d5]. It keeps the game more tense and less boring. The ensuing structures can get quite interesting and throughout working on this section I regularly came across structures I had never seen before in my 23 years of playing! There are a few positions in which other moves would be better for White but for the most part, I have built the repertoire around [e3]. I will mention those situations as they occur. It should be stated that we could go for setups involving [e2]-[e4] which would likely transpose to the Grand Prix Attack of the Sicilian Defense. I didn't go this way for a few reasons: Many courses have been done on the Grand Prix, including by the GingerGM himself. To be comprehensive, it would have to be much too meaty for what it's worth. The chances of your opponent responding with ...[c5] are 15-20% of those of them playing ...[d5] systems, so even if they are Sicilian players against [e4], they will probably not play ...[c5] against our Bird. I will mention whenever possible, if we can transpose into the GingerGM's fascinating British Grand Prix Attack repertoire.} Nc6 {This is by far the most popular 2nd move for Black, being played 46% of the time.} ({➢} 2... d6 {is played 16% of the time.} 3. e3 (3. e4 {would bring us into a British Grand Prix Attack.} Nf6 {Nc6} 4. Be2 {, [d2]-[d3] will arrive on the board, with the classic BGPA setup.})) ({4.d3 , White will follow with [Be2], getting the classic setup of the British Grand Prix. 3...Nc6 and here the standard [Bb5] will be met by ...[Bd7], when Black would relish being able to recapture on [c6] with the bishop, when it will scan the wonderful light-squared diagonal. Instead, we will head for peculiar positions with the unorthodox 4.d4!? 3...Nf6 is a less explored but nonetheless valid option. We will aim for murky waters with the cold-hearted 4.Bb5+ . ➢} 2... e6 {is played 12% of the time. It doesn't make much strategic sense since Black could immediately occupy [d5] with a pawn advance − there's not much need to prepare it. Amongst all the positions, this is the one most probably suited to going for a Grand Prix Attack. The ...[e6] move seems a bit slower than the more orthodox setup with pawns on [d6] and [g6].} 3. e3 {, we carry on with [e3] to aim for a more birdy setup; [e4], of course, would have been completely fine. Another reason we play [e3] here is that we play [e3] after 2...Nc6 and so Black could simply trick us into going for [e3] first with 2...Nc6 before opting for ...[e6] setups. We will aim for a queenside fianchetto in the classic heritage of the Bird; ...[d7]-[d5] is extremely natural in such positions and so we will likely transpose back to ...[d5] systems. (3.e4 is another chance for us to head to a British Grand Prix Attack. For example, 3...Nc6 4.Be2 d5 5.d3 with the classic setup. )}) ({➢} 2... Nf6 {is played 2% of the time, yet it is ranked highest by Stockfish. This is probably because rearing our engines with the British Grand Prix is now impossible due to the knight's control over [e4]. We will duly address it, though most likely things will transpose to the other Sicilians after} 3. e3 {.}) ({➢} 2... g6 {, these positions can be quite interesting for the Black player, being played 4% of the time.} 3. e4 {will be the one exclusive time we can aim for the British Grand Prix Attack with [Be2] and [d2]-[d3]. The move order is quite important here. We will likely meet ...[Bg7] with [c2]-[c3] and an eventual [d2]-[d4] with a big pawn center. Black has other options here besides the popular ...[Bg7] and all will be discussed. For instance, if Black immediately plays ...[d5], we could throw in [Bb5]+ to muddy the waters. 3.c3 could lead to interesting play, but I decided against it because if Black plays 3...d5 , we'd have to learn an entirely new setup. 3...Bg7 4.c3 and we attempt to build a big center with an eventual [d2]-[d4] and [e4]-[e5].}) 3. e3 {We will get interesting positions in which [Bb5] will be a common idea. We will probably aim for a queenside fianchetto as well with [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2].} (3. e3 {Black can also play} d6 {or 3...e6 , transposing into 2...e6 and 2...d6 systems.}) (3. e4 {would bring things back to a British Grand Prix Attack, vroom vroom!}) *

