1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... e6 {[%csl Rd6,Re7,Rf6,Rg7,Rh6][%cal Rd7e6,Rf7e6,Rf7g6,Rh7g6] This is a classic positional error that serves as a good lesson in my chess classes with students. When you move a pawn out of the way of your king's bishop, whether it's the pawn on [e7] or [g7], you are weakening squares that the bishop should protect by developing along that diagonal. For instance, ...[e7]-[e6] weakens [d6] and should be met with a bishop developing to [e7] to cover it. Here lies the problem with the 'M' structure of pawns on [d7]-[e6]-[f7]-[g6]-[h7]. There is no way for the [f8]-bishop to both develop and to watch all the weak squares on [d6], [e7], [f6], [g7], and [h6]. In this case, the bishop has moved to [g7], leaving the [d6]-square more vulnerable.} 5. d4 {Seizing the center.} cxd4 (5... Ne7 {has been tried a bit. The d-pawn has been waiting at the dinner table long enough.} 6. dxc5 {± , time to dig in! The [c5]-pawn grips the [d6]-square with the glove of destiny. We will defend the pawn with [Be3] and enjoy the material while our central control remains unperturbed. A simple plan would be [Be3], [Bc4], [O-O] and eventually, [Be3]-[d4] to trade the only good piece in Black's position: the [g7]-bishop.}) 6. cxd4 Ne7 {This is the only way to make sense of the e6+g6 structure. The knight eyes the center from this more restrained position where, unlike [f6], it doesn't block the [g7]-bishop. One of the central ideas is that the knight can immediately bounce to [f5] if we play [e4]-[e5].} (6... Nf6 $2 {just blocks the bishop on [g7].} 7. Nc3 {, defending the center. We will play [e5] shortly to boot the knight from [f6] and develop normally with a great center.}) 7. Nc3 O-O ({Pushing} 7... d5 {too soon welcomes a stronger [e4]-[e5].} 8. e5 Nf5 {, the knight gets the [f5]-square but that's not everything. The reason this ...[d5] push hurts Black so much is that they can never chip at our space with ...[d7]-[d6].} 9. g4 {, pushing the knight away.} Nh4 10. Be3 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 {± and White has an enormous space advantage. The plan is simple − castle queenside, secure the king with [Kb1], and then throw the h-pawn up the board. Black has enormous practical problems to solve, as both bishops are locked in by the nature of White's space.}) 8. Be3 d6 {Black is best advised to wait with the d-pawn like this.} (8... d5 {, Black threatens to take on [e4], rupturing our structure with weaknesses on the light squares, which Black's pieces would ruthlessly exploit.} 9. e5 Nf5 10. Bf2 {± , the knight will be duly kicked out with [g4], when Black suffers from an oppressive lack of space. Black's minor pieces will suffer the whole game. Once we are set up properly, breaking through on the kingside should bring about some decisive resolution.}) 9. Bd3 Nbc6 10. Qd2 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1,Ga1c1,Yh1d1] We have a great advantage in space. We will aim to castle kingside, place rooks on [c1] and [d1], and when the moment is right, initiate central tension with [e4]-[e5].} *

