1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... d5 {Black immediately initiates central tension against our [e4]-monolith.} 5. d3 {I love this move, which looks like a silent draw offer. After all, Black can trade on [e4] and trade queens with what looks like a fine endgame.} (5. Bb5+ $5 {is an interesting alternative likely to keep the queens on. If it is more to your taste, feel free to study it for yourself.}) 5... dxe4 $6 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {[%cal Ge4d5,Gf4e5,Ge4f5,Gf4g5] Well, the endgame isn't as easy as it seems! White has several small advantages, which all together constitute something significant. The bishop on [g7] is blunted by our [c3]-pawn. Meanwhile, Black's [c5]-pawn juts out, creating a visible weakness on the light squares around it. Our pieces will naturally find good squares while Black's pieces struggle to find a harmonious setup. Our e- and f-pawns are also nice, controlling a coherent swath of the 5th rank.} Nf6 8. Bb5+ Bd7 (8... Nc6 9. Re1 {would transpose to 7...Nc6 8.Bb5 Nf6 9.Re1 .}) 9. Bxd7+ {[%csl Gc3,Rc5,Rg7][%cal Rg7c3] We trade off the [c8]-bishop because of all Black’s minor pieces, it had the best prospects. Black's [c5]-pawn combined with the [g7]-bishop being blunted by our [c3] concrete, gives us a good positional edge.} Nbxd7 10. Re1 {Securing [e4]. We don't want to block our bishop from [e3] by playing [Nbd2] too soon.} O-O 11. Kc2 {[%csl Gc4,Rd7][%cal Ga2a4,Gb1a3,Ga3c4] The knight on [d7] also looks a bit strange; it's a horse sitting on the d-file highway, and once the cars get over there, it will have to move. We will play [a2]-[a4] and then sit our knight on [c4] with [Nb1]-[a3]-[c4].} *

