1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... d5 {Black immediately initiates central tension against our [e4]-monolith.} 5. d3 {I love this move, which looks like a silent draw offer. After all, Black can trade on [e4] and trade queens with what looks like a fine endgame.} (5. Bb5+ $5 {is an interesting alternative likely to keep the queens on. If it is more to your taste, feel free to study it for yourself.}) 5... dxe4 $6 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {[%cal Ge4d5,Gf4e5,Ge4f5,Gf4g5] Well, the endgame isn't as easy as it seems! White has several small advantages, which all together constitute something significant. The bishop on [g7] is blunted by our [c3]-pawn. Meanwhile, Black's [c5]-pawn juts out, creating a visible weakness on the light squares around it. Our pieces will naturally find good squares while Black's pieces struggle to find a harmonious setup. Our e- and f-pawns are also nice, controlling a coherent swath of the 5th rank.} Nc6 8. Bb5 Bd7 9. Be3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge3c5] We get the harmonious setup. We didn't want to move our knight to [d2] before our bishop on [c1] got out. Our bishop places good pressure on [c5] from here.} Nf6 10. Nbd2 {[%csl Gd2,Ge3][%cal Gd2e4] Now everything is defended. White has a solid edge and Black is already required to find some difficult moves to stay afloat.} b6 $6 ({This compromises the light squares too much.} 10... Bh6 {had to be played, attacking [f4] with the idea of} 11. Bxc5 $2 (11. g3 {would solidify [f4], keeping a slight edge.}) 11... Bxf4 {⩱ , when Black's pieces get the great [e5]-square.}) 11. a4 O-O 12. Ke2 {[%cal Gh1d1]} (12. Ke2 {We will continue with Rhd1. Black can't move a muscle. If Black pushes our bishop with} a6 {, we will simply retreat} 13. Bd3 {⩲ , when both [a6] and [b6] are weakened.}) *

