1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... d5 {Black immediately initiates central tension against our [e4]-monolith.} 5. d3 {I love this move, which looks like a silent draw offer. After all, Black can trade on [e4] and trade queens with what looks like a fine endgame.} (5. Bb5+ $5 {is an interesting alternative likely to keep the queens on. If it is more to your taste, feel free to study it for yourself.}) 5... dxe4 $6 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {[%cal Ge4d5,Gf4e5,Ge4f5,Gf4g5] Well, the endgame isn't as easy as it seems! White has several small advantages, which all together constitute something significant. The bishop on [g7] is blunted by our [c3]-pawn. Meanwhile, Black's [c5]-pawn juts out, creating a visible weakness on the light squares around it. Our pieces will naturally find good squares while Black's pieces struggle to find a harmonious setup. Our e- and f-pawns are also nice, controlling a coherent swath of the 5th rank.} Nc6 8. Bb5 Nf6 9. Re1 {[%csl Ge4] Securing our [e4]-pawn. We don't want to push it any time soon since the [c8]-bishop would relish the new opportunity on [f5]. It won't be easy for us to move our bishop to [e3] since it hangs the [e4]-pawn. No matter, our bishop will simply wait on [c1] while we make other progress.} O-O 10. Bxc6 {Paying homage to the classic chop.} bxc6 11. Kc2 $14 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Gd2b3] White has a much better structure and Black's bishop pair isn't scary. Our knights have very good squares, particularly on [c4]. We will look to develop our knight to [c4] via [d2]-[c4] and if Black stops us with something like ...[Ba6], we can redeploy to [b3] to target the vulnerable [c5]-pawn. Black's position is quite uncomfortable and from a practical standpoint, they are fighting a serious uphill battle.} *

