1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... d5 {Black immediately initiates central tension against our [e4]-monolith.} 5. d3 {I love this move, which looks like a silent draw offer. After all, Black can trade on [e4] and trade queens with what looks like a fine endgame.} (5. Bb5+ $5 {is an interesting alternative likely to keep the queens on. If it is more to your taste, feel free to study it for yourself.}) 5... Nc6 {The more sober path but almost no Black player can play such a patient reserved move.} 6. Be2 d4 {Initiating tension against our [c3]-pawn.} 7. O-O {[%csl Yb1,Yc4][%cal Ga2a4,Yb1a3,Ya3c4] Keeping the position nice and steady. The position is complex and balanced. We should aim to secure the queenside light squares with [a2]-[a4] and then play [Nb1]-[a3]-[c4] at the right time. We need to take care that this doesn't hang the [c3]-pawn. Regarding the tension between [c3] and [d4], we do not want to budge. The [c3]-pawn should stay where it is to keep control over the [d4]-square.} *

