1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... d6 5. d4 cxd4 {This is the most popular, being played 72% of the time. Luckily for us, it's an instructive mistake.} (5... Nc6 {has also been tried, despite being a serious error.} 6. d5 {± and the [c3]-pawn prevents the knight from jumping too much. The knight can choose between two spots on the rim, [a5] or [d8], both of which are dim, grim, and slim!}) 6. cxd4 {[%cal Gb1c3] The trade of pawns on [d4] traded off [c5] for [c3]. So, we've just gotten the great [c3]-square for our [b1]-knight.} Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O {[%cal Gc8g4] Black lacks space and so will seek the [g4]-square for the bishop where they can trade it easily for our knight on [f3]. Spending a tempo on [h2]-[h3] would be too slow, but we can anticipate the bishop move with our own light-squared bishop.} 8. Be2 Nc6 {This is played a lot but runs into an obvious issue.} (8... Bg4 9. O-O Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nc6 11. e5 {± , booting the [f6]-knight and unleashing our [f3]-dragon on the world. White has an enormous advantage.}) 9. d5 Na5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gd4d5,Gg7a1] Our recent [d4]-[d5] kicked the knight out of its good square but at the same time compromised the [a1]-[h8] diagonal.} 10. Be3 $14 {[%cal Ge3d4] Our bishop will sit comfortably on [d4] to oppose the [g7]-bishop when it inevitably gets released. Notice that Black's [a5]-knight, having been booted to the edge, has no recourse to fight against this. We will castle and play [Rc1]. We have a better center and good pieces. The black bishop will go to [g4] sooner or later so our bishop is good on [e2]. Meanwhile, if it had gone to [d3], our queen's visage over the important [d4]-square would have been obstructed.} *

