1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... d6 5. d4 Nf6 $1 {The only move to keep Black in the fight for equality.} (5... Nc6 {has also been tried, despite being a serious error.} 6. d5 {± and the [c3]-pawn keeps the knight from jumping too much. The knight can choose between two spots on the rim, [a5] or [d8], both of which are dim, grim, and slim!}) 6. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4] Holding on to our [e4]. We can start to appreciate why ...[Nf6] immediately is so much stronger than doing so after trading. We weren't able to bring the knight to [c3] and so our bishop had to settle for this second-best option. Our bishop belonged on [e2] to parry the eventual black bishop coming to [g4].} O-O 7. O-O (7. e5 $5 {could be an interesting alternative, but the recommended move will likely transpose to other variations, saving us some effort in having to memorize superfluous variations. Feel free to analyze at home.}) 7... Nc6 {The only other popular move in this position; however, it is just bad due to the classic reason.} (7... cxd4 {will transpose back to the 6...cxd4 variation after} 8. cxd4 {.}) 8. d5 {Booting the knight out of the central ring.} Na5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Ge7e6,Ge6d5] Here Black hopes to play ...[e7]-[e6] and systematically implode White's center...} 9. f5 $1 {A beautiful prophylactic move against Black's ...[e7]-[e6] idea.} gxf5 10. exf5 {[%cal Ge1h4,Gd1e1] It might look like [d5] is hanging and it is. But fortunately, [Qe1]-[h4] is too strong a threat. I'd like everyone to recognize just how great our [f5]-pawn is in segmenting the board. The [c8]-bishop can never fight against things on the kingside. Meanwhile, the [f5]-pawn is so far advanced that it doesn't obstruct any rook lifts. And if the knight leaves [f6], we will be able to entertain ideas of [f5]-[f6] sacrifices, clearing the diagonal for the [d3]-bishop.} Nxd5 (10... Kh8 11. Qe1 {+- , when [Qe1]-[h4] and [Nf3]-[g5] is a winning attack.}) 11. Qe1 $16 {[%cal Ge1h4,Gf3g5,Gc1g5,Gg5h6,Yf5f6,Yf1f3,Yf3h3] Qe1-[h4] will follow. After that, White can up the pressure in a variety of ways. [Bc1]-[g5] or [Bc1]-[h6] is always on the table, while [Nf3]-[g5] brings the knight to the party and clears the way for a tremendous rook lift.} *

