1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... d6 5. d4 Nf6 $1 {The only move to keep Black in the fight for equality.} (5... Nc6 {has also been tried, despite being a serious error.} 6. d5 {± and the [c3]-pawn keeps the knight from jumping too much. The knight can choose between two spots on the rim, [a5] or [d8], both of which are dim, grim, and slim!}) 6. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4] Holding on to our [e4]. We can start to appreciate why ...[Nf6] immediately is so much stronger than doing so after trading. We weren't able to bring the knight to [c3] and so our bishop had to settle for this second-best option. Our bishop belonged on [e2] to parry the eventual black bishop coming to [g4].} cxd4 {This opens [c3] for our knight, but the damage has already been done to some extent. Our bishop in placing itself on [d3] can never go to [e2] without wasting an extra move.} 7. cxd4 O-O 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. f5 $5 {[%csl Rc8,Gf4][%cal Rc8g4,Gc1h6] Played in 1% of games to reach this position, but by golly, it looks bonkers. We impede the [c8]-bishop's path to [g4] and open up our own [c1]-bishop's path into Black's kingside.} (9. O-O Bg4 {, when Black's bishop does a great job with the pin, and there is a lot of pressure on [d4]. Black is completely equal. For reference, if our bishop were on [e2] rather than [d3], here we would be better.}) 9... a6 (9... Nb4 {can be comfortably met with the bishop retreat:} 10. Bb1 {.}) (9... gxf5 10. exf5 {leads to an unusual structure for both sides. We should aim to play on the kingside with [O-O] and stuff like [Be3], [Qd2] and [Bh6], or [Qe1]-[h4]. Our [f5]-pawn might appear vulnerable, but it does a good job of restricting the [c8]-bishop.}) 10. O-O b5 11. Kh1 {[%cal Rb6g1] This sidesteps any potential pin and also creates long-term ideas of [Rf1]-[g1].} b4 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd3c4] This might seem like a logical consequence of ...[b7]-[b5], but it weakens the [c4]-square long term, improving our bishop's prospects significantly.} 12. Ne2 e5 {[%csl Re2][%cal Rd4d5] Here [d4]-[d5] wouldn't be as strong since it would leave the knight on [e2] paralyzed by Black's [e5] and [b4]-pawns. The computer indicates that taking on [e6] or [g6] will bring a big advantage.} 13. fxe6 ({As an alternative you could play on the kingside with} 13. fxg6 hxg6 14. Bg5 {and [Qe1]-[h4] will kick off White's offensive on the kingside.}) 13... fxe6 14. Be3 $16 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gd1b3,Ge2f4,Gf3g5] Where is White's advantage? Simply put, our pieces and pawns are just better. Our center is good while Black's central pawns are timidly placed on [d6] and [e6]. Another problem for Black is the amount of pawns that they have pushed. Only the h-pawn stands on its starting square. The [c4]-square is weak as are the [e6] and [d6]-pawns. The knight on [c6] is also loose and as White builds pressure on the c-file, Black will likely have to move it. A plan I like is [Qb3] followed by [Ne2]-[f4] and [Nf3]-[g5] with annoying pressure against the [e6]-weakness.} *

