1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... d6 5. d4 Nf6 $1 {The only move to keep Black in the fight for equality.} (5... Nc6 {has also been tried, despite being a serious error.} 6. d5 {± and the [c3]-pawn keeps the knight from jumping too much. The knight can choose between two spots on the rim, [a5] or [d8], both of which are dim, grim, and slim!}) 6. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4] Holding on to our [e4]. We can start to appreciate why ...[Nf6] immediately is so much stronger than doing so after trading. We weren't able to bring the knight to [c3] and so our bishop had to settle for this second-best option. Our bishop belonged on [e2] to parry the eventual black bishop coming to [g4].} cxd4 {This opens [c3] for our knight, but the damage has already been done to some extent. Our bishop in placing itself on [d3] can never go to [e2] without wasting an extra move.} 7. cxd4 O-O 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. f5 $5 {[%csl Rc8,Gf4][%cal Rc8g4,Gc1h6] Played in 1% of games to reach this position, but by golly, it looks bonkers. We impede the [c8]-bishop's path to [g4] and open up our own [c1]-bishop's path into Black's kingside.} (9. O-O Bg4 {, when Black's bishop does a great job with the pin, and there is a lot of pressure on [d4]. Black is completely equal. For reference, if our bishop were on [e2] rather than [d3], here we would be better.}) 9... Qb6 {Posting up to put big pressure on our [d4]-pawn.} (9... Nb4 {can be comfortably met with the bishop retreat:} 10. Bb1 {.}) (9... gxf5 10. exf5 {leads to an unusual structure for both sides. We should aim to play on the kingside with [O-O] and stuff like [Be3], [Qd2] and [Bh6], or [Qe1]-[h4]. Our [f5]-pawn might appear vulnerable, but it does a good job of restricting the [c8]-bishop.}) 10. Na4 $1 {Pushing the queen back and also laying a sneaky trap. It is very easy to think that a queen check would get Black somewhere, but realistically, one check is losing and the other sets Black on a tightrope of only moves.} Qa5+ ({This just helps us develop.} 10... Qb4+ $4 11. Bd2 $1 {+- and the queen is trapped!}) 11. Bd2 Nb4 {The only logical way to justify the queen check. Black tries to rationalize the queen's placement on [a5].} (11... Qc7 {⩲ just gave us a free tempo. We will castle and play [Rc1] with a fun game ahead.}) 12. O-O {Now [a2]-[a3] is a serious threat.} Bd7 13. b3 {[%cal Ga2a3,Rd2a5]} gxf5 ({After} 13... Bxa4 $4 14. bxa4 {, the queen has no way out.} Qb6 15. Rb1 a5 16. a3 {decides easily.}) 14. exf5 b5 {Attacking our knight. We counter with a threat to their knight.} 15. a3 bxa4 16. axb4 Qd5 17. bxa4 Ne4 (17... Bxf5 {instead is well met by} 18. Bxf5 Qxf5 19. Nh4 Qh5 20. Nf5 {, which will turn into a bad endgame for Black. The [e7]-pawn is hanging while the bishop on [g7] is not very pleased either about the prospects of leaving the board. White is better.}) 18. Bxe4 Qxe4 19. Re1 Qxf5 20. Rxe7 $14 {Black has a strong bishop pair and our light squares are compromised somewhat, but we are still up a pawn and Black's kingside has been fractured. A simple goal would be to trade off the dark-squared bishops, which would achieve the dual aims of weakening the black king and getting a better grip on their weakened dark squares.} *

