1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... Nf6 5. e5 {[%cal Gd2d4] Beginning to build the mighty phalanx; next up, we will throw the pawn to [d4].} Nd5 {The logical move, which is also the run-away favorite.} 6. d4 $1 {[%cal Gc3c4,Gd4d5] If Black plays slow, we will simply have too much space. Both [dxc5] or [c3]-[c4] and [d4]-[d5] remain big strategic threats.} ({It's too late to turn back with something restrained like} 6. d3 $2 d6 $1 {⩱ , crunching on the strong pawn! White will be worse after [e5] is traded off. This is due to our [e3]-square being weak and our pieces having development issues. Notice we have the [c1]-bishop and [b1]-knight, both of which could use the [d2]-square. Somehow we have more space and yet, due to the fantastic knight on [d5], it is us this time who will suffer the positional cramp.}) 6... d6 7. dxc5 $1 {[%cal Gd6c5,Gd6e5] Black faces an important fork in the road: trade on [e5] and scheme to eventually equalize the material based on [e5]'s vulnerability, or recapture on [c5] and accept the reality of the [g7]-dragon being locked in the tomb created by the [e5]-prison.} (7. c4 $6 Nb4 {and despite appearances, our central structure is more of a balloon, which is in the midst of being punctured by [c5] and [d6]. The balloon will pop, and unfortunately, the party will soon be over.} 8. d5 $4 {is the move I always yearn to play. But sadly, our [e5]-[d5] pawn wedge can't weather the storm on [c2].} Bf5 {, yikes!} 9. Na3 {, all looks okay for the moment, and the clouds around White's lack of development appear to dissipate...} e6 $1 {-+ is a thunderbolt in the center! Black builds a powder keg against White's center, when the pawns will not survive. Once the center implodes, Black's bishops will remain to rake the board.}) 7... dxc5 $2 {The wrong recapture, but 47% of players still opt for it as the most popular choice!} 8. Bc4 {Asking the important questions. To stabilize the knight or not? Black is running out of lifelines.} Nb6 (8... Be6 9. Ng5 {, ouch! We will chop on [e6] shortly.} Nc6 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. O-O {+- , the ...[fxe6] capture has ruined Black's position. It is not only a permanent weakness but also represents the hopelessness of the [g7]-bishop, which without the ...[f6] break has no hope of seeing past [e5].}) 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bxf7 {Netting a pawn but isn't the bishop getting trapped?} e6 11. f5 $3 {Not so fast! Whichever way Black recaptures, a retreat diagonal for our bishop is opened.} gxf5 {We might be losing the pawn, but this gives us the essential tempo to begin playing against the king with a strong check.} 12. Bg5+ Kc7 13. Na3 {[%cal Ga3b5,Gb5d6] Threatening [Nb5]-[d6].} a6 14. Be7 $18 {[%csl Rc5,Rc7,Rd6][%cal Ge7d6] Now both [Bd6]+ or [Bxc5] are annoying threats. We will castle queenside with great play against the black king. The advantage is already decisive according to Sir Stockfish.} *

