you will still need to find many more good moves to net the full point.} b6 {We can trade on [b6], with a healthy extra pawn, or opt for the text move.} 9. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Why does this work? Aren't we behind in development? Well, Black's kingside is cramped and none of their pieces can get over there in time because of how boxed-in they are.} bxc5 10. h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5g6,Gh5h6] With two dangerous threats of [hxg6] and [h5]-[h6]; while the former threatens immediate mating ideas, the latter would guarantee an overwhelming positional bind late into the endgame.} d6 {Black is attempting to crunch the center open and create pathways for their pieces to get over to the danger zone in time.} 11. hxg6 hxg6 (11... fxg6 {(on the one hand stops them from getting mated by the barbaric [Qe2]-[f2]-[h4] as now Black can play ...[h7]-[h6] or ...[h7]-[h5]. We can continue with the calm pressure cooker)} 12. Be3 {+- , when [Ng5] and [Bd3] will begin a second wave of attack against the black king. Black can prevent this at any time with ...[dxe5], when the queens will get traded. Unfortunately, however, this would leave their structure in shambles and the ripe apple on [c5] would quickly drop.}) 12. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2f2,Gf2h4] And [Qf2]-[h4] will spearhead a decisive attack.} *

