1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {Here White can try} 5. d4 {, 5.d3 , or 5.Bc4 , but I like a more unique move in the vein of the rest of the course.}) 5. Bb5 {What a strange position! After [Bb5] we are playing a Rossolimo Sicilian with [f2]-[f4] thrown in, a Rossolimo Grand Prix if you will! This position has only been reached around 61 thousand times in the database and keep in mind most of those started from Sicilians.} (5. Bb5 {If you get this from the Bird, there is a good chance your opponent will be completely on their own from this position. The most common moves are} e6 {and 5...a6 . We will look at the top 4 moves played in this position.}) 5... a6 {This leads to fine versions of the Rossolimo. As mentioned in other variations, the inclusion of [f2]-[f4] will be to our benefit after the ensuing exchange.} 6. Bxc6 dxc6 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc5c4] Black wants to grip the [d3]-square with ...[c5]-[c4] before we push our [d2]-pawn. We must not allow this.} 7. d3 Bg4 {This has been commonly tried, but we can force the trade to get a great position.} 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Nf6 10. O-O O-O {Our structure looks healthier but how exactly should we use it? We should aim our knight at [c4] and [b3] with [Nb1]-[d2].} 11. Nd2 {[%csl Rb3,Rc4][%cal Gd2c4,Yb7b5,Yd2b3,Ga4a5,Ga2a4] We will aim to play [a2]-[a4] and if possible [a4]-[a5], when we will have stopped ...[b7]-[b5] for good, guaranteeing our knight an outpost on [c4]. If Black prevents this by playing ...[b7]-[b5] early, then they will be weakening [c5] and allowing us to target the [c5]-pawn with [Nd2]-[b3]. Importantly, we can look to push [e4]-[e5] at the right moment to build concrete against the [g7]-bishop, but we don't have to.} *

