1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {Here White can try} 5. d4 {, 5.d3 , or 5.Bc4 , but I like a more unique move in the vein of the rest of the course.}) 5. Bb5 {What a strange position! After [Bb5] we are playing a Rossolimo Sicilian with [f2]-[f4] thrown in, a Rossolimo Grand Prix if you will! This position has only been reached around 61 thousand times in the database and keep in mind most of those started from Sicilians.} (5. Bb5 {If you get this from the Bird, there is a good chance your opponent will be completely on their own from this position. The most common moves are} e6 {and 5...a6 . We will look at the top 4 moves played in this position.}) 5... a6 {This leads to fine versions of the Rossolimo. As mentioned in other variations, the inclusion of [f2]-[f4] will be to our benefit after the ensuing exchange.} 6. Bxc6 bxc6 7. d3 {Solidifying our pawn and light squares. We need to play carefully with our pawns. It's essential to be able to play [e4]-[e5] to stunt the [g7]-bishop, and [c3]-[c4] to build concrete against the light-squared bishop should it move to [a6] or [e6]. Neither of these pawn pushes is mandatory and should not be rushed recklessly, but we do need to keep them as options as the middlegame twists and turns − they will be essential for handling Black's bishop pair.} d6 8. O-O e6 $2 {[%csl Rc8,Re6][%cal Rc8g4] This is a strategic blunder, but that hasn't stopped it from being the second most popular move with a frequency of 21%.} 9. e5 $18 {[%csl Rc8,Rg7] Both bishops point into the abyss. The [c8]-bishop points into its very own pawn wall forever frozen on [e6]. Meanwhile, [e5] will be solid enough and can be reinforced if Black tries to encircle it. If Black takes on [e5], they will be left with hideous c-pawns and will never be able to move the pawn to [d5] to keep our queen's knight out of [c4] or [e4]. But what is Black to do then, play ...[d6]-[d5] and let the [e5]-concrete sit unchallenged? Black's position has many questions, yet no answers.} *

