1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e4 {The only time we play [e4] in one go against the Sicilian.} Bg7 4. c3 {This position has arisen a bit out of Anti-Sicilians in which White tries a quick [f2]-[f4]. At the moment, around 250000 games in the database have been played here, but keep in mind that 90+% are from games starting with [e2]-[e4]. The likelihood of reaching this from a Bird remains very low.} (4. c3 {Black's top move is to develop the queen's knight with} Nc6 {, which enjoys a frequency of 44%. Apart from this, Black usually opts for 4...e6 , 4...d6 , or 4...d5 .}) 4... Nc6 (4... Nc6 {Here White can try} 5. d4 {, 5.d3 , or 5.Bc4 , but I like a more unique move in the vein of the rest of the course.}) 5. Bb5 {What a strange position! After [Bb5] we are playing a Rossolimo Sicilian with [f2]-[f4] thrown in, a Rossolimo Grand Prix if you will! This position has only been reached around 61 thousand times in the database and keep in mind most of those started from Sicilians.} (5. Bb5 {If you get this from the Bird, there is a good chance your opponent will be completely on their own from this position. The most common moves are} e6 {and 5...a6 . We will look at the top 4 moves played in this position.}) 5... d6 ({This is arguably Black's best response. It often transposes to the same positions as those after} 5... Nf6 {.}) 6. d3 Nf6 7. O-O O-O {The position is balanced. Both sides have a decent control of the center.} 8. Bxc6 {We take on [c6] and double the pawns.} bxc6 9. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4] Our knight heads to [c4]. Black is okay because neither of their bishops has been sufficiently entombed. We will analyze Black's four most common options.} Bg4 {Here we should be happy to force Black's bishop pair off the board.} (9... Ba6 10. c4 Rb8 11. h3 {transposes to the 9...Rb8 line.}) 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 $14 {[%cal Ga3c4] We will play [Nc4] with a nice edge due to the better structure. We can aim for [e4]-[e5] in the future.} *

