1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 {This is played 7% of the time, constituting Black's 5th most popular option.} 4. Bb5 {Going for Rossolimo-style pressure against the [c6]-knight. While the game is level here, Black tends to immediately err, with 80% of games seeing erroneous pawn moves in this position that allow us to advantageously chop on [c6].} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6b5,Gb6c6] Black's 6th most frequent move at 8%. It happens to be one of Black's best, however. The queen protects against our plan to destroy the pawn structure and hits our bishop in the process. We must not give in to the queen's demands though.} 5. c4 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gc4b5]} ({Our bishop stays put. We choose this move over, for instance,} 5. a4 {or 5.Qe2 because it takes more control of the center.}) 5... e6 {This isn't sensible since Black's b-pawn is blocked by the queen and so the [c8]-bishop will probably have to escape by way of the [c8]-[h3] diagonal. Of course, the problem now is that this diagonal is increasingly cramped.} 6. Ne5 $13 {[%cal Ge1g1,Yc6e5,Yf4e5] Initiating fun tension against the [c6]-knight. The computer insists this is close to equal but obviously, this isn't an appraisal of the practical dimensions of the position.} (6. Ne5 {Two moves hold the balance here for Black:} Qc7 {and 6...d6 . Neither is obvious and compared to other moves, they are not intuitive. We will castle and ride the waves of the ensuing chaos with confidence. The eagle flies high.}) *

