1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 {This is played 7% of the time, constituting Black's 5th most popular option.} 4. Bb5 {Going for Rossolimo-style pressure against the [c6]-knight. While the game is level here, Black tends to immediately err, with 80% of games seeing erroneous pawn moves in this position that allow us to advantageously chop on [c6].} d6 {This is played 13% of the time and, fortunately for us, allows a good exchange on [c6]. We can expect a moderate positional advantage due to the favorable structure.} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 {As we will go on to see, Black's position will be difficult in two ways. First, while they're not so weak, the c-pawns make Black's structure inflexible − if Black ever pushes ...[d6]-[d5], the [c5]-pawn becomes vulnerable. Second, the light-squared bishop has little to do; [c6] keeps the long diagonal closed and other diagonals don't look appealing.} 6. b3 {Setting up the queenside fianchetto.} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4d1] The bishop bets its activity on pinning the knight. The problem is that Black has already taken on a structural weakening from the doubled c-pawns and is now destined to cede back the bishop pair.} 7. h3 {Asking the question that must be answered.} Bxf3 (7... Bh5 {would not work here. Our [f4]-pawn will seal Black's fate.} 8. g4 Bg6 9. f5 {+- and White is up a piece.}) 8. Qxf3 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gf3c6]} (8. Qxf3 {Funnily, the 2nd and 3rd most popular moves here are} g6 {and 8...e6 at 18% and 13% respectively even though that just hangs 9.Qxc6+ .}) 8... Qc7 9. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2h8] The bishop scans the diagonal. Black has a difficult decision of how to open the [f8]-bishop's development since White's [Bxf6] might be waiting right around the corner.} e6 10. g4 {[%csl Gf4,Gg4][%cal Yg4g5,Yf8e7]} (10. g4 {Gaining good scope on the kingside. Black is stuck, as} Be7 {runs into} 11. g5 {, when White wins the [g7]-pawn.}) 10... Rg8 {Defending the [g7]-pawn in anticipation of [g4]-[g5].} 11. e4 $16 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gb1d2] We will play [d2]-[d3] and [Nd2]. Our king will likely go to the queenside and then we can continue expansion on the kingside with [h3]-[h4] and [h4]-[h5] or [g4]-[g5]. Black is left to scrap together some mediocre plan with their dysfunctional setup. Black can no longer castle kingside because of ...[Rg8] and will go to the queenside, where the king will momentarily be safe, but if they ever want to expand with ...[d6]-[d5] or ...[e6]-[e5] will have to take significant risk.} *

