1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 {This is played 7% of the time, constituting Black's 5th most popular option.} 4. Bb5 {Going for Rossolimo-style pressure against the [c6]-knight. While the game is level here, Black tends to immediately err, with 80% of games seeing erroneous pawn moves in this position that allow us to advantageously chop on [c6].} d6 {This is played 13% of the time and, fortunately for us, allows a good exchange on [c6]. We can expect a moderate positional advantage due to the favorable structure.} 5. Bxc6+ bxc6 {As we will go on to see, Black's position will be difficult in two ways. First, while they're not so weak, the c-pawns make Black's structure inflexible − if Black ever pushes ...[d6]-[d5], the [c5]-pawn becomes vulnerable. Second, the light-squared bishop has little to do; [c6] keeps the long diagonal closed and other diagonals don't look appealing.} 6. b3 {Setting up the queenside fianchetto.} Ba6 {[%cal Re1g1,Ga6f1] This is seen 10% of the time. If the diagonal was forced to stay open, then the bishop would be good here, but we will build concrete against it easily.} 7. d3 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Gd3]} g6 {[%cal Ga6c8,Gc8g4] Black's best way to handle the position. This keeps ...[Ba6]-[c8]-[g4] still available if Black's light-squared bishop chooses to reroute.} 8. Bb2 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe1 $14 {[%cal Ge1a5,Ge1h4] This move is recommended in tons of positions and it is quintessential of the Bird. The queen eyes both diagonals and protects the vulnerable [e3]-pawn. It might look bad to block in the [f1]-rook in this fashion, but the rook will be happy to stay on the f-file, where rook lifts from [f1]-[f3]-[h3] could happen and where it could support the pawn advance [f4]-[f5] eventually. We will be happy to trade dark-squared bishops whenever the moment presents itself. Meanwhile, we will slowly encroach with our pawns, either with [e3]-[e4] or [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4]. In this way, we'll expand while keeping the enemy's light-squared bishop pointed into concrete. It should be mentioned that there will be discovery issues between the opposing bishops on the long diagonal. Make sure to watch out for these ideas! [Rf2] is a useless move but I chose it to show this tactical device in action.} (10. Rf2 Ne4 $1 11. dxe4 (11. Bxg7 Nxf2 {-+ , our queen is hit, and if we recapture on [f2], Black will recapture on [g7], remaining up the exchange.}) 11... Bxb2 {-+ and we can say goodbye to the mango on [a1].}) *

