1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 {This is played 7% of the time, constituting Black's 5th most popular option.} 4. Bb5 {Going for Rossolimo-style pressure against the [c6]-knight. While the game is level here, Black tends to immediately err, with 80% of games seeing erroneous pawn moves in this position that allow us to advantageously chop on [c6].} g6 {This is played 15% of the time. It makes more sense than ...[a7]-[a6], but even without the free tempo, chopping on [c6] will promise us good chances.} 5. Bxc6 dxc6 {This is only chosen 26% of the time. It leads to a harmonious structure for Black in which both bishops have clear lanes for development. The drawback is that Black forgoes ever bringing a pawn to [d5], which means we can gradually plan to bring a pawn to [e4] in most middlegame positions.} 6. b3 {The old fashioned queenside fianchetto.} Bg7 {This position has only been seen 50 times in the database.} 7. Bb2 {The bishops eye one another. We will not complain if we have to trade them, for the dark squares around the enemy king would become weak.} O-O 8. O-O b5 $1 {The healthiest move, getting the b-pawn to [b5] before we can get [a4] in. This entire position seems very strange and the purpose of achieving a pawn on [b5] is not entirely obvious. I suspect the reasoning is that with this pawn on [b5], Black will be able to jettison the ugly [c5]-pawn with ...[c5]-[c4] at the right moment, seeking adequate compensation in the fact that collecting it will require us to rupture our structure irreparably.} 9. a4 $13 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gd1e2,Gd2d3,Ge3e4] This natural move is a novelty. The idea is to control the levers of the a-file and only execute [axb5] when our rook can get something with its unleashed activity down the a-file. Meanwhile, we will improve our position with [Nf3]-[e5], [Qd1]-[e2], and the classic [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4]. The position is balanced, but I prefer White. It is easier to play with a healthy structure than a mangled one and an ambiguous bishop pair.} *

