1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 {This is played 7% of the time, constituting Black's 5th most popular option.} 4. Bb5 {Going for Rossolimo-style pressure against the [c6]-knight. While the game is level here, Black tends to immediately err, with 80% of games seeing erroneous pawn moves in this position that allow us to advantageously chop on [c6].} g6 {This is played 15% of the time. It makes more sense than ...[a7]-[a6], but even without the free tempo, chopping on [c6] will promise us good chances.} 5. Bxc6 dxc6 {This is only chosen 26% of the time. It leads to a harmonious structure for Black in which both bishops have clear lanes for development. The drawback is that Black forgoes ever bringing a pawn to [d5], which means we can gradually plan to bring a pawn to [e4] in most middlegame positions.} 6. b3 {The old fashioned queenside fianchetto.} Bg7 {This position has only been seen 50 times in the database.} 7. Bb2 {The bishops eye one another. We will not complain if we have to trade them, for the dark squares around the enemy king would become weak.} O-O 8. O-O Bg4 {The most popular at 46%.} 9. a4 {[%cal Ga4b5,Rb7b5] Contesting Black's ...[b7]-[b5]. This has only been reached once before in online play. In that game, Black played ...[Ne4]. We will look at this as well as other logical moves. I should state that this position is rather unnatural so understanding the ideas and getting experience in the positions is exponentially more important than memorizing the moves.} Ne4 $2 {This is just waiting to be kicked by [d2]-[d3] with a free tempo for White.} 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. d3 Nd6 12. Nbd2 $14 {[%cal Gd1e1,Ge1h4,Yd1c1,Yc1b2,Ge3e4] We will play [e3]-[e4] with a much healthier structure. Our queen can either go to [h4] or [g3] via [e1] or to [b2] via [c1] where it will scope the long diagonal, a queenside fianchetto if there ever was one! While Black's structure reveals no immediate vulnerabilities, it lacks flexibility and Black will have to sit patiently and wait, something that most online players won't find pleasant at all.} *

