1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 {This is played 7% of the time, constituting Black's 5th most popular option.} 4. Bb5 {Going for Rossolimo-style pressure against the [c6]-knight. While the game is level here, Black tends to immediately err, with 80% of games seeing erroneous pawn moves in this position that allow us to advantageously chop on [c6].} g6 {This is played 15% of the time. It makes more sense than ...[a7]-[a6], but even without the free tempo, chopping on [c6] will promise us good chances.} 5. Bxc6 bxc6 {This is played 74% of the time as opposed to the other capture, which has a frequency of 26%. This poses absolutely no problems. Black's only way to make sense of this central structure will be to play ...[d7]-[d5], transposing into comfortable positions we know from our study of the ...[d5] systems.} 6. b3 Bg7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. O-O d5 {This comes very close to transposing to positions reached in the kingside fianchetto chapter in the ...[d5] systems, but in those, the [c8]-bishop had exchanged on [f3] and we recaptured from [d1] with our queen. There is no real way to transpose, and so this is one position of the ...[d5] systems we can only reach via the Sicilians.} 9. Nc3 $5 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc3a4] Heading for [a4] where it will press against the lonely [c5]-pawn. This position has been reached in 914 games, and we will look at Black's most popular 4 options.} Bg4 {The most popular, being chosen 23% of the time.} 10. Na4 Nd7 ({Parrying our knight on a4.} 10... Qd6 $2 {is played most often but just drops the pawn to the basic trick:} 11. Be5 {.}) 11. Bxg7 {While the computer insists that this is fine for Black, there is always a risk involved with building the fianchetto structure only to trade the bishops. The dark squares around the king are permanently weak even if White's pieces are not geared toward exploiting this factor in the near future.} Kxg7 12. h3 {Claiming the bishop back.} Bxf3 13. Qxf3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge3e4] Here Black can play ...[Qa5] and hold the balance. Objectively though, this move is not natural at all. In any case, White obviously has a practical edge due to the better structure. We'll aim to play [e3]-[e4], when the pressure on [d5] will get uncomfortable. Of course, if our opponent plays ...[dxe4], we will happily recapture, when Black's c-pawns have become isolated and all the more vulnerable.} *

