1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6 {This is played 7% of the time, constituting Black's 5th most popular option.} 4. Bb5 {Going for Rossolimo-style pressure against the [c6]-knight. While the game is level here, Black tends to immediately err, with 80% of games seeing erroneous pawn moves in this position that allow us to advantageously chop on [c6].} a6 $2 {This is the most popular move and yet it works out great for us.} 5. Bxc6 {We get the exchange we want with a free tempo since Black's ...[a7]-[a6] was otherwise useless.} bxc6 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Rc8a6] Played twice as often as the other recapture. Now [a6] looks particularly out of place in view of Black's [c8]-bishop being blocked from a natural square on [a6].} 6. O-O {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge3e4,Yb2b3,Yc1b2] It is better to keep flexibility for the moment. We might play for [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4] or [b2]-[b3] and [Bb2].} e6 {[%csl Ra6,Rc6,Rc8,Rd7,Re6,Rf7] This is Black's second most popular move, though it is hideous to place yet another pawn on a light square. Black's bishop has even less hope of ever finding relevance now.} 7. c4 {[%csl Rc5,Rf8][%cal Rf8c5] Getting a grip on the center and in particular making sure the diagonals stay closed. The [c5]-pawn hasn't been mentioned yet, but it stifles the [f8]-bishop's mobility.} d5 {Black challenges the pawn. The worst move possible would be to take here. Trading on [d5] allows ...[cxd5], when the [c8]-bishop's prospects are immediately improved by the removal of [c6]. Meanwhile, the [c5]-pawn would be free to move to [c4], liberating the [f8]-bishop.} 8. b3 $16 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc1a3,Gb1c3,Gc3a4] Holding everything in place. We have several ideas here. White can play [Bb2] with the classic play on the long diagonal. Another perhaps stronger idea is to aim at the [c5]-weakness with [Ba3] and [Nc3]-[a4].} *

