1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nf6 ({This position is reached only a third as often as the position after} 3... Nc6 {is. Here we'll go for a less essayed but nonetheless strong option.}) 4. Bb5+ $1 {Our bishop returns once again to [b5]. We are fine with trading the bishops if they block with ...[Bd7]. Meanwhile, if they block with the [b8]-knight on either square, we will have promising opportunities.} Nbd7 {Already on move 4 we reach a position which has only been reached 813 times in the online database! For reference, the main line of the Ruy Lopez on move 4 has been reached nearly 4.5 million times. We are truly in uncharted territory. The computer screams equal but what will that matter when our Black opponent will be brought into an unorthodox position in which we have a ton of experience and knowledge, and they have none! If our opponent isn't out of their element now, they will certainly be after our next move...} (4... Nc6 {is chosen 23% of the time. We should be happy to see this since it allows us the classic favorable exchange on [c6].} 5. Bxc6+ {, the return of the chop chop! After} bxc6 {, we see the old reliable weak doubled c-pawns. This transposes right into the lines discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter in the 4...[d6] variations.}) 5. Be2 $5 {No, your eyes aren't dreaming! The second bishop move in 2 turns! The point was to not allow ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] with tempo. Now if Black tries ...[a6], we can respond with [a2]-[a4] or [c2]-[c4] with a solid grip. But why didn't we put the bishop on [e2] move 4? Why did we give Black the 'free tempo' of ...[Nbd7]? Well, it's not so free after all! The knight belongs on [c6] and if Black wants to put it there, Black is actually a move farther behind in development now. To be clear, the position is equal but heavily unorthodox. It appears like that of a Closed Sicilian or a Grand Prix Attack until you notice that the white king pawn is on [e3] not [e4]. I am very confident the player with more experience here will score tremendously from this position. This position has only been reached 13 times in the online metaverse. I can confidently say if you arrive here, there is a 99.99% chance your opponent has never played against this before. We will analyze the four moves that have been tried in this position, as well as 2 others that the computer also likes.} a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] The second most popular continuation at a frequency 4 of the 13 games. Black is of course preparing ...[b7]-[b5].} 6. c4 {[%cal Rb7b5] So we prevent it! No ...[b5] for you!} g6 7. O-O Bg7 {[%csl Ra6,Gc4] This will heavily resemble the lines after 5...g6 , but the inclusion of [c4] and ...[a6] is strongly in our favor. [c4] is a useful move while without ...[b7]-[b5] coming soon, ...[a6] is borderline useless.} 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Kh1 {We must prepare [e3]-[e4] in this meticulous manner. Check the note to the immediate [e4] to understand better why this is.} (9. e4 $6 {This type of advance should be plotted very carefully. Black can undermine our center now, making use of the ...[a6] move.} b5 10. cxb5 Qb6 {and a sample line is} 11. bxa6 c4+ 12. Kh1 Bxa6 {. Now [d3] is very weak and if Black is given time to play ...[Nc5], White's [d3] and [e4] will be seriously aching.} 13. d4 $1 {, pushing through the siege.} cxd3 14. Bxd3 Nc5 15. Bxa6 Qxa6 {∞ , Black has beautiful Benko-style compensation with a healthy structure, pressure on [e4], and two nice open a- and b-files to lay siege to our under-advanced queenside pawns. I'd rather be Black here.}) 9... b6 10. e4 Bb7 11. d3 {[%cal Gd1e1,Ge1h4,Ye2d1,Yd1a4,Ya1b1,Ya2a3,Yb2b4] White's center is nice. Both sides have healthy structures and harmonious setups, so the game is balanced. We could transfer our queen to [h4] via [e1], or play for [a2]-[a3] and [b2]-[b4] with [Rb1]. There are so many ideas in this position. Another cool one is playing [Qe1] to open up the [d1]-square for a bishop transfer via [e2]-[d1]-[a4]! Happy snacking!} *

