perience here will score tremendously from this position. This position has only been reached 13 times in the online metaverse. I can confidently say if you arrive here, there is a 99.99% chance your opponent has never played against this before. We will analyze the four moves that have been tried in this position, as well as 2 others that the computer also likes.} e6 {Preparing a conservative setup with ...[Be7].} 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 {Seizing part of the center. We always need to be very careful about how we mix [c4] and [f4] into a structure since both moves together weaken the central e- and d-files. Here Black's d-file is closed and the [d7]-knight impedes the strength of any ...[d5] push. Even so, we must consider how to respond to the thematic central aggression.} (7. d3 $6 {White is preparing [e4].} b5 $1 {Now ...[b5]-[b4] will be very annoying to our setup with [Nc3] and Black likely has the better chances.} (7... d5 8. Nc3 {transposes to a position examined after d5.}) 8. e4 O-O 9. a3 a5 10. Nc3 $2 {runs straight into Black's idea.} b4 {⩱ , Black has more space and a more harmonious setup. Without [c3], our knight will lack decent options.}) 7... d5 8. b3 {Going for the hackneyed [Bb2].} (8. d3 {(is an interesting alternative for those who don't want to elect for the queenside fianchetto. The position looks very weird, but our structure is fluid with breaks on [d4] and [e4] always being in the air. And with the pawns all connected via [c4]-[d3]-[e3]-[f4], there remain no obvious weak squares or weak pawns previously one existed on the weak [d3]-square.)}) 8... O-O 9. Bb2 {[%csl Rd7] Notice the whole justification for this [b3]-[c4] setup is the knight on [d7]. If the knight were on [c6], Black could encroach aggressively with ...[d5]-[d4]! Black can either play with the knight on [d7] or try to reroute it to [c6]. We will briefly analyze both schemes.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] The bishop goes to [b7].} 10. Nc3 Bb7 11. Qe1 $13 {[%cal Ge1g3,Gg3h4] Our queen will go to [g3] or [h4]. The position is unbelievably complicated and whoever has more experience will have extremely good odds. Some plans involve [Nc3]-[d1]-[f2] followed by [g2]-[g4] or [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4]. Another is [Rd1] and [d2]-[d4]. Remember, no pieces have been traded! When chaos breaks out you better be ready!} *

