1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nf6 ({This position is reached only a third as often as the position after} 3... Nc6 {is. Here we'll go for a less essayed but nonetheless strong option.}) 4. Bb5+ $1 {Our bishop returns once again to [b5]. We are fine with trading the bishops if they block with ...[Bd7]. Meanwhile, if they block with the [b8]-knight on either square, we will have promising opportunities.} Nbd7 {Already on move 4 we reach a position which has only been reached 813 times in the online database! For reference, the main line of the Ruy Lopez on move 4 has been reached nearly 4.5 million times. We are truly in uncharted territory. The computer screams equal but what will that matter when our Black opponent will be brought into an unorthodox position in which we have a ton of experience and knowledge, and they have none! If our opponent isn't out of their element now, they will certainly be after our next move...} (4... Nc6 {is chosen 23% of the time. We should be happy to see this since it allows us the classic favorable exchange on [c6].} 5. Bxc6+ {, the return of the chop chop! After} bxc6 {, we see the old reliable weak doubled c-pawns. This transposes right into the lines discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter in the 4...[d6] variations.}) 5. Be2 $5 {No, your eyes aren't dreaming! The second bishop move in 2 turns! The point was to not allow ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] with tempo. Now if Black tries ...[a6], we can respond with [a2]-[a4] or [c2]-[c4] with a solid grip. But why didn't we put the bishop on [e2] move 4? Why did we give Black the 'free tempo' of ...[Nbd7]? Well, it's not so free after all! The knight belongs on [c6] and if Black wants to put it there, Black is actually a move farther behind in development now. To be clear, the position is equal but heavily unorthodox. It appears like that of a Closed Sicilian or a Grand Prix Attack until you notice that the white king pawn is on [e3] not [e4]. I am very confident the player with more experience here will score tremendously from this position. This position has only been reached 13 times in the online metaverse. I can confidently say if you arrive here, there is a 99.99% chance your opponent has never played against this before. We will analyze the four moves that have been tried in this position, as well as 2 others that the computer also likes.} e6 {Preparing a conservative setup with ...[Be7].} 6. O-O b6 {Black prepares a queenside fianchetto.} 7. d3 {[%cal Ge3e4] Preparing [e3]-[e4].} Bb7 8. e4 Be7 9. Nc3 {There is no reason for our knight to avoid this healthy square here. Notice that it wouldn't have any serious prospects on [c4] with ...[d6]-[d5] and ...[b6]-[b5] always in the air so there wouldn't be any point in placing it on [d2] in this structure.} O-O 10. Qe1 $14 {[%cal Ge1g3,Gg3h3,Gc3d1,Gd1e3,Gc1d2] White has a small but stable edge. We will begin transferring pieces over to the queenside to make some play there. We will transfer our queen to [h3] via [g3] h4 would be nice but the bishop on [e7] would be looking right at her majesty and we can follow with ideas like [Bd2], [Nd1]-[e3]. Our queen is good on [h3], as we'll be able to launch the g-pawn forward to [g4] and [g5] whenever the moment is right. Black has little to do with their setup and structure. We will meet ...[d6]-[d5] with [e4]-[e5], keeping things closed. Meanwhile, ...[e6]-[e5] would be positionally dangerous, as we would be able to make use of the weakened [f5]-square in various ways, such as [Nf3]-[h4]-[f5].} *

