on on the kingside. Future plans could be [Bd3] and [Qe2]-[e4] or [Nc3]-[e4]-[d6]/[g5]. I also like the idea of advancing the a-pawn to [a4] (and potentially [a5]) to limit any potential queenside expansion. Notice Black hates where the [c5]-pawn is, as it stifles the [d7]-knight and bishop. By securing [b5] with [a2]-[a4], we prevent any potential for ...[b5], when Black would be able to remove this obstructing pawn over to [c4].}) 10. Nb1 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c4,Gb1d2,Gd2c4] Depending on the circumstances, the knight will continue along via [d2] or [a3] to [c4].} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] Preparing to fianchetto the bishop.} 11. a4 $1 {Securing [b5] to make sure that when our knight reaches [c4], it will be protected from any annoying ...[b6]-[b5] harassment. We are better and control the levers of the position. After the knight transfer, we will continue making slow improvements on the kingside (like [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4] for instance) before eventually committing to something serious like [f4]-[f5] or [e4]-[e5].} *

