1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nf6 ({This position is reached only a third as often as the position after} 3... Nc6 {is. Here we'll go for a less essayed but nonetheless strong option.}) 4. Bb5+ $1 {Our bishop returns once again to [b5]. We are fine with trading the bishops if they block with ...[Bd7]. Meanwhile, if they block with the [b8]-knight on either square, we will have promising opportunities.} Nbd7 {Already on move 4 we reach a position which has only been reached 813 times in the online database! For reference, the main line of the Ruy Lopez on move 4 has been reached nearly 4.5 million times. We are truly in uncharted territory. The computer screams equal but what will that matter when our Black opponent will be brought into an unorthodox position in which we have a ton of experience and knowledge, and they have none! If our opponent isn't out of their element now, they will certainly be after our next move...} (4... Nc6 {is chosen 23% of the time. We should be happy to see this since it allows us the classic favorable exchange on [c6].} 5. Bxc6+ {, the return of the chop chop! After} bxc6 {, we see the old reliable weak doubled c-pawns. This transposes right into the lines discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter in the 4...[d6] variations.}) 5. Be2 $5 {No, your eyes aren't dreaming! The second bishop move in 2 turns! The point was to not allow ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] with tempo. Now if Black tries ...[a6], we can respond with [a2]-[a4] or [c2]-[c4] with a solid grip. But why didn't we put the bishop on [e2] move 4? Why did we give Black the 'free tempo' of ...[Nbd7]? Well, it's not so free after all! The knight belongs on [c6] and if Black wants to put it there, Black is actually a move farther behind in development now. To be clear, the position is equal but heavily unorthodox. It appears like that of a Closed Sicilian or a Grand Prix Attack until you notice that the white king pawn is on [e3] not [e4]. I am very confident the player with more experience here will score tremendously from this position. This position has only been reached 13 times in the online metaverse. I can confidently say if you arrive here, there is a 99.99% chance your opponent has never played against this before. We will analyze the four moves that have been tried in this position, as well as 2 others that the computer also likes.} g6 {The most popular, being seen in 6 of the games. It brings the not-so-subtle idea of fianchettoing the king's bishop.} 6. O-O Bg7 {As with all the other variations after 5.Be2, we have several ways to guide the game toward complicated yet balanced positions.} 7. c4 {I am biased toward grabbing more of the center, but [a4] also seemed perfectly fine.} O-O 8. Nc3 e6 {[%cal Gd6d5] Black is getting ready to play ...[d6]-[d5]. It makes sense to take more of the center now while it's still possible.} (8... a6 {would transpose to the 5...a6 variation.}) 9. e4 $1 b6 10. d3 ({After} 10. d4 $2 {, the [e4]-pawn will become terminally weak now. The d-pawn should have stayed behind on [d3] to help its brother weather the approaching storm.} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Bb7 12. Bf3 a6 {and ...[Nc5] is gonna be hella annoying. Black is definitely the one in the driver's seat. The game has turned into one of the nicest hedgehog setups Black has ever seen.}) 10... Bb7 11. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1g3,Gg3h4] I shouldn't even have to say where the queen is going. You've probably seen it 100 times by this point.} a6 {[%cal Gb6b5] If ...[b6]-[b5] is able to be done effectively, Black will trade our c-pawn off, getting a sizable stake in the center. So we should clamp down on this break before it can ever be realized.} 12. a4 $13 {[%cal Yd6d5,Ye4e5] The game is level. Frankly, the lines the computer gives are insanely hard to understand. I believe whoever shows more patience here will have the upper hand. We should wait in the jungle behind the shadows, and when they get flustered and play ...[d6]-[d5], we pounce like a puma with [e4]-[e5]. Meanwhile, if they get anxious with ...[e6]-[e5] we sabotage them with [f4]-[f5]. Both of these happenings would lead to huge advantages for us. If they stay patient, I don't know what to tell you, I've never seen two jungle lurkers fight.} *

