pressure on the weak [d3]-pawn.} (9... O-O 10. e4 {and we've finally arrived at a normal-looking Anti-Sicilian. The game is even and a complicated struggle awaits. We can start with [h2]-[h3] to prevent ...[Ng4] and then play [Be3] and [Qd2].}) 10. e4 $1 d4 {[%csl Gd4] We arrive at a reversed Czech Benoni structure in which Black's [d4]-pawn grants the second player a lot of extra space.} (10... dxc4 11. dxc4 {transposes to 10...dxe4 11.dxe4 .}) 11. Nd5 {The knight never gets to this stronghold in the normal Czech Benoni.} Nxd5 $2 {This allows us to get a pawn to [d5], which will debilitate Black's entire position.} 12. exd5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Rc6e5,Gf3e5] Booting the knight from [c6]. Our knight waits with anticipation for the opportunity to break ground on [e5].} Nb4 13. Ne5 Bxe5 14. fxe5 $18 {[%csl Yd5,Ye5][%cal Yd5c6,Yd5e6,Ye5d6,Ye5f6] With 2 golden pawns on [e5] and [d5], Black's pieces suffocate under the lack of space.} *

