5,Rd5][%cal Gc3d5,Gc3b5] Initiating an attack against [d5] but also introducing ideas of [Nb5].} e6 {Black reinforces [d5] so we must bring a new piece in to pressure that pawn.} 9. Qf3 {Black must budge now, as other moves to maintain [d5] give us a nice edge.} Qd8 $2 {It's never good to be moving your queen back to its starting square on the third move it's had in an opening.} 10. O-O Be7 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 Nbd7 {Compared to ...[Nc6], we can't trade to rupture the structure, but this does block the black queen's view of [d5], making that pawn much more vulnerable in the long term.} (12... Nc6 13. Nxc6 {, inflicting the famous original doubled c-pawns on Black's structure.} bxc6 14. d3 {followed by [e3]-[e4] with a fun and healthy advantage.}) 13. Rad1 {[%cal Gc4d5] With [d2] defended, we are now threatening [cxd5]. Black's position is unpleasant. They will have to contort their pieces in uncomfortable ways to deal with the pressure against [d5]. Meanwhile, we can slowly play for kingside expansion with [h2]-[h3], [g2]-[g4], and even [f4]-[f5]. If Black trades on [c4], we will take the pawn with a solid center.} (13. cxd5 $2 {would be impatient and greedy.} Nxd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Qxd5 $6 (15. Ng4 {∞ would have still kept the game level.}) 15... Nxe5 $1 16. Qxd8 (16. Qxe5 Bf6 {-+ , that's gotta be painful.}) 16... Rfxd8 {, we have to drop [d2] here so we won't even keep the pawn.} 17. Bxe5 Rxd2 {and Black is better with the active rook on [d2].}) *

