1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nf6 ({This position is reached only a third as often as the position after} 3... Nc6 {is. Here we'll go for a less essayed but nonetheless strong option.}) 4. Bb5+ $1 {Our bishop returns once again to [b5]. We are fine with trading the bishops if they block with ...[Bd7]. Meanwhile, if they block with the [b8]-knight on either square, we will have promising opportunities.} Bd7 {This is the most popular response, being chosen 59% of the time.} (4... Nc6 {is chosen 23% of the time. We should be happy to see this since it allows us the classic favorable exchange on [c6].} 5. Bxc6+ {, the return of the chop chop! After} bxc6 {, we see the old reliable weak doubled c-pawns. This transposes right into the lines discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter in the 4...[d6] variations.}) 5. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 {The knight does not belong here, but that hasn't stopped 74% of Black players from essaying it.} 6. O-O (6. O-O {Here people only play} g6 {and 6...e6 . 6...b5 looks like it is the best move so we will analyze that too.}) 6... b5 {Black immediately stops us from playing [c2]-[c4], which would fix the c-pawn in place and grab some good squares in the center. This is only played 1% of the time so I don't think y'all have much to worry about.} 7. Qe2 {[%csl Rb5] Pressing upon the b-pawn immediately. Black must answer the age-old question, to push or not to push?} b4 $1 {Digging out our [c3]-square, making it hard for us to develop the [b1]-knight. I find it hard to believe someone will play this way. The structure seems overextended and most people myself included would be inclined to secure their light squares first with the incorrect ...[a7]-[a6].} 8. b3 $1 {In playing ...[b4] Black has committed the positional transgression of placing all the pawns on one color. We immediately grip onto the light squares to highlight this deficiency.} g6 9. Bb2 Bg7 10. d3 O-O 11. Nbd2 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ge3e4,Gd2c4] We can play [a2]-[a4] and [e3]-[e4], and install the knight on [c4] with a comfortable game. Objectively, it is only a faint edge, but White's position is definitely more fun.} *

