1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nf6 ({This position is reached only a third as often as the position after} 3... Nc6 {is. Here we'll go for a less essayed but nonetheless strong option.}) 4. Bb5+ $1 {Our bishop returns once again to [b5]. We are fine with trading the bishops if they block with ...[Bd7]. Meanwhile, if they block with the [b8]-knight on either square, we will have promising opportunities.} Bd7 {This is the most popular response, being chosen 59% of the time.} (4... Nc6 {is chosen 23% of the time. We should be happy to see this since it allows us the classic favorable exchange on [c6].} 5. Bxc6+ {, the return of the chop chop! After} bxc6 {, we see the old reliable weak doubled c-pawns. This transposes right into the lines discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter in the 4...[d6] variations.}) 5. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 {The knight does not belong here, but that hasn't stopped 74% of Black players from essaying it.} 6. O-O (6. O-O {Here people only play} g6 {and 6...e6 . 6...b5 looks like it is the best move so we will analyze that too.}) 6... e6 7. c4 d5 8. d3 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rd7c5] Keeping our light squares under control. Here we can observe one of the big issues with the [d7]-knight. It's pointed into the frozen [c5]-pawn, giving an impression of serious disharmony. I suspect this is why the computer likes [c2]-[c4] so much since it fixes the [c5]-pawn in this deleterious position.} Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. e4 {[%cal Gd3c4,Gd3e4,Gd5c4,Gd5e4] We have great play in the center. We will happily recapture with the d-pawn on [c4] or [e4]. Sooner or later Black will have to admit the knight's misplacement on [d7] and reroute it to [c6] via [b8]. By the way, I suspect many players in Black's situation would just put it on [b6], but if it goes there, we can always build a tree against it with [b2]-[b3]. While Black is figuring things out, we will play [e4]-[e5] and begin strumming up play on the queenside with classic plans like [Qe1]-[g3]. [Nc3]-[e4] would also be a great follow-up to [e4]-[e5], but this is only available if Black has already traded off the [d5]-pawn.} *

