1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nf6 ({This position is reached only a third as often as the position after} 3... Nc6 {is. Here we'll go for a less essayed but nonetheless strong option.}) 4. Bb5+ $1 {Our bishop returns once again to [b5]. We are fine with trading the bishops if they block with ...[Bd7]. Meanwhile, if they block with the [b8]-knight on either square, we will have promising opportunities.} Bd7 {This is the most popular response, being chosen 59% of the time.} (4... Nc6 {is chosen 23% of the time. We should be happy to see this since it allows us the classic favorable exchange on [c6].} 5. Bxc6+ {, the return of the chop chop! After} bxc6 {, we see the old reliable weak doubled c-pawns. This transposes right into the lines discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter in the 4...[d6] variations.}) 5. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 {The knight does not belong here, but that hasn't stopped 74% of Black players from essaying it.} 6. O-O (6. O-O {Here people only play} g6 {and 6...e6 . 6...b5 looks like it is the best move so we will analyze that too.}) 6... g6 {Black fianchettoes the bishop.} 7. c4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5][%cal Gc4d5,Gf4e5] The [f4] and [c4]-pawns are like a crab's pincers, gripping the important [d5] and [e5]-squares for dear life.} Bg7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. d3 {[%csl Rd5,Rd7][%cal Ge3e4,Rd8d5] We will play [e4] next and there is nothing Black can do about it. Notice what a huge factor the [d7]-knight's poor placement plays in everything. If it stood anywhere else, the black queen wouldn't be blocked and Black could play ...[d6]-[d5], which would break open the position with equal chances. Here, on the other hand, Black will have to watch like a spectator as we encroach further into the center with our e-pawn.} e6 10. e4 {The computer keeps wanting ...[Nb8], but that is very hard for people to do.} Nb6 {This is obviously ugly, but that won't stop people from venturing for it. The position is tough after all.} 11. Bd2 d5 $2 {This is just a blunder. Whenever Black pushes this, we should look for the best possible execution of [e4]-[e5]. In this case, it's the following:} 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Rf6][%cal Ge5f6] Because [c4] and [e6] have been traded, we have a potent kingside majority combined with the invaluable [e5]-thorn to stick into Black's camp.} Nfd7 14. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5] Threatening [a4]-[a5] to hem Black's pieces in further and hassle the [d5]-pawn. We'd be happy to follow up with [Bd2]-[e1]-[h4] or [Nb5]-[d6]. White is already strategically winning.} *

