1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nc6 4. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5] I like this move for several reasons. Objectively, it's one of the best moves. According to the database, Black immediately loses their path, and when this happens, we can count on a hefty advantage. Third, even if Black traverses the dangerous forest flawlessly, we reach a weird unorthodox version of a Carlsbad with a pawn on [f4] in which our experience should count for the difference. I expect great things from [d4] and will watch its career with great interest. We aim to play [d4]-[d5] to kick the knight out of [c6] with tempo. Black must stop this in one form or another, or immediately be left in the dust.} (4. Bb5 {would be the most natural move for us, pinning the knight on [c6].} Bd7 {is the most popular move at a frequency of 53%. After this, I was not able to find anything good for White. Black's position is harmonious and any trade on [c6] will allow the [d7]-dragon to breathe fire down the diagonal from [c6].}) ({For this reason, I went with the more obscure and less simple} 4. d4 {. Sure, the positions here are close to equal, but the practical chances here compared to those after [d4] are infinitely bigger.}) 4... e6 {This move is rarely seen but stops our idea of [d4]-[d5]. We can respond in several ways here, my preferred being the text move.} 5. c3 {[%cal Gf1d3] We will follow with [Bd3] and complex play in a Stonewall. Note that Black has not particularly dug into the notorious weakness of the Stonewall structure of the [e4]-square. If Black does not play ...[d6]-[d5] soon, we may be able to push forward with [e3]-[e4] at the right time.} *

