1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nc6 4. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5] I like this move for several reasons. Objectively, it's one of the best moves. According to the database, Black immediately loses their path, and when this happens, we can count on a hefty advantage. Third, even if Black traverses the dangerous forest flawlessly, we reach a weird unorthodox version of a Carlsbad with a pawn on [f4] in which our experience should count for the difference. I expect great things from [d4] and will watch its career with great interest. We aim to play [d4]-[d5] to kick the knight out of [c6] with tempo. Black must stop this in one form or another, or immediately be left in the dust.} (4. Bb5 {would be the most natural move for us, pinning the knight on [c6].} Bd7 {is the most popular move at a frequency of 53%. After this, I was not able to find anything good for White. Black's position is harmonious and any trade on [c6] will allow the [d7]-dragon to breathe fire down the diagonal from [c6].}) ({For this reason, I went with the more obscure and less simple} 4. d4 {. Sure, the positions here are close to equal, but the practical chances here compared to those after [d4] are infinitely bigger.}) 4... d5 {This is played in less than 1% of games, but it remains Black's best option. We will analyze it sparingly, as you will likely see it only a few times over a lifetime. Black's structure looks healthy, but it did take 2 moves to get the pawn to [d5]. This position is arrived at from a few other transpositions leading to it, having been seen in 331 games.} 5. dxc5 {Maybe the only time we will play [dxc5] in the entire course. I'm sure other moves were also okay, but this demands more precision than the rest. If Black does not immediately recapture our pawn with ...[e6], we have reasons to hope for an advantage.} e6 $1 {Played 41% of the time. Black will take on [c5] shortly with the bishop.} 6. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] Preparing to respond to ...[Bxc5] with [b2]-[b4].} Bxc5 7. b4 {[%cal Gc1b2] Now assuming we can deal with the weakness of [e3], we might be able to achieve a great bishop on [b2].} Bb6 8. c4 $1 {[%cal Gc4c5] The game is level but only if Black finds a few very unobvious moves. This is another great deal for us − any slip-up gives an easy edge. We threaten [c4]-[c5] to entomb the [b6]-bishop and finally free our [c1]-bishop from the shackles of the [e3]-weakness.} Nf6 9. c5 Bc7 10. Bb2 $14 {[%cal Gf1d3,Ge1g1] This is only slightly better but looks so much more fun for White. Just look at that [b2]-dragon roar! We can play [Bd3], castle kingside, and prepare attacking ideas against Black's castled king.} *

