1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nc6 4. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5] I like this move for several reasons. Objectively, it's one of the best moves. According to the database, Black immediately loses their path, and when this happens, we can count on a hefty advantage. Third, even if Black traverses the dangerous forest flawlessly, we reach a weird unorthodox version of a Carlsbad with a pawn on [f4] in which our experience should count for the difference. I expect great things from [d4] and will watch its career with great interest. We aim to play [d4]-[d5] to kick the knight out of [c6] with tempo. Black must stop this in one form or another, or immediately be left in the dust.} (4. Bb5 {would be the most natural move for us, pinning the knight on [c6].} Bd7 {is the most popular move at a frequency of 53%. After this, I was not able to find anything good for White. Black's position is harmonious and any trade on [c6] will allow the [d7]-dragon to breathe fire down the diagonal from [c6].}) ({For this reason, I went with the more obscure and less simple} 4. d4 {. Sure, the positions here are close to equal, but the practical chances here compared to those after [d4] are infinitely bigger.}) 4... Bg4 $4 {Played 8% of the time and is already lost for Black! Being on move 4, that must be some sort of record. :} 5. d5 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gd5c6] Poking the knight out.} Nb8 6. h3 {Collecting the one decent piece in Black's position.} Bxf3 (6... Bd7 $6 {would just be sad for the [b8]-knight, which after 2 moves still has no obvious path to relevance.}) 7. Qxf3 g6 {The bishop threatens to come to [g7] with some pressure on the long diagonal. [c2]-[c4] wouldn't make complete sense, therefore, as it concedes the chance to ever build concrete against the bishop with [c2]-[c3].} 8. Nc3 Nf6 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gg2g4] Here both [e4] and [g4] claim decisive advantages. As a matter of principle, I aim to go for less orthodox positions in this course, so you can guess which one I'm recommending.} 9. g4 Bg7 10. e4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4,Gg4] The pawn arrives at [e4] after all.} Nbd7 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb7b5] We want to castle queenside and throw our pawns on the kingside, but we should be careful to take into account Black's potential aggression with ...[Rb8] and ...[b7]-[b5].} 11. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c3]} ({We need to be solid with our king's castle.} 11. Be3 $2 {disconnects our queen from the queenside by blocking the third rank.}) 11... Rb8 12. O-O-O a6 {Black's pawns begin to come forward, but we will be first to the punch.} 13. Re1 {This highlights another issue with our bishop going to [e3]. It would block our rook from supporting [e4]-[e5] down the e-file.} b5 14. e5 {Boom!} dxe5 15. fxe5 Ng8 {This is one of those positions that is obviously losing, but the winning breakthrough is always pretty.} 16. e6 {[%cal Ge6d7,Ge6f7] With twin threats to [f7] and [d7].} fxe6 17. dxe6 Ndf6 18. g5 $18 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3f7,Ge6f7] And we can scoop up [f6] whenever we like. It might be prettier just to leave everything on the kingside the way it is... Nothing is getting out soon!} *

