1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nc6 4. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5] I like this move for several reasons. Objectively, it's one of the best moves. According to the database, Black immediately loses their path, and when this happens, we can count on a hefty advantage. Third, even if Black traverses the dangerous forest flawlessly, we reach a weird unorthodox version of a Carlsbad with a pawn on [f4] in which our experience should count for the difference. I expect great things from [d4] and will watch its career with great interest. We aim to play [d4]-[d5] to kick the knight out of [c6] with tempo. Black must stop this in one form or another, or immediately be left in the dust.} (4. Bb5 {would be the most natural move for us, pinning the knight on [c6].} Bd7 {is the most popular move at a frequency of 53%. After this, I was not able to find anything good for White. Black's position is harmonious and any trade on [c6] will allow the [d7]-dragon to breathe fire down the diagonal from [c6].}) ({For this reason, I went with the more obscure and less simple} 4. d4 {. Sure, the positions here are close to equal, but the practical chances here compared to those after [d4] are infinitely bigger.}) 4... Nf6 $2 {This is tried 5% of the time, but does it stop [d4]-[d5] though?} 5. d5 $1 Na5 6. a3 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gb2b4] We immediately threaten to trap the knight with [b2]-[b4].} b6 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ga5b7] Clearing the shameless [b7] for the knight.} 7. Nc3 $16 {[%cal Ge3e4] With [e4], [Bb5]+, [O-O], and a powerful [e5] to follow, White has a close to decisive advantage with the better center and more space.} *

