1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nc6 4. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5] I like this move for several reasons. Objectively, it's one of the best moves. According to the database, Black immediately loses their path, and when this happens, we can count on a hefty advantage. Third, even if Black traverses the dangerous forest flawlessly, we reach a weird unorthodox version of a Carlsbad with a pawn on [f4] in which our experience should count for the difference. I expect great things from [d4] and will watch its career with great interest. We aim to play [d4]-[d5] to kick the knight out of [c6] with tempo. Black must stop this in one form or another, or immediately be left in the dust.} (4. Bb5 {would be the most natural move for us, pinning the knight on [c6].} Bd7 {is the most popular move at a frequency of 53%. After this, I was not able to find anything good for White. Black's position is harmonious and any trade on [c6] will allow the [d7]-dragon to breathe fire down the diagonal from [c6].}) ({For this reason, I went with the more obscure and less simple} 4. d4 {. Sure, the positions here are close to equal, but the practical chances here compared to those after [d4] are infinitely bigger.}) 4... cxd4 5. exd4 $1 {Keeping our pawn high up top in the center. Our [c1]-bishop breathes a sigh of relief, as one of the impediments on the [c1]-[h6] diagonal is already out of the way. Here we continue to threaten a favorable [d4]-[d5]. I am confident about our chances given that here the only two moves to keep things level for Black get a combined play frequency of 24%!} g6 {Black prepares the kingside fianchetto at a frequency of 18%. They still didn't learn the lesson.} 6. d5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gd5c6] Push the knight away while there is still time! The [d6]-pawn might move to [d5] at any moment and the opportunity must be seized.} Nb8 {The most popular here, being played in an overwhelming 72% of games in the database.} 7. c4 {We continue as usual. Compared to similar positions to reach this space advantage with the pawn on [d5], this is only slightly better for us. It's due to the fact that Black will get a normal setup and our 'free move' of [f2]-[f4] doesn't change much about our position and in some ways weakens [e4] to our disadvantage.} Nf6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Be2 {[%csl Rg4] Keeping an eye on [g4].} O-O 10. O-O $14 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gc1e3,Ye7e6,Yd5e6] We will play [Nd4] and [Be3] with a solid space advantage and faint positional edge. If Black ever plays ...[e6], we must always chop to rupture the structure and reveal a weak [d6]-pawn on the opened d-file.} *

