If Black moves the knight, we will have gotten a great free tempo. Black should take, but then again the plan was to secure [d5] for our knight.} exd5 8. Nxd5 Bg7 {The bishop arrives at the fianchetto.} 9. c3 {Notice how both sides' structures have serious problems. The lack of our d-pawn and our far advanced f-pawn have created serious weaknesses on the e-file. But the flip side is that [d5] is a big weak square in Black's camp and [d6] will be quite a weak pawn going forward. The weaknesses should even out as both sides develop. We will observe that both White and Black will do their best to shore up the respective shortcomings in their positions.} Nf6 {Trading off our strong knight on [d5]! Black wants to gain control of this weak square to ultimately push the weak [d6]-pawn there.} 10. Nxf6+ Bxf6 11. Bd3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rc8f5,Gd3f5] Covering the weak square [e4] and preventing ...[Bf5].} (11. Bd3 {Neither} Qe7+ 12. Qe2 {nor 11...Bh4+ 12.Nxh4 Qxh4 13.g3 bothers White, as the king can always find a safe home on [f2] if need be.}) 11... O-O 12. O-O $13 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gd6d5] I will leave you here dear pioneer. The game will get tense. Black will throw the d-pawn weakness forward. On the other hand, we will try to make sense of the structure by throwing our f-pawn forward. The chances of you reaching this in a game is virtually 0 so it is a fine place to let you burn your own trails.} *

