 look suspect, the lead in development gives us at least equal chances.} 7. Bd3 {We will analyze these positions in more detail after 5...d5 .} Be7 (7... Nb4 {is well met by} 8. Bb5+ {, when the knight should better return to [c6] since} Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Ne5 Qd8 11. O-O {followed by [f5] would spell trouble for Black.}) 8. O-O Nf6 ({Once again,} 8... Nb4 {runs into the same issue as one move earlier due to} 9. Bb5+ {, when we can copy-paste the same comment, as it works like a charm here as well.}) 9. a3 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc6b4,Ge7b4] Both the black knight to harass our [d3]-bishop and the black bishop to harass our [c3]-knight might have wanted [b4] to annoy our coordination.} O-O 10. Be3 {[%cal Gf3e5] This secures [d4] preparing [Ne5] to come shortly. The knight on [e5] will stand tall with the support of both the [f4] and [d4]-pawns.} Ne8 11. Ne5 Nd6 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5][%cal Gd6e4,Gd6f5] The knight sits comfortably on this square where it eyes potentially vulnerable [e4] and [f5]-spots.} (11... Nxe5 $2 {If Black ever chops here, we should know which way to recapture.} 12. fxe5 $1 {With a newly opened rook on [f1] and bishop on [e3], our attack will proceed swimmingly. Not to mention the black knight is now permanently prohibited from returning to the healthy defensive square of [f6].}) 12. Qf3 {We continue bringing things over to the kingside.} g6 13. Rae1 {We have a very comfortable setup and will look to expand on the kingside with [g2]-[g4] in the near future. Black can choose a variety of ways to handle this all relating to their f-pawn. Black can leave it on [f7] to keep [e6] secure, push it to [f6] to kick our [e5]-knight out, or push it to [f5] to secure the [e4]-square for their knight.} f5 {Black builds a reversed Stonewall to meet our [e5]-stronghold with one on [e4]. A going word of advice − never take on [e4] because the pawn that arrives there to recapture will be more annoying than the enemy knight. As much as you want to capture, it's usually best to simply play around the [e4]-knight.} 14. Ne2 {The knight moves out of the way of the c-pawn.} Ne4 15. c4 $1 {[%csl Re6][%cal Rd5c4,Gd3c4] Initiating nice tension against [d5]. If Black takes, we can recapture with the bishop with great pressure on the weak [e6]-pawn. We might want to play [c4]-[c5] to gain further ground. But we will only go for this if we know we can reinforce it with [b2]-[b4].} Bd7 {Here our [e5]-knight is better than the [d7]-bishop so wen won't be executing the trade anytime soon.} 16. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gc4d5] Now [cxd5] becomes stronger, as our pieces are much better placed than Black's for action on the c-file.} *

