 to start thinking about whether they should be worried about White's [Nxc6]. This position has been reached 7 times! We will look at all the moves Black has tried here.} Qc7 {[%cal Gc7c6] The queen protects [c6].} 7. Nc3 $5 {This might look strange since our c-pawn probably belongs on [c3] or [c4], but nevertheless, we attack [d5] and might have [Nb5] ideas if Black places the bishop on [d6].} e6 8. Be3 {Notice our knight on [e5] is not budging. We want Black to trade so that we can recapture with the f-pawn.} Nf6 9. a3 $1 {This guarantees our bishop a solid footing on [d3] where it won't be harassed by ...[Nc6]-[b4].} Bd6 ({After} 9... Be7 10. Bd3 {± , we will castle with a very healthy attack. Notice how only a few black pieces can help out with events on the kingside meanwhile, all of our pieces can take part there in the battle. The [e5]-knight and [e6]-[d5] chain form a mountain range that makes the zone exclusive to our heavy pieces while locking those of Black out.}) 10. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7,Gb5d6] This will net us the two bishops.} Qa5+ 11. b4 Qd8 12. Nxd6+ Qxd6 13. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Ge1g1] White has a healthy edge due to the bishop pair and powerful knight on [e5]. We can continue with [O-O] and then some kingside aggression like [Rf1]-[f3]-[g3] or [Qd1]-[f3]-[h3].} *

