 to start thinking about whether they should be worried about White's [Nxc6]. This position has been reached 7 times! We will look at all the moves Black has tried here.} Nh6 $1 {This is another unplayed move that is correct. The knight aims for the vulnerable [f5]-square. Only really strong players will ever play something like this as you need to have a nuanced understanding of the Stonewall structure with pawns on [d4] and [f4] White's position has begun to resemble.} 7. Bd3 Nxd4 {Black can snatch this pawn for the price of giving us a serious initiative.} 8. Be3 $1 {Now, if the knight moves, our [d3]-bishop might swing to [b5] with decisive effect.} Nhf5 {Securing the [d4]-knight for the moment.} 9. Bf2 {Dominating the enemy knight on [f5] from advancing at all. The knights defend one another but therein have some issues. If one has to move, say after we play [g2]-[g4], then the other might drop like a ripe apple.} Nc6 {Retreating while there's still time.} 10. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Rc6,Rd5][%cal Gb5e8,Gd1d8] And the initiative begins. Our bishop pressures [c6] and our queen pressures [d5].} Qd6 (10... Bd7 11. Qxd5 {± and we regain the pawn while continuing to build threats.}) 11. Nc3 {With each move, White attacks the center more and more.} e6 12. g4 $1 {[%csl Rf5] Batting the one good piece back.} Nfe7 13. Qf3 {[%cal Ge1c1] We will castle queenside with wonderful compensation. All of our pieces are active and useful; meanwhile, Black is just holding things together. It is unclear how they even plan to untangle. The knight on [e7] stabilizes [c6] but by the same token, it will not be able to be moved to make way for the [f8]-bishop. If Black ends up castling kingside, our pawns are already ahead in the race on [g4] and [f4] to quickly initiate a pawn storm.} *

