1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. e3 Nc6 4. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4d5] I like this move for several reasons. Objectively, it's one of the best moves. According to the database, Black immediately loses their path, and when this happens, we can count on a hefty advantage. Third, even if Black traverses the dangerous forest flawlessly, we reach a weird unorthodox version of a Carlsbad with a pawn on [f4] in which our experience should count for the difference. I expect great things from [d4] and will watch its career with great interest. We aim to play [d4]-[d5] to kick the knight out of [c6] with tempo. Black must stop this in one form or another, or immediately be left in the dust.} (4. Bb5 {would be the most natural move for us, pinning the knight on [c6].} Bd7 {is the most popular move at a frequency of 53%. After this, I was not able to find anything good for White. Black's position is harmonious and any trade on [c6] will allow the [d7]-dragon to breathe fire down the diagonal from [c6].}) ({For this reason, I went with the more obscure and less simple} 4. d4 {. Sure, the positions here are close to equal, but the practical chances here compared to those after [d4] are infinitely bigger.}) 4... cxd4 5. exd4 $1 {Keeping our pawn high up top in the center. Our [c1]-bishop breathes a sigh of relief, as one of the impediments on the [c1]-[h6] diagonal is already out of the way. Here we continue to threaten a favorable [d4]-[d5]. I am confident about our chances given that here the only two moves to keep things level for Black get a combined play frequency of 24%!} d5 {This is only played 7% of the time, but it is the most logical and strong. We will focus our primary attention on it.} 6. Ne5 $5 {An experienced chess player would look at the moves played by both players and assume they'd never been taught the rules of openings and how speedy development is important. But indeed, this move is one of the best here! It prevents any ...[Bg4] pin and immediately puts the onus on the opponent to start thinking about whether they should be worried about White's [Nxc6]. This position has been reached 7 times! We will look at all the moves Black has tried here.} Nxe5 {This is played in 57% 4 of the 7 of the games. It is already a big strategic mistake and we should be happy to see it appear on the board.} 7. fxe5 {Our [f4]-pawn had been in the way of our bishop and also blocked the f-file. It has transformed from the ugly [f4]-duckling into the beautiful [e5]-swan. It prevents ...[Nf6] and leaves the f-file and [c1]-[h6] diagonal open for White to develop a swift attack with [Bd3] and [O-O].} g6 8. Bd3 Nh6 {The knight has to go for this square, as [f6] is off the table.} 9. Qf3 {[%csl Rd5] Attacking d5 and introducing the threat of 10.Bb5+ Bd7 11.Qxd5 to net a healthy pawn.} a6 {Bb5+ had to be stopped, but White can get an even bigger lead in development now.} 10. O-O {[%csl Rf7,Rh6][%cal Gc1h6,Gf3f7] The threat of [Bxh6] and [Qxf7]+ looms.} Be6 11. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2b3] The knight will head to [b3].} Bg7 12. Nb3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gb3c5] The knight can potentially hop to [c5] to harass the [e6]-bishop.} O-O 13. Bf4 $16 {[%cal Ga1e1,Gc2c3] White will play [c3] to secure the [d4]-pawn and [Rae1]. Black has nothing to do with their position. Black's structure is solid so it will be hard to crack but sooner or later something should begin to falter. The [h6]-knight is not well placed but as long as it can come to [f5], we can't target it with [Qe3]. Perhaps the best idea is building a tree against it with [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4] and then pressuring with [Qe3].} *

