1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({These systems are not as popular as those with} 2... d6 {, but they still deserve consideration. Keep in mind that in many of these positions, ...[d7]-[d5] is the most popular move, but it will be ignored in this chapter, as those positions revert straight into lines covered in the chapters on the ...[d5] systems.}) 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Nf6 {can also be tried first, but it will likely transpose to 3...Nc6 or if Black plays ...[d5] soon, then back to the ...[d5] systems. In either case, this won't lead to anything not covered elsewhere in the course.}) 4. b3 (4. Bb5 $2 {was what I wanted to work, but Black can ruin all our plans of chopping with} Nge7 $1 {and we'll never rupture any structure! If anything, Black is better, as they will be able to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] fast.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bb5 {The black knight left [g8] so ...[Nge7] is no longer possible here. We will look at some very rare tries for Black that don't involve ...[d7]-[d5], which would take us back into the ...[d5] systems.} Be7 (5... a6 $2 {is played second most at 23%.} 6. Bxc6 {leads to a great position discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter.}) 6. Bxc6 bxc6 7. c4 $1 {This transposes to a position analyzed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter as well.} *

