1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({These systems are not as popular as those with} 2... d6 {, but they still deserve consideration. Keep in mind that in many of these positions, ...[d7]-[d5] is the most popular move, but it will be ignored in this chapter, as those positions revert straight into lines covered in the chapters on the ...[d5] systems.}) 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Nf6 {can also be tried first, but it will likely transpose to 3...Nc6 or if Black plays ...[d5] soon, then back to the ...[d5] systems. In either case, this won't lead to anything not covered elsewhere in the course.}) 4. b3 (4. Bb5 $2 {was what I wanted to work, but Black can ruin all our plans of chopping with} Nge7 $1 {and we'll never rupture any structure! If anything, Black is better, as they will be able to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] fast.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bb5 {The black knight left [g8] so ...[Nge7] is no longer possible here. We will look at some very rare tries for Black that don't involve ...[d7]-[d5], which would take us back into the ...[d5] systems.} Qc7 {[%cal Gc7c6] The queen protects against positional ruin after White's [Bxc6]. This is quite uncommon but all the other moves transpose to other chapters.} (5... a6 $2 {is played second most at 23%.} 6. Bxc6 {leads to a great position discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter.}) 6. Bb2 a6 {This is played 40% of the time. Our bishop must take a decision: to chop or to retreat.} 7. Bxc6 Qxc6 {Unfortunately, we haven't elicited any structural weakening in Black's structure. But they have wasted a lot of time with their queen and a-pawn. The game is still equal.} 8. Qe2 b5 {[%cal Gc8b7] Preparing to place the bishop on [b7].} 9. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga4b5] Crunching on the structure. We'd like to trade on [b5] and [a8] and then scoop up [b5].} b4 $2 {[%csl Yb1,Yc4][%cal Rb5b4] A big strategic blunder. Our [b1]-knight can rejoice that it will eventually sit on the [c4]-square.} 10. d3 Bb7 11. e4 $16 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Gf3e5] Our knights will swarm the strong squares of [e5] and [c4]. White has a comfortable edge. Notice Black can still fight against our [Nb1]-[d2]-[c4] maneuver with ...[d7]-[d5], but then this would grant our other knight full dominion of the [e5]-square, as ...[d7]-[d6] would no longer be possible.} *

