1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({These systems are not as popular as those with} 2... d6 {, but they still deserve consideration. Keep in mind that in many of these positions, ...[d7]-[d5] is the most popular move, but it will be ignored in this chapter, as those positions revert straight into lines covered in the chapters on the ...[d5] systems.}) 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Nf6 {can also be tried first, but it will likely transpose to 3...Nc6 or if Black plays ...[d5] soon, then back to the ...[d5] systems. In either case, this won't lead to anything not covered elsewhere in the course.}) 4. b3 (4. Bb5 $2 {was what I wanted to work, but Black can ruin all our plans of chopping with} Nge7 $1 {and we'll never rupture any structure! If anything, Black is better, as they will be able to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] fast.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bb5 {The black knight left [g8] so ...[Nge7] is no longer possible here. We will look at some very rare tries for Black that don't involve ...[d7]-[d5], which would take us back into the ...[d5] systems.} Qc7 {[%cal Gc7c6] The queen protects against positional ruin after White's [Bxc6]. This is quite uncommon but all the other moves transpose to other chapters.} (5... a6 $2 {is played second most at 23%.} 6. Bxc6 {leads to a great position discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter.}) 6. Bb2 a6 {This is played 40% of the time. Our bishop must take a decision: to chop or to retreat.} 7. Bxc6 Qxc6 {Unfortunately, we haven't elicited any structural weakening in Black's structure. But they have wasted a lot of time with their queen and a-pawn. The game is still equal.} 8. Qe2 b5 {[%cal Gc8b7] Preparing to place the bishop on [b7].} 9. a4 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga4b5] Crunching on the structure. We'd like to trade on [b5] and [a8] and then scoop up [b5].} Bb7 {[%cal Rf3e5,Gc6g2,Gb7a8] The bishop develops, defending the rook on [a8] at the same time. [Ne5] drops the [g2]-pawn so we'll hold off on it for the moment.} 10. O-O Be7 11. Ne5 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Ge2g2,Gg1g2] Now [g2] is defended enough for us to launch forward like this.} Qb6 12. axb5 axb5 13. Na3 {[%csl Rb5] Nudging the b-pawn forward; you can already guess where our knight wants to go.} b4 14. Nac4 Qd8 (14... Qb5 $4 15. Nd6+ {+- and the damsel's days are numbered on [b5].}) 15. Ng4 $13 {[%cal Yd7d5,Yc4e5,Gb2h8] Pressuring [f6] and opening up the [b2]-dragon's scope to light the long diagonal ablaze. Notice our knight on [c4] sits comfortably. If Black ever pushes it away with ...[d7]-[d5], Black will be blocking the [b7]-bishop and allowing us to enter [e5] without fear of any ...[d7]-[d6] in the future. Black does have the bishop pair to fully balance these factors and so the game is equally double-edged.} *

