1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({These systems are not as popular as those with} 2... d6 {, but they still deserve consideration. Keep in mind that in many of these positions, ...[d7]-[d5] is the most popular move, but it will be ignored in this chapter, as those positions revert straight into lines covered in the chapters on the ...[d5] systems.}) 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Nf6 {can also be tried first, but it will likely transpose to 3...Nc6 or if Black plays ...[d5] soon, then back to the ...[d5] systems. In either case, this won't lead to anything not covered elsewhere in the course.}) 4. b3 (4. Bb5 $2 {was what I wanted to work, but Black can ruin all our plans of chopping with} Nge7 $1 {and we'll never rupture any structure! If anything, Black is better, as they will be able to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] fast.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bb5 {The black knight left [g8] so ...[Nge7] is no longer possible here. We will look at some very rare tries for Black that don't involve ...[d7]-[d5], which would take us back into the ...[d5] systems.} Qc7 {[%cal Gc7c6] The queen protects against positional ruin after White's [Bxc6]. This is quite uncommon but all the other moves transpose to other chapters.} (5... a6 $2 {is played second most at 23%.} 6. Bxc6 {leads to a great position discussed in the Sicilian Two Knights chapter.}) 6. Bb2 Be7 {The most popular move here at a frequency of 41%.} (6... d5 {(looks like it would have been analyzed in the French Setup chapter ...[d5] systems, but it wasn't, as ...[Qc7] on move 6 isn't common. However, as we will see, natural moves transpose back into those systems.)} 7. O-O Be7 8. Ne5 Bd7 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 {and we are in the variation 8...Qc7 9.O-O Be7 covered in the French Setup chapter.}) 7. Ne5 $1 {Black's only move to fight for borderline equality is the hard-to-find ...[Na5]. However, this was never played in the 18 games to reach this position. Instead, Black played inaccurately in 100% of the games to reach this position. We will analyze two logical and natural moves that have been tried, including ...[Na5].} Na5 $1 {The knight sidesteps the entire game to spectate on things from the edge of the board for a while. If your opponents play this, they are probably using a computer.} 8. Qf3 {Our queen enters the fray.} a6 9. Be2 d6 {Black beats our pieces back in hopes of being able to return the knight to [c6] with a normal position soon enough.} 10. Ng4 $13 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gg4f6] We have nice pressure along the long diagonal and especially at the [f6]-nexus. The game remains level if Black plays perfectly, but that's a tall task. Here, for instance, they must play the counterintuitive ...[Qd8] to hold the balance. I like White's chances. We will see whether we can wreck the structure on [f6], and go on to castle and play [Nc3] with healthy development.} *

