1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({These systems are not as popular as those with} 2... d6 {, but they still deserve consideration. Keep in mind that in many of these positions, ...[d7]-[d5] is the most popular move, but it will be ignored in this chapter, as those positions revert straight into lines covered in the chapters on the ...[d5] systems.}) 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Nf6 {can also be tried first, but it will likely transpose to 3...Nc6 or if Black plays ...[d5] soon, then back to the ...[d5] systems. In either case, this won't lead to anything not covered elsewhere in the course.}) 4. b3 (4. Bb5 $2 {was what I wanted to work, but Black can ruin all our plans of chopping with} Nge7 $1 {and we'll never rupture any structure! If anything, Black is better, as they will be able to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] fast.}) 4... b6 {Played 4% of the time; the black bishop wants to fianchetto on the healthy [b7]-square.} 5. Bb2 Bb7 {Stockfish considers Black's setup as extremely healthy. Notice our [Bb5xc6] chopping ideas just threaten to hand Black the bishop pair and a strong dragon from [c6]. We have to play accurately to get a completely level position.} (5... Bb7 {The odds of reaching this are very low and even lower are those of playing an experienced player who will have analyzed these obscure positions in depth. For this reason, feel free to blaze your own trails with some of the slightly less strong moves like} 6. Qe2 {, 6.Be2 , or 6.Bd3 .}) 6. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2] It's double fianchetto time!} Nf6 7. Bg2 d5 8. O-O Be7 9. Ne5 $13 {[%csl Gb2,Gg2][%cal Gd2d3,Gb1d2] A complicated struggle awaits. Our bishops compensate for the lack of any pawns in the center. We can continue with [d2]-[d3] and [Nd2]. The game is equal and having more experience than your opponent in these positions will guarantee you the practical edge.} *

