1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({These systems are not as popular as those with} 2... d6 {, but they still deserve consideration. Keep in mind that in many of these positions, ...[d7]-[d5] is the most popular move, but it will be ignored in this chapter, as those positions revert straight into lines covered in the chapters on the ...[d5] systems.}) 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Nf6 {can also be tried first, but it will likely transpose to 3...Nc6 or if Black plays ...[d5] soon, then back to the ...[d5] systems. In either case, this won't lead to anything not covered elsewhere in the course.}) 4. b3 (4. Bb5 $2 {was what I wanted to work, but Black can ruin all our plans of chopping with} Nge7 $1 {and we'll never rupture any structure! If anything, Black is better, as they will be able to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] fast.}) 4... Nge7 {This is only played 4% of the time, but it's not completely incorrect. Just slightly dubious.} 5. Bb2 d5 {Even though the bishop on [f8] has no way to get out, the position remains equal. Black plans to reinforce [g7] with ...[Nf5] at some point and then play ...[Be7] and ...[O-O].} 6. Bd3 {It might look like we're preparing to chop on [f5] if a knight appears there, but actually, this is just a good position for our bishop. No chopping will be done. We will look at Black's two most popular moves in this position. Only 200 games have reached this position so just like all other frontiers covered in this course, you are welcome to do your own independent analysis and blaze other trails.} Nf5 {This enjoys a frequency of 16%. The knight stands well here.} 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Ne5 $5 {The knight advances into the center once again. We are happy to chop on [c6] and ruin the opponent's structure a bit. But what's the plan if they trade on [e5]?} Nxe5 9. fxe5 {[%cal Ge1g1] Our pawn on [e5] might look ugly, but it segments the board in 2 by locking the central pawns. We'll have a free hand on the kingside and can quickly whip up an initiative after Black plays some natural moves.} O-O $6 (9... d4 $1 {was better but not by any means obvious.} 10. Ne4 {∞ and the position remains super complex. If Black snatches the pawn on [e3], we can respond with [Qe2] with a burning initiative. Our king could be good on either side here depending on how things shake out.}) 10. O-O g6 {Fortifying the diagonal against the [d3]-dragon.} (10... b6 11. Nxd5 $1 {± is a neat trick to remember; ...[Qxd5] runs into [e3]-[e4] and ...[exd5] is met with [Bxf5].}) (10... Bd7 $2 {drops a pawn to the trick shot} 11. Nxd5 {± .}) 11. Ne2 $14 {[%cal Ge2f4,Gd1g4] The knight will transfer to [f4] and the queen will zoom to [g4]. We have comfortable kingside play.} *

