1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({These systems are not as popular as those with} 2... d6 {, but they still deserve consideration. Keep in mind that in many of these positions, ...[d7]-[d5] is the most popular move, but it will be ignored in this chapter, as those positions revert straight into lines covered in the chapters on the ...[d5] systems.}) 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Nf6 {can also be tried first, but it will likely transpose to 3...Nc6 or if Black plays ...[d5] soon, then back to the ...[d5] systems. In either case, this won't lead to anything not covered elsewhere in the course.}) 4. b3 (4. Bb5 $2 {was what I wanted to work, but Black can ruin all our plans of chopping with} Nge7 $1 {and we'll never rupture any structure! If anything, Black is better, as they will be able to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] fast.}) 4... Nge7 {This is only played 4% of the time, but it's not completely incorrect. Just slightly dubious.} 5. Bb2 d5 {Even though the bishop on [f8] has no way to get out, the position remains equal. Black plans to reinforce [g7] with ...[Nf5] at some point and then play ...[Be7] and ...[O-O].} 6. Bd3 {It might look like we're preparing to chop on [f5] if a knight appears there, but actually, this is just a good position for our bishop. No chopping will be done. We will look at Black's two most popular moves in this position. Only 200 games have reached this position so just like all other frontiers covered in this course, you are welcome to do your own independent analysis and blaze other trails.} Ng6 {The knight does not look great here. It is away from the center and already quite dominated by White's [f4]-pawn. However, we should not get comfortable and let Black's setup begin to justify itself after something like ...[f7]-[f6]. Instead, we should chase the knight. Immediately!} 7. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] A novelty in this position; [h4]-[h5] is a very uncomfortable threat. We will throw the pawn forward and obstruct Black's coordination and development.} h5 $2 {This stops [h5] but removes some essential defense from the [g6]-knight.} 8. Bxg6 {Choppin' up the kingside.} fxg6 {[%csl Re6,Rg6,Rg7] Black's kingside is ruined. Our bishop on [b2] will dominate the diagonal, as Black can no longer stunt it with ...[f7]-[f6]. Our knight also gets some great outposts on the [e5] and [g5]-squares. And of course, [e6], [g6], and [g7] have become clear targets. A great deal indeed for our [d3]-bishop.} 9. Qe2 $16 {[%csl Re5,Re6,Rg5,Rg6,Rg7][%cal Gf3g5,Gf3e5,Gb2h8] Black is stuck! The computer recommends ...[Kf7] as Black's best move. Try finding that in a blitz game! We are close to winning. Some ideas are [Qd3] or [Qf2]-[g3] to target [g6] and castling kingside. [e3]-[e4] to open up the e-file could work but only if Black can't play ...[d5]-[d4] for some reason.} *

