1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({These systems are not as popular as those with} 2... d6 {, but they still deserve consideration. Keep in mind that in many of these positions, ...[d7]-[d5] is the most popular move, but it will be ignored in this chapter, as those positions revert straight into lines covered in the chapters on the ...[d5] systems.}) 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Nf6 {can also be tried first, but it will likely transpose to 3...Nc6 or if Black plays ...[d5] soon, then back to the ...[d5] systems. In either case, this won't lead to anything not covered elsewhere in the course.}) 4. b3 (4. Bb5 $2 {was what I wanted to work, but Black can ruin all our plans of chopping with} Nge7 $1 {and we'll never rupture any structure! If anything, Black is better, as they will be able to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] fast.}) 4... Be7 {[%cal Ge7f6]} ({Played 5% of the time. The only independent value of this move over} 4... Nf6 {is to play an early ...[Be7]-[f6] or ...[f7]-[f6].}) 5. Bb2 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gb2g7] Shooting at [g7] immediately.} f6 {[%csl Re7][%cal Rg8e7] This is rarely played at a frequency of only 2%, but that doesn't make it bad. Unfortunately though, now the bishop on [e7] blocks ...[Nge7], so we can say hi to an old friend.} 6. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5c6] Hello again, bishop chop!} Qc7 {Defending the chop on [c6]. Here Stockfish pointed out a really interesting idea to complicate the struggle.} 7. Ng5 $5 {[%cal Rf6g5,Gb2g7] If they take on [g5], we scoop up the goodies on [g7] and [h8]! But what is the knight doing there exactly? We're preparing to meet ...[d7]-[d5] with [Qg4].} d5 8. O-O Bd7 9. Bd3 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Re8c8,Gg5f7] A second point of [Ng5] is revealed, castling queenside is impossible for Black on account of [Ng5]-[f7]. Black must safeguard [h7] against [Bxh7] and [Nxh7] ideas.} g6 10. Qg4 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gg4e6] Attacking [e6].} f5 {[%csl Re5,Ge6] Pushing the queen away. Black's [e6]-pawn is happy, but the weakened [e5]-square is annoyed.} 11. Qh3 $13 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb1c3,Gd3b5,Gc6e5] The position remains extremely complex and balanced. Black will defend the [h8]-mango with ...[Nf6], ...[Bf6] or ...[e6]-[e5]. We should develop with [Nc3] or [Na3]. [Bb5] to chop on [c6] might be good to secure control over the critical [e5]-square.} *

