1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 ({These systems are not as popular as those with} 2... d6 {, but they still deserve consideration. Keep in mind that in many of these positions, ...[d7]-[d5] is the most popular move, but it will be ignored in this chapter, as those positions revert straight into lines covered in the chapters on the ...[d5] systems.}) 3. e3 Nc6 (3... Nf6 {can also be tried first, but it will likely transpose to 3...Nc6 or if Black plays ...[d5] soon, then back to the ...[d5] systems. In either case, this won't lead to anything not covered elsewhere in the course.}) 4. b3 (4. Bb5 $2 {was what I wanted to work, but Black can ruin all our plans of chopping with} Nge7 $1 {and we'll never rupture any structure! If anything, Black is better, as they will be able to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5] fast.}) 4... Be7 {[%cal Ge7f6]} ({Played 5% of the time. The only independent value of this move over} 4... Nf6 {is to play an early ...[Be7]-[f6] or ...[f7]-[f6].}) 5. Bb2 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gb2g7] Shooting at [g7] immediately.} f6 {[%csl Re7][%cal Rg8e7] This is rarely played at a frequency of only 2%, but that doesn't make it bad. Unfortunately though, now the bishop on [e7] blocks ...[Nge7], so we can say hi to an old friend.} 6. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5c6] Hello again, bishop chop!} Nh6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 {Despite appearances, this version of the Bird/Rossolimo hybrid is not that bad for Black.} 8. d3 d5 9. Qe2 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ge2e3] Securing [e3]. The king looks like it will be safer on the queenside so we will slowly prepare castling that way.} O-O 10. Nbd2 {[%cal Ge1c1]} a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] It is essential to not allow ...[a5]-[a4xb3]. Our king doesn't want to move to a house with a leak in the ceiling after all.} 11. a4 $14 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ge1c1] Freezing [a5] in place. White can castle queenside with confidence. Once our king is settled we can begin pawn advances on the e- and g-files with [e3]-[e4] and [h2]-[h3] + [g2]-[g4].} *

