1. f4 c5 (1... Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 {transposes.}) 2. Nf3 Nf6 {After I sent in my files for this course, in December 2023, and in between the publication of this course in July 2024, GM Ganguly released a good course with some very strong recommendations on how to deal with the Bird. His recommendations are some of the most testing against our entire setup, and in a few cases, it might be objectively best for us to aim for a repetition. Before you get worried about what this might mean, I want to assure you that the Bird is still 100% playable. If I could critique Ganguly's recommendation it would be as follows: his chapter is 19 variations for a system Black will only see 1% of the time. I don't know anyone who would memorize 19 long variations for a system they would see 1% of the time, just to get ⩱ according to him, I will show lines that actively contest equality. Back when I was playing regularly as a GM, I would never memorize 19 variations for something as offbeat as the Bird the best opening in the land. The lines are also not particularly obvious by any stretch. The variations recommend this peculiar setup with ...[c5] followed by ...[d6] and then ...[e5]. In sum, do not expect to EVER see this line in practice unless: Your opponent knows you play the Bird and has intentionally prepared against you. Your opponent is an opening theoretician who spends time memorizing lines at home to get ⩱ against rare offbeat openings. I have played the Bird now for 15 months and I think I have seen this setup 2 or 3 times in the 2000 online games I have played against people in the upper echelons.} ({Back when I was making this course, I deliberately avoided covering} 2... Nf6 {since it is only played 2% of the time. Feel free to study this chapter and master the ideas, but the reality is that this chapter is more of a thought experiment and case study in interesting structures than anything that will ever affect your games over the board. I want to emphatically say that you are literally wasting your time if you are under 2300 FIDE and trying to memorize this chapter. It is not worth it, trust me. This chapter exists to guarantee that the Bird is playable at all levels and among all time controls. Unless you are playing IM and GM level opponents in classical time controls, you will likely never encounter the variations below in your entire life.}) 3. b3 {We will continue with the queenside fianchetto. At the early stages of this opening line, the computer does insist that Black is slightly better. But no worries, we will simply go deep enough into the variations to get playable equality.} g6 (3... d5 4. e3 {and we're back in our famous original repertoire.}) 4. Bb2 Bg7 5. e3 Nc6 $6 {One of the main reasons I am not phased at all by Ganguly's recommendation is the sheer impracticality of it all. It is easy for Black to mix up the moves and play the knight out right now.} 6. Bb5 $10 {We don't have to lose a tempo on this move compared to the lines in which our bishop develops to [e2] first. We are playing such positions up a tempo and enjoy an equal game.} *

