ing all day to sit on this position!}) 8. Bb5 $1 {The name's 46. Depth 46. Agent [c6]-chop returns after much delay. Yes, unfortunately, we have to waste the tempo, but there was no way to objectively sidestep this without risk. If you want to try to get the bishop here in one go, then check out my alternative 6.a4!?! , (which while not completely sound will likely work against an unprepared opponent. The text threatens to take on [c6] and the computer here asserts -0.2, which is technically equal. And that's assuming they play computer best moves which is most likely not going to happen. Guess what the best move for Black here is according to the computer. Take your time...)} Qc7 {Defending the knight on [c6] and avoiding any worsening of the structure after White's [Bxc6].} 9. Bxc6 Qxc6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black keeps the structure healthy and aims to play ...[b7]-[b5] shortly, which would seize some good space.} (9... bxc6 {, it doesn't make any sense to double the pawns in this way.} 10. d3 {⩲ and White has the same old ideas of [Qe2], [Nbd2], and [e3]-[e4] with a slight edge.}) 10. a4 $1 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga4b5] Preventing Black from pushing ...[b7]-[b5].} b6 (10... a6 {, Black is digging in to push through ...[b7]-[b5], we mustn't allow this.} 11. a5 $1 {⇆ , digging into [b6] so if Black pushes the b-pawn to [b5], we can take en passant.}) 11. d3 Bb7 12. Qe2 $132 {[%cal Gb1d2,Ge3e4] We will play [Nbd2] and [e3]-[e4]. The computer favors Black infinitesimally but realistically, this will evaporate in the light of the 1st player's better experience. Both sides have a tricky game ahead. Black has the bishop pair, but if Black moves any pawn recklessly, they could easily cede the white knights some great outposts.} *

