ing all day to sit on this position!}) 8. Bb5 $1 {The name's 46. Depth 46. Agent [c6]-chop returns after much delay. Yes, unfortunately, we have to waste the tempo, but there was no way to objectively sidestep this without risk. If you want to try to get the bishop here in one go, then check out my alternative 6.a4!?! , (which while not completely sound will likely work against an unprepared opponent. The text threatens to take on [c6] and the computer here asserts -0.2, which is technically equal. And that's assuming they play computer best moves which is most likely not going to happen. Guess what the best move for Black here is according to the computer. Take your time...)} Bf5 {[%csl Rf5] The bishop makes little sense here. It is waiting to get kicked by an eventual [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4].} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. d3 $14 {[%cal Gd1e2,Gb1d2] We will play for [Qe2], [Nbd2] our knight wants to sit on [c4] eventually and [e3]-[e4]. If Black plays ...[a7]-[a5], we will respond in kind with [a2]-[a4], fixing the [a5]-pawn as a permanent weakness.} (10. h3 $1 {The computer is adamant this is slightly better than 10.d3 , but it makes little sense and is based on complex counterintuitive ideas.}) *

