ing all day to sit on this position!}) 8. Bb5 $1 {The name's 46. Depth 46. Agent [c6]-chop returns after much delay. Yes, unfortunately, we have to waste the tempo, but there was no way to objectively sidestep this without risk. If you want to try to get the bishop here in one go, then check out my alternative 6.a4!?! , (which while not completely sound will likely work against an unprepared opponent. The text threatens to take on [c6] and the computer here asserts -0.2, which is technically equal. And that's assuming they play computer best moves which is most likely not going to happen. Guess what the best move for Black here is according to the computer. Take your time...)} Bg4 {Black allows the favorable chop.} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 {We arrive at a position very similar to that analyzed in the Sicilian section.} 10. h3 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh3g4] Forcing Black's hand.} Bxf3 11. Qxf3 $14 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge3e4,Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Yd6d5,Yb1c3,Yc3a4] White has a slight edge. We will play [d2]-[d3] and aim for [e3]-[e4]. We can move the knight to [c4] via [d2] or, if Black covers [c4] with ...[d6]-[d5], to [a4] to target [c5].} *

