1. f4 c5 (1... Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 {transposes.}) 2. Nf3 Nf6 {After I sent in my files for this course, in December 2023, and in between the publication of this course in July 2024, GM Ganguly released a good course with some very strong recommendations on how to deal with the Bird. His recommendations are some of the most testing against our entire setup, and in a few cases, it might be objectively best for us to aim for a repetition. Before you get worried about what this might mean, I want to assure you that the Bird is still 100% playable. If I could critique Ganguly's recommendation it would be as follows: his chapter is 19 variations for a system Black will only see 1% of the time. I don't know anyone who would memorize 19 long variations for a system they would see 1% of the time, just to get ⩱ according to him, I will show lines that actively contest equality. Back when I was playing regularly as a GM, I would never memorize 19 variations for something as offbeat as the Bird the best opening in the land. The lines are also not particularly obvious by any stretch. The variations recommend this peculiar setup with ...[c5] followed by ...[d6] and then ...[e5]. In sum, do not expect to EVER see this line in practice unless: Your opponent knows you play the Bird and has intentionally prepared against you. Your opponent is an opening theoretician who spends time memorizing lines at home to get ⩱ against rare offbeat openings. I have played the Bird now for 15 months and I think I have seen this setup 2 or 3 times in the 2000 online games I have played against people in the upper echelons.} ({Back when I was making this course, I deliberately avoided covering} 2... Nf6 {since it is only played 2% of the time. Feel free to study this chapter and master the ideas, but the reality is that this chapter is more of a thought experiment and case study in interesting structures than anything that will ever affect your games over the board. I want to emphatically say that you are literally wasting your time if you are under 2300 FIDE and trying to memorize this chapter. It is not worth it, trust me. This chapter exists to guarantee that the Bird is playable at all levels and among all time controls. Unless you are playing IM and GM level opponents in classical time controls, you will likely never encounter the variations below in your entire life.}) 3. b3 {We will continue with the queenside fianchetto. At the early stages of this opening line, the computer does insist that Black is slightly better. But no worries, we will simply go deep enough into the variations to get playable equality.} g6 (3... d5 4. e3 {and we're back in our famous original repertoire.}) 4. Bb2 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 {I want to emphasize that your opponent will be extremely likely to play ...[d5] and revert back to classic ...[d5] structures. Looking at this position, I was shocked at how strong Ganguly's recommendation of ...[d6] and ...[e5] is. It is not obvious at all that Black should be playing for ...[d6] and ...[e5]. Even if your opponent has memorized this far, I could see a lot of opponents who have bought Ganguly's course simply playing ...[d5] and transposing to our Fianchetto chapter.} (6. a4 $6 {avoids losing the tempo on the [Be2]-[b5] stuff, which occurs later in the main variation. This isn't technically sound though and with best play, Black is slightly better. The idea is to meet Black's} Nc6 {with [Bb5]. I will work on this more in the future if this variation picks up in popularity. For now, this chapter is already bigger than it has to be.}) 6... Nc6 7. O-O d6 (7... d6 {This is what Ganguly recommends and here he only looks at} 8. Qe1 {and 8.c4 , both of which lead to slightly better outcomes for Black. Black is playing for ...[e7]-[e5], which if it is achieved, it often leads to a solid edge for the second player. Up to depth 41 Mr. Stockfish insists that 8.c4 is best, but at higher depths, it begins to change the tune. Yes, I left my computer running all day to sit on this position!}) 8. Bb5 $1 {The name's 46. Depth 46. Agent [c6]-chop returns after much delay. Yes, unfortunately, we have to waste the tempo, but there was no way to objectively sidestep this without risk. If you want to try to get the bishop here in one go, then check out my alternative 6.a4!?! , (which while not completely sound will likely work against an unprepared opponent. The text threatens to take on [c6] and the computer here asserts -0.2, which is technically equal. And that's assuming they play computer best moves which is most likely not going to happen. Guess what the best move for Black here is according to the computer. Take your time...)} a6 {Black allows a favorable exchange.} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. d3 $14 {And we are in a normal post-chop structure of the Sicilian. Check other chapters for more insight on how to handle such positions. White has a comfortable edge.} *

