ing all day to sit on this position!}) 8. Bb5 $1 {The name's 46. Depth 46. Agent [c6]-chop returns after much delay. Yes, unfortunately, we have to waste the tempo, but there was no way to objectively sidestep this without risk. If you want to try to get the bishop here in one go, then check out my alternative 6.a4!?! , (which while not completely sound will likely work against an unprepared opponent. The text threatens to take on [c6] and the computer here asserts -0.2, which is technically equal. And that's assuming they play computer best moves which is most likely not going to happen. Guess what the best move for Black here is according to the computer. Take your time...)} Bd7 9. a4 {Securing [b5]. Sooner or later Black will want to play ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5], making this waiting move useful.} a6 {Forcing our hand. We have to chop.} 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. a5 $1 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ga5b6] White digs into the [b6]-square and guarantees Black's pawn will not get to [b5]. This is very significant for a few reasons. First, the [b1]-knight can aim to sit comfortably on [c4] since if Black ever plays ...[d5] that gives our knight the fantastic [e5]-square. Also now that our pawn is not on [a4] any longer, Black cannot try to rip the a-file open with ...[b7]-[b5].} (11. Qe2 $2 {We cannot continue calmly like this. After} b5 {∓ , Black's bishops are great and White's queenside is getting opened. One particular issue is that our [b1]-knight has no clear place to situate itself on.}) 11... Qc7 12. Qe2 $132 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Gd2d3,Gb1d2,Gd2c4] We will slowly work to bring our knight to [c4] after [d2]-[d3] and [Nb1]-[d2]. Black should aim for ...[e5] shortly, after which we can trade and solidify our control on the light squares with [e3]-[e4] assuming it's defended by [d3]!. The game is balanced.} *

