ing all day to sit on this position!}) 8. Bb5 $1 {The name's 46. Depth 46. Agent [c6]-chop returns after much delay. Yes, unfortunately, we have to waste the tempo, but there was no way to objectively sidestep this without risk. If you want to try to get the bishop here in one go, then check out my alternative 6.a4!?! , (which while not completely sound will likely work against an unprepared opponent. The text threatens to take on [c6] and the computer here asserts -0.2, which is technically equal. And that's assuming they play computer best moves which is most likely not going to happen. Guess what the best move for Black here is according to the computer. Take your time...)} e5 {This could easily happen if our opponents weren't paying attention to our last move.} 9. Bxc6 {[%csl Re5] Taking the important knight and undermining the [e5]-pawn's defense.} bxc6 10. fxe5 Ng4 {[%cal Gg7b2] Introducing a pin along the long diagonal. We will have to cede the extra pawn back.} ({After} 10... dxe5 11. Bxe5 {± , White is just a solid pawn up.}) 11. Qe1 dxe5 12. e4 $14 {[%cal Gh2h3] White threatens to win the [e5]-pawn with [h2]-[h3], when the knight on [g4] is kicked from its defense. Black's c-pawns are weak and so is the [c4]-square. Long term we should play [d2]-[d3] and aim our [b1]-knight at [c4] via [b1]. We have a nice edge.} *

