ing all day to sit on this position!}) 8. Bb5 $1 {The name's 46. Depth 46. Agent [c6]-chop returns after much delay. Yes, unfortunately, we have to waste the tempo, but there was no way to objectively sidestep this without risk. If you want to try to get the bishop here in one go, then check out my alternative 6.a4!?! , (which while not completely sound will likely work against an unprepared opponent. The text threatens to take on [c6] and the computer here asserts -0.2, which is technically equal. And that's assuming they play computer best moves which is most likely not going to happen. Guess what the best move for Black here is according to the computer. Take your time...)} Na5 $1 {Will your opponents ever play this in a real game!?!?!?!?!?!?!?!? I don't expect it. The knight sidesteps the bishop threat and moves to a seemingly useless square.} 9. Be2 Bf5 $1 {Black declines the repetition.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge3e4] A weird placement of the knight. But we are playing alien chess here. We aim to follow with [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4].} (10. c4 {could be worth researching. In the future, I will include updates to this as an alternative as well. Black is slightly better, but this will not be a game between 2 engines. I don't know a single person who can honestly say they've studied this structure and are confident in it. Therefore, practice and experience are key.}) (10. h3 {, cutting out ...[Ng4] ideas and waiting to see what Black commits to. Black should be slightly better here but again, this is such a unique structure that the White player with more experience should have a fair share of the chances.}) 10... Nc6 11. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] We're back for another chance of the chop!} Re8 $2 {A serious error.} 12. Bxc6 {The revenge of the chop!} bxc6 13. Qe2 $14 {[%cal Gc3a4,Gd2d3,Ge3e4] White has a serious edge. We will put the knight on [a4] to open up the bishop's lane and then gradually play for [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4].} *

