 literally wasting your time if you are under 2300 FIDE and trying to memorize this chapter. It is not worth it, trust me. This chapter exists to guarantee that the Bird is playable at all levels and among all time controls. Unless you are playing IM and GM level opponents in classical time controls, you will likely never encounter the variations below in your entire life.}) 3. b3 {We will continue with the queenside fianchetto. At the early stages of this opening line, the computer does insist that Black is slightly better. But no worries, we will simply go deep enough into the variations to get playable equality.} g6 (3... d5 4. e3 {and we're back in our famous original repertoire.}) 4. Bb2 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 {I want to emphasize that your opponent will be extremely likely to play ...[d5] and revert back to classic ...[d5] structures. Looking at this position, I was shocked at how strong Ganguly's recommendation of ...[d6] and ...[e5] is. It is not obvious at all that Black should be playing for ...[d6] and ...[e5]. Even if your opponent has memorized this far, I could see a lot of opponents who have bought Ganguly's course simply playing ...[d5] and transposing to our Fianchetto chapter.} (6. a4 $6 {avoids losing the tempo on the [Be2]-[b5] stuff, which occurs later in the main variation. This isn't technically sound though and with best play, Black is slightly better. The idea is to meet Black's} Nc6 {with [Bb5]. I will work on this more in the future if this variation picks up in popularity. For now, this chapter is already bigger than it has to be.}) 6... Nc6 7. O-O d6 (7... d6 {This is what Ganguly recommends and here he only looks at} 8. Qe1 {and 8.c4 , both of which lead to slightly better outcomes for Black. Black is playing for ...[e7]-[e5], which if it is achieved, it often leads to a solid edge for the second player. Up to depth 41 Mr. Stockfish insists that 8.c4 is best, but at higher depths, it begins to change the tune. Yes, I left my computer running all day to sit on this position!}) 8. Bb5 $1 {The name's 46. Depth 46. Agent [c6]-chop returns after much delay. Yes, unfortunately, we have to waste the tempo, but there was no way to objectively sidestep this without risk. If you want to try to get the bishop here in one go, then check out my alternative 6.a4!?! , (which while not completely sound will likely work against an unprepared opponent. The text threatens to take on [c6] and the computer here asserts -0.2, which is technically equal. And that's assuming they play computer best moves which is most likely not going to happen. Guess what the best move for Black here is according to the computer. Take your time...)} Na5 $1 {Will your opponents ever play this in a real game!?!?!?!?!?!?!?!? I don't expect it. The knight sidesteps the bishop threat and moves to a seemingly useless square.} 9. Be2 Bf5 $1 {Black declines the repetition.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge3e4] A weird placement of the knight. But we are playing alien chess here. We aim to follow with [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4].} (10. c4 {could be worth researching. In the future, I will include updates to this as an alternative as well. Black is slightly better, but this will not be a game between 2 engines. I don't know a single person who can honestly say they've studied this structure and are confident in it. Therefore, practice and experience are key.}) (10. h3 {, cutting out ...[Ng4] ideas and waiting to see what Black commits to. Black should be slightly better here but again, this is such a unique structure that the White player with more experience should have a fair share of the chances.}) 10... Nc6 11. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] We're back for another chance of the chop!} Bd7 {Preparing to meet the chop with the natural bishop recapture.} 12. d3 a6 {They have to waste the tempo to elicit the chop.} 13. Bxc6 {Unfortunately we do have to chop here even though their structure with pawns on [d6] and [c5] will harmonize with the bishop on [c6].} Bxc6 14. Qe1 $13 {On depth 48 its -0.16 according to Stockfish so Black has an extremely faint edge. However, the game is extremely complex and I'd expect both players to begin butchering their accuracy from here. The computer recommendations for both sides are rather strange and if you get your experience try playing this against Stockfish level 5 or level 6 you should do fine. We will play for [e4] shortly. Some ideas are to transfer the knight to [f2] via [d1] or put the queen to [h4]. Black has the asset of the bishop pair but the game is sufficiently closed for the knights to have their tricks.} (14. e4 $2 {is a very natural mistake. Black can put our structure under serious pressure with some precise moves.} Nh5 {, targeting [f4].} 15. Qd2 f5 {⩱ , threatening to trade on [e4] and win [f4]. We have to play [g3] to stabilize [f4] but that weakens our light squares in the long term. Black is unequivocally for choice here.}) *

