1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 Qh4+ {This has been tried in 9% of games to reach this position so it is worth a mention. Black has sacrificed a central pawn and is already practically losing. White will parry the simple threats while bringing the pieces out and reinforcing the center.} (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. g3 Qh5 4. Nc3 {The best move. If Black takes the pawn back, our initiative will be overwhelming.} Qxe5 5. d4 Qa5 6. e4 Bb4 7. Bd2 $18 {White will play [a3] and recapture on [c3] with the bishop. Our center, lead in development, and bishops will be too spicy to handle.} *

