1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 Qh4+ {This has been tried in 9% of games to reach this position so it is worth a mention. Black has sacrificed a central pawn and is already practically losing. White will parry the simple threats while bringing the pieces out and reinforcing the center.} (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. g3 Be7 {[%cal Gg3h4,Re7h4] This is a tricky line I've seen in some NYC scholastic chess recently. Of course, ...[Be7] is bad, but it is very likely for a kid to get excited and capture the queen only to be stunned by checkmate on the next move.} 4. Nf3 {Steady hands.} Qh5 5. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Gf3] White has an extra pawn and great development, we couldn't have asked for more.} *

