1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 Nf6 {[%cal Rf6g4,Rh7h5,Rh5h4] This is played 19% of the time. Black threatens ...[Nf6]-[g4] and a quick ...[h7]-[h5]-[h4].} 5. g3 {We respond with this calm pawn advance. White stunts the [d6]-bishop while preparing our own development to [g2].} Ng4 {Played 13% of the time; Black threatens ...[Nxh2] with checkmate on [g3].} 6. Bg2 {Now if ...[Nxh2] and [Bxg3]+, the king has the [f1]-square.} O-O 7. O-O c5 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. b3 Re8 10. e3 $16 {[%csl Rd6,Gf3,Gh2][%cal Gc1b2,Gc3b5,Gf3h2] White has dodged all the threats and prepares [Bb2]. We may continue [Nb5] to attack the [d6]-bishop, or even transfer it via [e2]-[f4] where it will stunt the [d6]-bishop's scope even further. We should be very careful to not move the [f3]-knight, which would allow ...[Nxh2], [Kxh2], and ...[Qh4]+ tricks.} *

