1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 Nf6 {[%cal Rf6g4,Rh7h5,Rh5h4] This is played 19% of the time. Black threatens ...[Nf6]-[g4] and a quick ...[h7]-[h5]-[h4].} 5. g3 {We respond with this calm pawn advance. White stunts the [d6]-bishop while preparing our own development to [g2].} O-O {Played 40% of the time. It doesn't seem to make that much sense though. The From's Gambit is about striking while the iron is hot and this move invests serious time in abstract aspects of development. It carries a sentiment that Black can't attack White immediately and instead has to regroup for an optimal middlegame setup.} 6. Nc3 ({Though this will likely come to the same effect as} 6. Bg2 {, the computer is quite certain this is the best move order. We will continue with [Bg2] and [O-O] in short order and then deal with advancing our pawn center. The vast majority of games have chosen 6.Bg2 so at this point we are already dealing with a tiny sample size, albeit we may very well transpose back into more frequented positions.}) 6... Re8 {Lasering down the e-file and pressuring the [e2]-pawn and [e3] and [e4]-squares. We will need to take great care in advancing our d-pawn since it will invariably weaken these squares further.} 7. Bg2 Bg4 8. O-O Nc6 9. d3 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4] White will play [e2]-[e4] next move with a solid advantage.} *

