1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 Nf6 {[%cal Rf6g4,Rh7h5,Rh5h4] This is played 19% of the time. Black threatens ...[Nf6]-[g4] and a quick ...[h7]-[h5]-[h4].} 5. g3 {We respond with this calm pawn advance. White stunts the [d6]-bishop while preparing our own development to [g2].} O-O {Played 40% of the time. It doesn't seem to make that much sense though. The From's Gambit is about striking while the iron is hot and this move invests serious time in abstract aspects of development. It carries a sentiment that Black can't attack White immediately and instead has to regroup for an optimal middlegame setup.} 6. Nc3 ({Though this will likely come to the same effect as} 6. Bg2 {, the computer is quite certain this is the best move order. We will continue with [Bg2] and [O-O] in short order and then deal with advancing our pawn center. The vast majority of games have chosen 6.Bg2 so at this point we are already dealing with a tiny sample size, albeit we may very well transpose back into more frequented positions.}) 6... c5 {Black can't wait any longer and finally digs into the center with the pawns. The [c5]-pawn attacks the [d4]-square, making [d2]-[d4] no longer attractive in the majority of scenarios.} 7. d3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White adjusts course and prepares the phalanx along the light squares of [c2]-[d3]-[e4].} Nc6 8. Bg2 Bg4 9. O-O h6 {Sooner or later this move had to be played to prevent our bishop from getting out to [g5].} 10. e4 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd1d2] White wants to play [Be3] and [Qd2], maintaining an edge due to the pawn surplus.} Qb6 {The queen eyes [b2]. We shouldn't play the perfunctory move [Be3] here, as that's what Black is hoping for.} 11. Kh1 {Sidestepping any tricks associated with the ...[c5]-[c4] discovered checks.} Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c2,Gd4f3] The pressure is kicked up a notch. Most normal developing moves carry some obvious issues now due to the combined pressure against [b2], [c2], and [f3].} 12. Rb1 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gb1b2] Cool as a cucumber! Black was not actually threatening anything immediately. We defend [b2] and prepare the development of the [c1]-bishop.} Rad8 13. Bf4 {White is significantly better. If Black trades on [f4], White will recapture with the g-pawn, when we have a nice King's Indian style formation. In that case, White could begin ideas like [Qd2], [Ne5], and [Rg1] to put some pressure on the black king along the newly opened file.} *

