1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3,Gd8h4] Another popular move. It's played 33% of the time so almost at the same frequency as ...[g7]-[g5]. Black threatens to capture on [f3] and follow with a dangerous check on [h4].} 5. e3 {[%cal Gd1f3]} Qe7 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Be2 {[%cal Gd2d4,Ge2d3] Just developing calmly. The bishop might reroute to [d3] at some point, but that will only be appropriate after [d2]-[d4] has been played.} Nc6 8. O-O O-O-O 9. d4 Kb8 10. Bd3 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc3b5,Gb5d6] White will probably try to exchange the knight for [d6]-bishop with [Nb5] sooner or later, so Black's move here is understandable.} a6 {[%cal Rc3b5,Ga6b5] On the one hand, [Nb5] is stopped but on the other, Black has made a hook on [a6] that White can initiate tension against with an eventual b-pawn push.} 11. Bd2 h5 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gh4h3] Black throws the h-pawn down the board and will see how far it can be pushed. White will have to move some of the pawns on the kingside sooner or later, creating new weaknesses.} 12. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Ga2a3]} h4 13. a3 h3 {White cannot allow the exchange since that would open the [h8]-rook onto the kingside. White's response is forced.} 14. g3 Rde8 15. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1f2,Yb2b4,Yb4b5] The queen transfers to [f2], when it will secure all parts of the kingside. White can then slowly continue with our own play on the b-file. Notice that due to Black's knight being on [c6] in this line, White was never able to easily achieve [e3]-[e4] since Black's ...[Bxf3] would leave the [d4]-pawn hanging.} *

