1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4f3,Gd8h4] Another popular move. It's played 33% of the time so almost at the same frequency as ...[g7]-[g5]. Black threatens to capture on [f3] and follow with a dangerous check on [h4].} 5. e3 {[%cal Gd1f3]} Nf6 6. Be2 c5 {[%cal Gc5d4] This is a decent setup for Black. Due to the pawn push, the queenside will be more exposed and Black will have to castle kingside. But the flip side is that finally Black has some stake in the center and achieving [e3]-[e4] and [d2]-[d4] for White will be nearly impossible.} 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nc3 O-O {[%cal Yc1b2,Yb2b3,Gd2d3,Ge3e4] In these structures, we have two ways to develop. Either with [d2]-[d3] and [e3]-[e4] followed by [Bg5], or by [b2]-[b3] and [Bc1]-[b2].} 9. b3 {This is what the computer prefers.} Re8 10. Bb2 a6 {White has a healthy structure with no obvious weaknesses. We simply need to find a way to untangle, get the queen out, and connect the rooks. Once that happens, we can count on a solid advantage.} 11. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Ge2g4,Ye1d3,Yd3f4] Threatening to trade the bishops and preparing [Ne1]-[d3]-[f4] under the proper circumstances.} Bxe2 12. Nxe2 Ne4 13. Nf3 f5 {White's structure has kept its composure, but sooner or later we will have to kick out the knight with [d2]-[d3]. We need to manage this in such a way that we don't critically weaken the [e3]-pawn though.} 14. g3 Be7 {[%cal Ge7f6] The bishop transfers to [f6] to trade for the [b2]-dragon.} 15. Nf4 Bf6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. d3 Nc3 18. Qd2 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Ga1e1] White will play [Rae1] and [e3] will be secure. We can entertain of playing down the f-file with [Nh4] and [Nfg2] or [Nh5].} *

