1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 g5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 34% of relevant games.} 5. g3 g4 (5... h5 {has been tried in five games but after} 6. d4 {, the threat of [Bg5] freezes Black's plan of going ...[g5] and ...[h4].} f6 7. Qd3 {+- and the hunter becomes the hunted. [Qg6] is an uncomfortable threat and Black is still down a pawn.}) 6. Nh4 (6. Nd4 $5 {is also interesting and would make a nice alternative. It doesn't stop ...[h5]-[h4], which makes it a tad riskier. I'll leave it to the student for independent analysis since our analysis of 6.Nh4 will be perfectly sufficient.}) 6... Be7 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Ge7h4] This is played with the idea to push the knight out of [h4] and then throw the h-pawn down with ...[h7]-[h5]-[h4].} 7. Ng2 Nc6 8. d3 h5 {Black has to try this sooner or later to make any sense of the earlier ...[Be7].} 9. Bf4 $1 h4 ({After} 9... Nf6 10. Nc3 Be6 11. Qd2 {± , White will castle queenside and advance [e2]-[e4]. We can then aim for [Ng2]-[e3] and [Bg2]. Black has no compensation for the pawn deficit.}) 10. Nxh4 {White will place the bishop securely on [g3] after any exchange on [h4].} *

