1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 g5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 34% of relevant games.} 5. g3 g4 (5... h5 {has been tried in five games but after} 6. d4 {, the threat of [Bg5] freezes Black's plan of going ...[g5] and ...[h4].} f6 7. Qd3 {+- and the hunter becomes the hunted. [Qg6] is an uncomfortable threat and Black is still down a pawn.}) 6. Nh4 (6. Nd4 $5 {is also interesting and would make a nice alternative. It doesn't stop ...[h5]-[h4], which makes it a tad riskier. I'll leave it to the student for independent analysis since our analysis of 6.Nh4 will be perfectly sufficient.}) 6... Be7 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Ge7h4] This is played with the idea to push the knight out of [h4] and then throw the h-pawn down with ...[h7]-[h5]-[h4].} 7. Ng2 h5 {What's important to understand about these variations is that while it appears like we're simply responding to our opponent's threats and therein giving them ample time, all these pawn pushes will likely backfire on them later. All these far advanced pawns will be not strong but rather weak and exposed.} 8. Nf4 h4 9. Bg2 {[%cal Gg2h1,Rh4g3,Gh2g3] The rook is protected so ...[hxg3] isn't scary.} h3 {[%csl Gg3,Gh2] Black continues 'winning tempi' but is running out of things to threaten and the h-file is closed.} 10. Be4 (10. Bf1 $6 {wouldn't make sense. After} Nc6 {, White is still significantly better, but it makes no sense to give Black such a large lead in development. For instance} 11. e4 f5 12. d3 fxe4 13. dxe4 Qxd1+ 14. Kxd1 Bd7 {(and it doesn't seem that clear me to that White should be much better as the computer indicates. Black's pieces are coming in quickly and White will need to follow a careful path to keep the advantage.)}) 10... f5 11. Bd3 {We arrive at an extremely unorthodox-looking position in which the bishop has arrived at [d3] without White having moved the e-pawn.} Nf6 12. Bc4 Nc6 13. Rf1 {After all the pawn advances, it's revealed that all Black has achieved is creating a weakness on [f5]. We will invade with [Ne6] at the right moment, when we can recapture with [Bxe6] and start rounding up the [f5]-pawn.} (13. O-O {??} Qd4+ {+ -+ and our bishop drops.}) 13... Ne5 14. Bb3 Bc5 {This is more tricky than it appears.} 15. Nc3 (15. c3 $2 {is the instinctual way to prepare [d2]-[d4].} Qe7 {, the threat of ...[Nf3] makes this position an unmitigated mess! For instance} 16. d4 Nf3+ 17. Rxf3 gxf3 18. dxc5 Ng4 {∞ . Feel free to analyze this insane position on your own! My computer insists chances are level. White's king is weak and the [h2]-pawn might drop, when the [h3]-pawn becomes a real powerhouse. But White does have 2 pieces for a rook after all.}) 15... a5 {[%cal Ga8a6,Ga6h6] Introducing ideas of ...[Ra8]-[a6] to activate the queen's rook.} 16. d4 $1 {[%csl Rc8,Rf5][%cal Rc8f5] Sacrificing the pawn to catch up in development. It turns out Black's [f5]-pawn it is weak and also completely stunts the [c8]-bishop from developing normally is so strategically bad that evening the material won't solve the problems. Even though the loss of the d-pawn seems to ruin White's structure. we'll be able to develop very smoothly now.} ({The natural} 16. Ne6 $4 {is a big blunder. It turns out our knight was serving an underappreciated role of holding Black's kingside majority back.} Bxe6 17. Bxe6 f4 $3 18. Rxf4 {(18.gxf4 g3 − I have never seen such simple play with a pawn majority in the opening. 19.hxg3 (19.fxe5 g2 and the issue in all these lines is that White isn't only losing material but the only cover for the king has been blown to bits so overwhelming attacks will follow any of these variations. 20.exf6 Qxf6! 21.Rxf6 g1=Q+ 22.Rf1 Bf2# . ) 19...h2 20.Rh1 Qe7 , Black's queen slowly breaks through the traffic to get to the kingside. 21.fxe5 Qxe6 22.exf6 Qh3 , White will lose at least a rook and the king is nowhere close to castling so we will likely get mated after. )} Bg1 $1 {Black will scoop up [h2] and [g3], when the [h3] and [g4]-pawns will allow them to coast to victory.}) 16... Qxd4 17. Qxd4 Bxd4 18. Ncd5 Nxd5 19. Nxd5 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gd5c7,Gd5f6] Nxc7+ is threatened, and ...[Rh7] would fall to a new knight fork on [f6].} Kd7 20. c3 Bc5 21. Bf4 $18 {[%csl Gb3,Gf4][%cal Ye1c1] White's bishops reign supreme. We can castle queenside when we want, and begin collecting the pawns on [c7] and maybe [f5] if we can pressure it enough.} *

