 central pawns. We will have to play precisely to dodge the various tricks that get thrown our way, but if we can manage that, we will be much better. Here ...[Nxd4] followed by ...[Bxg3]+ is threatened so White should cement the [d4]-pawn.} 10. c3 Be6 11. Bg2 (11. Nd2 $5 {(should also bring an advantage it will probably transpose.)}) 11... Qe7 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gc1g5] Introducing ideas of [Ne4] and [Bg5] or supporting [e2]-[e4].} O-O-O 13. Ne4 Bf5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf5d3]} 14. O-O {[%csl Rc8][%cal Ge4d6,Gd6c8] The pin is never dangerous due to [Nxd6]+ coming with check.} Be5 {[%cal Gh8h2,Ge7h4,Ge5h2] Black preserves the dark-squared bishop for at least a while longer. They always have ideas of ...[Rxh2] followed by ...[Qh4] so we must always be careful here.} 15. Bf4 $1 {[%cal Gf4e5] Bullying the bishop off the diagonal!} Bxf4 16. Rxf4 Rh5 {[%csl Re4,Rh2][%cal Gh5h2,Gf5d3] Black's h-file pressure might look scary, but White can anticipate this well.} 17. Qe3 $1 {Sidestepping the pin.} Kb8 {With this move, Black can now play ...[Rdh8] without fearing [d5]. But White can arrange properly to organize active play.} (17... Rdh8 18. d5 $1 {+- and a hidden dimension of the [Qe3] move is revealed. [a7] will drop when White gets a quicker attack.}) 18. Qf2 {The queen is well placed here. It secures the [g2]-bishop and powers down the f-file. A bit of offense and defense.} Rdh8 19. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gd2f1] White wants to secure [h2] with [Nf1] and then advance in the center with an enormous advantage.} Rxh2 $2 {This is Black's last stand to go for it, but it fails miserably.} 20. e4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4] A beautiful center at last!} Bc8 (20... Be6 21. d5 {and the fork wins the day.}) 21. Rxf7 Qg5 22. Nf1 $1 {[%csl Gh1,Gh2,Gh3][%cal Gg2h3,Gg2h1,Gf1h2] Even though ...[Rxh2] has been played, White has been able to construct a healthy insulation of the kingside. The bishop watches [h1] and [h3] while the knight scopes [h2]. The black battery on the h-file is powerless.} R2h5 (22... Qh5 {, the queen tries to play hardball on the h-file.} 23. Nxh2 Qxh2+ 24. Kf1 {+- , I am the captain now.}) 23. Qf4 $18 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gf4g5,Rg5d8,Gf4c7] Any queen trade leads to an easily winning endgame but otherwise, Black will have to play a very passive move like ...[Qd8] or ...[Qa5] since White is also threatening [Qxc7]+.} *

