[ECO "A02"]
[PlyCount "35"]
[GameId "2127765607425424"]

1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 g5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 34% of relevant games.} 5. g3 g4 (5... h5 {has been tried in five games but after} 6. d4 {, the threat of [Bg5] freezes Black's plan of going ...[g5] and ...[h4].} f6 7. Qd3 {+- and the hunter becomes the hunted. [Qg6] is an uncomfortable threat and Black is still down a pawn.}) 6. Nh4 (6. Nd4 $5 {is also interesting and would make a nice alternative. It doesn't stop ...[h5]-[h4], which makes it a tad riskier. I'll leave it to the student for independent analysis since our analysis of 6.Nh4 will be perfectly sufficient.}) 6... Ne7 7. d4 Ng6 {[%cal Gg6h4]} (7... Ng6 {Here both} 8. Nxg6 {and 8.Ng2 are promising. [Ng2] retreats and keeps the h-file closed but does so at the cost of the [f1]-bishop's coordination. In this repertoire, we will only focus on [Nxg6], but feel free to analyze [Ng2] on your own.}) 8. Nxg6 hxg6 {[%csl Rg3,Rh2][%cal Gh8h1,Gd6g3] The whole point of Black's maneuver. The h-file is opened and ...[Bxg3]+ looms over White's kingside.} 9. Qd3 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Gd3g3]} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gd6g3,Yd8d4] The underlying logic of such positions is the following: White is materially and strategically better due to the two extra central pawns. We will have to play precisely to dodge the various tricks that get thrown our way, but if we can manage that, we will be much better. Here ...[Nxd4] followed by ...[Bxg3]+ is threatened so White should cement the [d4]-pawn.} 10. c3 Be6 11. Bg2 (11. Nd2 $5 {(should also bring an advantage it will probably transpose.)}) 11... Qe7 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gc1g5] Introducing ideas of [Ne4] and [Bg5] or supporting [e2]-[e4].} f5 {This limits our [d2]-knight's options drastically.} 13. O-O {It seems bad for White to willingly move the king closer to [h2]. But everything is under control actually. White has an antidote to ...[Qh7].} Rxh2 {A neat trick that almost works.} 14. Bxc6+ {This clears the [g2]-square, making our response to the coming ...[Qh4]+ a lot simpler.} bxc6 15. Kxh2 Qh4+ {[%cal Rd6h2,Rh4h2] Smoke and mirrors.} 16. Kg2 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Gg2g3,Gd3g3] The king watches its step. The tightrope isn't too narrow and victory waits at the end of the line.} Bd5+ 17. e4 fxe4 {The queen has been hanging all this time so...} (17... Bxe4+ 18. Qxe4+ $1 {Our queen for a bishop, but with a very important check! The frozen queen on [h4] looks on in terror.} fxe4 19. gxh4 {and that's the game.}) 18. gxh4 $18 {We're still up a rook, though converting against those pesky bishops will require some technique.} *

