1. f4 e5 {The famous From's Gambit, which is tried in 8% of games. While you can't expect it every game, you can count on it occurring once every few tournaments. Black sacrifices a pawn to immediately start playing for checkmate from the get-go. This is one of the responses that should always make us smile. If we are able to remember everything we need to, we will be much better and be able to head into the middle and endgame with a hefty advantage.} 2. fxe5 d6 (2... Nc6 3. Nf3 {and Black is best advised here to play} d6 {, when after a trade we will transpose to a variation with 4...Nc6.}) 3. exd6 Bxd6 {Now ...[Qh4]+ is an enormous threat that must be dealt with.} (3... Nf6 4. Nf3 {, Black really should take at this point, when things will just transpose to Nf6 in the main variation.}) 4. Nf3 g5 {The most popular move, being essayed in 34% of relevant games.} 5. g3 g4 (5... h5 {has been tried in five games but after} 6. d4 {, the threat of [Bg5] freezes Black's plan of going ...[g5] and ...[h4].} f6 7. Qd3 {+- and the hunter becomes the hunted. [Qg6] is an uncomfortable threat and Black is still down a pawn.}) 6. Nh4 (6. Nd4 $5 {is also interesting and would make a nice alternative. It doesn't stop ...[h5]-[h4], which makes it a tad riskier. I'll leave it to the student for independent analysis since our analysis of 6.Nh4 will be perfectly sufficient.}) 6... Ne7 7. d4 Ng6 {[%cal Gg6h4]} (7... Ng6 {Here both} 8. Nxg6 {and 8.Ng2 are promising. [Ng2] retreats and keeps the h-file closed but does so at the cost of the [f1]-bishop's coordination. In this repertoire, we will only focus on [Nxg6], but feel free to analyze [Ng2] on your own.}) 8. Nxg6 hxg6 {[%csl Rg3,Rh2][%cal Gh8h1,Gd6g3] The whole point of Black's maneuver. The h-file is opened and ...[Bxg3]+ looms over White's kingside.} 9. Qd3 {[%csl Gg3][%cal Gd3g3]} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gd6g3,Yd8d4] The underlying logic of such positions is the following: White is materially and strategically better due to the two extra central pawns. We will have to play precisely to dodge the various tricks that get thrown our way, but if we can manage that, we will be much better. Here ...[Nxd4] followed by ...[Bxg3]+ is threatened so White should cement the [d4]-pawn.} 10. c3 Be6 11. Bg2 (11. Nd2 $5 {(should also bring an advantage it will probably transpose.)}) 11... Qe7 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gc1g5] Introducing ideas of [Ne4] and [Bg5] or supporting [e2]-[e4].} f5 {This limits our [d2]-knight's options drastically.} 13. O-O {It seems bad for White to willingly move the king closer to [h2]. But everything is under control actually. White has an antidote to ...[Qh7].} Qh7 14. Bxc6+ $1 {[%cal Gf2h2] Clearing the 2nd rank for lateral protection by the rook.} bxc6 15. Rf2 {[%csl Gg3,Gh2][%cal Gf2h2,Gd3g3,Rd6g3] White must be careful to keep [g3] under control, as otherwise ...[Bxg3] would crash through.} Qg8 {[%csl Ge6,Gg8][%cal Gg8c4,Rd2c4] A strange move but one that makes sense as we look at the position longer. First, the queen and the bishop form a battery on the diagonal, stopping any White ideas of [Nc4] to trade off the bishop on [d6]. The queen also supports the advance of ...[g6]-[g5], which will be necessary sooner or later to continue play on the kingside.} 16. Nf1 {Preparing [Bf4].} Bc4 (16... g5 $2 {This sensible move just doesn't work.} 17. Rxf5 Bxf5 18. Qxf5 {, White already has two pawns for the exchange and Black's structure is in shambles.}) 17. Qc2 Bd5 18. c4 {A cheeky sacrifice.} Bxc4 19. e4 fxe4 20. Bf4 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gc2c8,Gf1e3,Gf4d6] White has sacrificed two pawns but what a transformation! We've opened all parts of the board up and gotten a great blockading square on [e3] for the knight. White is comfortably better.} O-O-O 21. Ne3 Bd5 22. Raf1 {[%csl Ra7] With the light squares blocked, White has no reason to fear for the king. We should consider probing Black's queenside to pressure some of the weaknesses a7, and maybe the [c5]-square if the bishops trade.} *

