1. f4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will discuss Black's attempts at Queen's Indian setups involving a queenside fianchetto.} 2. Nf3 b6 {A good rule of thumb: in these ...[Nf6] variations we want to play [e3] only after ...[e6]. This is because it might be more advantageous to develop our [f1]-bishop to [g2] depending on how things shake out.} (2... e6 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 {will transpose to a position analyzed in the variations following 2...b6 .}) 3. b3 Bb7 4. Bb2 e6 {The most popular move, being played 41% of the time.} 5. e3 {Moreover, many players can arrive here with the moves 1.f4 Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 3.e3 b6 4.b3 Bb7 , when White plays 5.Bb2 transposing to the current position. This position has been reached 3600 times and deserves more attention than the other setups involving ...[c5] or ...[g6].} Be7 6. g3 {This might seem strange, but we're heading to a position covered against 4...c5 . It's just more active to place our bishop on [g2] to counter the enemy one on [b7].} O-O 7. Bg2 c5 8. O-O d5 9. c4 Nc6 10. Qe2 {This transposes to a position discussed after 4...c5 .} *

