1. f4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will discuss Black's attempts at Queen's Indian setups involving a queenside fianchetto.} 2. Nf3 b6 {A good rule of thumb: in these ...[Nf6] variations we want to play [e3] only after ...[e6]. This is because it might be more advantageous to develop our [f1]-bishop to [g2] depending on how things shake out.} (2... e6 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 {will transpose to a position analyzed in the variations following 2...b6 .}) 3. b3 Bb7 4. Bb2 g6 {Black goes for this double fianchetto setup 22% of the time.} 5. e3 {This seems to be thematic development; our bishop seems to be on its way to [e2].} Bg7 6. g4 {Psych! That's the wrong number! We're actually playing kingside aggression after all. This move is only played in 2% of games so it is sure to catch your opponent off guard! We will go over Black's 3 most popular moves from here.} (6. g3 {with [Bg2] to follow is a more sane way to play things if the craziness of [g2]-[g4] is too much to bear. We will castle shortly with an equal game. There is still a bit of tension in the position, as both sides' central pawns have yet to meet each other in the middle.}) 6... d6 ({This is played 12% of the time.} 6... Nxg4 $4 {is played 13% of the time. No kidding. :} 7. Bxg7 {+- , we'll take that burger to go, thank you!}) 7. g5 {Kicking the knight out as expected.} Nh5 8. Bxg7 Nxg7 9. Bg2 {[%csl Gb7,Gg2] Opposing Black's [b7]-sniper with a sniper of our own.} Nd7 {The most popular, keeping the diagonal clear for the bishop to scope from its fianchetto.} 10. Nc3 $13 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gd1d2,Ge1c1,Gh2h4,Gd1e2] We will play [Qe2] or [d2]-[d3], [Qd2], castle queenside, and play [h4]. Notice we would love to play [h4]-[h5], but Black's [g7]-knight is well placed in guarding this advance. The game is super complex and balanced. Get lots of experience and practice and the results will begin pouring in.} *

