1. f4 Nf6 {In this chapter we will discuss Black's attempts at Queen's Indian setups involving a queenside fianchetto.} 2. Nf3 b6 {A good rule of thumb: in these ...[Nf6] variations we want to play [e3] only after ...[e6]. This is because it might be more advantageous to develop our [f1]-bishop to [g2] depending on how things shake out.} (2... e6 3. e3 b6 4. b3 Bb7 {will transpose to a position analyzed in the variations following 2...b6 .}) 3. b3 Bb7 4. Bb2 c5 {This is only played 3% of the time with roughly 300 games reaching this position in the database. It's quite strong though and digs into the center from the get-go.} 5. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2] We will go for the double fianchetto.} Bxf3 {This has never been played but brings a weird structure we should discuss a tad.} 6. exf3 Nc6 {Black has great control of the center to compensate for the bishop pair. The ideas here are very strange but suffice it to say we must be forthright in taking on Black's center. If we allow Black to just play ...[d7]-[d5]-[d4], then our bishops will be buried.} 7. f5 $5 {Weighing down on [g6] and [e6] and making the opening of the [a8]-[h1] diagonal easier for the [f1]-bishop, as now only the [f3]-pawn has to move.} d5 8. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gb5e8] Hitting the weakened knight.} Qc8 $1 {This is the only move to hold the balance since Black can play ...[a7]-[a6], as it's supported by the ...[Qc8].} (8... Qc7 $2 {doesn't support …a7-[a6], allowing White to get a grip with} 9. Qe2 $1 {⩲ and White is better. We will castle and play [Re1], when Black has issues finishing development. The [f5]-pawn sticks into Black's camp like a thorn in their side.}) 9. Qe2 a6 10. Bxc6+ Qxc6 11. O-O $13 {[%cal Gf1e1,Yf5g6,Yg7g6] We will power down the e-file with [Re1]. Black will have to push ...[e6] or ...[g6], which will allow us to trade off the doubled f-pawn. The game is balanced.} *

