ial zwischenzug gives Black a fierce initiative.} 14. Qc2 Nxb2 15. Qxb2 d3 {∓ and ...[Bc5]-[d4] combined with ...[Ng4] will make White wince. The ...[d4]-[d3] move worked perfectly to keep our knight out of [c2] as well, which stops it from fighting against the ...[Bc5]-[d4] stuff.}) 13... Ne4 (13... Bxg2 $2 14. exf6 {leaves two pieces hanging. We will win material:} Bxf1 15. fxe7 Qxe7 16. Qxf1 {. With 2 pieces for the rook and pawn, we have a strategically winning advantage. Of course, good technique will be required though.}) 14. Rf4 {[%csl Rd4,Re4][%cal Gf4d4] Shooting through the two vulnerabilities on [d4] and [e4].} Nc5 15. Bxb7 Nxb7 16. Nb5 $16 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd1e2,Ge2f3,Ya1e1,Ye1f1] The [d4]-pawn is in trouble and pushing it to [d3] will separate it too far from the rest of his army. White is much better. We will play [Qe2] or [Qf3] and swing the rook over to [e1] or [f1]. Our [e5]-pawn gives us a grip all over the board.} *

