1. f4 b6 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {Here Black should really revert back to the standard QID setup with ...[e7]-[e6]. All other options give White the chance for a huge advantage.} g6 {This is chosen 20% of the time. Black opts for a double fianchetto setup. We should be happy to see this move since it allows us to take a full stake in the center.} 4. d4 {Taking the full center!} Bg7 5. Nf3 {[%csl Yd4,Ye4,Yf4] Three fantastic pawns on the fourth rank, what more could we ask for?} d6 {This is tried 22% of the time. It looks as though Black is trying for a Hippo setup with ...[d6] and ...[Ne7] + ...[Nd7].} 6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O Nd7 {The important thing to know about the Hippo is that if you let Black complete the setup with both knights on [e7] and [d7], then they have a chance of getting solid. Instead, we should strike while the Hippo is still waking up.} 8. f5 $1 {[%csl Re6,Rf7][%cal Gc4f7] Crunching on the [e6]-dam.} exf5 ({After} 8... gxf5 9. exf5 {+- , Black is left with the uncomfortable choice: chop on [f5], when the f-pawns will drop like apples? Or let White chop on [e6], when [Nf3]-[g5] will begin making dangerous threats to [f7] and [e6]?}) 9. exf5 $18 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gf3g5,Gc1g5,Gc4f7,Gf5g6,Gf1f7] Ng5 or [Bg5] and tricks on the f-file with our [f1]-rook combined with [fxg6] should decide.} *

