1. f4 b6 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {Here Black should really revert back to the standard QID setup with ...[e7]-[e6]. All other options give White the chance for a huge advantage.} g6 {This is chosen 20% of the time. Black opts for a double fianchetto setup. We should be happy to see this move since it allows us to take a full stake in the center.} 4. d4 {Taking the full center!} Bg7 5. Nf3 {[%csl Yd4,Ye4,Yf4] Three fantastic pawns on the fourth rank, what more could we ask for?} Nf6 {This is tried 13% of the time. Black is really flying close to the sun with this one. Black has no pawns in the center and yet expects the knight to sit on [f6] unperturbed.} 6. e5 $1 Nd5 7. Nxd5 Bxd5 8. c4 {What a space advantage!} Bb7 9. h4 $18 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6,Yh7h5,Yf3g5] We launch our h-pawn down the board. The center is closed enough to permit this delay of development. We want our h-pawn to reach [h6] and entomb the [g7]-bishop on [f8] or if Black has castled, [h8]. Meanwhile if Black prevents us with ...[h7]-[h5], we get an effective outpost for our [f3]-knight on [g5].} *

