1. f4 e6 2. Nf3 (2. e4 {is too soon. Black will play} d5 {with a good French.} 3. e5 {would turn into an ugly type of setup with [f4] vs. the French Defense. Black would play ...[c5] to pressure [d4] and a knight would glide to [f5]. Perhaps it's close to equal, but Black is already in the driver's seat.}) 2... b6 (2... Nf6 3. e3 b6 {will transpose into positions already discussed in the 1...Nf6 lines.}) 3. e4 {Let's take the center finally!} d5 {This seems antithetical to the whole plan of fianchettoing the bishop on [b7] along an open diagonal.} 4. e5 {Now we have a great French with ...[b6] and [f4] included. While [f4] is useful for us in reinforcing [e5], ...[b6] is less useful for Black. Sure, it introduces ideas of ...[Ba6], but this never brings full equality in the main lines either.} Ne7 5. d4 c5 6. c3 Nbc6 7. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4,Ge3f4] Reinforcing our space advantage.} Nf5 8. Bf2 h5 {[%cal Rg2g4,Gh5g4] Protecting against [g2]-[g4].} 9. Bd3 Be7 10. O-O {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3c2] Our setup is very healthy. Black's pressure against our [d4] has come to a boil and the pawn will withstand the torrent for the foreseeable future. We can continue with [Na3]-[c2] and then begin dealing with the [f5]-knight with plans for [h2]-[h3] and [g2]-[g4]. A really neat point here is that if Black castles, the position goes from worse to close to lost.} O-O $2 11. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4]} Bb7 12. g4 hxg4 13. hxg4 Nh6 14. g5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gg5h6,Ge5f6] Such wonderful space on the kingside.} Nf5 15. Bxf5 exf5 16. Kg2 $16 {[%cal Gf1h1] And we will begin the task of building a battery on the h-file. We can simply play [Rh1], [Qg1], and [Qh2] to begin turning up the heat. Black will have to pull several rabbits out of a hat to survive this one.} *

