1. f4 e6 2. Nf3 (2. e4 {is too soon. Black will play} d5 {with a good French.} 3. e5 {would turn into an ugly type of setup with [f4] vs. the French Defense. Black would play ...[c5] to pressure [d4] and a knight would glide to [f5]. Perhaps it's close to equal, but Black is already in the driver's seat.}) 2... b6 (2... Nf6 3. e3 b6 {will transpose into positions already discussed in the 1...Nf6 lines.}) 3. e4 {Let's take the center finally!} Bb7 {This is played 92% of the time so it will be the move we focus the most on.} 4. Nc3 d5 {Probably Black's best bet to confront White in the center, but it's only chosen 5% of the time.} 5. exd5 {Trading on [d5].} (5. e5 $2 {would be great if we could immediately play [d2]-[d4], but Black will burn this possibility to ash with the strong response} d4 $1 {∓ , which leaves our light squares vulnerable and our [c3]-knight in need of a healthy home.}) 5... exd5 {This is the healthy recapture and also the most popular at a frequency of 77%.} (5... Bxd5 $2 {is played 22% of the time but makes no sense.} 6. Nxd5 {, grabbing the bishop pair.} Qxd5 7. g3 {± with [Bg2] and castles kingside to follow. Black lacks the light-squared bishop and yet has played ...[b7]-[b6], weakening the entire queenside − not a healthy combination!}) 6. Ne5 $1 {The knight launches into the center for some tricks. The position is quite strange. On the one hand, our [f4] push has weakened the [e4]-square a bit, but on the other hand, Black's pawn on [d5] is completely disharmonious with the fianchettoed bishop on [b7]. This position has only been reached 108 times. We will cover Black's 3 most popular responses, only one of which gives Black a chance at equality.} Nd7 $4 {Elected 15% of the time, but it's just losing.} 7. Bb5 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gb5e8] The pin hurts! Black is best advised to play ...[c6] and just give up a pawn. If Black insists on holding everything together, the position will simply ache more.} Ngf6 $6 {Trying to keep everything covered.} 8. Bc6 $18 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gc6b7] White is completely winning here due to various tactics associated with the e-file. A cute variation here is:} Rb8 9. Bxb7 Rxb7 (9... Nxe5 10. fxe5 {and if Black recaptures on [b7], White can net the piece on [f6].}) 10. Nc6 {[%csl Rd8,Re7][%cal Gc6e7] A double attack against the queen on [d8] and [e7]-square.} Qc8 11. Qe2+ {[%csl Re8][%cal Ge2e8] Splat! Black must hemorrhage a serious amount of material immediately if the king is to survive.} *

