e move to get things going on the kingside.} (7... Nbd7 $2 {is chosen 24% of the time but allows a strong pin on [b5].} 8. Bb5 Bd6 9. Nc6 $1 {⩲ , digging into the weak [c6]-square. Black has an uncomfortable choice: move the queen to the remote [c8]-square, or cede the bishop with ...[Bxc6], when White will dominate the weakened light squares remaining from the expired fianchetto.}) 8. g4 $5 {It's obvious things are headed toward a mess. The g-pawn will go to [g5] if allowed to dig the knight out of [f6]. The position is complex and balanced. This position has only been reached 3 times across all eternity so this offers excellent chances of getting your opponent out of their comfort zone. Each of the 3 games has followed different paths from here − we will address each of the moves tried.} Nc6 $2 {Black logically fights against the [e5]-stronghold but only at an enormous cost.} 9. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Rc6,Re8][%cal Gb5e8] Freezing the knight.} Bxe5 {Black trades to relieve the pressure but will sorely miss the dark-squared bishop.} 10. fxe5 Ne4 {We've pushed so many pawns that whenever the knight comes here, we should be very careful about the threat of ...[Qd8]-[h4].} 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. g5 {[%cal Rd8h4] Stopping ...[Qh4] through unorthodox means.} O-O {Here we'd like to set up a healthy blockade with [Be3], but as long as the enemy knight stands on the board, it will be able to undermine this with ...[Ne7]-[f5]. So we must preemptively trade on [c6].} 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Be3 $14 {We will play [Qd2] and castle queenside. Once our king is settled, we will throw our pawns forward on the kingside to uncover the enemy king. White has a solid edge due to the space and farther advanced pawns on the kingside. If a pawn race ever develops in which they pawn storm our queenside, we will be first to the punch.} *

