1. f4 e6 2. Nf3 (2. e4 {is too soon. Black will play} d5 {with a good French.} 3. e5 {would turn into an ugly type of setup with [f4] vs. the French Defense. Black would play ...[c5] to pressure [d4] and a knight would glide to [f5]. Perhaps it's close to equal, but Black is already in the driver's seat.}) 2... b6 (2... Nf6 3. e3 b6 {will transpose into positions already discussed in the 1...Nf6 lines.}) 3. e4 {Let's take the center finally!} Bb7 {This is played 92% of the time so it will be the move we focus the most on.} 4. Nc3 Nf6 {Chosen 15% of the time. Whenever Black plays this and hasn't played ...[d7]-[d6], our follow-up should be instinctive. Attack the knight, forward!} 5. e5 Nd5 {By far the most popular square for the knight, being chosen 67% of the time.} 6. Nxd5 {Notice that Black's structure has no weaknesses but at the same time hasn't established itself in the center. We should rush to make inroads while Black is still adjusting. With this capture, Black must put the bishop too far out where it will be vulnerable to more tempo-gaining pawn advances like [c2]-[c4].} Bxd5 (6... exd5 $4 {(is rarely chosen 3% and for good reason.) The [b7]-bishop is buried and we have a potent kingside pawn majority after} 7. d4 {+- . With [Bd3], castles kingside, and some thematic ideas like [f4]-[f5] or [Nf3]-[g5], White has a winning initiative.}) 7. d4 {Gaining more and more of the center.} c5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc5d4] Black challenges our center and digs into [d4], which could potentially become weak. Notice we've pushed our e- and c-pawns so have no recourse to defend it with pawns if the moment calls for it. White has one precise way to an advantage − after all other moves, Black secures a comfortable equality.} 8. c4 {[%csl Rd5] Chasing down the bishop while we still can.} Bb7 {This is a mistake chosen 70% of the time! Black wants to keep the bishop and can you blame them? Black's entire opening setup was geared towards scoping the board.} 9. d5 $1 {But of course, being buried alive on [b7] was not part of the plan either. White is close to winning with the massive space advantage. The pawns on [d5] and [e5] control so much of the board and keep all the minor pieces on their toes.} d6 $1 {Black confronts the center immediately.} 10. f5 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge5,Gf5] The pawns are having a party in the middle of the board. [f4]-[f5] crunches into [e6] and frees our [c1]-bishop for opportunities on [g5] or [f4], and introduces ideas of [Ng5] by the same token. Only one of Black's pawn captures survives, can you guess which one???????} exd5 $1 {The correct way for Black to traverse the narrow path. Unfortunately for Black, we are still close to winning with best play.} (10... dxe5 $2 11. fxe6 fxe6 12. Bd3 {+- and now [Nxe5]/[Ng5] and [Qh5]+ or [O-O] and [Re1]/[Nf7] should decide. White has a flaming initiative and Black's weaknesses burn bright.}) 11. cxd5 {[%cal Ge5e6] Black must capture again to prevent the decisive advance [e5]-[e6], after which our space advantage would be too great to bear.} dxe5 12. Bb5+ Nd7 13. O-O Bd6 14. Ng5 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gg5e6,Gg5e4,Yf7e6,Yf5e6] 15.Ne6 fxe6 16.fxe6 is threatened as well as 15.Ne4 followed by [f5]-[f6]. Black is in for a bad time. We might be down a pawn, but we're up a position. Our d-pawn is a latent asset that could prove critical at crunch time.} *

