1. f4 e6 2. Nf3 (2. e4 {is too soon. Black will play} d5 {with a good French.} 3. e5 {would turn into an ugly type of setup with [f4] vs. the French Defense. Black would play ...[c5] to pressure [d4] and a knight would glide to [f5]. Perhaps it's close to equal, but Black is already in the driver's seat.}) 2... b6 (2... Nf6 3. e3 b6 {will transpose into positions already discussed in the 1...Nf6 lines.}) 3. e4 {Let's take the center finally!} Bb7 {This is played 92% of the time so it will be the move we focus the most on.} 4. Nc3 Nc6 {[%csl Rb7,Rc6][%cal Rb7c6] This is elected 5% of the time. It really makes no sense, as Black is just blocking the bishop they aimed their entire setup around.} 5. d4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4] Taking even more of the center. The white pawns form a nice armada.} Bb4 {The most commonly played here.} 6. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1,Yd7d5,Ye4e5] We will castle kingside with a healthy advantage. Sooner or later, Black will try to get some of the center with ...[d7]-[d5], and to this, we should respond with [e4]-[e5] with strong thematic play on the kingside f4-[f5] advances would be great where we have much more access than Black.} *

