1. f4 e6 2. Nf3 (2. e4 {is too soon. Black will play} d5 {with a good French.} 3. e5 {would turn into an ugly type of setup with [f4] vs. the French Defense. Black would play ...[c5] to pressure [d4] and a knight would glide to [f5]. Perhaps it's close to equal, but Black is already in the driver's seat.}) 2... b6 (2... Nf6 3. e3 b6 {will transpose into positions already discussed in the 1...Nf6 lines.}) 3. e4 {Let's take the center finally!} Bb7 {This is played 92% of the time so it will be the move we focus the most on.} 4. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb4c3,Gb7e4] This is played 48% of the time and is by far the most popular choice. Black threatens to chop on [c3] and scoop up [e4].} 5. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2e4] Our queen reinforces [e4]. This may look like it blocks our [f1]-bishop, but we can always opt for a kingside fianchetto with [g2]-[g3]. This strong move is rarely tried though, and already on move 5, we are at a position that has only been reached roughly 4000 times. We will look at Black's only two commonly chosen moves in this position, each of which has a frequency of 40%.} Nf6 6. e5 Nd5 {The knight swings to the weakened [d5]-square and eyes the hanging [f4]-pawn.} (6... Bxc3 7. dxc3 {would transpose to 5...Bxc3 6.dxc3 variations.}) 7. g3 {[%cal Gg3f4] Reinforcing [f4].} Be7 {The computer recommendation though I don't think most people will have the maturity to retreat a bishop unprompted like this.} 8. Ne4 {[%csl Ge4] Our knight repositions to the nice [e4]-square.} O-O 9. Bg2 Nc6 10. d3 $14 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ge1g1] We will castle with a healthy edge due to our nice space advantage.} *

