1. f4 e6 2. Nf3 (2. e4 {is too soon. Black will play} d5 {with a good French.} 3. e5 {would turn into an ugly type of setup with [f4] vs. the French Defense. Black would play ...[c5] to pressure [d4] and a knight would glide to [f5]. Perhaps it's close to equal, but Black is already in the driver's seat.}) 2... b6 (2... Nf6 3. e3 b6 {will transpose into positions already discussed in the 1...Nf6 lines.}) 3. e4 {Let's take the center finally!} Bb7 {This is played 92% of the time so it will be the move we focus the most on.} 4. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb4c3,Gb7e4] This is played 48% of the time and is by far the most popular choice. Black threatens to chop on [c3] and scoop up [e4].} 5. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2e4] Our queen reinforces [e4]. This may look like it blocks our [f1]-bishop, but we can always opt for a kingside fianchetto with [g2]-[g3]. This strong move is rarely tried though, and already on move 5, we are at a position that has only been reached roughly 4000 times. We will look at Black's only two commonly chosen moves in this position, each of which has a frequency of 40%.} Bxc3 {Black chops in the hope of getting better control over the central light squares that our knight was defending, even if it costs the bishop pair. Here we have an interesting dilemma, as both captures make sense. It is better to open our bishop with [dxc3], or strengthen our central presence with [bxc3]?} 6. dxc3 {It turns out both captures are equally valid; objectively though they lead to quite different struggles. The move chosen leads to a healthier dynamism and a comfortable advantage derived from speedy development and an open d-file. If it's not your cup of tea, feel free to investigate [bxc3].} Ne7 {It makes sense to develop the knight in this way, which avoids any [e4]-[e5] thrust.} 7. Be3 $1 {[%cal Ge1c1] Our e-pawn can be left hanging due to a tactical trick.} O-O 8. e5 {Gripping onto the dark squares.} Nf5 9. O-O-O {It turns out that Black has some issues with the d-file. The [d7]-pawn is backward and a prime target along the open d-file.} d6 {Black tries to fix the weakness by moving it here to eventually trade it.} 10. Bf2 {[%cal Ge3f2,Rf5e3] Dodging any knight trades and opening up our queen's view of the e-file.} Qe8 11. b3 {[%cal Re8a4,Gb3a4] Keeping Black's queen out of the game by covering ...[Qa4] ideas.} dxe5 12. fxe5 {Black may have traded the pawns, but it turns out that wasn't their only problem. We will quickly cook up an initiative involving [Rg1], [g4], and [Ng5] or [Nd2] to reroute the knight to the strong [e4]-square.} c5 13. Rg1 Nd7 14. g4 Ne7 15. Nd2 $18 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gd2e4,Ge4d6] Our knight reroutes to the weakened [d6]-square via [e4].} *

