1. f4 e6 2. Nf3 (2. e4 {is too soon. Black will play} d5 {with a good French.} 3. e5 {would turn into an ugly type of setup with [f4] vs. the French Defense. Black would play ...[c5] to pressure [d4] and a knight would glide to [f5]. Perhaps it's close to equal, but Black is already in the driver's seat.}) 2... b6 (2... Nf6 3. e3 b6 {will transpose into positions already discussed in the 1...Nf6 lines.}) 3. e4 {Let's take the center finally!} Bb7 {This is played 92% of the time so it will be the move we focus the most on.} 4. Nc3 Bb4 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb4c3,Gb7e4] This is played 48% of the time and is by far the most popular choice. Black threatens to chop on [c3] and scoop up [e4].} 5. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2e4] Our queen reinforces [e4]. This may look like it blocks our [f1]-bishop, but we can always opt for a kingside fianchetto with [g2]-[g3]. This strong move is rarely tried though, and already on move 5, we are at a position that has only been reached roughly 4000 times. We will look at Black's only two commonly chosen moves in this position, each of which has a frequency of 40%.} Bxc3 {Black chops in the hope of getting better control over the central light squares that our knight was defending, even if it costs the bishop pair. Here we have an interesting dilemma, as both captures make sense. It is better to open our bishop with [dxc3], or strengthen our central presence with [bxc3]?} 6. dxc3 {It turns out both captures are equally valid; objectively though they lead to quite different struggles. The move chosen leads to a healthier dynamism and a comfortable advantage derived from speedy development and an open d-file. If it's not your cup of tea, feel free to investigate [bxc3].} Nf6 {Attacking [e4].} 7. e5 {[%csl Rf6]} Ne4 $1 {This is only played 20% of the time. The knight stands better here. Black can reinforce the knight with ...[f7]-[f5] or ...[d7]-[d5] at a moment's notice.} 8. Be3 O-O {This is not the right way to go, but it's very natural to look to evacuate the king immediately in such fashion. The king will be vulnerable to a pawn storm sooner or later. Our king will be very safe on the queenside due to having 4 pawns around it.} 9. O-O-O d6 10. g4 $1 {[%cal Gf1g2]} Nd7 11. Bg2 {[%csl Re4] The knight on [e4] begins to feel uncomfortable. It doesn't have many retreat options.} Ndc5 12. Bd4 $16 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge2e4] The knight on [e4] is a recurring sore point. White has all the play here. We can throw our h-pawn forward and create some weaknesses around the black king. Another strong idea is moving our knight to [d2] or [g5] to pressure the [e4]-knight further. White has a huge advantage and even a tiny slip from Black could turn this decisive.} *

