1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 {In this manner, Black first commits to ...[d6] before going for the likely fianchetto with ...[g6]. Because Black burned a tempo on the d-pawn, we can take a chance in the center.} 3. d4 $1 {We will look at Black's 3 most common moves.} Nbd7 {This is tried 10% of the time. Here we have an interesting choice. Objectively, the best is to pursue a classic Stonewall with [e3]. But I will mention an interesting alternative as a gamble.} (3... g6 {is chosen 46% of the time by Black.} 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 {and we transpose to a position discussed in the variation 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 Bg7 4.Nc3 d6 5.d4 .}) 4. e3 (4. Nc3 $5 {is a gamble. The top 5 moves by popularity are} c6 {, 4...g6 , 4...c5 , 4...e5 , and 4...e6 , and comprise a combined frequency of 90%. Against 4...c5 , you can respond with 5.d5 . Meanwhile, you can just take [e5] if they play that. And against the other less confrontational moves you can simply seize the center with [e2]-[e4]. 4...d5= (is extremely unlikely with a frequency of just 1%,) but if your opponent plays ...[d5], then the game is just equal, as the knight is badly placed on [c3] in a Stonewall setup.}) 4... c6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Tried in 24% of games. Black controls [d5] and prepares to play on the queenside wing in the style of the Pirc with ...[b7]-[b5].} 5. a4 $1 Qc7 {[%cal Ge7e5] Aiming for ...[e7]-[e5] shortly.} 6. c4 {Gaining even more of the center.} e5 7. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Gf3] Black's best bet. They need to try to gain some central squares before we complete development and consolidate things.} Be7 {The computer doesn't like this, but I could see most Pirc players continuing this way.} 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O a5 10. b3 $16 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gd1d2,Ya1e1] We will continue with [Bb2], [Qd2] and [Rae1]. White has great control. The 4 pawns between the c- and f-files revolve around the center. We have no weaknesses. Meanwhile, it is hard for Black to budge. We will recapture with the e-pawn whenever a trade happens on [f4] or [d4].} *

