ear future. We will castle and play [Ne5]. Our position is great. Black's queen is misplaced on [c7] and will just be a target for the eventual [Nb5] or [Rc1]. An even bigger clown is that horsey on [d7], which manages to block the [c8]-bishop from developing anywhere.}) 10. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7] Our bishop immediately shores up the newly available [c4]-square. It will pressure [d5] until the knight moves, when it will scope the [f7]-target.} N7f6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf6d5] Reinforcing [d5]. It should be said that Black has a healthier structure than us. Therefore, we should play extremely energetically to guarantee that our lead in development matters more.} 11. O-O Be7 {Shielding the king from checks while preparing to castle.} 12. Ne5 {[%csl Gd4,Gf4][%cal Gf4e5,Gd4e5] The best part about having pawns on [f4] and [d4] is planting a knight on [e5]!} O-O 13. f5 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Gf5] Stifling the bishop, preventing it from ever developing to relevant squares of [f5] and [g4]. We will continue with aggressive development. [Qd3]-[g3] is strong and [Bg5] would also pressure Black's defenses. We welcome any trade on [c3] that would allow us to capture on [c3] with our b-pawn, significantly strengthening our center.} *

