1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 {In this manner, Black first commits to ...[d6] before going for the likely fianchetto with ...[g6]. Because Black burned a tempo on the d-pawn, we can take a chance in the center.} 3. d4 $1 {We will look at Black's 3 most common moves.} Nbd7 {This is tried 10% of the time. Here we have an interesting choice. Objectively, the best is to pursue a classic Stonewall with [e3]. But I will mention an interesting alternative as a gamble.} (3... g6 {is chosen 46% of the time by Black.} 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 {and we transpose to a position discussed in the variation 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 Bg7 4.Nc3 d6 5.d4 .}) 4. e3 (4. Nc3 $5 {is a gamble. The top 5 moves by popularity are} c6 {, 4...g6 , 4...c5 , 4...e5 , and 4...e6 , and comprise a combined frequency of 90%. Against 4...c5 , you can respond with 5.d5 . Meanwhile, you can just take [e5] if they play that. And against the other less confrontational moves you can simply seize the center with [e2]-[e4]. 4...d5= (is extremely unlikely with a frequency of just 1%,) but if your opponent plays ...[d5], then the game is just equal, as the knight is badly placed on [c3] in a Stonewall setup.}) 4... c5 {Black's 3rd most popular option with a frequency of 14%.} 5. d5 {We take the center. It turns out the knight on [d7] doesn't exactly sit well in the Benoni setup we're about to approach. This is because it blocks the bishop from supporting ...[e7]-[e6] and blocks the queen's defense of [d6]. Therefore, ...[e7]-[e6] doesn't work as usual since after [dxe6] and ...[fxe6], we can snatch on [d6] with a healthy extra pawn against Black's ruined structure.} g6 6. Nc3 (6. c4 $5 {was also a fine way to play, when White has bolstered the [d5]-pawn at the cost of a tempo.}) 6... Bg7 7. e4 O-O {[%cal Gb7b5] Black wants to play ...[b7]-[b5] as a sacrifice to deflect our knight or bishop to a vulnerable square. We are best advised to take time to quash this queenside resistance.} 8. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4b5,Rb7b5] No more ...[b5] to worry about.} a6 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O e6 $2 11. dxe6 {It's choppin' time!} Rxe6 $2 ({This wouldn't be any better than} 11... fxe6 {.}) 12. Ng5 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gg5e6,Gg5f7] Pointing straight at the vulnerabilities on [e6] and [f7].} Re7 13. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4f7,Gd1d6] Now [d6] and [f7] creak. A nice sample combination is:} Nb6 14. Bxf7+ Rxf7 15. Nxf7 Kxf7 16. e5 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Ge5d6,Ge5f6,Gd1d8] The pawn is immune to capture due to the pin along the d-file.} Ng8 17. a5 {Continuing to bat Black's pieces back.} Nd7 18. Ne4 $18 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Ge4d6,Ge4g5] Black's king looks on in terror as the White pieces begin the final assault. [Ne4]-[d6] or [Ne4]-[g5] combined with [Qd5] or [Qxd6] will be decisive.} *

