1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 {In this manner, Black first commits to ...[d6] before going for the likely fianchetto with ...[g6]. Because Black burned a tempo on the d-pawn, we can take a chance in the center.} 3. d4 $1 {We will look at Black's 3 most common moves.} Nbd7 {This is tried 10% of the time. Here we have an interesting choice. Objectively, the best is to pursue a classic Stonewall with [e3]. But I will mention an interesting alternative as a gamble.} (3... g6 {is chosen 46% of the time by Black.} 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 {and we transpose to a position discussed in the variation 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 Bg7 4.Nc3 d6 5.d4 .}) 4. e3 (4. Nc3 $5 {is a gamble. The top 5 moves by popularity are} c6 {, 4...g6 , 4...c5 , 4...e5 , and 4...e6 , and comprise a combined frequency of 90%. Against 4...c5 , you can respond with 5.d5 . Meanwhile, you can just take [e5] if they play that. And against the other less confrontational moves you can simply seize the center with [e2]-[e4]. 4...d5= (is extremely unlikely with a frequency of just 1%,) but if your opponent plays ...[d5], then the game is just equal, as the knight is badly placed on [c3] in a Stonewall setup.}) 4... c5 {Black's 3rd most popular option with a frequency of 14%.} 5. d5 {We take the center. It turns out the knight on [d7] doesn't exactly sit well in the Benoni setup we're about to approach. This is because it blocks the bishop from supporting ...[e7]-[e6] and blocks the queen's defense of [d6]. Therefore, ...[e7]-[e6] doesn't work as usual since after [dxe6] and ...[fxe6], we can snatch on [d6] with a healthy extra pawn against Black's ruined structure.} g6 6. Nc3 (6. c4 $5 {was also a fine way to play, when White has bolstered the [d5]-pawn at the cost of a tempo.}) 6... Bg7 7. e4 O-O {[%cal Gb7b5] Black wants to play ...[b7]-[b5] as a sacrifice to deflect our knight or bishop to a vulnerable square. We are best advised to take time to quash this queenside resistance.} 8. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4b5,Rb7b5] No more ...[b5] to worry about.} a6 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 {[%cal Ge7e6] Black is planning ...[e7]-[e6].} 11. Kh1 {This takes the sting out of ...[Nf6]-[g4] ideas since Black can't check with the bishop on [d4] or with the queen on [b6] after ...[c5]-[c4]. Because of this, [Kh1] gets White ready to deal with Black's ...[e6] break.} e6 12. e5 $1 {[%cal Ge5f6] Asking the knight a serious question.} Nxd5 13. Ne4 $1 {A beautiful pawn sacrifice.} dxe5 14. fxe5 $36 {[%csl Rd6,Ge5,Rf6,Rf8][%cal Gc1g5,Ge4d6,Ge5d6,Ge5f6] We dominate the dark squares. Our bishop will swing to [g5] and our knight will penetrate the enemy territory via [d6]. Black will likely lose an exchange the [e8]-rook in the process. [c2]-[c4] to boot the only good black piece from the center could also be considered. The control is already close to overwhelming and objectively Black must walk a tightrope to survive. In other news, the knight on [f8] won the LVP award of 2023, for Least Valuable Player. :} *

