1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 {In this manner, Black first commits to ...[d6] before going for the likely fianchetto with ...[g6]. Because Black burned a tempo on the d-pawn, we can take a chance in the center.} 3. d4 $1 {We will look at Black's 3 most common moves.} Bg4 {Played 12% of the time. I am always happy to see such moves. We have already taken some of the center, and Black is still preoccupied with some abstract notions of development. We must relish every tempo Black gives to gain more control over the central high ground.} (3... g6 {is chosen 46% of the time by Black.} 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 {and we transpose to a position discussed in the variation 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 Bg7 4.Nc3 d6 5.d4 .}) 4. c4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Gf4] We have 3 pawns in the center. The dream is close to being realized. We should energetically work to complete the portrait with [Nc3] and [e2]-[e4].} Nbd7 5. Nc3 e5 $1 {Bringing the fight to the center before we can secure dominance with [e2]-[e4] and normal development. Here we have several interesting ways to play the position. I like the following plan.} 6. g3 $5 {[%cal Gg3f4] This strengthens [f4] and prepares a bishop fianchetto to [g2].} Be7 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O $14 {[%cal Gh2h3,Ye5d4,Yf3d4,Ye5f4,Yc1f4,Ge2e4] White has a slight edge. If Black chops on [d4], we can take back with the knight. Meanwhile, if they take on [f4], both the bishop and the g-pawn recaptures make sense, though the bishop recapture looks healthier. We should aim to play [e2]-[e4] as soon as possible to gain a solid stake in the center. This would also shore up potentially weak squares on the e-file like [e3] and [e4], which, due to our [d2]-[d4] and [f2]-[f4] advances, have been weakened for the long term. We should play [h2]-[h3] sooner or later to force Black to trade the bishop on [f3], ceding us the bishop pair.} *

