1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Nf6 {In this manner, Black first commits to ...[d6] before going for the likely fianchetto with ...[g6]. Because Black burned a tempo on the d-pawn, we can take a chance in the center.} 3. d4 $1 {We will look at Black's 3 most common moves.} Bg4 {Played 12% of the time. I am always happy to see such moves. We have already taken some of the center, and Black is still preoccupied with some abstract notions of development. We must relish every tempo Black gives to gain more control over the central high ground.} (3... g6 {is chosen 46% of the time by Black.} 4. c4 Bg7 5. Nc3 {and we transpose to a position discussed in the variation 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 Bg7 4.Nc3 d6 5.d4 .}) 4. c4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Gf4] We have 3 pawns in the center. The dream is close to being realized. We should energetically work to complete the portrait with [Nc3] and [e2]-[e4].} Bxf3 {Chopping here is Black's most popular option.} 5. exf3 $1 {This capture opens and strengthens our kingside pawn mass. This may not seem important, but the game is heading to one in which our king will go to the queenside and theirs will head toward the kingside. In such a turn of events, our pawns on the kingside will be able to race quickly up the board and this will be complemented nicely by our bishop pair.} e6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Fighting for the [d5]-square while preparing ...[Be7] and ...[O-O].} 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Qb3 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gb3b7] Poking at Black's queenside.} Qc8 9. O-O-O $36 {[%cal Gc1b1,Gg2g4,Gh2h4] We will play [Kb1] to get our king a bit farther away from the volatile center and then begin flinging our pawns forth on the kingside. [g2]-[g4]-[g5] and [h2]-[h4]-[h5] can both be played without any special preparation.} *

