1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Nf6 {This is rarely played here, being tried only 2% of the time. Believe it or not, we're in a tricky situation. If we play [e3], then Black can play ...[c5], aiming for a Fianchetto Sicilian that takes us out of our repertoire remember we play [c2]-[c3] and [e2]-[e4] against Sicilians with an early fianchetto. Meanwhile, if we play [d3], Black can play ...[d5], taking us into an entirely different family of ...[d5] systems than the ones we're accustomed to with [e2]-[e3]. I will suggest a novel approach to shake the game up. We won't cover it in too much detail, as Black is extremely unlikely to get here to begin with.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. c4 $5 {Gaining a stake in the center in a novel way. Your opponent's are likely to have never seen anything like this.} Bg7 {Continuing with the fianchetto as planned.} 4. Nc3 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Gf3,Gf4] Setting up both our knights in the positionally healthy way behind the pawns. Both work in complement with the pawn in front of them to fight for an important central square.} d6 {Black opts for this 27% of the time. Their setup is beginning to resemble a King's Indian with a kingside fianchetto and plans for ...[d7]-[d6] and ...[e7]-[e5]. Here we have a choice to grip the central light squares with [e2]-[e4] or the dark squares with [d2]-[d4].} 5. d4 {It's better to grip the dark squares, as Black was planning some funny business with ...[e7]-[e5].} c5 $1 {This is objectively strongest, but only 3% of games to reach this position have tried it.} 6. dxc5 {A good try that holds some poison.} (6. d5 {is also a fine way to handle it. I normally recommend this space-focused approach, but here Black could drag us into a popular line of the Benoni.} O-O 7. e4 e6 {and all of a sudden we're in the famous tabiya of the Four Pawns Attack of the Modern Benoni. This is outside the purview of the course. If you are a space-hungry chess player like me who wants to control the whole board with pawns, feel free to analyze this at home.}) 6... O-O $1 {The strongest, but it is the 3rd most popular at a frequency of 22%.} 7. cxd6 exd6 8. e3 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1] We will continue with [Be2] and castling kingside. Black has good compensation due to the weak pawn on [e3] and the weak square of [e4]. For the moment the game is level, but if we can figure out a way to assert [e3]-[e4] with confidence, our weaknesses will vanish and we will be in the driver's seat.} *

