Indian. It does not make sense to go for theoretical moves, as this position is so unlikely to occur from a Bird that the memorization and learning would not be commensurate to the frequency with which you would ever have to play it. For reference, the chances of getting this in your games are something like .05% and it would be an entire chapter's worth of material. Not worth the squeeze if you ask me! [d5] and [Be2] are the best moves though, so if you want to spend a day inside studying such positions, feel free to.}) 7. dxc5 $5 {This is a second rate move but will catch our opponents off guard.} Na6 $1 {The best continuation is to sac the pawn for great play with ...[Nc5] and on the dark squares in general. This has been played roughly 0% of the time though, with only 37 games out of approximately 8000 following this path. We should walk a fine line to keep the balance.} 8. cxd6 exd6 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gf8e8] Black threatens to get a fantastic initiative with ...[Nc5] and ...[Re8] so we are best advised to force matters and trade queens with a central push.} 9. e5 dxe5 10. Qxd8 {With the queens off, we can breathe a sigh of relief. There won't be any miniature of us getting checkmated on move 15, big guy!} Rxd8 11. fxe5 Ng4 12. Bf4 {Maintaining [e5] under control.} Nb4 13. Rc1 $13 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Ge1f2] The game is balanced. We should play [Be2] and get our king castled or [f2] would also be fine if the knight on [g4] was kicked.} *

