1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} e6 $2 {This is a really funky and frankly unsound way to play that has a formidable frequency of 21%. I tell my students that mixing ...[e6] with ...[g6] early on in the game is usually bad because it weakens the dark squares too much and this is no exception. Black is trying to play the Hippo and we should be happy to let them. :} 4. d4 $1 {Taking on even more of the center.} Ne7 {The overwhelming favorite here.} (4... d6 {can also be tried in an attempt to get to the Hippopotamus Defense. This will likely transpose to the same positions as after 4...Ne7 .}) 5. Bd3 O-O {This is popular, but it is not the right way to play the Hippo. Once the king has committed to the kingside, we can launch forward to begin aggressive measures.} 6. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] Normally in the Hippo this move can be met with ...[h6] to meet our [h4]-[h5] with ...[g6]-[g5]. But with our pawn present on [f4] here, that idea goes up in smoke!} b6 $2 {Black simply ignores our plans.} 7. h5 Bb7 8. g4 $1 {A nice multipurpose move! The g-pawn might move to [g5] to push a minor piece like the [g7]-bishop if it were to move there back from [f6]. It also clears the second rank such that [Qd2]-[h2] and [Qe2]-[h2] have become possible.} Nbc6 9. hxg6 hxg6 (9... fxg6 {would not be any better.} 10. c3 {+- . we will continue with [Qe2]-[h2]. Black might be able to keep things at bay with ...[h7]-[h6], but after developing a bit and castling queenside, some breakthrough like [f4]-[f5] should decide.}) 10. c3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc3d4] Cementing the pawn. The queen transfer to [h2] could have happened immediately, but Black can't deal with it anyway so there is no rush.} f6 {[%cal Gg8f7] Creating an escape hatch for the king.} 11. Qe2 Kf7 {The king has made it out alive it seems.} 12. Na3 $18 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge1c1] But that is the end of the good news. We will play [Bd2], castle queenside, set our rooks pointed at the king on squares like [g1] and [f1], and finally break through with [f4]-[f5]; [f4]-[f5] is the perfect breakthrough because by initiating tension against two of the black pawns, Black can't avoid a file opening to reveal their stranded king.} *

