th ...[f7]-[f6], such a move would destroy the bishop's potential and leave them with a new weakness on [g6].} 7. e5 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc3e4] Seizing more space and preparing [Nb1]-[c3]-[e4].} d6 {[%cal Gd6e5] Black crunches immediately on the pawns. This was the drawback to playing [e4]-[e5] before Black had played ...[d7]-[d5]. We could continue with [Nc3] with normal development and a slight edge, but we have a nice way to play for an energetic attack.} 8. g4 $1 hxg4 9. Ng5 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Rc8g4,Gd1g4] The point of our early [e4]-[e5] stuff is revealed. Black can never protect the [g4]-pawn with ...[e6]-[e5], as [e5] stands like a boulder in the e-pawn's way.} dxe5 10. dxe5 Nbc6 11. Qxg4 {[%cal Gh4h5] With [h4]-[h5] to follow shortly, White is on the verge of a winning attack. Black must walk a tightrope starting with the positionally hideous ...[f7]-[f6].} f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Qg2 {[%cal Rc8g4] Sidestepping any tricks with ...[e6]-[e5].} e5 14. Nc3 $40 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge1c1] Black has survived our first wave of attack by getting the [c8]-bishop out in time, but that's where the good news ends. We will play [Bd2] and castle queenside with a much safer king. With such an exposed king like that on [g8], we can conduct wave after wave until the black king finally falls. Black's position is extremely difficult practically, even if it is objectively tenable.} *

