1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} e6 $2 {This is a really funky and frankly unsound way to play that has a formidable frequency of 21%. I tell my students that mixing ...[e6] with ...[g6] early on in the game is usually bad because it weakens the dark squares too much and this is no exception. Black is trying to play the Hippo and we should be happy to let them. :} 4. d4 $1 {Taking on even more of the center.} Ne7 {The overwhelming favorite here.} (4... d6 {can also be tried in an attempt to get to the Hippopotamus Defense. This will likely transpose to the same positions as after 4...Ne7 .}) 5. Bd3 O-O {This is popular, but it is not the right way to play the Hippo. Once the king has committed to the kingside, we can launch forward to begin aggressive measures.} 6. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] Normally in the Hippo this move can be met with ...[h6] to meet our [h4]-[h5] with ...[g6]-[g5]. But with our pawn present on [f4] here, that idea goes up in smoke!} d5 {This is the most popular continuation and a deep strategic blunder.} 7. e5 $1 {We seize space on the kingside and with the d-pawn locked in on [d5], the center is completely closed. This means we can attack with ease on the kingside as if it were a vacuum. Just imagine how Black's queenside pieces like the [c8]-bishop would ever be able to get over the central mountain of pawns to help out with things.} h5 {Black tries to hold off our attack, but ...[d7]-[d5] dug their hole already.} 8. Rg1 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gg2g4] Choo, choo, all aboard the [g4]-train.} c5 {Black desperately tries to open the center to eventually get the pieces over to aid the kingside.} 9. g4 $1 {[%cal Gg4h5]} c4 {Pushing our bishop back.} (9... cxd4 $2 {would collapse quickly. After} 10. gxh5 gxh5 11. Ng5 {+- , [Qxh5] and [Qh7] will decide immediately.}) 10. Bf1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gg4h5,Gf3g5] While our bishop has been pushed away from an immediately aggressive position, look at what Black has done. The pawn on [c4] locks the position even more, as ...[cxd4] is no longer on the table. We threaten [gxh5] and [Ng5] with [Qd1xh5] threats.} hxg4 {This keeps the structure more compact and avoids taking a weakness on [h5], but on the flip side, we can now chip away with [h4]-[h5].} 11. Rxg4 Nf5 12. h5 {[%cal Gh5g6] Initiating some tension. Taking on [h5] spells the opening of the g- and h-files making it not feasible for Black.} Nc6 13. Nc3 Bd7 14. Bh3 $18 {[%cal Gg4g2,Yc3e2,Ye2g3,Yf3g5] We have a winning attack even if things may not look so clear. We will move the rook back to [g2] to open the bishop's sights on [f5]. Then we will aim for [Nc3]-[e2]-[g3] and [Nf3]-[g5] to pressure the kingside more. [c2]-[c3] would be useful in strengthening our center during this time as well. Notice we are not taking on [g6] yet, as that would just open the f-file for the opponent.} *

