1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} b6 {Black goes for the double fianchetto in such fashion in 10% of games.} 4. d4 {As per usual, we take even more of the center.} Bb7 5. Bd3 e6 {Black is yet again going for a Hippo setup with pawns on [b6], [d6], [e6], and [g6].} 6. Nc3 {A very healthy setup is beginning to take form.} Ne7 7. Be3 O-O {Whenever we see this, we should immediately consider making use of our [h1]-rook by initiating a pawn storm.} 8. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5,Gh5g6] Now [h4]-[h5xg6] constitutes a huge threat over Black's camp. If we're able to achieve it, a simple transfer of the queen to the h-file and a queenside castle will begin a simple attacking rout of the enemy king.} h5 {Stopping our advance.} 9. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Yd7d5,Ye4e5] We will castle queenside and prepare [g2]-[g4] to chip away at [h5]. Once Black takes on [g4], we will look to play [h4]-[h5], THE FINAL CHIP. Remember, if they play ...[d7]-[d5], we should respond with [e4]-[e5], when we have a great space advantage on the kingside, and with the closed center, our exclusive access to this section of the board means we can effortlessly conduct the attack in an effective vacuum.} *

