1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} d5 $5 {An interesting way for Black to attempt to wrest control of the light squares from White's setup. While not that popular at a frequency of only 6%, there are pockets of players throughout the world that specialize in such systems. A Russian player at my local club, the Marshall, named Yevgeniy Margulis, used to play such a setup. He called it the Margulis system and as much as I tried to break it, his light-squared blockade always resisted successfully. I was left with a strong impression of such setups and even to this day feel a bit unconfident in facing the scheme.} 4. e5 $1 {Gaining space! The pawn sits like a boulder on [e5], clogging the scope of the [g7]-bishop.} c5 $1 {The strongest and Black's 2nd most popular choice at a frequency of 19%. The pawn digs into our center and complicates our achieving a proper center with [d2]-[d4]. Here Stockfish points out a very surprising move as White's best.} 5. Nc3 $5 {We are waiting Black out. We wanted to push [d4], but at the moment Black can fight against it with ...[cxd4] and ...[Nc6]. With our knight on c3, 6.d4 cxd4 7.Qxd4 hits hard, as the [d5]-pawn will be hanging. Black has a difficult choice ahead of them.} d4 {Black stops [d4] but at the expensive price of the [e4]-square.} 6. Ne4 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge4c5]} b6 7. Bb5+ {Initiating a trade of light-squared bishops so Black will be left with several weaknesses on the light squares and an ugly dark-squared dragon.} Bd7 8. a4 $16 {[%cal Gd2d3,Yd7b5,Ya4b5,Ge1g1] We are happy to trade but in no rush. If Black trades, we will be able to recapture with the a-pawn, bringing the pawn to [b5] where it dominates the [b8]-knight from any active options on [c6]. We will continue with [d3], castle kingside, and can consider ideas like [Qe1]-[h4]. As long as our bishop stands on [b5], it could make sense to retreat it to [c4] where it targets [f7]. Especially if Black avoids the bishop trade and plays ...[Nc6], this will constitute a strong regrouping.} *

