of them.} Nc6 6. Bb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5e8] Our bishop pins the knight, wresting further control of the [d4]-square.} a6 $2 7. Bxc6+ {The return of the chop.} bxc6 8. Na4 {[%csl Rc5] Now [c5] is put under immediate pressure. Black appears to have transposed into an awful version of the Rossolimo Sicilian in which the [g7]-bishop is buried and Black has already played ...[d6]-[d5], compromising the [c5]-square.} c4 9. O-O Nh6 10. d3 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd3c4] Chopping away. [c4] is a doubled pawn, but it's cemented by [d5] so it's not the real weakness in their position. Instead, the weak [c5]-square and [c6]-pawn are our targets. With [d3] we threaten to trade on [c4], giving Black doubled isolated pawns. Black will oblige us by trading on [d3], when we can open the c-file and unleash the power of the rooks.} cxd3 11. cxd3 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6][%cal Gd3d4,Gc1d2,Ga1c1,Gc1c6] With [d3]-[d4] to cement control over [c5], and [Bd2] and [Rac1] to follow, White has an enormous positional advantage. The [c6]-weakness will burden Black well into the final stages of the game.} *

