1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} d5 $5 {An interesting way for Black to attempt to wrest control of the light squares from White's setup. While not that popular at a frequency of only 6%, there are pockets of players throughout the world that specialize in such systems. A Russian player at my local club, the Marshall, named Yevgeniy Margulis, used to play such a setup. He called it the Margulis system and as much as I tried to break it, his light-squared blockade always resisted successfully. I was left with a strong impression of such setups and even to this day feel a bit unconfident in facing the scheme.} 4. e5 $1 {Gaining space! The pawn sits like a boulder on [e5], clogging the scope of the [g7]-bishop.} f6 {This is played 17% of the time. Black desperately tries to free the [f6]-square for the [g8]-knight.} 5. d4 {[%csl Ge5] Reinforcing the strong pawn. Remember to always make your opponent's life as hard as possible. If they want to bring the knight to [f6], we should make that impossible.} fxe5 $6 {This is chosen all the time but just makes Black's position a bit worse.} 6. fxe5 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gc1g5] We can take stock of the trade. Our [f4]-pawn obstructed our [c1]-bishop and additionally, our [b1]-knight can now use [f4] via [b1]-[c3]-[e2]-[f4] to pressure the weak [e6]-square. Meanwhile, Black has gotten almost no use out of the removal of the [f6]-pawn. The [g7]-bishop still points into [e5]-concrete and the [g8]-knight is still prohibited from [f6].} Nh6 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gh6f5] Such development is natural in the Margulis system. The knight aims for the tender [f5]-square.} 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2 Bg4 {Black wants to chop on [f3], play ...[e6] to consolidate [d5], and bring the [h6]-knight to [f5].} ({After} 8... Nf5 9. O-O {± , we will kick the [f5]-knight out shortly with [g2]-[g4], and after the knight runs, cement [g4] with [h2]-[h3]. White has a huge advantage due to extra space and better pieces.}) 9. Ng5 $1 {Trading off the bishop, which was Black's only defender of [e6].} Bxe2 10. Nxe2 $16 {[%csl Re6][%cal Ge2f4] White will play [Nf4] and castle kingside, when our knights have a strong grip on the weak [e6]-square. Black's bishop is still awful, as it remains pointed into the concrete. We will look to dig a knight into [e6] and keep it there perhaps with [Qd1]-[d3]-[h3]. With the knight dug in, Black's coordination will suffer greatly and one slip will push the disadvantage past the threshold of decisive.} *

