1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} d5 $5 {An interesting way for Black to attempt to wrest control of the light squares from White's setup. While not that popular at a frequency of only 6%, there are pockets of players throughout the world that specialize in such systems. A Russian player at my local club, the Marshall, named Yevgeniy Margulis, used to play such a setup. He called it the Margulis system and as much as I tried to break it, his light-squared blockade always resisted successfully. I was left with a strong impression of such setups and even to this day feel a bit unconfident in facing the scheme.} 4. e5 $1 {Gaining space! The pawn sits like a boulder on [e5], clogging the scope of the [g7]-bishop.} Bg4 $6 {Black's most popular choice. It is sensible to trade off the [c8]-bishop before locking the game with ...[e7]-[e6], but on the other hand, this gives us a free hand in the center.} 5. d4 e6 6. Be3 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Rc7c5] White has a fantastic version of Advanced French. First, Black's bishop makes no sense on [g7] where it points into the [e5]-cement and does not help the ...[c7]-[c5] break at all. Second, we got in [f2]-[f4] for free, which is thematically very good for our structure. [f4]-[f5] is the thematic break in these structures and while it is still a ways off, it requires much less preparation than if the pawn were on [f2]!} Ne7 {The knight aims at [f5].} 7. Nbd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2f3] Reinforcing the [f3]-knight. We wanted to play [h2]-[h3], but recapturing with the queen on [f3] looked a bit awkward for our control over [d4]. Now we can play [h2]-[h3] with ease, as the [d2]-knight will recapture on [f3] with healthy stability.} O-O 8. Be2 Nf5 9. Bf2 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gf2d4,Gf2h4] Our bishop dominates all the knight's advances. The knight might look good on [f5], but don't worry, we will boot it with [g2]-[g4] eventually.} c5 {[%cal Gc5d4] A thematic idea to mess up our center.} 10. dxc5 $1 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gf2c5] Unlike normal French positions, Black cannot count on winning [c5] back. Our bishop defends it well and the black bishop has diverted its gaze from [c5] by placing itself on [g7].} f6 $1 {Our pawn has left [d4] and Black makes sense of the [c5]-sacrifice by chopping further in the center.} 11. exf6 Qxf6 12. c3 $16 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3,Re6][%cal Ge1g1,Rf6c3] The black queen and bishop point across the diagonal... at granite! We have great control and will castle and boot the bishop with [h2]-[h3]. Black's structure is strategically weak and if we are able to coordinate properly, [e6] will show itself to be an enormous weakness.} *

