ure. [f4]-[f5] is the thematic break in these structures and while it is still a ways off, it requires much less preparation than if the pawn were on [f2]!} Ne7 {The knight aims at [f5].} 7. Nbd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2f3] Reinforcing the [f3]-knight. We wanted to play [h2]-[h3], but recapturing with the queen on [f3] looked a bit awkward for our control over [d4]. Now we can play [h2]-[h3] with ease, as the [d2]-knight will recapture on [f3] with healthy stability.} O-O 8. Be2 Nf5 9. Bf2 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gf2d4,Gf2h4] Our bishop dominates all the knight's advances. The knight might look good on [f5], but don't worry, we will boot it with [g2]-[g4] eventually.} Nd7 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 $16 {[%cal Ge1g1,Yg2g4] White will castle and prepare [g2]-[g4] at the right moment. If Black plays ...[c5], we have two options. We can reinforce our center with [c3], when we will recapture on [d4] with the c-pawn, keeping the good center. Or we could snatch [c5] and attempt to hold onto the pawn by means of building a pawn tree with [b2]-[b4] and [c2]-[c3]. White has a close to winning advantage due to the extra space and the bishop pair.} *

