1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} d6 {Black's most popular move, being chosen in 40% of games.} 4. d4 $1 {Taking even more of the center.} c5 $1 {Only played 4% of the time, but it remains Black's best chance to fight for equality.} 5. d5 {We gain space and head to a pseudo-Benoni-style position in which we haven't yet pushed [c4].} Nf6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf6e4] Attacking [e4].} 6. Nc3 {In defending [e4] we forgo being able to play [c2]-[c4]. No matter, we will develop normally with good chances for an advantage in the middlegame.} O-O 7. Bd3 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5] Black correctly initiates tension against our space while there is still time. If we let the trade on [d5] happen, we may be left with a weak pawn on [d5].} 8. dxe6 Bxe6 9. O-O Nc6 10. f5 $14 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gd1d2] We push the bishop back and can continue with kingside play such as [Bg5] or [Be3] and [Qd2]. Black's [d6]-pawn could reveal itself to be quite the weakness going forward. We are slightly better.} *

