1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} d6 {Black's most popular move, being chosen in 40% of games.} 4. d4 $1 {Taking even more of the center.} Bg4 $2 {Tried 15% of the time, but it remains dubious. Black pressures the knight in an attempt to gain control over [d4]. Black isn't challenging our space and moreover, with the bishop placed here, Black is committing to cede the bishop pair with ...[Bxf3] sooner or later.} 5. c3 $1 {[%cal Gc3d4] Reinforcing [d4].} Nd7 6. h3 {Taking the bishop pair to the bank.} Bxf3 ({Of course not} 6... Bh5 7. g4 {+- .}) 7. Qxf3 e5 {Black attempts to gain some control over the dark squares.} 8. Be3 $16 {[%cal Ye5d4,Ye3d4,Gb1d2,Gf1c4,Ge1g1] Fortifying the center. We are happy to recapture on [d4] with the bishop if Black plays ...[exd4], as a bishop trade would leave Black's kingside dark squares of [g7], [h6], and [f6] very vulnerable. Otherwise, we will just continue development with [Nd2] and [Bc4], when our bishop zooms down the open [a2]-[g8] diagonal. We can castle either way, but I prefer kingside, which is a bit safer and a bit less risky.} *

