1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} d6 {Black's most popular move, being chosen in 40% of games.} 4. d4 $1 {Taking even more of the center.} Nd7 {This is played 12% of the time but doesn't make much sense. It blocks the [c8]-bishop even though ...[Bg4xf3] is one of the key thematic ideas to ease the spatial disadvantage by trading pieces.} 5. Nc3 {Controlling [e4] and [d5].} Ngf6 {This has been tried quite a bit, but it leads to the world's worst Pirc Defense.} 6. e5 $18 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Rf6d5,Gc3d5] The knight cannot run to either of the usual squares of [d7] or [d5]. Instead, it has a choice between 3 awful options on [h5], [g4] and [g8]. Black's best option is ...[Ng8], but even then we are strategically winning due to the enormous amount of time Black has lost in moving the knights aimlessly. We will play [Be3], [Bd3], and castle kingside with an overwhelming amount of space and crisp lead in development.} *

