1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} d6 {Black's most popular move, being chosen in 40% of games.} 4. d4 $1 {Taking even more of the center.} Nc6 {Played 10% of the time.} 5. Be2 $1 {Of course, my first instinct is to push [d4]-[d5], but handling the position this way is much more accurate. Our bishop cushions the [f3]-knight against any potential pin of ...[Bg4]. Meanwhile, we can still push [d4]-[d5] in the near future if the conditions for doing so improve.} e5 {A natural try to break in the center, but we are well prepared to meet it.} 6. dxe5 $1 dxe5 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 (7... Nxd8 8. Nxe5 {and we net a pawn.}) 8. O-O Nge7 9. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gc1e3,Ge2c4] White has a big advantage due to the lead in development and misplaced king on [e8]. Notice without queens on the board, we don't have a winning attack against the aloof king, but nonetheless the king still stands in the way of the rooks' development and will cost Black at least a few tempi to fix the position. We can play for [Be3] and a quick [Rad1]. There is a lot of tension in the center so depending on how things shake out, our better development should allow us to build an initiative on weaknesses that pop up.} *

