1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} d6 {Black's most popular move, being chosen in 40% of games.} 4. d4 $1 {Taking even more of the center.} Nf6 (4... Nf6 {The favorite of Black players here, being essayed 36% of the time. We have an interesting choice.} 5. Nc3 {would transpose into the Austrian Attack of the Pirc variation. Meanwhile, 5.e5 would likely transpose into Alekhine lines in which White has played an early [f2]-[f4].}) 5. e5 $1 {This is a space-hungry repertoire after all.} Nd5 {Black's best response, but it is only played 6% of the time.} 6. c4 Nb6 7. h3 {[%cal Rc8g4,Gh3g4] Stopping ...[Bg4] ideas, which would help Black undermine our central control over [d4].} O-O 8. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gf1e2,Yc7c5,Ge1g1,Yd4d5] We will continue with [Be3], [Be2] and castle kingside. Our space advantage gives us an edge. Black's pieces suffer a serious cramp. Importantly, if Black tries to wreck our center with ...[c7]-[c5], we will advance further with [d4]-[d5], gaining a permanent wedge into the vital [c6]-square that Black's [b8]-knight fawns over.} *

