1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} d6 {Black's most popular move, being chosen in 40% of games.} 4. d4 $1 {Taking even more of the center.} Nf6 (4... Nf6 {The favorite of Black players here, being essayed 36% of the time. We have an interesting choice.} 5. Nc3 {would transpose into the Austrian Attack of the Pirc variation. Meanwhile, 5.e5 would likely transpose into Alekhine lines in which White has played an early [f2]-[f4].}) 5. e5 $1 {This is a space-hungry repertoire after all.} dxe5 $6 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf4e5,Gc1g5] Black's most common response, but this doesn't make much sense. When we recapture with the [f4]-pawn, our [c1]-bishop will scope the whole diagonal. Meanwhile, Black hasn't achieved anything with the disappearance of the d-pawn.} 6. fxe5 Nfd7 {Here the knight is even worse placed than on [d5]. It clogs [d7] and manages to block the queen, the [c8]-bishop, and the [b8]-knight while uselessly pointing at the [e5]-concrete.} 7. Bf4 O-O 8. Nc3 Nb6 9. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gf1e2,Yf4h6] We will castle queenside and develop with [Be2]. Long term, we can either attack the black king with a quick attack of [Bh6] and [h2]-[h4]-[h5], or we can play in the center and try to get [d4]-[d5] going with an overwhelming space advantage. In either case, we have great chances!} *

