1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {Of all the variations of the kingside fianchetto we cover, this is the most popular, with nearly 400000 games having reached this position in the database. It might not be great, but for many people who don't want to study openings, it is a simple first 2 moves for them to remember.} (2... d6 3. e4 Bg7 {is played with overwhelming popularity here, leading right back into the position analyzed after 1.f4 g6 2.Nf3 Bg7 3.e4 .}) 3. e4 {We seize more of the center while we can. In most of our Sicilian chapters, we dreamt of being able to go [e2]-[e4] in one go. The good news is that Black's best move transposes into territory we've already covered. Meanwhile, most other moves give great chances of an edge.} d6 {Black's most popular move, being chosen in 40% of games.} 4. d4 $1 {Taking even more of the center.} Nf6 (4... Nf6 {The favorite of Black players here, being essayed 36% of the time. We have an interesting choice.} 5. Nc3 {would transpose into the Austrian Attack of the Pirc variation. Meanwhile, 5.e5 would likely transpose into Alekhine lines in which White has played an early [f2]-[f4].}) 5. e5 $1 {This is a space-hungry repertoire after all.} dxe5 $6 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf4e5,Gc1g5] Black's most common response, but this doesn't make much sense. When we recapture with the [f4]-pawn, our [c1]-bishop will scope the whole diagonal. Meanwhile, Black hasn't achieved anything with the disappearance of the d-pawn.} 6. fxe5 Nd5 {Played 62% of the time.} 7. c4 {Chasing the knight away.} Nb6 8. h3 $1 {[%cal Rc8g4,Gh3g4] Preventing the important ...[Bg4], which would allow Black to trade off one of our critical defenders of the vital [d4]-square. I'd like to mention that GM Gajewski covers these Alekhine positions in his White repertoire for [e4] Part 2. It provides a much deeper coverage of such positions than will be discussed here, so if you find these positions interesting, feel free to check it out.} O-O 9. Nc3 {White's pieces can all develop to fantastic squares. Our knights sit on the great squares [f3] and [c3]; meanwhile, we will soon develop the bishop to [e2] or [d3] and castle.} c5 {When Black pressures [d4] in such a manner, remember the precise follow-up:} 10. d5 {Our pawns dig into the half of the enemy's third rank. Notice how because Black has pushed the c-pawn, our center is even stronger since Black can never challenge our d-pawn with ...[c7]-[c6].} e6 {Here we must again play precisely.} 11. Bg5 $1 {Poking the queen around.} (11. d6 $2 {is always my first inclination, but the problem is that our e-pawn will get promptly encircled by the enemy knights. Following} Nc6 12. Bf4 Nd7 {∓ , Black has great pressure on [e5] and the position can blow open with ...[f7]-[f6], when White's king will be left exposed and our pieces underdeveloped.}) 11... Qe8 12. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5c7] Now [Nc7] looms as a big threat.} Na6 13. d6 $16 {[%csl Ra6,Gd6][%cal Gf1d3,Ge1g1] We can finally put our pawn on this strong square. The difference between this and the position after 11.d6? Nc6 12.Bf4 Nd7 is that the black knights cannot coordinate effectively against our [e5]-pawn. We will get our [f1]-bishop out, castle, and have a close to winning space advantage with Black's pieces cramped from our [d6]-boulder. Sooner or later we may want to scoop up the exchange with [Be7], but right now development is more important.} *

