1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Bg4 {Black immediately threatens an exchange on [f3]. We shouldn't be too worried, as this is Black's good bishop after all.} 3. e4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] Taking the center.} c5 {Black is going for a Sicilian after all.} 4. h3 {Collecting the bishop is not only the simplest route to an advantage but also the strongest.} Bxf3 5. Bb5+ $1 {By playing this move immediately, Black has to decide if they want to allow the unfavorable chop on [c6].} (5. Qxf3 {would also be fine, when White has a great version of a Grand Prix Attack due to the unopposed light-squared bishop.} Nc6 6. Bb5 Qb6 {is the difference from our recommended line. We are not able to force a doubling of the black c-pawns, though White is still a bit better even here.}) 5... Nc6 (5... Nd7 6. Qxf3 {is a great Grand Prix Attack. We will castle, play [d3] and [Nc3], and eventually play for [f4]-[f5].}) 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. Qxf3 {White has a comfortable edge due to the inflexible Black's structure. This structure of [c6]+c5+d6 is covered in depth in our Sicilian chapters. Here however we haven't had to waste a tempo on [e2]-[e3] and then [e3]-[e4].} g6 $1 {Black must do this before we play [b3].} 8. O-O (8. b3 $6 Bg7 {and we don't dominate the diagonal, although even here Stockfish insists White is slightly better.}) 8... Bg7 9. d3 {It makes sense to first secure the [e4]-pawn.} Nf6 10. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] Our knight is best placed on this structure on [c4]. Hence this is why we decided against [Nc3].} O-O 11. Rb1 $14 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] Our rook moves off of the dangerous diagonal. We will play [b3] and [Bb2] and then perhaps [Nc4]. White has a stable edge due to the better and more flexible pawns.} (11. Nc4 $6 {is a bit inaccurate, as Black can sabotage White's structure immediately.} d5 12. Ne5 c4 {∞ and several pawn trades will happen. Even if we end up a pawn up, Black's better development and well-posted [g7]-dragon will ensure good compensation.}) (11. b3 $4 {would be a huge mistake.} Nxe4 {leaves our rook on [a1] exposed.}) *

