1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Bg4 {Black immediately threatens an exchange on [f3]. We shouldn't be too worried, as this is Black's good bishop after all.} 3. e4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] Taking the center.} e5 {This makes more sense than the immediate capture on [f3] since at least we'll have to burn a move on [h3] to elicit the trade.} 4. h3 Bxf3 5. Qxf3 {[%csl Rc7,Rd6,Re5] Black still has committed the mistake of placing the pawns on the color of their remaining bishop.} Nc6 6. Bb5 {Black is playing a tempo up over positions analyzed after 3...Bxf3 . Therefore Black is only a bit worse as we will see in some sample variations.} Nf6 {Straightforward development.} 7. O-O Qd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] Avoiding any infliction of doubled pawns after a [Bxc6].} 8. Nc3 Be7 {Here we could continue calmly with [d3] and retain a nice edge. But there is something even stronger...} 9. Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd5e7,Gd5f6,Gb5e8] The pressure against Black's position is beginning to mount. Black can never take on [d5] on account of [exd5], winning the [c6]-knight.} O-O 10. d3 a6 {Black has to burn this move to get us to resolve the tension.} 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Ne3 $16 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Ge3f5] White's knight will arrive on [f5] shortly. White has a great kingside initiative meanwhile Black is left grasping at straws to find any logical middlegame plan.} *

