1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Bg4 {Black immediately threatens an exchange on [f3]. We shouldn't be too worried, as this is Black's good bishop after all.} 3. e4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] Taking the center.} Bxf3 $2 {Black's most popular move but an obvious positional error.} 4. Qxf3 {Black's idea makes little sense. Black has gone out of their way to trade their best minor piece and cede the bishop pair.} e5 {Fighting for the dark squares, but again this makes no sense with Black having traded their light-squared bishop.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 {Here any plan of simple development would secure us a hefty edge on account of our extra space and bishop pair. But the computer finds a very nice way to mobilize quickly.} 6. b3 $1 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ge1c1] The plan is to castle queenside!} Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. O-O-O {[%cal Gd2d4] Already White threatens to blast open the position with [d2]-[d4].} Nc6 {Stopping our [d4] plan and developing − this is by far Black's best chance.} 9. Ne2 $16 {[%cal Gd2d4] The knight rebounds to counter the [c6]-knight's grasp on [d4]. We'll throw [d4] in shortly! White will have a big advantage with the extra space, better pieces, and bishop pair. We should aim to attack the black king, as this is a position in which the kings have castled to opposite sides of the board this makes the games more attacking.} *

