1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Bg4 {Black immediately threatens an exchange on [f3]. We shouldn't be too worried, as this is Black's good bishop after all.} 3. e4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] Taking the center.} Bxf3 $2 {Black's most popular move but an obvious positional error.} 4. Qxf3 {Black's idea makes little sense. Black has gone out of their way to trade their best minor piece and cede the bishop pair.} c5 5. Bb5+ {[%csl Rc6,Rd7] Black's light squares are feeling weak without their best protector the [c8]-bishop.} Nc6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. b3 $16 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ge1g1] White has a big advantage. We will play [Bb2], [O-O] and aim to develop the knight either to [d2] or [c3] depending on circumstances. Likely we will look to transform the position with an expansion of [e4]-[e5] or [f4]-[f5]. Black's position is uncomfortable especially since with White having played [b3], Black is not in time to play ...[g6] and ...[Bg7].} *

