1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Bg4 {Black immediately threatens an exchange on [f3]. We shouldn't be too worried, as this is Black's good bishop after all.} 3. e4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] Taking the center.} Bxf3 $2 {Black's most popular move but an obvious positional error.} 4. Qxf3 {Black's idea makes little sense. Black has gone out of their way to trade their best minor piece and cede the bishop pair.} c5 5. Bb5+ {[%csl Rc6,Rd7] Black's light squares are feeling weak without their best protector the [c8]-bishop.} Nd7 6. O-O a6 {Should we trade the bishop?} 7. Bc4 {Of course not! White's bishop looks great on the [c4]-perch.} Ngf6 8. a4 {Securing the light squares. Any harassment of our bishop with ...[b7]-[b5] will no longer be possible. Also, our bishop can now retreat to [a2] if Black is ever able to accomplish ...[d6]-[d5].} e6 $6 {This setup is even worse for Black than the fianchetto.} 9. Nc3 Be7 10. d3 O-O 11. g4 $16 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gf4f5] White is already on the verge of winning. We will aim to boot the knight out of [f6] with [g4]-[g5] notice that, unlike positions with ...[g7]-[g6], Black does not have the ...[Nh5] retort, and break open the diagonal for the [c4]-bishop with [f4]-[f5]. White has great control and Black's position is unbelievably uncomfortable.} *

