1. f4 {In this chapter, we'll be looking at Black setups involving the kingside fianchetto.} d6 2. Nf3 Bg4 {Black immediately threatens an exchange on [f3]. We shouldn't be too worried, as this is Black's good bishop after all.} 3. e4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] Taking the center.} Bxf3 $2 {Black's most popular move but an obvious positional error.} 4. Qxf3 {Black's idea makes little sense. Black has gone out of their way to trade their best minor piece and cede the bishop pair.} c5 5. Bb5+ {[%csl Rc6,Rd7] Black's light squares are feeling weak without their best protector the [c8]-bishop.} Nd7 6. O-O a6 {Should we trade the bishop?} 7. Bc4 {Of course not! White's bishop looks great on the [c4]-perch.} Ngf6 8. a4 {Securing the light squares. Any harassment of our bishop with ...[b7]-[b5] will no longer be possible. Also, our bishop can now retreat to [a2] if Black is ever able to accomplish ...[d6]-[d5].} g6 9. d3 {[%csl Gc2,Gd3,Ge4][%cal Ge4d5,Gd3c4] Complementing the [c4]-bishop nicely.} Bg7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. g4 $16 {[%cal Gf4f5] White has the world's best Grand Prix Attack. We will play [f5], when the f-file might be opened at any moment. After [f4], we will consider several ideas such as [Bg5], [g4]-[g5], and other attacking motifs. Many of the computer lines here already consider the attack so serious that Black is recommended to sacrifice a pawn with ...[b7]-[b5] to divert some of White's pieces.} *

