1. f4 f5 {The famed copycat opening. Bird's opening is quite unique in that Black can respond in this way with minimal risk. Against 1.e4 , 1.d4 and 1.c4 playing the copycat risks a lot. Here however Black can continue mirroring our moves up until around move 10. For this opening, I went in a relatively different direction from the rest of the repertoire and opted for the fianchetto system with [g2]-[g3]. This is because with the bishops on the long diagonals, there is more dynamism to the position, making it harder for Black to copy us at little cost. This chapter will only deal with moves where Black copies us as long as it's viable. There is a chance they deviate sooner but the vast majority of players who go for 1...f5 just like to sit back, relax, and mimic us until it becomes unfeasible.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 {The one time in the course we go for a kingside fianchetto. The bishop will scope the board via [g2].} g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 {Introducing the potential of [e2]-[e4] in the future.} d6 {[%cal Ge2e4]} 6. Nc3 {Reinforcing [e2]-[e4] even more.} Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] With some interesting pressure in the center.} e6 9. a4 $5 {A strange waiting move to gain some space while the tension in the center continues to boil.} (9. e5 $2 {doesn't work because of the classic trick} dxe5 10. fxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Qd4+ {∓ and Black will soon be a healthy pawn up.}) 9... a6 10. a5 {[%csl Ga5] More space, please!} Rb8 11. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5] Creating some ideas of a revitalized [e4]-[e5].} e5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Bg5 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gd1d2,Yf3d2,Yd2c4,Yg2c6] White has some nice pressure on [e5]. We can consider [Qd2] or [Nf3]-[d2]-[c4] to unleash the dormant bishop on [g2].} *

