1. f4 f5 {The famed copycat opening. Bird's opening is quite unique in that Black can respond in this way with minimal risk. Against 1.e4 , 1.d4 and 1.c4 playing the copycat risks a lot. Here however Black can continue mirroring our moves up until around move 10. For this opening, I went in a relatively different direction from the rest of the repertoire and opted for the fianchetto system with [g2]-[g3]. This is because with the bishops on the long diagonals, there is more dynamism to the position, making it harder for Black to copy us at little cost. This chapter will only deal with moves where Black copies us as long as it's viable. There is a chance they deviate sooner but the vast majority of players who go for 1...f5 just like to sit back, relax, and mimic us until it becomes unfeasible.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 {The one time in the course we go for a kingside fianchetto. The bishop will scope the board via [g2].} g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 {Introducing the potential of [e2]-[e4] in the future.} d6 {[%cal Ge2e4]} 6. Nc3 {Reinforcing [e2]-[e4] even more.} Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] With some interesting pressure in the center.} e6 9. a4 $5 {A strange waiting move to gain some space while the tension in the center continues to boil.} (9. e5 $2 {doesn't work because of the classic trick} dxe5 10. fxe5 Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Qd4+ {∓ and Black will soon be a healthy pawn up.}) 9... a5 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Ga4a5] Stopping our ambiguous a-pawn pushes.} 10. Qe2 e5 11. fxe5 dxe5 12. Nb5 $1 {An interesting way to counter the opponent's ...[Nc6]-[d4] ideas.} Re8 13. Be3 Be6 $6 14. Rae1 $1 {A cool computer move with a clever point.} (14. Ng5 $5 {is interesting but not as strong as [Rae1].} Nd4 {(14...Bd7?? 15.d4! +- , the queen comes to [c4] with decisive effect! )} 15. Nxd4 exd4 16. Nxe6 Rxe6 17. Bg5 Qe7 18. Bh3 {and the computer insists this is close to equal, but it looks much more comfortable for White. Black can resolve some of the tension with} h6 19. Bxf6 Rxf6 {(19...Bxf6 20.Qg2! ± and White will succeed in weakening Black's kingside. )} 20. Bg2 b6 21. Rae1 {, the computer screams equal but this still looks more fun for White. Our bishop is already good while Black will have to do some work to fix the bishop, which is blocked by the pesky [d4]-pawn. Importantly, Black needs to watch out for the trick} fxe4 $4 22. Bxe4 {, when the twin threats to the rook and the discovered check on [d5] are looming.}) 14... fxe4 15. Ng5 $1 Bg4 (15... exd3 16. Qxd3 $1 {, when the queen's come off, the [c7]-pawn will drop like a ripe apple!}) 16. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2c3,Gc3c4] Our queen plans to come to [c3] and then [c4] with a dangerous check.} exd3 17. Qc3 {The threat of [Qc4]+ is almost impossible to meet.} Re7 18. cxd3 {We had to deal with this pawn sooner or later.} Kh8 19. Bc5 Rd7 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. Na7 {[%csl Rc6,Ge1,Re5,Gf1][%cal Ga7c6,Gf1f7,Ge1e7] White will soon recollect the pawn, when our incredible activity secures us an advantage. Notice that [d3] is not yet hanging, as the [Nf7] fork is still an option.} *

