1. f4 f5 {The famed copycat opening. Bird's opening is quite unique in that Black can respond in this way with minimal risk. Against 1.e4 , 1.d4 and 1.c4 playing the copycat risks a lot. Here however Black can continue mirroring our moves up until around move 10. For this opening, I went in a relatively different direction from the rest of the repertoire and opted for the fianchetto system with [g2]-[g3]. This is because with the bishops on the long diagonals, there is more dynamism to the position, making it harder for Black to copy us at little cost. This chapter will only deal with moves where Black copies us as long as it's viable. There is a chance they deviate sooner but the vast majority of players who go for 1...f5 just like to sit back, relax, and mimic us until it becomes unfeasible.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 {The one time in the course we go for a kingside fianchetto. The bishop will scope the board via [g2].} g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 {Introducing the potential of [e2]-[e4] in the future.} d6 {[%cal Ge2e4]} 6. Nc3 {Reinforcing [e2]-[e4] even more.} Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] With some interesting pressure in the center.} e5 9. exf5 {Finally, we reach a crossroads in which Black can only keep copying at the extreme detriment of their position.} exf4 {This variation reminds me of my primary school days. Everyone in my school would play this way, but it tended to never work out for the Black player.} 10. fxg6 fxg3 11. gxh7+ {Finally a check to end the copying!} Nxh7 {The symmetry ends due to the check! We have several paths to an advantage here, the simplest of which is taking the pawn. But there exists a much stronger active option.} 12. Qe1 $1 {[%cal Ge1g3] If we're able to take on [g3] with the queen, this will keep our pawn on [h2], making our king much safer than it would be if our pawn had taken on [g3]. From [h2] it will keep our king safe and snug when it slides over to [h1]. Therefore, Black really has to take on [h2] here...} gxh2+ (12... Nd4 13. Qxg3 Nf5 14. Qf2 {± and White's king is safe as described above, with a huge advantage.}) 13. Kh1 Ne5 14. Qg3 Nxf3 15. Bxf3 Kh8 16. Bf4 {White has far superior activity and will quickly mobilize the rooks. Ideas here include [Rf2xh2] and pressure on the h-file. An important nuance is that Black can only develop the [c8]-bishop by giving up the [b7]-pawn.} (16. Bf4 {An interesting variation is} Be6 17. Rae1 Qd7 18. Bxb7 Rab8 19. Be4 {and Black can't take the pawn because of} Rxb2 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. Bxd5 Rxc2 22. Bh6 $1 {A nice shot, taking advantage of the weak [g8]-square.} Rc5 (22... Bxh6 23. Rxf8+ Bxf8 24. Qg8#) 23. Rxf8+ Nxf8 24. Qg5 {and one way or another White is about to start cashing in.}) *

