1. f4 f5 {The famed copycat opening. Bird's opening is quite unique in that Black can respond in this way with minimal risk. Against 1.e4 , 1.d4 and 1.c4 playing the copycat risks a lot. Here however Black can continue mirroring our moves up until around move 10. For this opening, I went in a relatively different direction from the rest of the repertoire and opted for the fianchetto system with [g2]-[g3]. This is because with the bishops on the long diagonals, there is more dynamism to the position, making it harder for Black to copy us at little cost. This chapter will only deal with moves where Black copies us as long as it's viable. There is a chance they deviate sooner but the vast majority of players who go for 1...f5 just like to sit back, relax, and mimic us until it becomes unfeasible.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 {The one time in the course we go for a kingside fianchetto. The bishop will scope the board via [g2].} g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 {Introducing the potential of [e2]-[e4] in the future.} d6 {[%cal Ge2e4]} 6. Nc3 {Reinforcing [e2]-[e4] even more.} Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] With some interesting pressure in the center.} e5 9. exf5 {Finally, we reach a crossroads in which Black can only keep copying at the extreme detriment of their position.} Bxf5 10. h3 {The bishop on [f5] begins to feel the heat.} exf4 11. Bxf4 Nd7 {It makes logical sense to clear the way for the [g7]-bishop, but this fails.} 12. Qd2 {White has several ideas on the kingside involving [g3]-[g4] or [Bg5] or [Bh6] and Black's position is immediately uncomfortable.} Kh8 13. Bh6 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh6g7]} Nde5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. g4 Be6 16. Bxg7+ {Trading the bishops already signifies a big accomplishment in these structures since Black's king will be terminally weak without the [g7]-elephant watching the fort.} Kxg7 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7,Rh6]} 17. Rxf8 Qxf8 18. Rf1 Qe7 19. d4 Nf7 (19... Nc4 20. Qe2 {, now [d5] threatens to win both the bishop and the knight, so White is completely winning.}) 20. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e7,Gg2a8] Now [d5] is threatened.} Qf6 21. Nb5 $18 {Black will likely lose more than one pawn on the queenside.} *

