1. f4 f5 {The famed copycat opening. Bird's opening is quite unique in that Black can respond in this way with minimal risk. Against 1.e4 , 1.d4 and 1.c4 playing the copycat risks a lot. Here however Black can continue mirroring our moves up until around move 10. For this opening, I went in a relatively different direction from the rest of the repertoire and opted for the fianchetto system with [g2]-[g3]. This is because with the bishops on the long diagonals, there is more dynamism to the position, making it harder for Black to copy us at little cost. This chapter will only deal with moves where Black copies us as long as it's viable. There is a chance they deviate sooner but the vast majority of players who go for 1...f5 just like to sit back, relax, and mimic us until it becomes unfeasible.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 {The one time in the course we go for a kingside fianchetto. The bishop will scope the board via [g2].} g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 {Introducing the potential of [e2]-[e4] in the future.} d6 {[%cal Ge2e4]} 6. Nc3 {Reinforcing [e2]-[e4] even more.} Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] With some interesting pressure in the center.} e5 9. exf5 {Finally, we reach a crossroads in which Black can only keep copying at the extreme detriment of their position.} Bxf5 10. h3 {The bishop on [f5] begins to feel the heat.} exf4 11. Bxf4 Qd7 12. g4 $1 {Batting the badgering bishop back.} Be6 (12... Nxg4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 14. Qd2 {+- and a few accurate moves in the short term will ensure White a decisive advantage. Black won't have a shred of compensation once we mobilize our piece-up army effectively.}) 13. Ng5 Nd8 14. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Re6] The light-squared bishop has nowhere to run so there is no reason to trade and develop their ugly [d8] knight for them. If we're allowed to continue developing with [Rae1] while Black fails to include the [a8]-rook in the game, we may accumulate a dangerous lead in development.} (14. Nxe6 $6 {would walk right into Black's plans.} Nxe6 15. Bg3 d5 {and the threat of ...[d5]-[d4] followed by ...[Nd5] gives Black a fine game with level chances. This line highlights the weakness of the [e3]-square and how essential it is for us to avoid allowing them to drill a knight into that outpost.}) 14... c6 $2 15. Rae1 {[%cal Ge1e2,Gf1e1] White threatens to double rooks on the e-file with enormous pressure and so Black has to cash out in one of several disadvantageous ways.} Re8 {Strengthening the e-file, but that allows White to go for the now weakened f-file!} 16. Qf2 h6 {[%csl Gf1,Gf2][%cal Gf2f8]} 17. Nge4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 {[%csl Rd6,Rf6,Rh6] White has pressure on several important dark squares such as [d6], [f6], and [h6]. Already [Bxd6] and [Bxh6] are threatened.} d5 19. Nc5 Qe7 20. d4 $16 {[%csl Rd8,Re6][%cal Gd8e6] Black is still holding on, but it will be a real struggle playing precisely to save the draw. Notice that with the black knight misplaced on [d8], we are in no rush to play [Nxe6] and solve the disharmony in Black's position by allowing them to play ...[Nxe6] and connect the rooks.} *

