1. f4 f5 {The famed copycat opening. Bird's opening is quite unique in that Black can respond in this way with minimal risk. Against 1.e4 , 1.d4 and 1.c4 playing the copycat risks a lot. Here however Black can continue mirroring our moves up until around move 10. For this opening, I went in a relatively different direction from the rest of the repertoire and opted for the fianchetto system with [g2]-[g3]. This is because with the bishops on the long diagonals, there is more dynamism to the position, making it harder for Black to copy us at little cost. This chapter will only deal with moves where Black copies us as long as it's viable. There is a chance they deviate sooner but the vast majority of players who go for 1...f5 just like to sit back, relax, and mimic us until it becomes unfeasible.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 {The one time in the course we go for a kingside fianchetto. The bishop will scope the board via [g2].} g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 {Introducing the potential of [e2]-[e4] in the future.} d6 {[%cal Ge2e4]} 6. Nc3 {Reinforcing [e2]-[e4] even more.} Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] With some interesting pressure in the center.} e5 9. exf5 {Finally, we reach a crossroads in which Black can only keep copying at the extreme detriment of their position.} Bxf5 10. h3 {The bishop on [f5] begins to feel the heat.} exf4 11. Bxf4 Qd7 12. g4 $1 {Batting the badgering bishop back.} Be6 (12... Nxg4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 14. Qd2 {+- and a few accurate moves in the short term will ensure White a decisive advantage. Black won't have a shred of compensation once we mobilize our piece-up army effectively.}) 13. Ng5 Nd4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd4e6] Black aims to play ...[Nxe6] without getting in the way of the rooks. But while the knight on [d4] doesn't block the pieces, it is much more vulnerable than on [d8] and so...} 14. Be3 $1 {[%cal Ge3d4] Provoking Black to push the pawn to [c5].} c5 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gg2a8] The bishop on [g2] will be great since Black can never move the pawn back to [c6] to stunt it. Further, the pawn can never control [d5] so the [c3]-knight will now apply permanent pressure to that weakened square.} 15. Qd2 {As long as the bishop on [e6] can't run from the knight's attack, there is no reason to exchange and allow Black to reposition the knight to the healthy and safe [e6]-square.} Rae8 16. Rae1 Kh8 17. Nxe6 Nxe6 18. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Ge2f4,Gd3d4] With ideas of [Nf4] to exchange the great [e6]-knight, or [d4] to introduce annoying tension to Black's pawn chain.} ({After} 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. Bxd5 {, White has the easier game thanks to the great light-squared bishop, though it is quite close to equal objectively, as our far advanced kingside pawns have created some weaknesses.}) 18... d5 19. c4 $1 {[%csl Ge3,Gg2][%cal Gc4d5] Technically, this is still very close to equal, but who wouldn't choose the bishops here?} *

