1. f4 f5 {The famed copycat opening. Bird's opening is quite unique in that Black can respond in this way with minimal risk. Against 1.e4 , 1.d4 and 1.c4 playing the copycat risks a lot. Here however Black can continue mirroring our moves up until around move 10. For this opening, I went in a relatively different direction from the rest of the repertoire and opted for the fianchetto system with [g2]-[g3]. This is because with the bishops on the long diagonals, there is more dynamism to the position, making it harder for Black to copy us at little cost. This chapter will only deal with moves where Black copies us as long as it's viable. There is a chance they deviate sooner but the vast majority of players who go for 1...f5 just like to sit back, relax, and mimic us until it becomes unfeasible.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 {The one time in the course we go for a kingside fianchetto. The bishop will scope the board via [g2].} g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 {Introducing the potential of [e2]-[e4] in the future.} d6 {[%cal Ge2e4]} 6. Nc3 {Reinforcing [e2]-[e4] even more.} Nc6 7. O-O O-O 8. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] With some interesting pressure in the center.} e5 9. exf5 {Finally, we reach a crossroads in which Black can only keep copying at the extreme detriment of their position.} Bxf5 10. h3 {The bishop on [f5] begins to feel the heat.} exf4 11. Bxf4 Qd7 12. g4 $1 {Batting the badgering bishop back.} Be6 (12... Nxg4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 14. Qd2 {+- and a few accurate moves in the short term will ensure White a decisive advantage. Black won't have a shred of compensation once we mobilize our piece-up army effectively.}) 13. Ng5 Rae8 14. Nxe6 Rxe6 {Just as in other variations, these positions are very close to equal, but White always has the easier game due to the bishops. Because of them, Black needs to take particular care not to allow things to open further.} 15. Ne2 $5 {I like this move a lot, as it seems to contain several ideas. First, it stops Black's ...[Nd4]. It also prepares a potential [Bh2] and [Nf4], when the knight hits the weak square [e6] as well as [d5].} Ne5 16. Qd2 c6 17. Bh2 {[%csl Re6,Gg2,Gh2][%cal Ge2f4] Ne2-[f4] looms and we will bring the rook over to [e1] or double the rooks with [Rf1]-[f2] and [Ra1]-[f1]. A complex game ensues but a fun one at that! I'd always choose the bishop pair in such a situation.} *

