1. f4 Nc6 {This unusual move is essayed 6% of the time on move 1. We should be humble in how we judge it; after all, we did open the game by moving the f-pawn up two squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 (2... d5 {will transpose back to the several chapters covering 1...d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 . 2...e6 3.e3 will transpose to a terrible version of the French setup in which Black has preemptively removed any chance to achieve ...[c7]-[c5] by blocking the c-pawn with the knight.}) 3. e3 (3. e3 {Likely Black will play} d5 {, transposing back into the Two Knights system of 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 in the ...[d5] system. We will look at the only other viable options for Black here.}) 3... g6 4. d4 Bg7 (4... d5 5. Be2 Bg7 6. Ne5 {will likely transpose to the Stonewall analyzed after 4...Bg7 , while 4...d6 would transpose to 3...d6 4.d4 g6 .}) 5. Nc3 {Black really should stop [d4]-[d5] kicking the knight out now.} d5 6. Ne5 O-O 7. Be2 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Gd4,Ge3,Ge5,Gf4][%cal Rc7c5,Ge1g1] We have a fine Stonewall. Our knight is solid on [e5] and Black's knight on [c6] isn't correctly placed, blocking the natural ...[c7]-[c5] to initiate tension against our center. We will castle with a comfortable edge.} *

