1. f4 Nc6 {This unusual move is essayed 6% of the time on move 1. We should be humble in how we judge it; after all, we did open the game by moving the f-pawn up two squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 (2... d5 {will transpose back to the several chapters covering 1...d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 . 2...e6 3.e3 will transpose to a terrible version of the French setup in which Black has preemptively removed any chance to achieve ...[c7]-[c5] by blocking the c-pawn with the knight.}) 3. e3 (3. e3 {Likely Black will play} d5 {, transposing back into the Two Knights system of 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 in the ...[d5] system. We will look at the only other viable options for Black here.}) 3... d6 4. d4 {[%cal Gd4d5] We want to advance to [d5].} e5 {[%cal Ge5d4,Ge5f4] This is principled stuff. We could win a pawn on [e5], but then our pawns would be doubled and isolated on the e-file.} 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ {Going for the endgame is our most promising prospect.} Kxd8 (6... Nxd8 {, moving the knight away means we can collect on [e5] without doubling the pawns.} 7. Nxe5 {± and we are up a clean pawn.}) 7. Ng5 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gg5f7]} Ke8 8. Bc4 $36 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4f7,Gg5f7] Launching into [f7]. White has a nice initiative. We can develop effortlessly with [Nc3] and [O-O]. Our bishop will move to [d2], which might not seem great, but we are waiting out Black trading on [f4], when we can recapture with our e-pawn and bring our rook to [e1] with good vibes.} *

