1. f4 Nc6 {This unusual move is essayed 6% of the time on move 1. We should be humble in how we judge it; after all, we did open the game by moving the f-pawn up two squares.} 2. Nf3 Nf6 (2... d5 {will transpose back to the several chapters covering 1...d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 . 2...e6 3.e3 will transpose to a terrible version of the French setup in which Black has preemptively removed any chance to achieve ...[c7]-[c5] by blocking the c-pawn with the knight.}) 3. e3 (3. e3 {Likely Black will play} d5 {, transposing back into the Two Knights system of 2...Nf6 3.e3 Nc6 in the ...[d5] system. We will look at the only other viable options for Black here.}) 3... d6 4. d4 {[%cal Gd4d5] We want to advance to [d5].} g6 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gd4d5,Ge3e4] We want to either play [d4]-[d5] or [e3]-[e4].} ({The immediate} 5. d5 {would not pack too much punch.} Nb8 6. c4 Bg7 7. Nc3 e6 {and Black will trade away the [e6]-pawn, opening the e-file on our weak [e4]-square and [e3]-pawn. The position is balanced and a much better game for Black than we had to allow.}) 5... Bg7 6. e4 $14 {This leads to a very weird position that looks like a King's Indian until you notice that White's pawn is on f4, not c4! This is actually an Austrian Attack that is a variation in the Pirc Defense, except with 5...Nc6 played by Black and White having burned an extra move with [e2]-[e3]-[e4]. This waste of tempo won't really affect things though. We will bring our bishops to [e2] and [e3] and either play [Qd2] and castle queenside, or just castle kingside. Obviously, a lot more could be analyzed here, but this is a Bird course not a Pirc course.} *

