1. f4 Nc6 {This unusual move is essayed 6% of the time on move 1. We should be humble in how we judge it; after all, we did open the game by moving the f-pawn up two squares.} 2. Nf3 d6 {Here we could play [e4] to transpose into a King's Gambit. If that's how you'd like to direct the game, go for it. We will aim for a more unorthodox option, which is equally good.} (2... d5 {will transpose back to the several chapters covering 1...d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 .}) (2... e6 3. e3 {will transpose to a terrible version of the French setup in which Black has preemptively removed any chance to achieve ...[c7]-[c5] by blocking the c-pawn with the knight.}) 3. d4 $1 {Immediately threatening [d4]-[d5] to boot the knight from [c6]. Black's best move is ...[e5], which is only played 8% of the time. This is great news for us − the other moves all grant a healthy advantage to White.} e5 $1 4. d5 {Pushing the knight back to [e7].} Nd4 {This just drops a pawn, but that hasn't stopped people from trying it 19% of the time.} (4... e4 {looks similar to many principled lines but also just drops a pawn:} 5. Ng5 {± .}) 5. Nxd4 exd4 6. Qxd4 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gb1c3] White's position plays itself.} *

