1. f4 Nc6 {This unusual move is essayed 6% of the time on move 1. We should be humble in how we judge it; after all, we did open the game by moving the f-pawn up two squares.} 2. Nf3 d6 {Here we could play [e4] to transpose into a King's Gambit. If that's how you'd like to direct the game, go for it. We will aim for a more unorthodox option, which is equally good.} (2... d5 {will transpose back to the several chapters covering 1...d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 .}) (2... e6 3. e3 {will transpose to a terrible version of the French setup in which Black has preemptively removed any chance to achieve ...[c7]-[c5] by blocking the c-pawn with the knight.}) 3. d4 $1 {Immediately threatening [d4]-[d5] to boot the knight from [c6]. Black's best move is ...[e5], which is only played 8% of the time. This is great news for us − the other moves all grant a healthy advantage to White.} e5 $1 4. d5 {Pushing the knight back to [e7].} Nce7 {Here we have two promising options: to take on [e5] and reinforce the strong [d5]-pawn with [e2]-[e4], or to play [e2]-[e4] when our [d5]-pawn looks less menacing, but Black's position is more cramped. I am recommending the one more in tune with my style, the second, though those who want to play a freer game are welcome to try out the first.} (4... e4 {looks similar to many principled lines but also just drops a pawn:} 5. Ng5 {± .}) 5. e4 {Part of the reason I like this move is that after 2 of the 3 most popular moves, we get a close to decisive space advantage.} Ng6 (5... Bg4 {is played 30% of the time.} 6. f5 $1 {± , seizing more space. We will play [h3] and retake on [f3] with the queen. Our pawns on the fifth rank completely cramp Black's camp, making it unbelievably difficult for their pieces to move around.}) 6. f5 $1 Nf4 (6... Nh4 $2 {Now we should test the queen's allegiance to the knight.} 7. Bb5+ $1 Bd7 8. Bxd7+ {+- and now taking with the king is obviously bad, but so is taking with the queen!}) 7. g3 {[%csl Rf4] Ensnares the intruding knight.} Nh5 8. Nxe5 $18 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gd1h5] And we scoop up a free pawn with the discovered attack on the [h5]-knight.} *

