ey should. We can't back it up so easily with [g2]-[g4], as that would run into ...[h7]-[h5], muddying the waters. Luckily, we can cash out to a nice thematic position.} 8. fxg6 hxg6 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Ng5 $16 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Ge1g1,Yf7f6,Yg5e6] We will castle with good pressure on the f-file. The position resembles a King's Indian in which Black has lost the h-pawn for our f-pawn. This is great for us since our knight can never be pushed from [g5] − if Black pushes the f-pawn at all, we will swing into [e6].} Bxb5 11. Qf3 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gf3f7] Qxf7 is a big threat. We can let the bishop on [b5] hang for the moment.} f6 ({After} 11... Nh6 12. Nxb5 {± , we will castle with easy play and a big advantage. The knight on [h6] will likely never get fixed.}) 12. Ne6 Qd7 13. Nxb5 $18 {The [b5]-knight is untouchable on pain of [Ne6xc7]+. With the [e6]-knight drilling down on [f8] and [d8], Black's king will be stuck on [e8] forever. White has a winning strategic advantage.} *

