1. f4 Nc6 {This unusual move is essayed 6% of the time on move 1. We should be humble in how we judge it; after all, we did open the game by moving the f-pawn up two squares.} 2. Nf3 d6 {Here we could play [e4] to transpose into a King's Gambit. If that's how you'd like to direct the game, go for it. We will aim for a more unorthodox option, which is equally good.} (2... d5 {will transpose back to the several chapters covering 1...d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 .}) (2... e6 3. e3 {will transpose to a terrible version of the French setup in which Black has preemptively removed any chance to achieve ...[c7]-[c5] by blocking the c-pawn with the knight.}) 3. d4 $1 {Immediately threatening [d4]-[d5] to boot the knight from [c6]. Black's best move is ...[e5], which is only played 8% of the time. This is great news for us − the other moves all grant a healthy advantage to White.} Nf6 4. d5 {Making good on our promise to evict the [c6]-knight from its home.} Nb4 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb4d5,Gf6d5] The knight attacks [d5]. We have a nice trick to reinforce our advanced pawn.} (4... Na5 5. e4 $1 {We will play [b2]-[b4] next, with our bishop covering the knight's escape to [c4]. Black is lost.}) (4... Nb8 {, this humble retreat is Black's best chance to survive.} 5. c4 {⩲ , turning the [d5]-pawn into concrete. We have a nice space advantage and will continue with [Nc3] and [e2]-[e4].}) 5. e4 $1 {[%cal Ga2a3,Gb1c3] We will kick the knight to [a6] with [a2]-[a3] and then play [Nc3].} Nxe4 6. c3 $1 {[%cal Gd1a4] Opening the lane for our queen to [a4].} Na6 7. Qa4+ $18 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ga4e4,Ga4e8] And Black's knight drops on [e4].} *

