1. f4 Nc6 {This unusual move is essayed 6% of the time on move 1. We should be humble in how we judge it; after all, we did open the game by moving the f-pawn up two squares.} 2. Nf3 d6 {Here we could play [e4] to transpose into a King's Gambit. If that's how you'd like to direct the game, go for it. We will aim for a more unorthodox option, which is equally good.} (2... d5 {will transpose back to the several chapters covering 1...d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 .}) (2... e6 3. e3 {will transpose to a terrible version of the French setup in which Black has preemptively removed any chance to achieve ...[c7]-[c5] by blocking the c-pawn with the knight.}) 3. d4 $1 {Immediately threatening [d4]-[d5] to boot the knight from [c6]. Black's best move is ...[e5], which is only played 8% of the time. This is great news for us − the other moves all grant a healthy advantage to White.} f6 {This is Black's 4th most popular option. Of course, it looks ridiculous, but we shouldn't waste our time laughing at it. Instead, we should look to play precisely since if we play our cards right, Black won't last another ten moves.} 4. d5 Nb8 (4... Nb4 5. a3 Na6 6. e4 {+- and the space advantage is overwhelming. If Black's knight comes to [c5], we will secure [e4] and then knock it away with [b2]-[b4].}) 5. e4 e5 {200 games have reached this position. Those of you who did my other course will already know my suggestion...} (5... e6 6. Nd4 $1 {, laying siege to the weak light squares. We should move our king's bishop out to [b5] or [d3], castle, and then attempt to break through on the e-file.}) 6. f5 $18 {[%csl Rb8,Rc8,Gf5,Rf8,Rg8][%cal Rf8d6,Rc8f5,Rg8f6,Rb8c6] Pawns on the fifth rank! We have a winning space advantage. Neither of the black knights can access their natural homes on [c6] and [f6]. Meanwhile, both bishops are also stifled, the [f8]-bishop blocked by its own pawns, and the [c8]-bishop is blocked by our phalanx on [e4]-[f5].} *

