1. f4 Nc6 {This unusual move is essayed 6% of the time on move 1. We should be humble in how we judge it; after all, we did open the game by moving the f-pawn up two squares.} 2. Nf3 d6 {Here we could play [e4] to transpose into a King's Gambit. If that's how you'd like to direct the game, go for it. We will aim for a more unorthodox option, which is equally good.} (2... d5 {will transpose back to the several chapters covering 1...d5 2.Nf3 Nc6 .}) (2... e6 3. e3 {will transpose to a terrible version of the French setup in which Black has preemptively removed any chance to achieve ...[c7]-[c5] by blocking the c-pawn with the knight.}) 3. d4 $1 {Immediately threatening [d4]-[d5] to boot the knight from [c6]. Black's best move is ...[e5], which is only played 8% of the time. This is great news for us − the other moves all grant a healthy advantage to White.} Bg4 {The most popular response, being tried by 35% of Black players.} 4. d5 Bxf3 (4... Nb8 5. e4 {± and we have a great center. We will continue with [Nc3] and [h2]-[h3]. Unless Black wants to waste more time, they will have to cede the bishop pair with ...[Bxf3]. Black has almost no central presence and is already close to lost.}) 5. exf3 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gf1b5] Happily opening our bishop. The [d5]-pawn combined with the two bishops will be a force to be reckoned with.} Nb8 {Here any normal scheme of development makes sense and will bring a good advantage, but I like the super aggressive path recommended by the computer.} 6. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5,Rg7g6] Preparing to meet ...[g6] with [h5].} g6 (6... e6 7. Bc4 $1 {, awaiting a trade on [d5].} exd5 $2 {walks into the trap.} 8. Qxd5 {with winning dual threats against [b7] and [f7].}) 7. h5 Bg7 8. g4 $16 {[%cal Gf4e5,Gg4f5,Gf4g5,Gb1c3,Gc1e3,Gd1d2,Yh5h6,Yg8f6] We break all development rules to control an enormous swath of the kingside. We will play [Nc3], [Be3], [Qd2], and eventually castle queenside. We'd be happy to see ...[Ng8]-[f6], when we can bury the bishop on [f8] with [h5]-[h6].} *

