1. f4 g5 {Someone asked for this to be in the course, so it is now in the course. The famous Hobbs Gambit. Black gives up a pawn on the first move for apparently no reason. I lost to Magnus from here though, so that's something.} 2. fxg5 e5 3. d4 $1 {Defending the [g5]-pawn and opening up the board. We will bring our knights out and develop calmly. Our [g5]-pawn is a thorn that sticks into Black's kingside and complicates the [g8]-knight's basic development.} (3. e4 {was what I chose in the game. It's slightly less accurate than 3.d3 but still gives White a huge advantage. Spoiler alert: I botched my rook and lost to Magnus.}) 3... e4 {The only challenging move for Black.} 4. d5 $18 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gg5f6,Gd5c6,Gd5e6,Gg5h6,Gc1e3,Gb1c3,Ge3d4] The pawn on [e4] is stranded from the d-pawn − Black can never play ...[d7]-[d5] now. We will play [Nc3], [Be3], and [Bd4] or [Qd4] if our opponent allows it. Our 2 pawns on the fifth rank dig into the opponent's knights natural development squares. White is winning.} *

