{Welcome to the Model Games. Since finishing the course (6 months ago) , I had the honor and privilege of using this repertoire to wreck the competition in several Titled Tuesdays. Ahead you will see a set of 11 games: 9 wins, 1 draw, and 1 loss to someone relatively well known! What ensues is some wacky and perplexing chess. I'd like to draw your attention to how even elite players quickly lose their way when confronted with such unorthodox aviation. Someone asked in the beta test why I don't include classical games. Well, simply put, there are almost none! This repertoire is meant to surprise opponents based on an online database that carries 1000x more games than the database of games played in physical tournaments between grandmasters. I would venture most of the positions in the chapters after move 4 or 5 have never been reached over the board. While the games in this chapter were played under quick time controls, I want to emphasize that they are still playing at a really high level. Anyone who has seen Hikaru's stream knows just how good top players can play even in Blitz and Bullet. The reason my opponents are quickly arriving at positions where they lose their way is that they haven't studied them! No one studies the Bird. My opponents lost because we got structures that they had not studied and so ideas that will be obvious to you after studying this course, weren't so obvious to them as 2500+ grandmasters.} 1. Z0 *

