{Here I'm paired against one of Slovenia's rising stars. I had played Jan a few years ago in Serbia when we were both IMs playing for our GM norms. That encounter had been a draw, but this one unfortunately would not be so peaceful. Now we're both GMs playing in Titled Tuesdays − time really flies!} 1. f4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 g6 4. Bb5 Qb6 5. Nc3 a6 {I would love to chop here, but that would be foolish with the queen ready to recapture on [c6], avoiding a fundamental weakening of the structure.} 6. Nd5 {[%cal Gb6b5,Gd5c7] A nifty trick! The bishop is immune from capture due to the [Nc7]+ rejoinder.} Qd8 7. Bxc6 {I achieve the ideal chop! Black will have to compromise the structure in some way.} bxc6 8. Nc3 {We've both wasted two extra moves − myself on [Nc3]-[d5]-[c3] and Black on ...[Qd8]-[b6]-[d8]. Unfortunately, the [c6]-pawn cannot be moved back to [b7], and now Black will duly suffer due to this vulnerability.} Bg7 9. d3 {[%cal Ge3e4] Building [e3]-[e4]. Thematics, thematics!} Nf6 10. e4 O-O 11. O-O {[%cal Ge4e5] White has an incredible version of a Rossolimo Sicilian. The pawn on [f4] strengthens the [e4]-[e5] idea and would guarantee the blocking in of the [g7]-bishop.} d5 $2 {This allows us a big phalanx on [e5] free of charge.} 12. h3 $6 {Taking away key squares, but it would have been better to just clog the board with [e4]-[e5] immediately.} ({After} 12. e5 $1 Nd7 13. Na4 {± , we will play [b2]-[b3] and [c2]-[c4], clogging the board and keeping the black bishop pair stifled for good. The advantage borders on winning.}) 12... c4 (12... dxe4 $1 {would have been better. Following} 13. dxe4 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Be6 {± , Black's pieces are a bit cramped with truly ugly pawns on [c5] and [c6]. But at the same time, Black's bishops are a lot more free than they'd be without the exchange and this gives my opponent some chances of a draw.}) 13. e5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4] You can call me Bob the Builder, cause I'm pouring cement!} Nd7 14. dxc4 dxc4 {[%csl Rc8,Rd7] Unlike the note to 12...dxe4 , here the [c8]-bishop has not arrived at [e6], which has created a huge headache for Black in coordination. The knight on [d7] is not that bad in terms of covering the weak squares on [b6] and [c5]; but by the same token, it will have to move from [d7] to clear the bishop's path and then return to [d7] to fight for said weaknesses.} 15. Be3 Qc7 16. Qd4 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd4c4] Scooping up the apple on [c4]. Note that without a knight on [c6], the queen is free to place itself on [d4].} Rb8 17. Qxc4 Rxb2 18. Nd5 $2 {Hopping into the enflamed center, but it was too soon!} (18. Rab1 $1 {was even stronger, striving for maximum activity.} Rxc2 {(18...Rxb1 19.Rxb1 , Black cannot move a muscle in the face of the [Nd5] threat. Black could try to stop it with the e-pawn. 19...e6 20.Ne4 +- , but the knight swarms the new weakness on [d6]. Black's position is so bad. So bad I looked up a synonym to describe the situation accurately on Google and that synonym is vexatious. )} 19. Qd3 {and the rook is trapped behind the enemy lines. A wayward mango dropped far from the tree!}) 18... Qd8 19. Qxc6 Bb7 $2 {[%cal Gb2b7] Now his rook has no way out.} 20. Qc3 Rb5 21. Nc7 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gc7b5] And the rook is trapped!} Bxf3 22. Nxb5 Be2 {Black manages to get the exchange back but not without serious repercussions.} 23. Nd4 (23. Rf2 Bxb5 24. a4 {+- would have collected the bishop who has run out of squares.}) 23... Bxf1 24. Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gc6d8] The queen has to bury itself on [e8] to avoid dropping another pawn to [Nxe7]+.} Qe8 25. Rxf1 Nb8 26. Nd4 (26. Na7 {+- digs into the [c8]-square and prevents Black from ever challenging White on the c-file. White will pile up on the stranded [b8]-knight, similarly to how it occurs in the game.}) 26... Qa4 27. Rb1 {[%csl Rb8] The knight has issues.} Qxa2 28. Rb7 {[%cal Rb8d7,Rb8c6] The knight is completely frozen. My plan is simple: attack it with the queen and collect the bounty.} Qd5 29. Qc7 Qe4 {[%cal Ge4e3] Attacking my bishop as a means to protect the [b8]-knight.} 30. Kf2 {[%csl Rb8] Time is running out. Black can attempt some saboteur attacks with his pawns, but objectively White's position is just too stable for Black to cause much trouble. It's nice to see that after all this, the [g7]-bishop is still entombed in its fianchetto as always.} g5 31. g3 {Calm reinforcements.} gxf4 32. gxf4 Qh1 33. Nf3 {I could collect the knight already, but why not stop the check on [h2]?} f6 34. Rxb8 fxe5 35. Qc4+ Kh8 36. Rxf8+ Bxf8 37. Qf7 {[%csl Gf7,Rh1] Black's queen is disconnected from the kingside and there is no defense. Stockfish already declares mate in 8. As it happens, Black collapses a bit quicker.} Bg7 38. Qe8+ {Black resigned.} 1-0

