{My opponent here is one of the strongest women in the world. She is one of Russia's top females and is, from what I can estimate, extremely close to achieving the GM title. She plays a solid setup against the Bird but unfortunately, it's one that I'm well prepared for and the game quickly descends into the complex jungle in which only I know what's going on.} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. c4 $1 {A bolt from the blue! I love this move. It never fails to throw my GM opponents off balance.} Nf6 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. d4 {[%cal Ge3e4] Seizing the center; next up is [e3]-[e4]. Thus far we are following the variations in the Unusual Birds chapter perfectly.} O-O 7. e4 Nb6 8. Nc3 $6 {Deviating slightly from the course, which recommends [Be2], but the general idea is the same. If I can finish development, my center will become enormous and I can count on a huge advantage.} Bg4 {Pressuring the knight to chip through. Polina understands that if she does not break through my center soon, her pieces will be left suffocated for lack of space.} 9. Be3 {Reinforcing [d4].} N8d7 $2 (9... Nc6 $1 {had to be played, as this applies just enough pressure against White's center to keep the balance.} 10. d5 Na5 11. Bd4 Bxf3 12. gxf3 {leads to a position I had against Eric Rosen in another Titled Tuesday. Here he blundered with} Nac4 {and I quickly mopped up with} 13. Bxc4 Nxc4 14. Bxg7 {. Next, [Qd4]+ will net the loose knight on [c4].}) 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4,Gf4] So much SPACE!} Rc8 12. O-O-O c5 {Trying to puncture the balloon.} 13. d5 $2 {This is a big error.} (13. e5 $1 {would have been correct, shutting the [d7]-knight and [g7]-bishop in for the long haul.}) 13... c4 $2 {Missing her chance.} (13... Bxc3 $1 {(was counterintuitive and correct! It is hard to part with the dragon bishop giving White 2 bishops vs. 2 knights, but this would allow Black to mobilize quickly against my exposed king. After)} 14. bxc3 Na4 {∓ , ...[Qb6] and ...[Qa5] would put White in the danger zone!}) 14. e5 {[%csl Rd7,Rg7] Shutting Black's pieces in.} Nc5 $2 15. h4 $2 {The right idea but the wrong execution! It is the perfect time with the center closed to launch an offensive operation on the h-file; but it must be handled with an eye to keeping the opponent's counterplay at bay.} (15. Bxc5 Rxc5 16. h4 $1 {Now [h5] and play on the h-file with ideas like [Qh3] should decide.}) 15... Nca4 $2 {Right square, wrong knight. The [b6]-knight should have been moved to free the queen's route to [a5] or [b6].} 16. Bd4 Nxc3 17. Bxc3 Na4 18. h5 {[%cal Gh5g6,Gh5h6] Continuing on! I have threats to play dynamically with [hxg6] and strategically with [h6], when the bishop would be buried on [h8].} Nxc3 19. Qxc3 Qd7 20. h6 $1 {Imprisoning the bishop in the corner. SPOILER ALERT: from [h8] it won't affect anything for the rest of the game!} Bh8 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Gh6g7] Not only is the bishop useless, but the pawn on [h6] also guarantees that some back-rank mating threats will prevail against the black king deep into the endgame.} 21. g3 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Gf1h3] A new challenger enters the arena.} b5 22. Bh3 {Now ...[e6] would be met with a painful [dxe6] chop, so Black just cedes the exchange.} Qb7 23. Bxc8 Rxc8 {I'm up an exchange, and my bishop is out of the game, so consequently, I'm playing up a rook. Natural moves should suffice to bring home a victory.} 24. Qb4 a5 25. Qxa5 b4 26. Rh2 Ra8 27. d6 $1 {A cool trick, but [Qc5] would have also done the job.} exd6 (27... Rxa5 28. d7 {+- and not only am I promoting a queen on [d8], but it will likely be checkmate.}) 28. Rxd6 {[%cal Gd6d8] The [a8]-rook still cannot take on pain of [Rd8] mate.} Rf8 29. Rd8 {Threatening [Rxf8]+ and [Qd8] mate; the checkmate threats never end!} Qe7 {Fortifying the 8th rank momentarily.} 30. Rhd2 {[%cal Gd8f8,Gd2d8] Here [Rxf8]+ and [Rd8] will decide. My opponent chops on [e5] before throwing in the towel.} Bxe5 31. fxe5 {Black resigned.} 1-0

