{Here I'm paired against one of Iran's strongest grandmasters with a Fide of 2597.} 1. f4 g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 {The fianchetto setup. Black hasn't advanced any pawns in the center so it's there for the taking.} 3. e4 c5 {Transposing into our Sicilian Fianchetto chapter.} 4. c3 d5 5. e5 $6 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4][%cal Gd2d4] Parts of the soon-to-be impressive phalanx can already be seen. But if we reference the Sicilian Fianchetto chapter, this is not what I recommended.} (5. d3 $1 {would lead to very interesting play in which White has good chances if Black goes for the endgame.}) 5... Nc6 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 Bg4 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4d1] Pressuring f3 and threatening 8...Bxf3 9.Qxf3 Nxd4 .} 8. Be3 Nh6 {[%cal Gh6f5] The knight heads to [f5].} 9. Bf2 Nf5 10. Be2 {Breaking the pin of the [g4]-bishop.} Qb6 {Attacking [d4] but forgetting [d5].} (10... e6 $1 {would give Black slightly better chances, which is quite surprising. The bishop on [g7] is pointed into concrete, but the rest of Black's pieces are good. Black would particularly like to secure the [f5]-square for the knight by digging into [g4] with ...[h7]-[h5]. After} 11. Nc3 h5 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Bf8 {∞ , the bishop will come to [e7] and Black's setup is healthy. The lack of space is compensated for by the well-placed minor pieces.}) 11. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5]} e6 12. O-O Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nfxd4 $2 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gd4f3,Gf2b6] Winning a pawn momentarily but at the cost of placing himself in a fatal pin. Black threatens to get the knight out of danger with ...[Nxf3]+.} 14. Kh1 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gd4f3] Getting out of the way.} Qb4 15. a3 {Pushing Black's queen around; it is tied to the knight and I can keep pushing it around until the horse falls.} Qc4 16. Nxd5 {[%cal Ga1c1] My rook needs to come to [c1] immediately if I want to push the queen away and net the knight. This wrecks Black's structure and threatens [Nc7]+.} exd5 17. Rc1 Qb5 18. Bxd4 {[%csl Gc1,Gd4,Ge5,Gf3,Gf4,Rg7] I finally regained the knight. White has a winning strategic advantage due to the bishop pair, better pawn structure, and a more developed position. It also doesn't hurt that the [g7]-bishop is shuttered in by the [f4]/[e5] concrete.} O-O 19. Bc5 Rfd8 20. b4 {[%csl Gb4,Rb5,Gc5][%cal Gf3e2] The queen begins to feel a bit claustrophobic with the threat of [Bf3]-[e2] in the air.} Qa6 21. a4 {[%cal Gb4b5,Gf3e2] With huge threats of [Be2] or [b4]-[b5].} b5 22. Qd3 Qxa4 23. Ra1 {The queen is nearly trapped.} Nxb4 {[%cal Gb4d3]} 24. Qd2 Qc2 {The queen makes it out but the second knight won't.} 25. Qxb4 {White is easily winning. With the extra piece by my side, I can easily focus on any weak pawns in my opponent's position to outnumber his army and win it.} a5 26. Qxb5 Rdb8 27. Bb6 a4 28. Bxd5 Ra7 29. Rac1 Qd2 30. e6 {Trading off the f-pawn to gain access to Black's weak king. The [g7]-bishop can finally peer out over the board, but it's too late.} fxe6 31. Bxe6+ Kh8 32. Rfd1 (32. Bd4 $3 {was a beautiful solution with the clever point of} Rxb5 33. Rc8# $1) 32... Qxf4 33. Bxa7 {Giving away the queen might be serious, but it's the mate that matters more.} Rxb5 34. Rd8+ Bf8 35. Rxf8+ Qxf8 36. Bd4+ {[%cal Gf8g7,Gc1c8] Black resigned. When the queen blocks on [g7], [Rc8]# ends things for good.} 1-0

