{Here I am paired against World #8 at the time of playing, Leinier Dominguez.} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. b3 Be7 5. Bb2 c5 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 $6 {He captures incorrectly! As mentioned in the French Setup chapters, the knight will just be misplaced here. It needs to be able to go to [c6] quickly so Black should have taken with the queen. I've said it once and I'll say it again. No one studies the Bird. Not the beginners, not the intermediate players, not the advanced players, not the grandmasters, not the #8 in the world.} 8. O-O O-O 9. d3 {I made the course, but even I haven't studied it enough! Here I also slightly misstep.} (9. c4 $1 {is what I recommend in the course.}) 9... Qc7 10. Nbd2 $6 ({Slightly inaccurate. It was better to play} 10. c4 {to fix the black [c5]-pawn in stone.}) 10... Bd6 11. Qe2 e5 12. e4 {Things are coming to a head in the center.} d4 $2 {This relinquishes all the pressure Black had on [c4] and [e4] − all systems ready for kingside expansion.} (12... Rfe8 $1 {was best, with the idea that if I close things with} 13. f5 {, Black can open the gates on the queenside with} c4 {⩱ and Black is slightly better; ...[c4]-[c3] and ...[cxd3] followed by ...[Qc2] or ...[Rc8] are both annoying threats. Instead, White should play 13.fxe5 Nxe5 14.Rae1! , keeping Black's edge to a minimum. Since I've achieved [e4], I no longer have a weak [e3]-pawn and so I have no structural long-term issues that normally exist when Black has achieved ...[e6]-[e5].}) 13. f5 $14 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gg2g4] Planning to expand with [h3] and [g4].} Ng4 $2 {[%cal Gg4e3] Threatening to invade on [e3], but this can be easily parried.} ({It was better to begin queenside expansion immediately with} 13... b5 $1 {, when Black will push to achieve ...[a5]-[a4] or ...[c5]-[c4].}) 14. Nc4 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gc4e3,Gg4e3]} b5 15. h3 $2 ({I had a very counterintuitive solution in mind in regards to allowing the knight into e3.} 15. Nxd6 $1 Qxd6 16. h3 Ne3 17. Rfe1 {and it turns out the knight is trapped. I will collect a pawn with [Bc1] and [Bxe3].}) 15... bxc4 16. hxg4 {The big problem for Black is what remains on the board. He is stuck with a toothless pawn mass on the queenside. Normally, if his b-pawn was still on [b5], he could play to open the c-file with ...[c5]-[c4]. Here, however, either pawn trade on [b3] or [d3] will simply give me great access to the [c4]-square with my [f3]-knight via [d2]. Meanwhile, my doubled g-pawns might in fact be an asset as they give me more room to build a battery on the h-file.} c3 $2 {This closes the center too much.} (16... cxd3 $1 17. cxd3 {⩲ was correct, when I am just slightly better. White will reroute the knight to [c4].}) 17. Bc1 a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Attempting to break the queenside open with ...[a5]-[a4] and ...[a4xb3]. The game resembles that of two bubbles. There is the kingside bubble which I control and where Black's pieces have no access or control. And there is the queenside bubble in which Black has all the access and play. This double bubble situation is from the closed nature of the center that forms an enormous mountain range insulating one bubble from the other. The game's objectives are defined. I will play for mate on the kingside, while Black will try to break through the queenside and use the first and second ranks to eventually get into my kingside to disturb my attack.} 18. a4 $1 {Batting Black's break back.} Rab8 19. g5 {My play is simple and easy. Push pawns and bring the heavy artillery to the h-file.} Qc6 20. g4 $18 {[%cal Ge2h2] Clearing the path to [h2]. White has a winning attack here.} c4 $1 {A very strong attempt to complicate matters. I will have to weaken either [e4] by taking with [d3] or [a4] by taking with [b3]. Black's minor pieces finally have access to [c5], which is a major improvement.} 21. bxc4 $1 {[%cal Gc2f5,Gf5f6,Gf6h6,Gh6h1,Gh1c1] Keeping things on the kingside as insulated as possible. Black's pieces can try as much as they want, I am not letting them in the green zone. Black can win [a4] and hope to push the a-pawn to stardom on [a1], but this plan will simply take too long.} (21. dxc4 $4 {would be a terrible error.} Nc5 {and all of a sudden Black has punctured White's bubble and begins to flood in the weaknesses.} 22. Re1 Rfd8 {-+ , White has no way to deal with the eventual ...[d4]-[d3], which will guarantee Black more access into White's camp. We would love to play [Ne1]-[d3] to seal this up, but unfortunately, our rook is tied to [e1] to defend the [e4]-pawn.}) 21... Rb4 22. Qh2 {Beginning the termination of the [g8]-majesty.} Rxa4 23. Rb1 Ra2 24. Rf2 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gf2c2] Defending [c2] so there is no way for Black to play ...[Rxc2] and disturb White's artillery.} a4 25. Qh4 {[%cal Gf2h2] Slow and steady. Now [Rh2] is a monstrous threat.} Re8 {[%cal Gd7f8] Clearing the [f8]-square to meet [Rh2] with ...[Nf8].} 26. g6 {[%cal Gf3g5] Clearing [g5] for my knight!} fxg6 27. fxg6 {There is no saving Black here. The computer already asserts this to be +5 even with best play on his part.} Nf8 (27... h6 28. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 29. Qxh6 Nf8 30. Rh2 {and [Qh8] will finish things off quickly.}) (27... hxg6 28. Ng5 Nf8 29. Rh2 {+- and [Qh8] forces Black to immediately throw the knight into the furnace with ...[Nh7].}) 28. gxh7+ Kh8 (28... Nxh7 29. Rh2 Nf6 30. Ng5 {and [Qh8] again seals the deal.}) 29. Ng5 {[%cal Gg5f7] Now [Nf7]# is threatened and the only way to avoid mate is to play ...[Qd7] and give the queen away for the knight when it arrives on [f7]. Black resigned − by far the strongest person I've ever beaten in any time control ever. It's no coincidence it was in the Bird!} 1-0

