{My opponent is an Iranian IM with a peak rating of 2410. This game is relatively quick as he tries the ...[Nh6] Horsefly Defense, but it quickly backfires.} 1. f4 Nh6 2. Nf3 g6 3. d3 d5 4. Qd2 $1 {I will always give this move an exclamation mark. For more coverage on it, check out the Unusual Birds chapter.} Bg7 5. e4 dxe4 6. dxe4 O-O 7. h3 $1 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gh3g4,Ge4f5,Rh6f5,Rh6g4] Hemming the horsefly in. The knight on [h6] will seriously struggle to find relevance from here onwards; it is completely dominated by White's pawns on [e4] and [h3].} Nd7 8. Nc3 b6 9. Qe3 {[%csl Ge4,Gf4] Preparing [Bd2] and queenside castling. My [e4] and [f4]-pawns perfectly restrain the enemy pieces while staying out of the way of my knights.} Bb7 10. Bd2 Qe8 {Black wants to play ...[e7]-[e5] and we must bolster the defense of [f5] so that we can advance [f4]-[f5] in response to any ...[e5] break.} (10... e5 $1 {would have been better, but Black is still struggling after} 11. fxe5 {, when the knight on [h6] faces uncomfortable pressure. For the moment, Black cannot recapture on [e5], as the [g7]-bishop would have to lose track of the [h6]-knight's defense.}) 11. g4 $1 Kh8 {Since [g4]-[g5] threatened to win the knight, Black clears the [g8]-square.} (11... e5 12. f5 {+- and Black remains stuck.}) 12. O-O-O {[%cal Gg4g5,Gh3h4,Gh4h5] My development continues effortlessly, while Black struggles to come up with a single active idea. I will advance on the kingside with [g5] and [h3]-[h4]-[h5] shortly.} Nc5 13. g5 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gg5h6] Pushing the knight back to its original square.} Ng8 14. h4 Na4 {[%cal Gd2c3] Trying to get some play on [c3], but my bishop and queen defend it sufficiently. We can continue on with the kingside pawns.} 15. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6,Gh5g6,Gf1b5] Here, [h5]-[h6], [hxg6], and [Bb5] are all enormous threats. Black quickly collapsed.} Qc6 16. Bb5 Qe6 17. Bxa4 {White nets a knight while the kingside offensive continues as well. Black resigned here.} 1-0

