{Here I am paired against David Navara, someone whose articles in New In Chess I used to read growing up! David's peak rating was 2751 and his peak ranking was World #13!} 1. f4 Nh6 2. Nf3 d5 3. d3 c5 (3... g6 4. Qd2 $1 {was what I had mistaken the game position for. Indeed, what's seen in the game gives Black a better version of things.}) 4. Qd2 $6 {I was so excited with the [Qd2] move that I played it incorrectly.} (4. e4 $1 {was better, when the [h6]-knight is thematically locked away on the rim by the [e4]-pawn.}) 4... d4 5. c3 Nf5 6. cxd4 $2 {By trading off the [c5]-pawn I give the [f8]-bishop much better scope and grant the [a8]-rook a promising future on the inevitable [c8]-square.} cxd4 $17 {Already I'm significantly worse due to Black's grip on the dark squares. What can I say, I mixed up the lines and ended up in the doghouse, but I fought on and made the game interesting. I selected this game as a testament to the importance of a fighting spirit in the Bird. You must not give up and not give in! Onward, and upward!} 7. Na3 Nc6 8. Nc2 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc2d4,Gg2g3,Gf1g2] Contesting the critical [d4]-pawn. With the [d4]-pawn wedged where it is, I will probably have to give up on ideas of getting the [f1]-bishop out with the e-pawn. Instead, the bishop seems more and more fated for being placed on [g2].} h5 9. b4 a6 10. Bb2 {[%csl Rd4] Working to hunt down the [d4]-pawn. Do me a favor and don't turn the evaluation on here. :. Just don't.} g6 11. a4 {[%cal Gb4b5] Doing everything I can to dislodge the [c6]-knight.} e5 $1 {[%cal Rf4e5,Gf8h6] Black attempts to deflect the [f4]-pawn in a bid to get the bishop to [h6] with a dangerous initiative.} 12. b5 axb5 13. axb5 Rxa1+ 14. Bxa1 Na5 15. Nxe5 {Finally getting rid of some intrusive pawns, but the [a5]-knight will land on [b3] with annoying threats.} Nb3 16. Qd1 Qa5+ 17. Kf2 {The king dodges the danger.} Ne3 {Attempting to distract my knight from its defense of the [a1]-bishop.} 18. Qb1 {Up until now my opponent has played a perfect game, but the Bird is too complex even for the best of inexperienced opponents. Sooner or later, the mistakes will begin to pour in, just wait.} Nxa1 $2 (18... Be6 $1 {would have been the nail in the coffin. Now when ...[Nxc2] happens, there is no bishop hanging on [c8]. Undoubtedly, I would keep trying to fight back, but at this point, White's position has too many problems to be salvageable.}) 19. Qxa1 Qxa1 $2 {Another one!} (19... Qd2 $1 {presents some serious questions regarding where my knight on [c2] plans to go. For instance} 20. Ne1 Nd1+ 21. Kg3 Qe3+ 22. N1f3 Qf2# {would indeed be the end of the road!}) 20. Nxa1 {With the queens off the board, my wayward king begins to make a lot more sense!} Bc5 $2 (20... Be6 {-+ would dominate my poor [a1]-horse and would keep Black in the driver's seat.}) 21. Nb3 {[%csl Rc5,Rd4] I have survived the largest wave of the attack and can take at least one sigh of relief.} Ba7 22. g3 h4 23. Bg2 Nxg2 $2 {Trading the second knight for my second bishop. Simple, logical, rational, and yet WRONG! The knight should have been kept on [e3] where it would influence the whole board.} 24. Kxg2 $2 (24. Ra1 $1 {was even stronger.} Bb6 25. Kxg2 hxg3 {and the point of [Ra1] is revealed here. I can simply recapture without allowing a trade of rooks:} 26. hxg3 {+- .}) 24... Be6 25. Ra1 Bd5+ 26. Kf2 $2 (26. Nf3 {+- would win. There is no ...[hxg3] with check here, so the rook will stay locked out on [h8] for longer, creating huge tactical issues for Black's camp. And the [d4]-pawn will likely drop with the [f3]-knight weighing on it as soon as the [d5]-bishop snags [b3].}) 26... hxg3+ 27. Kxg3 Bb8 28. Ra8 $2 ({I don't know why I didn't play} 28. Nxd4 {+- , honestly. I was so focused on getting the pieces on the last rank that I entirely forgot about the ripe apple on [d4].}) 28... O-O $4 {Have you ever seen castling so late in the game?!?!?!?!} (28... Ke7 $1 {would have avoided any [Nd7] tricks.}) 29. Nxd4 (29. Nd7 $1 {would have been simpler. At this point, we were both in time pressure and I avoided [Nd7] on account of the ...[Bxf4] discovery trick. But alas it didn't just threaten [f8] and [b8] but also the fork on [f6].} Bxf4+ 30. Kxf4 Rxa8 31. Nf6+ {+- and the knights will hop to victory.}) 29... g5 30. Nf5 $4 (30. Kg4 {+- and [Nd7] will punish Black just the same.}) 30... gxf4+ 31. Kf2 $2 {The rest of the game is a blunderfest in a time scramble.} (31. Kxf4 {⩲ would have kept an edge. I didn't like the pin but in fact, the threat of [Ne7]+ keeps everything in order.}) 31... Be6 32. Nh6+ Kg7 33. Nhg4 f5 34. Rxb8 Rxb8 35. h3 fxg4 36. hxg4 Kf6 37. d4 {Never give up! Being down a rook against a 2700 FIDE player is no excuse to resign.} Bd5 $4 {A blunder in return.} 38. Nd7+ Kg5 39. Nxb8 Kxg4 40. Nd7 Kf5 41. Nc5 b6 42. Nd3 Bc4 43. Kf3 Bxb5 44. Nxf4 Bc6+ 45. Ke3 {I thought I should have a win here due to my extra pawn and connected passers, but Stockfish calmly asserts that the game is dead equal.} b5 46. d5 Bb7 47. Kf3 Ke5 48. e4 Kd4 49. Ne6+ Ke5 50. Nc7 b4 51. Ke3 b3 52. Kd3 b2 53. Kc2 Kxe4 54. d6 Bc6 55. Kxb2 Ke5 56. Nb5 Bxb5 57. d7 Bxd7 {Game drawn by insufficient material. The moral of this story is: even if your memory fails you and you get an awful position, the structure is still so unorthodox that you'll get your fair share of the chances if you just hold on and resist with some grit!} 1/2-1/2

