{My opponent is an IM with a peak FIDE rating of 2550. He has 2 GM norms and is effectively of grandmaster strength. I played him once before in person, in a Blitz tournament in Belgrade in the spring of 2021. This game is not a great example of this repertoire but instead serves as a reminder that strong players, just like those of lower levels, lose their way almost immediately when faced with these unusual opening positions.} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 Nh6 3. b3 ({This game was played before I had done my Unusual Birds chapter. Now I know I should play} 3. d3 $1 {with the idea of [e2]-[e4] to curb the [h6]-knight.}) 3... c5 4. Bb2 Nc6 5. e3 a6 {Stopping my bishop from placing itself on the natural [b5]-square.} 6. Rg1 $2 {This was bad objectively. Pushing for [g4] will take too long, but I had broken one of my own rules and gotten reckless in a position whose exact circumstances I hadn't studied.} d4 (6... f6 $1 {was much better. Black intends to punch on [e5] with power. For instance} 7. g3 e5 8. fxe5 Be7 $1 {Black is happy to sacrifice the pawn. I have a few useful moves and Black plans to trade on [e5] and follow with ...[Bf6], when the trade of dark-squared bishops will spell White's demise. After} 9. exf6 Bxf6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nc3 O-O {, the [f3] and [f2]-weaknesses are beginning to hurt.} 12. Bg2 d4 {, pushing the knight away. It would be nice if we could just avoid the danger with [Qe2] and [O-O-O], but Black isn't giving us time for this.} 13. Nd5 Qd6 14. Nf4 {, shielding the f-file. Following} Bf5 {-+ , things are still dire, unfortunately. The black rook will come to [e8] and we have nothing to play for. Even if we get our king castled to the queenside, ...[c5]-[c4] will be a painful punch in the gut with the black queen entering [a3].}) 7. e4 $2 {I was trying to meet the mayor twice with this one. Keep in mind this is one of the earliest played games in this chapter and I hadn't a full grasp on the structures here.} Ng4 $2 {I selected this game for a reason. First, I won and I like to show my wins. Second, my opponent and I are both GM-level players, and yet look at just how many mistakes we're making! Neither of us would be playing so badly in positions that we had more experience in. This is why the Bird is so powerful. Unless someone has specifically studied these positions, they are going to lose their way quickly.} (7... e5 $1 8. fxe5 g5 {-+ would put my position on the brink of destruction. None of my pieces will make any sense after ...[g5]-[g4].}) 8. h3 Nf6 9. d3 e5 $1 {Opting for a healthy structure reminiscent of White's side of the King's Indian Defense.} 10. fxe5 $2 (10. f5 $1 {(was best, keeping the game closed. Even here, however, Black has a great position, as Black will be first to the punch with the thematic ...[c5]-[c4] in the ensuing middlegames. This is a reversed King's Indian in which I've spent time to unfavorably fianchetto my queen's bishop away from the diagonal that actually matters c1-[h6].)}) 10... Nh5 $2 {How many question marks can punctuate the game?!?!?!?! We're only on move 10!} (10... Nd7 $1 11. Nbd2 Ndxe5 12. Qe2 Bd6 {-+ and Black's control of [e5] combined with the fact that we'll have to castle to the queenside where Black is ready to throw their pawns at us, gives Black a winning advantage.}) 11. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] Rerouting to [c4].} Nf4 12. Nc4 b5 13. Qd2 {[%csl Rc4,Rf4][%cal Gb5c4,Gd2f4] Countering the threat to my knight with a threat to his!} bxc4 14. Qxf4 c3 15. Bc1 {We arrive at a weird position in which Black's pawn chain digs deep into my territory but at the same time has locked into the point where my king is safe enough for the time being.} Nb4 {[%csl Rc2]} 16. Kd1 $1 {An absolute must to defend [c2].} Be7 {I have nothing else to do with my position but throw the kingside pawn forward and wait.} 17. g4 O-O 18. g5 {I will bring the other one to [h5] and then try to generate some play with a push to [h6] or [g6].} a5 {[%cal Ga5a4] Black wants to break with ...[a5]-[a4].} 19. a3 {Booting the knight out, but actually Black could continue along with his pawn according to the computer recommendation.} Nc6 $6 ({Black missed his chance.} 19... a4 $3 20. axb4 axb3 21. Rxa8 b2 {-+ and Black may have lost a rook and knight but is about to spawn a new queen on [b1].}) 20. a4 Be6 21. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5] Transferring the knight to [f5].} Nb4 22. Nf5 Rb8 {I would love to get my pawns up the board, but Black is already threatening ...[Nxc2] and ...[Bxb3]+.} 23. Rb1 {[%cal Gb1b3] Holding steady.} Kh8 $2 {This gives me valuable time to stay afloat in the two-flanked race.} (23... Qd7 $1 {was best. Now Black eyes [a4] and so ...[c5]-[c4] will create huge issues for me.} 24. Qf2 c4 25. bxc4 {(25.dxc4 Bxf5 26.Qxf5 d3! Sacking the queen to threaten ...[dxc2]+ and respawning a new queen on [b1]. 27.Bxd3 Qxd3 + -+ is all she wrote. )} Nxd3 {, my queen and rook both hang. After} 26. Bxd3 Rxb1 {-+ , my pawns are in shambles and my king's roof is beginning to leak with [a4], [c4], and [e4] having become vulnerable.}) 24. Rg2 {[%cal Gg2c2] Reinforcing [c2] in case a sacrifice comes.} Re8 25. h4 {Up the board we go! Ideally, I'll get to [h5] and then push [g6] with a strong attack.} c4 $2 ({A mouse in the house.} 25... Qd7 {∓ would have still kept the advantage, though the game is very messy.}) 26. bxc4 $1 {[%csl Gc2,Gc4,Gd3,Ge4] Keeping my king's shelter secure.} Nc6 $2 (26... Bxf5 $1 27. exf5 Na2 {∞ would have led to both balanced and bonkers positions. White's pawns are beginning to breathe down the black king's neck, but Black's bringing the artillery down the b-file rapidly.}) 27. Rb5 $1 {[%csl Gb5] Continuing to insulate the king's shelter. No one is going to get past the rook on the b-file.} Bb4 28. h5 {[%cal Gh5h6,Gg5g6] Black is in trouble.} Rc8 29. g6 {The break finally happens! Now [gxf7], [gxh7], and [h6] are all threats that hang in the air.} Bxf5 30. Qxf5 fxg6 31. hxg6 Rf8 {Skewering my queen and bishop.} 32. Qh3 {[%csl Gh7] Attacking [h7] and threatening checkmate with [Qxh7].} Rxf1+ 33. Ke2 Qg8 {Stopping the mate, but I can simply collect the rook.} 34. Kxf1 {[%cal Gg2h2,Gb5b7] My opponent resigned here. His position is hopeless, as my rooks will soon flood the kingside via [h2] and [b7].} 1-0

