{Here I'm paired against a Czech IM with a FIDE rating of 2423. Not an easy opponent by any stretch; let's see what happened!} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 c6 {Opting for a lesser known system. This is rarely ever played, online and in person.} 3. e3 Nd7 4. b3 $5 {Why not the fianchetto? It was a fine time to go for a Stonewall. Black has wasted time with getting his pawn to [c5] and his bishop won't get to [f5] soon.} (4. d4 $1) 4... Ngf6 5. Bb2 e6 (5... e6 {We have good control over the dark squares, and we could have continued relatively peacefully with moves like} 6. c4 {or 6.d4 .}) 6. Rg1 {[%cal Gg2g4] Throwing [g4] down the board.} h5 7. d3 {[%cal Ge3e4] I switch paths and try to play for [e4].} Bd6 $6 (7... b5 $1 {would have given Black an advantage.} 8. Nbd2 a5 9. e4 $2 (9. a4 {⩱ , holding Black's queenside advance would be best.}) 9... a4 {∓ and Black is pushing my pieces too far back to be able to do anything. Once the c-pawn reaches [c5], neither of my knights will have anywhere useful to hop to.}) 8. Nbd2 Qc7 9. c4 $2 {I really should have known better, but this game was played before I knew a lot about the Bird. This game and the one against Nenezic are a warning that even strong players will take time to master the ideas; [c4] can not be played if Black can push ...[e5]! This tends to be true in most Birds, but I wasn't yet a Bird master when this game was played.} e5 $1 {[%cal Ge5f4] This one hurt. Now ...[exf4] threatens to reveal a very vulnerable e-file that's full of weaknesses.} 10. c5 {An attempt to distract the bishop to gain control over [e5].} Bxc5 11. fxe5 Ng4 12. d4 Be7 $2 ({Black could have started snacking with} 12... Nxe3 $1 {, hitting my queen to save his bishop.} 13. Qe2 Nxf1 {and after I recapture on [f1], Black's [c5]-bishop will find safety with a healthy extra pawn:} 14. Rxf1 Be7 {∓ .}) 13. Qe2 f6 $6 {Attempting to force his wayward [g4]-knight back to [f6].} (13... a5 {⩱ was better, when Black will drum up some play with ...[a5]-[a4]. It is very hard for me to wiggle out with my queen in front of the [f1]-bishop like this. With ...[a5]-[a4] and ...[c6]-[c5] breaks both in the cards, it's not appealing to castle queenside here.}) 14. e4 $1 {Punching at [d5] before Black can protect it with the king's knight. My queen wants to power down the e-file after all.} fxe5 {[%csl Gd4,Gd5,Ge4,Ge5] A powder keg in the center.} 15. exd5 (15. h3 $1 {was called for!} Ngf6 16. dxe5 $1 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Qxe4 {± and I'm back on top with a strong e-pawn and healthy threats on the light squares. The immediate [Qg6]+ is hard to deal with.}) 15... cxd5 16. dxe5 $2 {I wanted the strong pawn, but it was too high a cost.} Bc5 {[%csl Rg1] I have huge issues on the diagonal now.} 17. Rc1 Qb6 {[%cal Gc5f2,Gg4e3] Black not only threatens ...[Bxg1] but also ... [Bf2]+ and ...[Ne3], forcing me to surrender the queen. There is no question, I must sacrifice the exchange to rid the board of the pesky bishop.} 18. Rxc5 Nxc5 19. Bd4 Bf5 $2 (19... Qc6 {-+ would avoid the pin from [Bd4] and prepare ...[Ne6] with a winning strategic advantage.}) 20. h3 Nh6 21. Qe3 {Mr Stockfish says I should have traded queens with [Qb5] with only a slight disadvantage, but when I play the Bird, I go all in. I'm not looking to draw, I'm looking to win. Apparently, I'm lost now though.} Rc8 22. Nh4 {I'm doing my best to continue making threats. If Black finishes development, he may realize he's up an exchange and completely winning.} O-O 23. Be2 Qb4 24. g4 Nd3+ $4 {Black panics and folds his winning hand.} (24... Be4 {would have kept the advantage in order. It is very hard for me to generate threats with my king being attacked from more and more angles.}) 25. Bxd3 Rc1+ 26. Ke2 Rxg1 27. gxf5 {[%csl Ge2] My king is very safe now with all angles under control. Black doesn't have even a check on [g2], as my knight on [h4] covers it. My e- and f-pawns should decide things shortly, with my bishops composing an inadvertently beautiful picture of harmony.} Rh1 28. Ndf3 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Ge5e6] Covering the check on [h2] and bringing one more piece closer to the kingside for the final assault. I will push [e6] and [Qe5] or [e6]-[e7] with a quick finish.} Ng4 {Black has nothing else and flings this move out in desperation.} 29. hxg4 hxg4 30. Bc5 (30. f6 $1 {with [Qg5] to follow would have been more cold-blooded.}) 30... gxf3+ 31. Nxf3 Qa5 32. Bxf8 Qxa2+ 33. Qd2 Qxd2+ 34. Kxd2 Kxf8 35. Ke3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge5,Gf5] In spite of the endgame being materially balanced, my passed e-pawn and better king will easily convert this to victory. Here my opponent lost on time.} 1-0

