{This game is not theoretically significant or anything. Just an insanely fun game I played in the Bird. Do NOT play this way against the Sicilian Fianchetto. The one who lives by the sword dies by the sword. If you like such reckless play, just understand it will be accompanied by more frequent losses.} 1. f4 g6 2. Nf3 c5 3. h4 $2 ({Going for all the glory.} 3. e4 {is recommended in our chapter on the Sicilian Fianchetto.}) 3... Nf6 4. b3 Nc6 5. Bb2 Bg7 6. g4 $2 {Lo and behold such play should be punished objectively and indeed the computer points out how Black can win.} d5 $19 (6... e5 {-+ would also be a principled way to play. Initiating things quickly in the center while I'm still looking for irrelevant pawns to push.}) 7. h5 $2 {I'm burning ALL the bridges.} d4 $2 {[%csl Rb2,Gc5,Gd4] Clogging the lane and blocking the [b2]-bishop.} (7... Nxh5 {-+ would have snatched a pawn and left me with dubious compensation.}) 8. h6 $1 {Where I was always trying to go − at least we have one less minor piece to deal with.} Bf8 9. g5 {[%csl Gf4,Gg5,Gh6] The start of a royal pawn phalanx.} Nd5 10. e3 {[%csl Gd2,Ge3,Gf4,Gg5,Gh6] 5 in a row, that must be some type of bingo!} e5 $5 {Raining on my parade. All I wanted was a nice pawn phalanx and this guy has the nerve to blow the pawn chain up at [f4] with ...[e5].} 11. c4 $2 {I will never be able to crunch with [c3] ever again so this was a strategic mistake. My opponent responds in kind.} e4 $2 12. cxd5 Nb4 13. Ne5 d3 {[%cal Gb4c2] I'm up a piece, but ...[Nc2]+ is threatened. There were many ways to win, but an enterprising queen sacrifice caught my eye.} 14. Nc3 Bf5 15. a3 $1 {At this point, I had made up my mind that I wanted the position with the queen sac on [c2], even if I had to burn a tempo for it.} Nc2+ 16. Qxc2 $1 (16. Kf2 {was also winning, but moving out of a check doesn't get any glory.}) 16... dxc2 17. Bb5+ {[%csl Re8] Ouch! The king is forced up to [e7] where nothing will really fit together.} Ke7 {[%csl Rf8,Rh8] It's unclear how the bishop or rook will ever get out.} 18. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gb7b5] Securing [b5] in case Black tries ...[a7]-[a6] and ...[b7]-[b5].} a6 19. Bc4 {[%cal Ga4b5,Rb7b5] No ...[b5], no problem. All my pieces occupy nice positions.} Qd6 20. a5 Ke8 {He's threatening to wiggle out with ...[Be7] so here I took action to strike.} 21. d3 $1 {The good news is that it undermines the center. The bad news is that there is no more bingo from [d2] to [h6].} exd3 22. e4 {Pushing the one well-placed piece back.} f6 {Attempting to counter with a threat of his own.} 23. exf5 fxe5 24. Ne4 {Making use of the evacuated square! The knight sits perfectly and pushes the queen back as well.} Qe7 {I hope you're beginning to understand why I selected this game. The pawn structure resembles nothing I've ever seen before.} 25. d6 {Unfortunately, Black will untangle if I do not decisively win and so I do have to get on with finishing the game.} Qd8 26. f6 $6 (26. Nf6+ {, I had seen I could win the queen in this way, but I wanted to go out on a high note.}) 26... Bxd6 27. fxe5 Bc7 28. e6 {The pawns never stop.} Bd6 29. f7+ Kf8 30. Bg7+ {He resigned! I was so annoyed, as there was a beautiful checkmate waiting around the corner.} Ke7 31. Bf6+ Kf8 32. e7+ $1 {Forcing Black to occupy [e7] before returning to the [g7]-square.} Bxe7 33. Bg7# {Mate!} 1-0

