{Yes, you read that right. Ya boi played against Hikaru and chose to throw down the Bird against him. Hikaru is the best-versed player I've played yet in the Bird. He is the only person to ever know the strength of 4...e6 in the early fianchetto Bird. I have no idea why or how he knows this. Perhaps he was expecting the Bird in the candidates and did super deep prep on it.} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. c4 e6 5. d4 $6 {This was poor nerves, honestly. I wanted to see the eagle soar and lost track of what was objectively correct.} (5. Nc3 Ne7 6. b4 {is an outrageously strange position that the computer recommends as infinitesimally better for Black. Again, this is Black's best bet against the entire 1.f4. I know this because I locked myself in a Paraguayan sandwich shop for 3 months to do this course. How Hikaru knows of this variation, the world may never know.}) 5... dxc4 $6 {Hikaru also slips up! That's the Bird for you!} ({After} 5... c5 {⩱ , however, the cookie crumbles in between [c4], [d4], [c5], and [d5]. White will be left with a weak [e4]-square, a poor [c1]-bishop, and a potentially weak central pawn.}) 6. Bxc4 c5 {If Black takes, he will have a comfortable position. I should have realized this and taken on [c5] with a slight edge.} 7. O-O $6 (7. dxc5 $1 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Nd7 9. e4 $1 Nxc5 10. e5 {⩲ and Black's bishops do not impress. White is slightly for choice.}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 $2 {[%csl Rd4,Rf4] I have a really ugly isolani now; [e4] is a very weak square and my [f4]-pawn is no good. If it were on [f2], my bishop could at least develop quickly to attack some of the vulnerable dark squares in Black's camp.} (8. Nxd4 $1 {avoids the terrible structure you're about to see in the game.}) 8... Ne7 $15 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gg7d4] The knight aims for [f5] and also keeps the path clear for the [g7]-bishop to continue exerting control. Black's grip on the light squares and my misplaced [f4]-pawn give him a healthy edge.} 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be3 Nbc6 11. Qd2 b6 {My position is very tough. Normally, you can cash out isolanis by throwing the pawn to [d5], but here if I do so I will be left with glaring weaknesses on the e-file due to the [f2]-[f4] push. I can't stress it enough: avoid this structure with pawns on [f4], [d4], and no e-pawn!} 12. Rad1 Bb7 13. Ne5 {Please sir, may you fix my structure for me by taking on [e5]?} Rc8 {He is in the top 5 in the world and, unfortunately, knows not to take. :.} 14. Be2 Nb4 {The knights eye [d5]. White's position is increasingly uncomfortable. We have little else to do but wait as Black improves. One of the reasons the knight is so well placed on [e7] is that otherwise, we could at least flick [f4]-[f5] in to worsen Black's structure. Here, however, the knight will just take, when we will be left with no compensation.} 15. Bf3 Bxf3 16. Rxf3 Nbd5 17. Bf2 Qc7 18. Bh4 Nf5 19. Nxd5 exd5 {The structure shifts slightly. Even though Black's d-file is now closed, White is still left with a weak [d4]-pawn and a weak [e4]-square.} 20. Bf2 Qc2 {Hikaru breaks through on the c-file.} 21. Rc3 Qxd2 22. Rxd2 Rxc3 23. bxc3 Rc8 24. Rc2 Nd6 25. Kf1 $2 {This blunders a pawn, but my position was already quite tough to deal with.} (25. Be1 {⩱ would have kept a bit more control.}) 25... Nb5 $1 26. Ke2 Rxc3 27. Rxc3 Nxc3+ 28. Kd3 Bxe5 {What ensues is a losing endgame down a pawn. At some point, Hikaru slips up and briefly allows a draw, which I miss.} 29. dxe5 Nb5 $2 (29... Nxa2 {-+ would give Black a winning advantage due to the two extra pawns.}) 30. a4 Nc7 31. Kd4 Kf8 32. g4 Ke7 33. f5 gxf5 34. gxf5 Kd7 35. Bh4 a6 36. Be1 Kc6 37. Bh4 Ne8 38. Ke3 b5 39. axb5+ axb5 40. Be1 $2 (40. Be7 {would hold Black's queenside back.}) 40... Kc5 41. Kf4 b4 42. e6 f6 43. Ke3 Kc4 44. Kd2 Kd4 45. Ke2 $4 (45. Kc2 Ng7 46. Bxb4 Nxf5 47. e7 Ng7 48. Bc3+ Kc5 49. Bxf6 {and a draw could be easily achieved.}) 45... b3 46. Kd2 Ke4 47. Kc3 Kxf5 48. Kxb3 Kxe6 49. Kc3 Nd6 50. Kd4 Nf5+ 51. Kd3 Ne7 52. Bc3 Nc6 53. Bb2 Kf5 54. Ke3 d4+ 55. Kf3 Ne5+ 56. Ke2 Ke4 57. Ba1 f5 58. Kf2 f4 59. Ke2 d3+ 60. Kf2 Nc4 61. Bc3 d2 62. Ke2 f3+ 63. Kd1 f2 64. Ke2 f1=Q+ {I resigned. A sad day for the Bird.} 0-1

