{We finish the chapter with a short game played against Ukrainian GM Bernadskiy Peak 2636 FIDE.} 1. f4 Nh6 2. Nf3 g6 3. d3 Bg7 (3... d5 {allows for my favorite move...} 4. Qd2 $3) 4. e4 {[%csl Rh6] We observe the knight on [h6] beginning to encounter problems.} O-O 5. h3 $1 {[%csl Rh6] The knight is dead! When the knight is sequestered like this on [h6], we can count on an edge.} d5 {You should already know what's coming at this point.} 6. Qd2 $6 (6. g4 $1 {would have been better, preparing to go to a pleasant endgame after} dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 {± . White will put the bishop on [d3] and the king on [e2] with an enormous space advantage due to the fantastic kingside pawns.}) 6... Nc6 7. Nc3 {Insisting on Black exchanging on [e4].} dxe4 $2 (7... d4 $1 {would have been better.} 8. Ne2 f6 {and the knight will slowly recuperate via [f7].}) 8. dxe4 {[%csl Rh6] Now with the queens facing off against one another, White can already count on a great endgame. When in doubt, just turn your head to the right and look at the [h6]-knight.} Qxd2+ $2 {This helps my development, when Black can't afford to fall behind in time. Remember that Black will have to burn several moves sooner or later to fix the [h6]-knight.} (8... Nd4 $1 {would have been a better chance to try to get some play going with the other pieces.} 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Qxd4 Bxd4 11. Bd2 c6 {⩲ and the black bishop's activity at least looks nice, though the [h6]-knight will continue to give Black problems for the time being.}) 9. Bxd2 Rd8 10. O-O-O Be6 11. Ng5 {[%csl Re6] Pushing the bishop back. If Black allows [Nxe6], his structure will be ruined and my bishop on [c4] will quickly collect the [e6]-weakness.} Bd7 12. g4 $1 {[%cal Ye7e5,Yf4f5] Black wants to play ...[e7]-[e5] to trade on [f4] and gain the [e5]-square for his pieces. This should be anticipated by strengthening the grounds for a hypothetical [f4]-[f5] response.} Nd4 {Flinging the knight into the center but without a healthy backup team, this steed will soon encounter difficulties.} 13. Be3 {[%csl Rd4]} Bc6 $2 (13... c5 $1 {would have held on, though after} 14. Bc4 b5 15. Bd5 {± , White is clearly on top. Black hasn't solved his long-term issues, namely emphatic pause the [h6]-knight.}) 14. Nd5 $1 {With the knight off [f6], mine can enter the prime real estate on [d5]. Now [Nxc7], [Nxe7], and [Bxd4] are all threatened.} Bxd5 15. exd5 c5 (15... Rxd5 {+- would just drop a piece to} 16. c3 {.}) 16. c3 {[%csl Rd4] It seems the knight is trapped.} Rac8 {[%cal Gc8c1,Yc3d4,Yc5d4] Using the x-ray to give the horse one more breath.} 17. Kb1 $1 {The question remains: what will the knight do?} f6 {Pushing my knight away to get the [f3]-square as an escape hatch.} 18. Ne4 Nf3 19. Be2 Nh4 {His knight might have survived the blitz...} 20. Bxc5 {[%csl Rg7,Rh4,Rh6] Take a photo for the memories. Such awful minor pieces are a sight to behold!} f5 {[%cal Ge4c5] If my knight moves, my bishop falls. But I have a way out...} 21. Bxe7 {[%csl Rd8,Rh4][%cal Ge7h4,Ge7d8]} Re8 22. d6 {[%cal Gd6d7] The threat of [d7] is even stronger than collecting on [h4].} Rxe7 23. dxe7 {[%cal Gd1d8] With [Rd8] on the horizon, Black resigned. The [h6]-knight never moved after move 1! A warning to all Black players of this dubious setup!} 1-0

