1. f4 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. Be2 {There is nothing wrong with breaking the pin here, but I do prefer Raven's suggestion of playing [h3].} (4. h3 $1 {is the course suggestion and gives White a nice position after} Bxf3 5. Qxf3 e6 6. Nc3 $5 c6 7. g4 $1 {A key idea once Black has exchanged on [f3].}) 4... e6 5. b3 $1 {It is always a pleasure to develop the bishop on [b2]!} Bd6 6. Bb2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7 8. Ne5 ({This has always been my go-to idea.} 8. c4 $5 {would fit in nicely with Raven's course.}) 8... Bxe2 9. Qxe2 c6 10. Rf3 $5 {[%cal Gf3g3,Gg3g7,Gf3h3,Gh3h7,Gg3h3] An interesting concept that can crush the unexpecting opponent. I just want to swing my rook over and checkmate on [g7] or [h7].} Qc7 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. Rh3 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Ge2h5] Now [Qh5] is a big threat.} f5 (12... a5 $2 {shows just how dangerous my attack can be:} 13. Qh5 h6 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qxh6+ Kg8 16. Qh7# {.}) 13. Qh5 Nf6 {Forced but at least I can now cause some structural damage to Black's pawn formation.} 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. c4 $5 (15. Nc3 $1 {is simple and good:} Kh8 16. Ne2 Rg8 17. Nd4 {.}) 15... Qf7 16. Qh4 Kh8 17. cxd5 cxd5 18. Nc3 a6 19. Ne2 Rg8 20. Nd4 Rg4 21. Qh5 Qxh5 22. Rxh5 Re8 23. Rc1 (23. Rc1 {White has a slight advantage that I managed to convert:} Rg7 24. Kf2 Rc7 25. Rg1 Bc5 26. Nf3 Bb6 27. g4 fxg4 28. Rxg4 Ree7 29. Rh6 Rg7 30. h3 Rxg4 31. hxg4 Kg7 32. g5 Rf7 33. Rh1 Rf8 34. Kg3 Bc5 35. Kg4 Bb6 36. a4 Kg8 37. b4 Kg7 38. a5 Bd8 39. Nd4 Re8 40. f5 exf5+ 41. Nxf5+ Kg8 42. Nd6 Re5 43. Nxb7 Re4+ 44. Kf3 Bc7 45. Nc5 Rxb4 46. Nxa6 Rc4 47. Nxc7 Rxc7 48. gxf6 Ra7 49. Kf4 Rxa5 50. Ke5 h5 51. d4 Ra3 52. Kf4 Ra6 53. Rxh5 Rxf6+ 54. Ke5 Rf3 55. Rg5+ Kh7 56. Kxd5 Rxe3 57. Kd6 Kh6 58. Rg1 {.}) 1-0

