1. f4 ({I often played} 1. f4 {against players that I knew were exclusively 1.e4 experts. My logic was that they may not have encountered the Dutch setup before and for that reason, they may be unsure of the best piece configuration. That seemed to be the case here. Jack drifted in the opening and I quickly got a good position.}) 1... d5 2. e3 ({This normally transposes to} 2. Nf3 {.}) 2... c5 3. Nf3 g6 {One of the best responses from Black. Black wants to stop [b3] and place the dark-squared bishop on a good diagonal.} 4. Bb5+ {Following our rule of 'giving this bishop a purpose', and it is also Raven's suggestion.} Bd7 5. Be2 $5 {With this move I had a particular idea in mind, borrowed from the Classical Dutch.} (5. Bxd7+ {is our theory move, when play could continue} Qxd7 $1 {Black should keep the [b8]-knight for [c6].} 6. Ne5 {− see the theoretical section for more details.}) 5... Nc6 6. O-O Bg7 7. d3 {We are in a Classical Dutch standard setup but with two differences. First of all, we have an extra tempo and lastly, Black's light-squared bishop is on [d7], a square that I felt favored White.} Nh6 (7... Nf6 {would be more common, when my idea was} 8. Nc3 $5 d4 {. This is critical otherwise I would play [e4]. (8...O-O 9.e4 is a position that I very much enjoy playing. Also, note that Black can not exchange queens here with ...[dxe4], as there is a bishop in the way on [d7]. 9...dxe4 10.dxe4 . )} 9. Ne4 dxe3 10. Nxc5 {⩲ , when Black would rather have the bishop back on [c8]; hence the idea of playing [Bb5]+ and [Be2].}) 8. e4 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Ge4f5,Rh6f5] White has a nice position, and the black knight on [h6] just looks silly.} d4 $6 {I am always happy to see this move, as it gives White a free attack on the kingside.} 9. Qe1 {[%cal Ge1h4]} ({Tempting, but} 9. h3 $5 {killing Black's knight on [h6] may even be better.}) 9... O-O 10. h3 $1 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh6g4,Gg4f6] Stopping ...[Ng4]-[f6].} f6 {[%cal Gh6f7] The only way for Black to get the knight back into the game.} 11. c3 e5 12. cxd4 cxd4 13. fxe5 fxe5 14. Bd1 $1 {[%cal Gd1b3,Gb3g8]} Qe7 15. Bg5 Qd6 16. Na3 Nf7 17. Bb3 {All of White's pieces have found good squares. I am already significantly better.} Rae8 18. Nc4 Qb8 19. Na5 Be6 20. Nxc6 bxc6 21. Bxe6 Rxe6 22. Qc1 {[%csl Rc6]} Nxg5 23. Nxg5 Rxf1+ 24. Kxf1 Rf6+ 25. Nf3 Qb5 26. Ke2 Bh6 27. Qc4+ Qxc4 28. dxc4 {[%csl Gf3,Rh6] My knight is much better than Black's bishop in this ending.} Bf4 29. Ne1 (29. Ne1 {Going to the perfect square. The game continued} Kf7 30. Nd3 Ke6 31. Rf1 h5 32. Rf3 g5 33. Nf2 g4 34. hxg4 hxg4 35. Ra3 Rf7 36. Ra6 Kd6 37. b4 Rb7 38. b5 Rb6 39. Rxb6 axb6 40. bxc6 g3 41. Nd3 Kxc6 42. a4 {.}) 1-0

