{This game got awarded the brilliancy prize, a prize that I had won on three occasions at Hastings. It was a last-round game and I had nothing to play for except the prize and the magic of creating some 'chess art'. Raven does suggest that a transposition into the Four Pawns Attack King's Indian Defense may be a decent option, and that is precisely what happens here.} 1. f4 g6 2. Nf3 Bg7 3. c4 ({Going for the 'devil's horns'.} 3. e4 {is Raven's suggestion, as then we can often set up with pawns on [c4] and [d3].}) 3... d6 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. e4 {The Four Pawns Attack.} c5 {Black's main option.} 7. d5 e6 8. e5 $5 {An interesting and aggressive option; unfortunately, it is probably not 100% sound... White sacrifices a pawn for some tempi.} dxe5 9. fxe5 Ng4 {Critical and good.} 10. Bg5 (10. Bf4 {, there is no point trying to hang onto the pawn in this way. After} Nd7 {, it will drop anyway.}) 10... Qa5 (10... Qb6 $1 {is better.}) 11. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] Getting ready to castle quickly.} Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. O-O {White seems to have decent compensation here. White is fully developed, has a big pawn on [d6], and has chances to attack Black's kingside. Black has a lack of pieces over on the kingside.} f6 14. Bh6 Rf7 15. Ne4 {I had already seen an outrageous idea...} (15. Bg4 $1 {was even better:} f5 16. Qe2 Bd4+ 17. Kh1 fxg4 18. dxe6 {+- .}) 15... Bd4+ 16. Qxd4 $5 ({Crazy and not needed but a lot of fun.} 16. Kh1 {was simple and a lot better for White.}) 16... cxd4 17. Nxf6+ Kh8 18. Ne8 {This was my idea, to try and force a rook through on the f-file. With correct defense, Black is winning, but it was the last round and we were all tired...} Rf5 $1 {The first right plan.} 19. g4 exd5 $2 ({Black goes wrong. He could have kept on top with} 19... Rxf1+ 20. Rxf1 Nd7 21. dxe6 d3 $1 22. Bxd3 Qb6+ 23. c5 Qxe6 {.}) 20. gxf5 Bxf5 21. Bf3 {[%cal Gh6g7,Gf3d5] Threatening [Bg7]+ and [Bxd5]+.} (21. Bf3 {The game continued} dxc4 22. Bxb7 Qb5 23. Nd6 Qb6 24. Rae1 d3+ 25. Kh1 Nd7 26. Bxa8 Nf6 27. Nxf5 gxf5 28. Rxf5 {.}) 1-0

