{One of my very rare wins against David who nearly always got the better of me.} 1. f4 e5 2. fxe5 Nc6 3. Nf3 g5 $6 {A rather dubious idea, back in the days when David was more of a reckless player!} 4. d4 {Simple and good.} g4 5. Ng5 d6 6. e4 {[%cal Gf1c4,Ge1g1] Preparing to play [Bc4] and [O-O], when White will have the pawn and a raging attack.} h6 7. Nxf7 $1 {Of course, in the style of the King's Gambit!} Kxf7 8. Bc4+ Kg7 9. e6 $16 {[%cal Gd1g4,Ge1g1] I already have a great position with threats of [Qxg4]+ and simply [O-O].} Nf6 10. O-O Na5 {Black's pieces lack any mobility so David aims to swap off an attacker.} (10... Be7 {would be a normal developing move, but all of White's subsequent moves are very simple:} 11. Nc3 Rf8 12. Qd2 $1 Ng8 13. Rf7+ {+- .}) 11. Bd3 Bxe6 {Black captures a key pawn but still has many problems.} 12. d5 Nc6 ({Returning a piece to try and find some safety since} 12... Bf7 {is well met by} 13. Bd2 $1) 13. dxe6 Ne5 14. Nc3 c6 15. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Ge2d4,Gd4f5] Now [f5] is a great square for this knight.} Qe8 16. Nd4 c5 17. Nf5+ Kg6 18. Nh4+ Kg7 19. Bc4 $5 ({A crazy idea, which had to be carefully calculated.} 19. Bf4 {was simple and good, but I never did simple...}) 19... Nxc4 {Otherwise, I am simply winning.} 20. Rxf6 Kxf6 21. Qf1+ {The point. White gets some material back and keeps attacking Black's king.} Kxe6 22. Qxc4+ $2 ({A mistake! Better would have been} 22. Qf5+ Ke7 23. Ng6+ Kd8 24. Nxh8 {± .}) 22... Kd7 23. Bf4 Bg7 $2 ({David returns the favor.} 23... Qe6 24. Qb5+ Kc8 {should have been played.}) 24. Nf5 Be5 25. Nxd6 $1 Qe6 26. Qb5+ Kxd6 27. Rd1+ Ke7 (27... Kc7 28. Qxc5+ Kb8 29. Bxe5+) 28. Bxe5 Rhd8 (28... Qxe5 29. Qd7+ Kf6 30. Rf1+ Kg5 31. Rf5+ Qxf5 32. Qxf5+ Kh4 33. g3+ Kh3 34. Qf1#) 29. Qxb7+ Ke8 30. Rf1 $18 Rac8 31. Qg7 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gf1f8]} Qe7 32. Qg6+ 1-0

