{Finally, a crazy game where I simply play my favorite opening (The Classical Dutch!) reversed with an extra tempo. My opponent became a strong GM later in life.} 1. f4 d5 2. Nf3 g6 3. e3 Bg7 4. Be2 {When my opponents used to play this annoying ...[g6] idea,I would just pretend that I had the black pieces. The problem White has after ...[g6] is what to do with the bishops.} (4. c4 $5 {is the fascinating recommendation that Raven gives for this course.}) 4... c5 5. O-O Nc6 6. d3 Nf6 {I normally get this position with a tempo less.} 7. a4 {Generally, a useful move, stopping ...[b5] and giving my knight on [b1] a hold on that square.} O-O 8. Kh1 $5 {Taking Black but with my king on a different square!} Qc7 9. Nc3 {Now the point of [a4] can be seen.} a6 (9... d4 {is always the move to watch out for, as you generally want to avoid ...[dxe3] ruining your pawn structure. I can avoid this here by playing} 10. Nb5 Qb6 {and now that my knight is guarded, it is possible to play} 11. e4 {. The pawns on [e4] and [f4] give White great chances.}) 10. e4 $1 dxe4 11. dxe4 Rd8 12. Qe1 Nd4 {It is time to make a decision. Play sensible or set the board on fire!?} 13. Bc4 $5 {Set the board on fire! Of course, the computer hates this, but practically, it gives White a great attack. The masters of old would be proud...} (13. Bd1 {was the sound of mind choice.}) 13... Nxc2 14. Qh4 Nxa1 {Black has gained 6 whole points! But White has positioned all the remaining pieces very aggressively.} 15. f5 {[%cal Gc1h6,Gf3g5,Gf5g6] With the idea of playing maybe [Bh6], [Ng5] or simply [fxg6].} b5 $6 {A natural counterstrike, but Kramnik playing under another Russian's chess.com account showed the correct plan in this position.} (15... Rd4 $1 {is Kramnik's counterattack. This takes a lot of the sting out of my attack.}) 16. axb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 Qb7 $2 ({A mistake after which Black is struggling. Better was} 17... Qb6 {, when White has many attacking ideas, but none of them should work with the correct defense. For example,} 18. Ng5 {(18.e5 Ne4!! is an amazing computer defense. 19.Qxe4 gxf5 20.Qh4 Be6 and the position looks dangerous for Black, but apparently not so. 21.Bxe6 fxe6 22.Bh6 Qxb5 , now I want my king back on [g1]! )} h6 $1 {A very hard move to find, unless you're a robot!} 19. Nxf7 Ra4 $3 {is the only defense, otherwise White is doing well.} 20. Nxh6+ Kf8 {-+ .}) 18. Ng5 $16 {Now White is better, but who would be able to tell unless their engine was turned on!?} e6 19. Nxh7 (19. e5 $1 {was stronger.}) 19... Nxh7 20. Qxd8+ Nf8 21. Qh4 f6 $2 ({The final mistake. Black should have tried} 21... Nc2 {, with a complete mess. For example,} 22. Nd6 Qd7 23. Bh6 Qxd6 24. Bxg7 Nh7 $1 (24... Kxg7 $4 25. f6+ Kg8 26. Qh6) 25. fxg6 fxg6 26. Bc3 Ra1 27. Rxa1 Nxa1 28. h3 {is 'unclear', lol.}) 22. e5 $18 {Break on through to the other side.} g5 23. Qg4 Qe7 24. Bxg5 $1 fxg5 25. f6 Qf7 26. Bd3 Bxf6 27. exf6 Nh7 28. Nd6 Qd7 29. f7+ Kf8 30. Bxh7 {A fun and entirely sound game.} 1-0

